<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-ECON-I (Undated) _ It is still not clear that the
financial upheavals, which began in Thailand in July 1997, will
ever damage the United States. But the collapse of Brazil's
currency in January and the jolt that it brought to markets
worldwide underscored the continuing risks of ``the most serious
financial crisis in a half a century,'' as Clinton called it in his
State of the Union address. This series of four articles is a
narrative of the worldwide financial crisis that over the last 20
months has toppled some governments and hobbled others. The crisis
illustrates how globalization increasingly stitches lives all over
the world into a single economic quilt. In the new economic
landscape that has emerged in recent years, the pool of
international investments has grown to dwarf the sums that
governments can muster, and money zips around the globe far faster
than ever before. The result is a world more prosperous; but also,
perhaps, a bit more wobbly. By Nicholas D. Kristof with Edward
Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT10,11) have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT grahics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Undated) _ What IS the American interest in
sending troops to Kosovo? What tips it for the administration to
get involved? Does this presage further such deployments in areas
of no clear strategic value to the United States? By Serge
Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE-CORRUPT (Kiev) _ The arrest of Pavlo Lazarenko, a former
prime minister traveling on a Panamanian passport in Switzerland,
throws harsh light on corruption in this vast but impoverished
republic. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT14) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NATO-POLITICS (Paris) _ As NATO's 50th anniversary looms,
Europeans increasingly chafe at American demands to do more and
Washington's reluctance to relinquish control. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-NAZIS (Undated) _ Poles are demanding a share of any
settlement of slave labor claims dating from World War II.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-POLITICS (Miami) _ Exasperated and demoralized, a group
of centrist Republicans caucusing here on the weekend after
Clinton's acquittal warned that the party must broaden its appeal,
recapture its agenda and isolate its right wing if it expects to
heal the political wounds inflicted during its prosecution of the
president. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   GANGS-REUNION (New York) _ An exhibit of photos of former New
York City gang members by Bruce Davidson is expected to attract
many of the subjects, who are now several decades older.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-POLITICS (Seattle) _ In the legal debate over the
future of Americans' high-speed connections to the Internet, some
public figures clearly think they have found a potent political
issue. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT9) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-ARCHEOLOGY (Miami) _ Miami developers, archeologists
tangle over Indian ruins. By Pamela Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SUNKSUB_FOUND (Undated) _ In a small way, Paul Tidwell is
closing the circle for more than 100 Japanese families torn by war.
A half century ago, their loved ones disappeared at sea aboard the
I-52, a Japanese submarine. The craft was carrying two tons of gold
and other material to Hitler when American forces torpedoed her in
the Atlantic, sending the warship to a grave more than three miles
down. On Monday, Tidwell is flying to Japan to give the families
three shoes he found near the sunken warship. The families, all
members of a group formed to honor the I-52 dead, have planned
memorial services across the country this week. By William J.
Broad.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photo [NYT13) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
