<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS AGAIN FOLD IN THE STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Six games into the sprint, it's obvious the Lakers
haven't changed enough to beat the Utah Jazz and reach the NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   And even if they could somehow get past Utah and face the
Eastern Conference's expected representative, Indiana, the Lakers
would lose.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight Sunday, the Forum played host to the
NBA's marquee matchup, and just as they did a week ago, the Lakers
melted in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Call it experience, veteran leadership or whatever else you
want. The Lakers still lost 101-99 to fall to 0-2 in games that
really, really mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we lost against the two experienced teams, I still
think we're a better team,'' Lakers guard Derek Harper said. ``It's
having the resolve to hang in there, and we haven't found the
resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, who failed to record a double-double for the first
time this season, had a chance to find the Lakers' resolve, not to
mention make amends for a less-than-stellar outing, but couldn't do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant (18 points, two rebounds) pulled the Lakers within 100-99
with a 3-pointer with 4.8 seconds left, but after Rik Smits made a
free throw, Bryant's deep 3-pointer from straight away rattled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team that comes in here is coming in here thinking they
have an opportunity to win the game down the stretch,'' Bryant
said. ``That's exactly what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal mustered up some genie magic to heal his aching
abdomen, or groin, depending on who's doing the talking, to
dominate the middle with 36 points and 17 rebounds. Not that they
mattered much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individually, we have a lot of guys who can go out and score
points and have the game be all about them,'' Lakers forward Rick
Fox said. ``But then we're not going to win. It can only get worse.
Last year we were unselfish: Move the ball, take the open shot. If
it was open you shoot, or you pass it. We haven't gotten that
mindset yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Lakers' ability to relentlessly feed the ball into
the low post, which left O'Neal tossing up 30 shots, a key element
was missing from the offense.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't Robert Horry, who spent the afternoon in the
hospital after complaining of chest pains.
</P>
<P>
   The missing ingredient was getting to the free-throw line, which
Indiana did throughout the second half. The Pacers (4-2) shot 27
free throws in the second half, five more than the Lakers attempted
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   So in a game in which the Lakers shot fairly well, rebounded
extremely well and played solid defensively, it was another facet
that did them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about as well as we can play right now,'' Lakers coach
Del Harris said in a scary indictment of his team's predicament.
``We couldn't get to the foul line. A good veteran team like
Indiana is going to get themselves to the foul line, and I thought
that was the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veteran teams usually have a few more tricks that makes it
look like you got fouled whether you do or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   There was other evidence that savvy is lacking.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers led 84-76 early in the fourth quarter, but there was
no sign of panic by the Pacers, only poise and smarts and a
willingness by players to do the tough work.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows the last time a Lakers player took back-to-back
charges? The Pacers last did it with 3:19 and 2:52 to play against
the Lakers. It was done by Indiana's Antonio Davis, who got O'Neal
and Knight on consecutive possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller (26 points) followed the first one with a free
throw to give to give the Pacers a 91-90 lead, then finished it
with a 3-pointer after Knight's charge as Indiana went up 94-90.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling (our guys) when they were going on that run at
the end of the third quarter that we're only down two points,''
Miller said. ``Let experience take over in the fourth. Let's just
settle down, make plays, play within ourselves and just keep in
close. If we keep it close we'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   One would say the Pacers resolved to win this one down the
stretch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
