<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-SHOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS FLY BACK TO AFRICA WITH BODY OF SON KILLED BY POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Escorted by his physically and emotionally exhausted
parents, Amadou Diallo, the unarmed street peddler shot to death by
police officers 11 days ago, began the long, final journey home to
West Africa on Sunday in a simple wooden box.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving behind a crush of supporters and angry demonstrators who
gathered in Harlem to protest Diallo's death in a barrage of 41
shots, the gray hearse carrying his body formed the head of a long
motorcade that wound its way, under police escort, from 125th
Street in Manhattan to Newark International Airport in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   With the Rev. Al Sharpton at their sides and surrounded by a
crush of reporters and well wishers, Diallo's parents seemed almost
impervious to the intense scrutiny of their every move. Apparently
left with few words to say after a week as an object of worldwide
attention, they boarded a Continental Airlines jet bound for Paris,
with the pine coffin of their 22-year-old son in the cargo hold.
</P>
<P>
   The family, and Diallo's body, are scheduled to arrive in their
native land, Guinea, by Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Diallo had lived his days in New York
peacefully, but his departure added to the crescendo of outrage
among the city's black residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much anger, the black community is enraged,'' said
Wayne Hazzard, swathed in cream-colored African robes, standing
outside the National Action Network on Madison Avenue near 125th
Street, where the airport motorcade formed. He called for the Bronx
district attorney to act swiftly in investigating the four officers
who shot Diallo. ``If these cops here are not taken care of, this
city's going to go up in smoke.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, much of the outcry on that Harlem block, packed with
hundreds of people young and old, came in furious tones. Some
advocated violence to avenge Diallo's death, and everyone demanded
justice for his killing.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo was killed when four undercover New York City Police
officers fired 41 bullets in the early morning hours of Feb. 4.
Diallo, who was in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment building at
the time, was struck by 19 bullets.
</P>
<P>
   As mourners riding in cars festooned with Guinean flags and
carrying signs that read simply ``Amadou'' gathered on Monday
afternoon, protesters began intermittent chants of ``No justice, no
peace'' and ``Giuliani must go.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing away from the noise and bustle, Mary Butler, 55,
endured the day's deep chill in silence. Asked her thoughts on
Diallo's death, she spoke in one-word sentences: ``Cold. Blooded.
Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People will not forget about it,'' she added. ``He was only
22. That could have been my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one quarter of the 500 people in front of the National
Action Network, Sharpton's office, shouted angrily about the police
and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. But almost everyone agreed that the
anger would not dissipate with Diallo's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to go on for a while,'' said Henry Walker, 68,
calmly smoking a pipe as others chanted anti-Giuliani slogans.
``You can kill a man with just one bullet. It doesn't take 41
bullets to kill even an elephant.''
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall on Sunday, Giuliani continued his defense of the
police department.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people in other major urban police departments want to
learn about restraint,'' he said at a news conference, ``they come
to the city of New York and look at the things the Police
Department in New York City does to teach police officers
restraint, cultural awareness, cultural sensitivity. It's not done
perfectly, it will never be done perfectly, it should be done even
better, but the strategies actually are working very, very
effectively and almost everybody outside New York City who is in
this business understands that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also challenged the notion that the police are
disproportionately targeting members of minority groups. When a
reporter said that 85 percent of the people shot by the police in
the last five years were black or Hispanic, the mayor responded,
``But that is actually less than the number that are actually shot
in society.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the news conference, he said: ``There are more
shootings involving black victims and black shooters as a
percentage than there are of police officers doing it. So I know
those are difficult facts for people to deal with but what we
should be about in government and what you should be about in the
media is leading people to the truth, not to reinforcing biases and
prejudices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
