<HEADLINE>
PACERS OUTSMART LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Derek Fisher and a soaring Eddie Jones had the Forum
fans standing and cheering with the identical fast-break lob-dunks
that put the Lakers in front of the Indiana Pacers in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A spinning, snarling, shouting Shaquille O'Neal kept the crowd
on its feet with the three powerful dunks that gave the Lakers
their biggest lead of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Pacers' Antonio Davis made the biggest plays of the
afternoon, turning all of the Lakers' highlight footage into
meaningless fluff, with his spectacular display of . . . (begin
ital)standing still(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   So went the young Lakers' latest lesson in the art of winning
basketball from a smart, seasoned NBA opponent, a 101-99 loss
Sunday afternoon in a portentous early-season game.
</P>
<P>
   With just over 3 minutes to play and the Lakers trying to break
a 90-all tie, Davis drew a charging foul by O'Neal, leading to
Indiana's go-ahead free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to make sure he didn't fall on me,'' Davis
shrugged later.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)That's(end ital) smart.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, Davis drew another charge, this one by Travis
Knight, setting up the Reggie Miller 3-pointer that put the Pacers
in command.
</P>
<P>
   The same highlight films that show you the third-quarter
dunkfest will tell you the Lakers lost this game because Kobe
Bryant's buzzer-beating jump shot rimmed out.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not why the Lakers lost.
</P>
<P>
   They lost because it was one of those games that experience
seems to win every time. And knowing how to take advantage of
overwrought opponents, as Davis did, is what experience is all
about.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the charge _ twice in a row! _ was, dare we say, a Dennis
Rodman play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling (teammates), when they were going on that run
with all the dunking and whooping and hollering, at the end of the
third quarter we were only down by two points,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Let experience take over in the fourth quarter.
Settle down, play within ourselves, and we'll come up with big
enough plays.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Which they did, to win a game billed as an NBA finals preview,
just as the Utah Jazz did a week earlier, to win a game billed as a
Western Conference finals preview.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no Showtime here today,'' said Indiana's Sam
Perkins, the former Laker, ``because we played smart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antonio has been in the league a few years. Maybe at one time
he wouldn't have known any better and he would have challenged (the
driving Lakers). That's a good example of being smart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, consensus favorites to win the East in the first
year AM _ After Michael _ average 33 years of age in their starting
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   That means they're old enough to remember the Pacers' last
title, 1973 in the American Basketball Association, where George
McGinnis, Mel Daniels and Roger Brown overcame the Kentucky
Colonels' Dan Issel, Artis Gilmore and Louie Dampier in a
seven-game final series.
</P>
<P>
   That also means they weren't panicked by the prospect of
finishing the first full week of the lockout-shortened NBA season
with a 3-3 record after playing five straight on the road.
</P>
<P>
   They'd received so much publicity for being the lone NBA team to
work out together in the idle months, some people expected the
Pacers to blow rustier opponents off the court. But they knew
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did during the lockout isn't going to pay dividends
until late, when (other) teams will be tired,'' Miller said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Pacers appear better conditioned than other teams?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but we're not playing that well,'' coach Larry Bird said
before the game. ``Maybe it's the road. I don't know. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big game. I'd rather be 4-2 than 3-3 going home.
Maybe then we'll get our confidence back.''
</P>
<P>
   In front of a network audience and a 17,505-fan sellout,
including a season high for celebrities, the Lakers made the
spectacular plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, a clever assortment of role players, made the big
plays.
</P>
<P>
   They went to the free-throw line 42 times (making 33) while the
Lakers went just 22 times (making 16).
</P>
<P>
   They grabbed the rebounds of their own misses on back-to-back
possessions to cut a five-point Lakers lead to one with 5{ minutes
to play.
</P>
<P>
   They spread the scoring among Miller (6), Jalen Rose (5), Davis
(4), Travis Best (3) and Rik Smits (2) in the last 5{ minutes while
the Lakers got 13 of their last 17 points from O'Neal and Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   And they knew when to stand still.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely guys on this team who know how to make
plays late in the game and guys who aren't afraid to touch the
ball,'' said Best. ``You saw Kobe touch the ball a lot late in the
game, whereas there's probably three or four of us who are ready to
make plays and take free throws. That could be the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not they sign Rodman and shore up their own
experience, the Lakers could learn something from the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to learn how to play together,'' Davis said,
offering the kind of criticism the Jazz wouldn't last week. ``They
have to learn to play to each other's strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   All that Lakers talent, Davis said, ``should make the game that
much easier. But sometimes it makes it harder.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
