<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NILSMARK DEFEATS SORENSTAM IN PLAYOFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE _ Annika Sorenstam will be skiing today in Lake Tahoe,
enjoying herself and trying to clear her mind of golf.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing she wants to think about is what happened Sunday
in the final round of the Valley of the Stars Championship at
Oakmont Country Club. Sorenstam three-putted from four feet for a
bogey on the first hole of a sudden-death playoff and lost to
Catrin Nilsmark.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning end to a final round that featured a spirited
duel between good friends and fellow Swedes. Nilsmark was seeking
her first LPGA victory; Sorenstam had won 16 times since turning
pro in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never give up... never, ever,'' said Nilsmark, who won
$97,500 to Sorenstam's $60,510. ``It's not always going to end like
this, but sometimes it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked like the tournament was hers, especially after she
chipped in from 40 feet on the par-4, 360-yard 16th hole for a
two-stroke advantage, but Sorenstam, who shot a final-round 67,
wouldn't go away. Nilsmark then bogeyed the par-5 17th and
Sorenstam birdied the par-5 18th to force the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam was just short of the green on the first extra hole
(No.18) and chipped to four feet above the hole for what looked
like a certain birdie. Nilsmark was in a greenside bunker in two
holes and blasted out to five feet, but she missed the putt and
felt the tournament had slipped away.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's such a good putter,'' Nilsmark said. ``She's good when
it counts. Then my caddy said, `Well, you still had a good
tournament.' Then I said, `We still might go down 10.' A minute
later, I'm the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam, who missed from three feet, took the loss hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not shocked, just very disappointed,'' she said. ``But I
have to look at the bright side. I fought really well. I started
four shots behind, and this is a tough course to chase somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``You work really hard for 18 holes, then come out in a
playoff... the way it ended wasn't as fun as if somebody did it
with a birdie. It's not a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Nilsmark, who hasn't won since the 1994 Ford Golf Classic on the
Women's Professional Golfers' European Tour, attributed her victory
to good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what it takes to beat Annika when she's playing
well,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to several stunning shots, especially
Saturday's holed bunker shot on the 18th hole for an eagle. There
also was her drive on the par-4, 334-yard fifth hole Sunday.
Instead of going around a large tree that guards the dogleg, her
ball went through it cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was her chip-in on the 16th hole, when she was
desperately trying to stay ahead of Sorenstam. She hoped to get it
within 10 feet, and the next thing she knew she made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one was really tricky,'' she said. ``I actually was
standing over the ball and I thought, `Just remember you still have
a one-shot lead. Don't get too cute, and make sure you get over the
longer grass.' I was hoping it would stop 10 feet, if I was lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been happy with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Lowe, two strokes behind Nilsmark at the start of
Sunday's play, struggled to a 4-over 76 and finished in a
fourth-place tie with Jane Geddes. Liselotte Neumann finished alone
in second, at 8-under 208.
</P>
<P>
   La Canada's Helen Alfredsson and defending champion Dale
Eggeling tied for sixth at 3-under 213.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
