<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEUMANN BLAZED SWEDISH TRAIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE _ Liselotte Neumann certainly doesn't look the part of
a pioneer. She is only 32 years old and is blessed with Swedish
blonde good looks.
</P>
<P>
   But more than a decade ago Neumann began the Swedish invasion on
the LPGA Tour by winning the 1988 Women's U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big thing,'' said Catrin Nilsmark, a fellow Swede who
earned her first LPGA title on Sunday by defeating Swedish
superstar Annika Sorenstam in a playoff at the Valley of the Stars
Championship at Oakmont Country Club. ``That made a huge impact on
Swedish golf. Just the year before she had been playing with us (in
Europe).''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years after her breakthrough victory, Neumann is still
going strong. On Sunday she completed a one-two-three Swedish sweep
by shooting a final round 67.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably playing better than I did back then,'' said
Neumann, referring to her win at Five Farms in Maryland. ``I'm more
experienced, more solid, a better ball striker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I won the Open it was one of those weeks when everything
went my way. The thing now is to be able to go out and do it every
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Neumann, a winner of 12 titles and more than $3 million on the
LPGA Tour, has certainly has been consistent in recent years. She
has finished seventh or better on the money list in four of the
last five years and won a career-high $665,069 last season. This
year she has two top-10 finishes in four starts and is seventh on
the money list with $92,957.
</P>
<P>
   Neumann may not be the current queen of the Swedes when it comes
to the general public, but her peers know just how good she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very steady, a very good player,'' said Sorenstam.
``She's not overlooked at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Neumann, who jokes she is no longer one of the ``young ones,''
takes pride in whatever role she had in paving the way for players
such as Nilsmark, Sorenstam and Helen Alfredsson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to have been here from the beginning,'' she said.
``To maybe help open the doors and make people realize you don't
have to play 12 months a year to come out and be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   And she certainly enjoys seeing a leaderboard like Sunday's,
which also included Alfredsson, who finished tied for sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all live over here (in the United States) now, but it's
still fun to look up and see three Swedes. It makes you feel
good,'' said Neumann.
</P>
<P>
   Although Neumann fully realizes that ``a lot of girls don't make
it,'' she predicts more Swedish stars will surface on the LPGA Tour
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very determined and overall they are very good
athletes doing a lot of sports,'' said Neumann, who played soccer
and hockey as a youngster. ``They are hard workers and they have
goals and dreams and that's very important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 0058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5429 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     02-15 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IN retrospect, it was inevitable. We should have seen Charles
Barkley's injury coming. You stick a frisky 20-year-old kid in a
soon-to-be-36-year-old man's body, and this is what you get, a
mangled medial meniscus.
</P>
<P>
   For you laymen, that's a torn cartilage in the knee. Barkley
wanted at first to play through the pain, but that was never going
to work, so in went the arthroscope Sunday and out came the debris.
We're told Sir Charles will be as good as new in three to four
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, he won't be.
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, three to four weeks isn't what it used to be,
either.
</P>
<P>
   With NBA teams trying to cram 50 games into three months, a
ridiculous aspiration regardless of the circumstances, the
likelihood of players getting hurt greatly increases, and the
impact of even relatively minor ouches is magnified. If Barkley is
lost to the Rockets for the full four weeks, he'll miss 16 games,
or almost one-third of the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   That, by the way, is the equivalent of 26 in a normal season of
82. A comparable layoff at the outset of last season would have
cost him just 11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Say it then takes him another couple weeks to approach 100
percent _ lots of happy talk from the optimistic doctors
notwithstanding, rehabbing a knee is not the ideal way to maintain
one's aerobic conditioning, which has been a Barkley problem _ he
could be impaired for eight to 10 more games after his return.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, with tipoffs scheduled every other night, on average, the
risk of reinjury looms huge as well. Barkley has a lot of mileage
on that wide body of his already.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Rockets, in the interim, are in the midst of
trying to reinvent themselves with the integration of Scottie
Pippen, who is hardly your everyday plug-in, passing-through free
agent. Losing such a critical component as the Chuckster at such an
early juncture is tantamount to putting a match to Rudy
Tomjanovich's new playbook.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, while that itty-bitty cleft in Chaz's cartilage might be
mosquito-bite insignificant under different circumstances, it has
the potential to _ excuse my mixed metaphor here _ seriously
hamstring the Rockets' chances of positioning themselves properly
for a championship run.
</P>
<P>
   The current season is a mad sprint, not the usual leg- and
brain-numbing marathon. The margin for error is minuscule. Never
have the pro thump-thumpers embarked upon a more demanding, or
Darwinian, campaign, one that will ensure the survival of only the
most fit.
</P>
<P>
   Such are these weirdest of circumstances that Barkley, for once
in his career, might have been better served to report less fit,
then gradually work himself into condition instead of trying to
destroy opponents single-handedly.
</P>
<P>
   His contract calls for him to make $1 million, a veteran's
minimum, and frankly an insulting sum for a jock of his stature.
Yet he was acting as though Leslie Alexander had secretly slipped
him a major equity position in the franchise. He charged from the
gate, light on his feet and heavy on his opponents. There was a
hunger inside of him that had nothing to do with nachos,
cheeseburgers or cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen points and 17 boards per? This was a man on a mission,
with a point to prove. Pride may be a deadly sin _ it figures
Barkley would possess a surfeit of it _ but it isn't always all
bad.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley went soft on us last season. He knew it, and he knew we
knew it. There was no hiding his precipitous decline. I mean,
things devolved to the point where, exactly a year ago, he went on
national TV and said he was going on the wagon. Although of course
he fell off soon thereafter, that he would dare consider such a
drastic lifestyle change _ remember, his second Houston home used
to be a place called the Liquid Lounge _ told us how concerned he
had become.
</P>
<P>
   Since the real Charles, the essential Charles, is equal parts
mouth, butt and heart, he wasn't going to embarrass himself on the
floor any further. Admittedly, he had done so in a game against
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   After recovering from offseason elbow and hernia surgeries, he
perspired himself into arguably the best shape of his life. While
there were lapsed moments featuring the debauchery of old, they
lacked the former wantonness. He even experimented with meditation
_ the Zen kind, not what he used to practice at our local
gentlemen's clubs.
</P>
<P>
   He took a big one for the Rockets by reupping early, for a bunch
fewer dead presidents than he could have pocketed elsewhere, then
went to work proving that not every modern athlete is motivated
solely by the size of his check stub. When the season finally
began, he was completely recharged, a repentant round mound on full
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Then pop.
</P>
<P>
   A tough break, or tear, this. Barkley deserved better, doggone
it. Tell him so if you see him. He'll appreciate your kind words
and won't throw you through a window, I promise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 0101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
