<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5431 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-15 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEISTY BORGIA GAVE COMMAND PERFORMANCES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was a world of trains and DC-9s. It was a world of
10 bucks a day meal money _ if that. It was a world in which
trainers didn't go on the road. It was a world in which some of the
owners coached their own teams.
</P>
<P>
   It was the NBA of the 1940s, '50s, and even the '60s. It was a
very intimate, personal league, in which every player, coach and,
yes, referee had a recognizable personality. And, for 20 years,
there was no bigger officiating personality than the feisty Sid
Borgia, who died Jan. 25 at the age of 82.
</P>
<P>
   Borgia and Red Auerbach were one of the great pairs of the day.
Each man was short, bald, and of the opinion that he was the
smartest man in the room. One of the enduring images of the time is
that of Auerbach, the rolled-up program in his hand, shouting at
Borgia, who would be wagging his index finger in Red's face. If you
went to a Celtics game refereed by Borgia, and there was no Red-Sid
contretemps, you wanted half your money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one tough mother,'' reflects Auerbach, who was so moved
by the death of his old adversary that he sent a note to the family
described by son Joe as ``full of respect and love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He just loved controversy,'' Red says.
</P>
<P>
   That opinion was seconded by the late Earl Strom in his 1990
autobiography, ``Calling The Shots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He might have been the toughest of all time,'' the late NBA
officiating great tells us. ``He certainly was the most
rambunctious. Sid was fearless when it came to clashes on the court
or the stands. I swear, he was never happier than when he had
10,000 people howling for his head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you always wanted Sid on the road,'' Red explains.
``You never liked to see him at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Strom tells us about the time Sid flat-out popped a fan who had
challenged him to call a technical foul on Bill Russell. ``Sid told
him he could try his guts any time,'' wrote Strom. The fan stepped
onto the court and Sid nailed him, loosening some teeth. Not bad
for a guy who, according to his son, ``was 5-5 and going
downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in Syracuse,'' Auerbach recalls, ``and there was a
blizzard raging outside. We all come out of the arena and some kid
hits Sid with a snowball. He says, `Watch this,' pointing to his
bag, and he takes off after the kid. He chases the kid for a block,
block and a half, and he catches him. He rubs the kid's face in the
snow. When he comes back, he's got this big grin on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Sid was a man of his times. Simply put, he often made it up as
he went along. The following vignette is said to be the gospel
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Sid blows the whistle. Turning to the offensive player, he says,
``You walked.'' Turning to the defensive player, he says, ``You
made him walk. Forced walk. Offensive ball out of bounds!''
</P>
<P>
   Forced walk?
</P>
<P>
   Why not? For Sid Borgia is the man who coined the phrase, ``No
harm, no foul,'' which has made a comfortable leap from basketball
lingo to accepted American phraseology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't believe in ticky-tack fouls,'' points out son Joe,
himself an NBA official before injury forced him to retire. ``Sid
believed that not all contact was a foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Red, of course, agreed with that philosophy when the Celtics
were on defense. He was not quite so compliant when one of his guys
was knocked hither and yon while Sid stood by with the whistle in
his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say, `Sid, don't make up your own freakin' rules,''' Red
laughs, knowing there was no chance Borgia was ever going to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sid refereed everything,'' says Joe Borgia. ``Painting the
house. Dinner, even. He'd have the salt and pepper shakers out, and
he'd say, `OK, here's Russell. Here's Wilt. It's all about the
proper angle.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sid was out of the NBA before they added the third ref, and it's
a good thing because he never understood the need.
</P>
<P>
   ``To him it was like being a boxing ref,'' says son Joe.
```You've got to keep moving,' he'd say. `Stand still?''' He never
got it.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard for any new fan to imagine how powerful the referees
were in those days. Pat Kennedy. Richie Powers. Mendy Rudolph. Norm
Drucker. Strom. They were all strong personalities who really ran a
game, and no one ran one with more brio than Sid Borgia, who
officiated eight of the first 14 NBA All-Star Games (what more do
you really need to know?) and was a 20-year fixture in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   It's all different now. The modern NBA referee is bred to be
nothing more than an officiating robot. Nice theory. But
frightfully dull.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Borgia found himself torn when his own officiating career
was taking shape. He was Sid's kid, so naturally he had some Sid
tendencies. But the NBA wasn't looking for any new Sids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally had to say to him, `Dad, I can do it your way and
make you happy, or I can do it their way and get a job,''' Borgia
relates.
</P>
<P>
   Sid's NBA world is simply unimaginable today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was cleaning out his desk,'' says Joe, ``and I came across a
lot of fascinating stuff. There were old, old rule books. And there
was a letter from (first NBA commissioner) Maurice Podoloff
reminding people that `there is a TV game coming up and everybody
must behav.' I just sat there and said, `Wow.'''
</P>
<P>
   Red Auerbach knows more about the NBA than any man on Earth, and
here is what he has to say about Sid Borgia: ``Sid was always in
command. He wasn't going to call the chintzy stuff. Of all the
referees we've ever had, I'd say the three best were Pat Kennedy,
Earl Strom, and Sid Borgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it means something and maybe it doesn't, but let the
record show that both Red Auerbach quit coaching and Sid Borgia
quit officiating following the 1966 season. Somehow I think that
when Red himself reaches that Great Playoff Game In The Sky, he'll
find Sid Borgia waiting for him, the finger wagging, reminding Red
who was right and who was wrong on some play that took place in
Rochester or Syracuse 45 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
