<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMENGAMER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOOPER LEADS UPSET OF U.S. WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD GONZALEZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ On a cold and windy Sunday evening meant to celebrate
the U.S. national team's upcoming foray into Women's World Cup '99,
it was only fitting that Chicago resident Charmaine Hooper stole
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the bundled-up pro-American crowd of 15,367
that packed Spartan Stadium, Hooper is of Canadian descent.
</P>
<P>
   The former North Carolina State star scored twice within a
six-minute span early in the second half as the World All-Stars
humbled the U.S. national team 2-1 in an exhibition matchup
culminating the festivities for the Women's World Cup '99
tournament draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blame my dad, he was a diplomat and that pretty meant I became
a citizen there,'' Hooper said. ``I guess I could have just have
easily decided to become an American.''
</P>
<P>
   Since exhibition results aren't counted as official, the U.S.
women's team's 21-game international winning streak remains intact,
although its confidence might be another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprised (at losing)? I'd have to say no (because of their
talent),'' U.S. midfielder Mia Hamm said. ``But the fact they got
together just a couple of days ago... well, then yes (I'm
surprised).''
</P>
<P>
   The World All-Stars, whose first and only practice as a unit
came Saturday, were clearly plagued by a lack of timing on offense
at the outset, practically negating the short passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Americans repeatedly linked together passes
upfield, resulting in nine first-half shots. The U.S. finally found
the net at 23:03 of the first half, when a buildup at midfield
became a pass to Hamm flashing down the left wing. Hamm quickly
centered the pass to an on-rushing Julie Foudy, who chipped a
right-footed shot to beat World All-Stars keeper Gao Hong of China
inside the far right post for the 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   As the game wore on, however, the World All-Stars began to read
each other better, with second-half substitute Irina Grigorieva of
Russia emerging as a key playmaker the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Hooper tied the score when her direct kick at 54:09 deflected
off the wall set up by U.S. defenders and found itself just beyond
the reach of substitute goalkeeper keeper Tracy Ducar. Hooper
closed the scoring at 60:22 with her second unassisted goal, this
time beating Ducar on a quick shot from high inside the penalty
box.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let them have the opportunity to take the game away from us
and they did,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said. ``But I'm not
surprised. Soccer is a universal language and they eventually
played together beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were also dealt a blow early on. Midfielder
Michelle Akers was escorted off the field in the 13th minute after
a head-on collision with Norway's Linda Medalen. Akers, who was
rushed to the hospital, suffered a severe cut over her left eyebrow
and a severe bruise to her left cheekbone. Her near-term prospects
for returning to action were not immediately known, according to
team officials. &UR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
