<SLUG> BC-SKI-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALANDER, MILLER WORLD SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
 ALPINE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ In the largest crowd of spectators to watch a ski
race in this country, there was not one Finnish flag among the
dozens of national flags that were waving.
</P>
<P>
   Not one shirtless spectator had his face or body painted with
grease paint in Finland's colors. Austrian and Norwegian colors
dominated, with Swiss and Italian not far behind.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, before 23-year-old Kalle Palander came pounding
over the lip of Pepi's Face to win the slalom gold medal in the
World Alpine Championships, few race fans ever had seen a Finnish
Alpine racer.
</P>
<P>
   Palander, who vowed all week he would win a medal here, said his
breakthrough would turn his country on to Alpine skiing and loosen
up some cash from the ski federation, most of which goes to Nordic
events, for which Finland is famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was skiing well,'' said an ebullient Palander, who
was not used to the crush of reporters at the finish. ``I knew I
could make the podium if I stayed solid and made good turns, and
did not ski out on the ice. But I never dreamed this, a gold medal,
a world champion. It is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest to any Alpine ski glory for Finland came in 1996
when Janne Leskinin placed fourth in a World Cup slalom. Aside from
that, they never have made the top 10 in a World Cup, world
championship, or Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   Another sweet note for Palander: His astonishing second run _
more than eight-10ths of a second faster than the nearest
competitor _ knocked two from dominant ski countries down a peg on
the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Settling for the silver was Norway's Lasse Kjus, though he set a
world record with five medals in a world championships or Olympics.
Just behind him came Austria's Christian Mayer.
</P>
<P>
   The smarting United States team had its poorest showing since
the 1988 Olympics at Calgary. One of two bright spots in two weeks
of racing came Sunday when Bode Miller, a 21-year-old Franconia,
N.H., native who cut his edges on Sugarloaf Mountain in Maine with
the Carrabassett Valley Academy, started from deep in the second
seed to finish eighth, ahead of such Swiss stars as Michael Von
Gruenigen and Paul Accola. Two weeks ago, the US's Chad Fleischer
placed sixth in the Super-G.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous all the way down,'' said Miller of his second
run. ``But then I got to the top (of Pepi's Face) and I heard this
crowd roaring. It sounded like they were inside my helmet. I never
heard anything like that and I was really nervous. I just wanted to
stand up.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's morning run started at 30th place, and he had a
slashing, rhythmic run that propelled him to 13th, and a top-seed
start _ third _ in the afternoon, in which he picked up five more
places. Some 25,000 boisterous fans with flags and cowbells packed
the stands and lined the International Course with its rolling
terrain. According to US Ski and Snowboarding Association spokesman
Tom Kelly, Sunday's crowd was even larger than many European
Championship and Olympic crowds. ``Even (Alberto) Tomba didn't draw
this many at Sestriere (worlds, two years ago),'' said Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   For Miller, a rookie who has been showing hints of a top
performance all season, the second run loomed huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make a plan and stick to it,'' he said. ``When you
start skiing, you have to have the mind strength to stick to the
plan. It's hard, especially with all that crowd noise.''
</P>
<P>
   The trickiest part of the course was the last eight gates down
the steep Pepi's Face that drop into the stadium. Miller said he
knew the lip of Pepi's was sheer ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was obvious and I slowed down when I had to,'' he
said. ``Today I was lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's performance took some of the sting out of a dismal two
weeks for the US Ski Team, with particular disappointment in the
fizzle of medal hopeful Kristina Koznick Saturday in the women's
slalom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't perform here,'' said Bill Marrolt, president
and CEO of the US Ski Association. ``We came to ski better than we
did. We'll just have to start over with our young team and look
ahead to Salt Lake City.''
</P>
<P>
   The final medal count: Austria 13 (5 gold, 4 silver, 4 bronze);
Norway 9 (3 gold, 3 silver, 3 bronze); Sweden 2 (1 gold, 1 silver);
Switzerland 2 bronze; Australia 1 gold; Finland 1 gold; France 1
bronze.
</P>
</TEXT>
