<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDEN BOY IS NOW THE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The Golden Boy became the Hombre de Oro Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Challenged stiffly for the first time in his professional
career, Oscar De La Hoya responded as a champion must when trying
to defend a world title. He fought with fire.
</P>
<P>
   Those flames consumed undefeated former World Boxing Association
welterweight titleholder Ike Quartey in a firestorm of left hands
in the opening minute of the 12th round at the Thomas &AMP; Mack
Center, one sending Quartey crumpling to the floor seconds into the
final round of a close fight and two dozen more leaving him stunned
and badly hurt on the ropes before he could escape.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey, to his credit, refused to fall a second time, but by
the time De La Hoya's assault was over the crown prince of Hispanic
boxing had transformed himself from Golden Boy to a bruised but
still battling man.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, De La Hoya was spent and unable to finish Quartey
but he was awarded a curious split decision that allowed him to
retain the World Boxing Council welterweight title on a night when
he had answered all the critics who questioned his chin, his heart,
and his punching power when facing bigger men.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Larry O'Connell of England had Quartey a 115-114 winner
while scoring two rounds even, but John Keane of England had it
116-113 and Ken Morita of Japan scored it 116-112 for De La Hoya.
The Globe card also had De La Hoya winning, 116-112, by virtue of
his taking the last three rounds after the fight was even after
nine.
</P>
<P>
   It is those championship rounds _ the ones from the 10th on _
that often define who a fighter is, and in each of them it was De
La Hoya who threw more punches and, more important, landed more.
Quartey long has had a habit of fading down the stretch, as he did
in his last fight 16 months ago when he fought to a draw with Jose
Luis Lopez, and again was dropped late in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   The same pattern emerged against De La Hoya. Although the final
punch count was a razor-thin 206-201 for De La Hoya, he enjoyed a
wide margin in the last three rounds, including a devastating 41-18
edge in Round 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Oscar was going to kill him (in the final round),''
said De La Hoya's co-trainer, ring-wise Gil Clancy. ``He hit Ike
with left hooks I don't think anybody I know could take. The way he
stood up and tried to come back, you have got to give Ike a lot of
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Quartey believed he deserved more than that, angrily complaining
that he earned the decision but could not win on points in Las
Vegas, where unquestionably De La Hoya is king. Quartey spit those
words out through a right cheek so swollen it appeared someone had
stuffed three rolls of nickels inside it in case he wanted to play
the slots later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Yet neither his cheek, the fact he was knocked down twice, nor
the overwhelming advantage De La Hoya had in the final rounds could
keep him from believing things would have been different had they
been fighting in his native Ghana.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did nothing,'' Quartey (34-1-1) said. ``I did everything.
All he did was come to survive and that is what he did. You saw the
fight. You know I won the fight. You knew I couldn't win a decision
in Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   He also couldn't win one landing on the seat of his satin pants
twice or by being badly outpunched in the final round while
throwing only 41 and 43 punches in Rounds 10 and 11. He couldn't
win it if in the moments when a champion is crowned _ the late
rounds _ he was found wanting, which he was.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Quartey still gave De La Hoya his toughest 36 minutes in the
ring, a battle that forced the champion to be nearly an hour late
for the post-fight press conference. When he finally arrived his
left cheek was badly swollen and discolored, causing his eye to be
half shut and forcing him to press a Dixie cup full of ice against
it throughout the questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Now The Golden Boy who had traded as much on his charm and good
looks as his boxing ability to become a Hispanic cult hero finally
looked the way many Mexican fight fans like to see their champions.
He was pretty no more, a man now not a boy, but a champion still,
which was the point of enduring all the pain in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beat one of the best in the world,'' De La Hoya (30-0) said.
``I give him all the credit in the world. He's a solid fighter. A
strong fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went at it, but I was never worried that I had to come back
dramatically. I thought I was in total control. But I wanted to go
out with a bang. I wanted to prove I can fight. I wanted to do
everything possible to get a devastating win.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya did that, but not before suffering some problems of
his own. Quartey's thudding left jab did a great deal of damage,
reddening his face by the end of two rounds and causing his cheek
to begin the slow process of growing to twice its normal size.
</P>
<P>
   He also had an advantage nearly turn to disaster in the sixth
round when he dropped Quartey for the first time with a
tremendously fast left hook that sent the challenger to the floor.
De La Hoya tried to jump on Quartey then and learned the hard way
that he was in with a very strong man when he missed a wild right
uppercut and was countered by a thunderous left hook from Quartey
that sent the champion to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   When he got up De La Hoya was still hurt, his eyes wide now with
concern and astonishment more than concentration as Quartey pressed
him. But the challenger never was able to land the finishing
combination he needed and De La Hoya escaped a wiser man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a bit dazed, but I thought `I'm going to get right back
up and stay in this fight,''' De La Hoya said. ``I'm not a
quitter.''
</P>
<P>
   That was obvious, but he also became more cautious, giving
ground more than he had in any of his previous 29 victories as
Quartey kept walking straight in with a menacing smile, his left
jab thudding, thudding, thudding into the champion's mouth in the
middle rounds.
</P>
<P>
   As the fight wore on, however, Quartey seemed to wear down as he
often has. De La Hoya's people had done a computer analysis of
Quartey's punch stats and found he threw considerably less often in
the late rounds and when he began to slow down, De La Hoya picked
up the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, De La Hoya continued to ignore both his fight plan
and the pleadings of Clancy and head trainer Robert Alcazar, who
asked him to use his speed and movement to keep the mechanical
Quartey at bay. This he did not do, instead staying right in front
of Quartey while searching for openings, a Golden Boy choosing this
night to fight like a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted Oscar to stay on the outside and use his legs, which
he didn't do,'' Clancy said. ``He got caught up in it and showed he
has the ability to fight as well as box. He showed a lot of heart,
which is what got him through, but he spent the entire fight
fighting Quartey's fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he used his legs, it would have been a lot easier for
Oscar, but it was one of those nights he wanted to fight more than
he wanted to box.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end, he also wanted to fight more than Quartey did, a
point a man claiming to be Quartey's uncle made outside the Thomas
and Mack Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the difference between Ike and Oscar,'' he said.
``Oscar wanted to win more tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   And win he did over an opponent who elevated his status more in
defeat than by anything he had achieved in victory. What Ike
Quartey proved Saturday night was that he belongs among the world's
top welterweights.
</P>
<P>
   What Oscar De La Hoya proved was that he belongs at the top of
that list, a Golden Boy who is now The Man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
