<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS BACK TO OLD WAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even on calendar dates defined by stuttering
hearts, the beating goes on for the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Hallmark momentum killer was provided by the Minnesota
Timberwolves, who clobbered the home team 95-73 in front of 8,592
at the Sports Arena. When placed in cahoots with Golden State's
victory over Portland, the loss leaves the Clippers as the NBA's
only winless team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' said first-year coach Chris Ford, whose 0-5
team demonstrated both pulse and spine in Saturday's overtime loss
at Phoenix. ``It was looking like we were making strides. We've got
to go back to the drawing board tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The drawing board was cluttered with numbers that failed to add
up to Clippers success. The T'wolves (3-1) _ who had two nights of
rest after beating the Lakers in Minneapolis on Thursday _ played
with a defensive abandon that limited the Clippers to 37-percent
shooting from the field. And when they had the ball, the T'wolves
frequently found rangy forward Kevin Garnett available to finish a
fast break with a screaming dunk.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot Garnett, who somehow had made less than 40 percent of
his shots before this game, scored a game-high 24 points and
grabbed 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good game,'' said Clippers power forward Maurice
Taylor, who added understatement to his disturbing habit of
under-rebounding. ``Guys in the NBA are gonna have good games.''
</P>
<P>
   And tired teams without star-caliber players are going to
struggle with fresh teams that have players like, well, Garnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a superstar we can just hang our hat on,'' Ford
said. ``We have to have 12 guys who stay within the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who had a superstar-on-training-wheels offensive game in
Phoenix, led the Clippers with 19 points on Sunday but missed 10 of
16 field-goal attempts. For the second consecutive night, he had
only four rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never gonna say we can't have a good team,'' Taylor said.
``But we have to concentrate more on both ends.''
</P>
<P>
   A fine example of this would be the lively Garnett, whose
numbers included three steals and a blocked shot. His fastball slam
with 32 seconds left in the third quarter put the T'wolves up 73-53
and suggested that any signature Clippers rally would have to wait
for another night.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Lamond Murray had 12 points for the Clippers but managed
only 10 shots against the warrior defense of Garnett. The rapid
rise of rookie center Michael Olowokandi was stalled for the second
night in a row. The 7-footer from Pacific had just six points and
four rebounds in 27 minutes. Free-agent rookie Tyrone Nesby
continued to make Wednesday's cut-down day an interesting topic by
scoring nine points in 19 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that and a garbage-time moment that featured Taylor
guarding Minnesota's Bill Curley, there was little left to shout
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will they be embarrassed with this loss?'' Ford said of his
team. ``I hope so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
