<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE QUESTIONS THAN ANSWERS WITH RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Here, hard by the banks of the Caloosahatchee
River, in the home of those two beacons of light, Thomas Alva
Edison and Neon Deion Sanders, the Red Sox soon will announce their
presence for another spring.
</P>
<P>
   On Yawkey Way, the equipment truck was due to leave Monday
afternoon, stuffed with bats, balls, warmup jerseys, sunflower
seeds, and Dr. Joe Kerrigan's Pitching Pals, dummies all. The real
pitchers, along with the catchers, are due to report Saturday, with
the rest of the squad expected on hand next Tuesday. The first
exhibition game is March 4 here against the Minnesota Twins, with
the annual exhibition against Boston College the next night. The
regular-season opener will be April 5 in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the Red Sox' seventh spring here since their move
from Winter Haven, whose replacement tenants, the Cleveland
Indians, twice have been to the World Series since the Sox left. It
also is their first without Mo Vaughn, who will spend 40 days and
40 nights in the Arizona desert with his new band of followers, the
Anaheim Angels, who have given the slugging first baseman 80
million reasons never to look back.
</P>
<P>
   What will Vaughn's absence mean on Charlie Wagner Way, the
entrance to the Sox training complex that bears a red street sign
emblazoned with the name of the former Sox player, longtime scout,
and unofficial spring-training master of ceremonies?
</P>
<P>
   Glad you asked. That's as good a place as any to begin this
informal primer on the Sox' 81st spring since they last won the
World Series. What's to miss about Mo?
</P>
<P>
   Besides the 40 home runs, .337 average, and 115 RBIs, only this:
a camp so quiet, you'll be able to hear the wind ruffle the
bristles on the top of Dan Duquette's head. No weight controversy,
no public wishing the Rocket and Jose were still here, no contract
squabbles, no Duke-bashing, no strip clubs, no alcohol and drug
innuendo, no Harrington-bashing, no hugs for Kevin Kennedy, no
State of the Sox address, no pick-a-new-team speculation, no Leroy
and Shirley Vaughn, no king of the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   To that list, some might add these: No replacement, no fun, no
hope. But one man's ennui is another man's peace of mind, and
Messrs. Harrington and Duquette, assuming they leave their office
curtains open, may look down from their private boxes in City of
Palms Park and decide the view never has been better.
</P>
<P>
   OK, enough already about Mo. We've had since November to get
used to the idea that he's gone. If I'm laying out 35 bucks a seat,
I want to know about the guys who are still here. Tell me this: Is
there a chance this spring Duquette will find another big bat?
</P>
<P>
   Possible, but not likely. Plenty of big boppers changed teams
this winter _ Albert Belle, Rafael Palmeiro, Greg Vaughn, Brian
Jordan, Will Clark _ but none wound up in a Red Sox uniform. The
White Sox plan to hold on to Frank Thomas, so Duquette's best bet
may be to keep after the Atlanta Braves about first
baseman/outfielder Ryan Klesko, a Jimy Williams favorite from their
days in Atlanta. The Braves would move Klesko, but they were
seeking to extract one of Boston's best young prospects in return,
either 1998 No. 1 pick Adam Everett or top Dominican find Julio
Guerrero. Baseball rules prohibit the Sox from moving Everett
before June 1, but with the Braves having acquired Jordan over the
winter, they may be willing to move Klesko, a lefthanded slugger
who has averaged 23 home runs in the last five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   So, what are we supposed to make of Jose Offerman, besides the
fact that the baseball universe generally agrees it laughable that
the Sox shelled out $26 million for him?
</P>
<P>
   Pity the poor guy, for one, if you can find sympathy for a man
who crumbled under Tommy Lasorda-induced pressure in Los Angeles,
put up some nice offensive numbers in Kansas City, but never has
faced the scrutiny to which he'll be subjected in Boston,
especially in the wake of Vaughn's departure. Finding Offerman a
position will be Williams's biggest challenge. Originally an
error-prone shortstop for the Dodgers, he played exclusively the
last two seasons at second base, where the Sox have Jeff Frye
returning. First base is a possibility, but Offerman played there
just part-time one season. He'll make Vaughn look like a Gold
Glover by comparison. But he's making too much money to be only a
DH, which sets up a scenario where Frye could be odd man out, over
Williams's objections.
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitting Offerman could wind up hitting third in front
of Nomar Garciaparra, and off last season's numbers _ .315 average
(.360 after the All-Star break), .350 with runners in scoring
position, 13 triples, 45 steals _ could thrive there.
</P>
<P>
   But it hardly can be reassuring to Sox fans to hear what Royals
manager Tony Muser said about his leading hitter at a banquet after
the season. Muser first talked about how Hall of Fame inductee
George Brett once wished that on his last at-bat in the big
leagues, he'd have to hustle to beat out a routine grounder. Then,
Muser described Offerman's last at-bat as a Royal as ``a single
that Offy just jogged to first on.'' Muser reportedly added:
``That's OK, Offy. Take the $26 million and go to Boston. We're
going to get ya.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulp.
</P>
<P>
   Tell us about some of the kids. And what happens if Trot Nixon
has a terrible spring? Who plays right field?
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's the one, and at the moment there appears to be no
fallback plan. Michael Coleman's reputation needs reconstructive
surgery, and the only other outfielders in camp are minor league
journeymen. The plan is to employ the same platoon Williams used
with such success last season, with Nixon taking the place of
Darren Bragg in a rotation that included Darren Lewis and Damon
Buford. Nixon seems eminently qualified for the role, and has a
Braggian thirst for the action that will endear him to the fans,
but the Sox are thin here.
</P>
<P>
   The next great hope is Dernell Stenson, the 20-year-old
outfielder who is drawing the same kind of raves Coleman did a year
ago. Stenson doesn't turn 21 until June 17, so he's probably a year
away, but with a football player's build (6 feet 1 inch, 230
pounds) and lefthanded power, the Sox hope he comes quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the team's better young prospects are third basemen, Cole
Liniak and Wilton Veras, while two young catchers bear watching as
well. Shea Hillenbrand led the organization in hitting with a .349
average, though he has yet to find a position. And Peabody product
Steve Lomasney showed some pop (22 home runs) in Single A Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   By our calculation, Pedro Martinez, Bret Saberhagen, and Tim
Wakefield combined for 51 wins last season. But has the bottom of
the rotation been upgraded with the additions of Mark Portugal and
Pat Rapp?
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan is expecting 28 pitchers in camp, including seven
nonroster invitees. He and Williams did a masterful job of
protecting Saberhagen, who in 18 of his 31 starts had at least one
extra day of rest. By the end of the season, Saberhagen was
throwing harder than he had been in June. Portugal is 36 and has
been hurt so many times, his kids think his first name is D.L. Rapp
has won as many as 14 games in a season and once threw a one-hitter
in Denver, no easy feat. But he also walked a career-high 107 last
season, third highest total in the league. That's no way to survive
Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also don't have a lefthander in the rotation, which is
not the ideal scenario. Robert Ramsay and Brian Barkley are long
shots to break through, while righty Brian Rose will be brought
along slowly after last season's elbow woes.
</P>
<P>
   So, what does Tom Gordon do for an encore?
</P>
<P>
   He hopes that everyone has sense enough to know he can't
possibly duplicate last season's near-perfection. The Sox hope that
former Dodger Mark Guthrie will be a serviceable lefthanded setup
man, while Kerrigan will sift through a motley crew (Kip Gross,
Brad Clontz, Marino Santana) to see who will join Derek Lowe and
Jim Corsi as righthanded help.
</P>
<P>
   Does Nomar have a girlfriend?
</P>
<P>
   What kind of question is that? Happily, Garciaparra is a big
believer in keeping his private life out of the public domain. But
just in case you were wondering, the MVP-in-waiting devoted a big
chunk of his offseason as he usually does, in intense workouts that
require a monk's dedication.
</P>
<P>
   Will he miss Mo? Of course. Will it change anything about his
game? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Which in itself is reason to look forward to spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
