<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS WENT FROM BAD TO WORSE ON ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins spent all day Sunday flying back from a
dismal 1-2 road trip out west. Their plane landed late in the
afternoon but their playoff chances remained up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   They are injured, beat up, sick, and hurting. And that's just
the physical aspect. Truth be told, the Bruins could use a little
bit of repair on their psyche and a big-time retooling of the
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, they were trying to secure home ice for
a playoff spot. They didn't quite make it, but fifth place wasn't
anything to sneeze at. Now they'd be thrilled to make it at all.
Sure, there's plenty of time remaining in the season, but now is
not the time for the club's version of community auditions, and
that's what is happening. It's training camp all over again.
</P>
<P>
   After the odious 5-4 loss to the Islanders at home Feb. 4,
president/ general manager Harry Sinden brought up Antti Laaksonen
and Cameron Mann with the idea they would skate a regular shift for
coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   They gamely tried, but the fact is their presence wasn't the
answer and made no discernible difference as the roster grew
thinner and thinner because of injuries. Defenseman Darren Van Impe
(shoulder) went down in Edmonton, left wing Sergei Samsonov
(charley horse) went down in Calgary and spent a third day on
crutches Sunday, and left wing P.J. Axelsson (sprained right wrist)
went down in Vancouver. Steve Heinze is out with a hip flexor
strain, Kyle McLaren skated on the trip but didn't play because of
a bum shoulder, and Anson Carter played but still isn't 100 percent
after coming back from an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   Laaksonen was sent back Sunday and Mann remains. Next up from
Providence will be center Randy Robitaille and right wing Landon
Wilson. Will they make a difference? Perhaps, but not likely.
Wilson has been up here before and done nothing. Robitaille is a
decent scorer, but as we've seen with Mann, points in the AHL don't
always translate to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   The reinforcements needed are more substantial than what Boston
has in Providence, with all due respect to the players involved.
Burns is being asked to juggle 20 balls in the air at once, all of
varying sizes. The Bruins' roster was thin to begin with. If one of
those balls drops out of the air, the rest become more unstable.
Even a two-time Jack Adams Trophy winner as coach of the year can't
pull the trigger on an empty gun and expect it to fire.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins were devastated by the 4-3 loss to the Flames in
the final seconds Friday night, they were out-and-out depressed
after a 3-1 loss to the Canucks Saturday. The defining moment of
the Vancouver game was when big forward Todd Bertuzzi skated
through the entire team, knocked down normally reliable
6-foot-7-inch defenseman Hal Gill with one hand like he was 3-7,
and scored a highlight film goal that held up as the winner 33
seconds into the second period. It was gorgeous to watch but
horrible to deal with if you're a Bruin.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe management will make a deal, maybe it won't. Maybe,
instead, it'll let Burns tear out his hair while trying to put
together a competitive combination that is too talent-thin to
weather the loss of more than a couple of players. Burns is no
doubt crossing all fingers and toes and praying to any god who will
listen that nothing happens to Ray Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most upbeat players on the team _ goalies Byron Dafoe
and Rob Tallas _ seemed the most crestfallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only get four shots in the third period, one coming in the
final 20 seconds of the game, that's not being hungry, that's not
playoff hockey,'' said Tallas, who was tagged with the loss to the
Canucks. ``We're just not ready for it and that's what is
disappointing. I wish I had the answers. No one has the answers
right now. If something goes right, we're waiting for something to
go wrong. We can't do that. Last year, it didn't matter the score,
it didn't matter what was happening in the game, we were always
positive no matter what the outcome was. On most nights, even if we
lost, we know we put in a good effort. When we're losing like this,
we're not putting in a good effort. That's why it's hard''
</P>
<P>
   Burns has kept a stiff upper lip through the struggle, through
the occasional good games and the all-too-frequent bad ones. He's
mitigated the situation when he sensed his team's fragility, he's
gone to the whip when he thought it would help. More often, he's
used the velvet glove on a roster even he has to know won't take
him to the promised land. If Burns is frustrated by the front
office's inertia, he hasn't said so, but the players say they sense
the coach's anguish about the way this season has gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe this is happening to us, it's so
frustrating,'' said Tallas. ``You can just see it in the guys. It's
a strain. I think Pat has every right to be frustrated. It's the
little things that are killing us. It's the simple things that are
really hurting us on the ice. If there's a rebound, it's picking up
that second shot. We never had second shots that much last year. We
trapped so well that if a team made a mistake, we capitalized on it
and scored a goal and that's how it worked last year. He has every
right to be frustrated by us. He's continuing to stick with it. It
worked last year and there's no reason it shouldn't work this year.
I don't know why we're getting off the page and trying to do our
own things.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that it isn't the same team as last year.
The hunger of last season has been absent in some players. There
has been no second line. The defensemen are another year older and
some have been less effective. Contract squabbles put the Bruins
under the gun early and injuries are keeping them under the gun
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see teams that you know are having fun,'' said Tallas.
``You know the players are coming together. You know they're having
a good time. Things are rolling right. You always say we're getting
bad bounces, but you create your bad bounces.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we score a goal, we should be excited, and it's almost
like we sit down on the bench and we're quiet rather than getting
up and cheering. It's tough to do that when you're going through a
stretch like that. You don't want to be having too much fun (in a
tough time).
</P>
<P>
   ``We just fell into this rut and we can't allow ourselves to do
that. Last year, we took pride, we never lost too many games back
to back. If we did, the third game we won and that's one thing
we're getting away from. We've got to make a goal of it in this
dressing room. Right now, we're just sitting back and waiting to
see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an absence of confidence in this team, an absence of
enjoyment for some players. The roster that looks like it could use
an infusion of Prozac definitely could use an infusion of healthy
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been losing games in dramatic ways,'' said Dafoe, who
was in net for the dreadful loss to the Flames in which Jarome
Iginla won it with 3.4 seconds left in regulation. ``Not only do
you lose a game, but (when) you lose a game you should've won or
should've gotten a tie out of, it hurts twice as much. The way
we've been losing has really hurt our confidence. We come back,
have a couple strong games, and outside we're on top of the world.
Inside, I think there's still some hesitancy, guys just aren't
sure. We've got to blow that out, we've got to get rid of it.
You've got to be a confident hockey team to make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Tallas, Dafoe said he sees the frustration in the coaching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they are,'' he said. ``They put a lot of hours in,
showing video, coming up with different philosophies. From one
night to another, a certain player doesn't do it, a certain line,
I'm sure it's frustrating on their part. Pat can only come in and
give the same speech so many times.''
</P>
<P>
   At this moment, a two-word speech is all that is needed: ``Send
help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
