<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-CROSS-COUNTRY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSS COUNTRY CHAMP PICKS UP PERFECT VALENTINE GIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPANAWAY, Wash. _ In the chaos of getting ready for the USA
Winter Cross Country Championships, Alan Culpepper forgot one very
important thing.
</P>
<P>
   A Valentine's Day gift for his wife, Shayne.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Shayne got a glimpse of something she really wanted
during the two-day event at Lake Spanaway Golf Course. It was one
of the carved wooden duck bowls that were presented to the winners
in each of the six championship races.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came up just before my race started and said one of those
bowls would look really good in our home,'' said Culpepper, who
lives and trains in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   No problem? Competing with him in yesterday's senior men's
12-kilometer race were five of the past seven national champions.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Culpepper surged to a 20-yard lead midway through
the next-to-last lap in the six-lap race and won impressively in 34
minutes, 23 seconds. He was the only runner to break 34{ minutes
and finished seven seconds ahead of runner-up and Adidas teammate
Tony Cosey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've got Shayne's Valentine's Day present,'' Culpepper
said afterward, stuffing the bowl into his bag. ``Before this, I
was going to give her a flower.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he got the bowl and a trip for two to Northern Ireland
next month. The top six finishers in each of the championship races
qualified for the U.S. team that will compete in the World
Championships March 27-28 in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Shayne Culpepper will join her husband on the U.S. team because
she was fourth in Sunday's senior women's 4-kilometer race won by
defending champion Amy Rudolph.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's other championship race, Adam Tenforde, a senior at
Hanford High School in Richland, Wash., finished sixth in the
junior men's race to earn a place on the U.S. team. The race,
billed as 8 kilometers but shortened to 7,865 meters, was won by
Luke Watson, a freshman at Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   But the day belonged to the senior men, and that race was
claimed by Culpepper in part because no one else in the field of 96
runners seemed willing to take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this was going to be a one-move race,'' Cosey said,
``because the field was so even, but also because a lot of times in
these 12-kilometer events guys run just to make the team.''
</P>
<P>
   With the pace lagging, it was time for someone to do something
because, as Cosey put it, ``It's easy to get stale in the middle of
a race like this.''
</P>
<P>
   But who would be the mover? Not defending champion Tim Hacker.
He finished 43rd.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kicking yourself because you know no one is running
that hard, yet you can't go any harder,'' Hacker said. ``I tried to
quicken the pace, but I never felt good from the start today.''
</P>
<P>
   Former event winners Reuben Reina (1996 and 1994) and Todd
Williams (1993 and 1991) also struggled, finishing 27th and 14th,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   That left it up to Culpepper, who last year missed a spot on the
U.S. world team by one place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just got to the point where I said, `All right, if I'm
going to take this thing, I want to really break away,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Alan made the move,'' Cosey said, ``I didn't respond, and
no one else did either.''
</P>
<P>
   That left the rest of the field racing for second through sixth
to qualify for worlds. Cosey beat Dan Middleman (34:31) to the
finish line by a second, and Rodney DeHaven (34:34), Gary Stolz
(34:35) and Clint Wells (34:36) slugged it out down the final
stretch to finish in one-second intervals.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Ray Appenheimer, who led or shared the lead for
three laps only to slip to a non-qualifying seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running a good race,'' he said, shaking his head. Then,
pointing to his head, Appenheimer added, ``But you have to get it
done up here, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
