<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON CAPTURES DAYTONA 500 
</HEADLINE>
 500-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ First and foremost, Jeff Gordon gave
thanks to God for the many blessings _ all 2,172,246 of them _ that
were bestowed upon him after winning Sunsday's Daytona 500. Then,
almost in the same breath, Gordon gave thanks to runner-up Dale
Earnhardt, the man who rendered some unlikely drafting help that
enabled Gordon to pass Rusty Wallace for the lead on Lap 190, but
who also gave Gordon a hellish time in an exciting shootout in the
final 10 laps.
</P>
<P>
   Praise the Lord _ and the Intimidator _ and pass the loot.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up where he left off from his NASCAR Winston Cup
championship of a year ago, Gordon captured his second Daytona 500
in three years while thwarting Earnhardt's attempt to become a
repeat winner of a race in which he took 20 years to record his
first victory.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon stood upon the winner's podium in Victory Lane, where he
was joined by his wife, Brooke, crew chief Ray Evernham, and John
Hendrick, brother of ailing car owner Rick Hendrick, who retreated
to his Charlotte, N.C., home to watch the race. He was treated to a
confetti shower of imitation dollar bills after pocketing that
$2,172,246, the largest purse ever paid in an American auto race.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's record windfall was bolstered by a $1 million bonus
from the Winston No Bull 5 program, which also paid $1 million to a
lucky fan, Ray Grimm, 46, of Hagerstown, Md., one of five fans
paired with an eligible driver for the prize _ and a devout
Earnhardt fan.
</P>
<P>
   That was, of course, until Gordon made Grimm an instant
millionaire by winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to keep him behind me is one of the toughest things
I've ever had to do in a race car,'' said Gordon, who has won three
consecutive races dating back to last season at Rockingham and
Atlanta. ``I wanted it bad. He wanted it bad, and that's why it was
such a great race down to the checkered.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, and Gordon had just crossed the finish line
ahead of Earnhardt, with Kenny Irwin, Mike Skinner, and Michael
Waltrip right on their heels, the Intimidator's black No. 3
Goodwrench Chevrolet Monte Carlo pulled alongside Gordon's No. 24
Dupont Chevy Monte Carlo. Earnhardt then congratulated the winner
in his own inimitable style: He sideswiped Gordon's car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thinking that he was saying, `This car is going to
Daytona USA, and I'm just going to put my mark on it before it goes
(for enshrinement Monday),''' Gordon said with a laugh. ``I think
we both knew it was a great exciting race. There's been several
times there's been mention of it coming down to a finish between
Gordon and Earnhardt. Even though we battled for a championship in
'95, we really didn't have too many tight battles all the way to
the finish. I really can't think of a better way to do it than here
at the Daytona 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Earnhardt, who had to correct an ignition problem early on,
``I couldn't really muster much on Jeff. His car was strong from
the center of the corner off. I just never could get to him. If I
could've got to him in the corner, I might have got under him, but
I just couldn't get there. I got beat.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Earnhardt's gesture? ``I think he was just showing me how
much fun he was having,'' Gordon said. ``He's a great champion and
a great sport. He just came up and gave me a little donut _ and
then he waved.''
</P>
<P>
   But the goodwill gesture that really caught Gordon by surprise
was Earnhardt's decision to link up with him as he was gunning for
the lead on Lap 190, and ran three-wide into Turn 3 with Wallace
and Skinner, Earnhardt's stablemate at Richard Childress Racing.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon executed the day's most spine-tingling move at the start
of Lap 190 when Wallace, who led thrice for 102 laps total, tried
to hold his ground, forcing Gordon well below the yellow blend line
and into the path of Ricky Rudd's badly limping car, which had
returned to the race after it was involved in a 12-car melee
started by Dale Jarrett on Lap 136.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rusty was doing everything he could've done,'' said Gordon,
who averted disaster by squeezing his car between Rudd's and
Wallace's on the apron in Turn 1. ``He ran me down low. There's a
lot of apron there and I utilized it as much as I could. Then I got
down there and looked ahead of me and saw Ricky Rudd running. I
said, `Oh, Ricky, I hope you see me coming, because I'm coming
really fast.' Finally, he moved a little bit and I got up there,
but I didn't make the pass.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't until he got Earnhardt's help. Hung out to dry by the
Daytona Draft of single-file cars on more than one occasion, Gordon
was unable to find a drafting partner until Earnhardt tucked his
car behind Gordon's and helped him get past Wallace and Skinner as
they went three abreast into Turn 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty surprised,'' Gordon admitted, ``although I had
the preferred line, I had the bottom groove, and the bottom groove
was the way to go all day long today. He had a tough choice there.
He had a teammate, his buddy Rusty in the middle, and me. I thought
he would have gone with the other two long before he would have
gone with me, but I think he knew he had a fast race car and he
could race anybody. Maybe he just wanted to race me to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad he went with me, and I'm glad I was able to race
him all the way to the finish.''
</P>
<P>
   After wrapping up his 1998 Winston Cup campaign with 13
victories, more than $9 million in earnings, and his second
consecutive and third overall Winston Cup championship, ``People
ask me, `How can you top it?''' Gordon said, shaking his head in
disbelief. ``I'll tell you what ... a $2 million dollar payday ...
a battle with Dale Earnhardt to the finish ... and a second Daytona
500 victory, how can you beat that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 0149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
