<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      02-15 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS LOSE ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Heath Irwin is the Patriots' starting center
barring the signing of a veteran or the drafting of a center in
April. That became clear Sunday after the expansion Cleveland
Browns made Dave Wohlabaugh the richest center in the NFL with a
six-year deal averaging $3.5 million per.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who have lost two major free agents in the
offseason (punter Tom Tupa the other), weren't able to match that
offer, preferring to get Ty Law and Lawyer Milloy in the fold.
</P>
<P>
   As they were parting ways with Wohlabaugh, the Patriots were
putting a press on defensive tackle Henry Thomas, trying to sign
him before he defected to the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots vice president of business operations Andy Wasynczuk
made a new proposal and was mulling over a counter-proposal from
Thomas's agent, Jeffrey Durand, Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a big step made in the right direction,'' said the
Minneapolis-based agent. ``I liked the tone the conversation was
taking. Andy called with the intent of getting a deal done and
though what the Patriots proposed was still a little short of what
the other teams had offered, they were making progress with the
front portion of the contract, which is where we would like to see
the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Durand said he has three offers higher than the Patriots', but
said Thomas would take less to stay in New England.
</P>
<P>
   While it appeared the Patriots' offer was in the $2.5 million
range per year, that increased to more than $3 million given the
market established by other signings, including that of Gary
Walker, who bolted the Titans for the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlabaugh made a quick decision on Cleveland, realizing he
wouldn't get as much money in New England. The Patriots tried to
sign Wohlabaugh last offseason, but he wanted to test the free
agent waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the moment we visited Cleveland there was a good feel to
it,'' said Wohlabaugh. ``If I had to leave, this is the place I'd
leave New England to go to. The familiarity with Coach (Chris)
Palmer was very important. After he explained the offensive
philosophy to me, it's one that I'm familiar with having known
Chris when he was in New England (as wide receivers and later
quarterbacks coach). It just felt right for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a quality of life decision,'' said Wohlabaugh, who was
born and raised in Buffalo and graduated from Syracuse. ``We felt
this was a good area to raise our family. It's only about three
hours from my parents' home and it just seemed like it was the
right fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlabaugh enjoyed playing for Pete Carroll and the Patriots'
coaching staff. But he knew New England had a salary cap problem
and he quickly realized it wouldn't be resolved any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``For anyone who thinks the New England situation is
deteriorating, just watch that team next season,'' said Wohlabaugh.
``When they get their injured guys back they'll have an explosive
offense. No team could have done any better with all of the
injuries we had. Maybe we didn't get as far as we wanted to get,
but we were in the playoffs two years in a row under Pete, and we
had to overcome a lot of problems with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think after that Jacksonville game some things were said
that are going to help this team next year. I think the players got
a lot closer.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why leaving New England wasn't easy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a lot of good friendships with my teammates and with a
lot of people in the New England area from Foxborough up to New
Hampshire where I lived,'' he said. ``It's a time I'll never forget
and I wish it could have worked out. But I'll always remember good
things about the Patriots organization and New England. We went to
a Super Bowl and made the playoffs three out of my four years
there. That's tough to match, but hopefully we can do it in
Cleveland in a short period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Coach Palmer has a plan on how to build it up and I
think he's going to get the job done. I got to know him very well
in New England and he's a brilliant coach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
