<SLUG> BC-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KWAN CARRYING THE FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
 FIGURE SKATING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Maybe they should put Michelle Kwan in a
biosphere and keep her warm and germ-free for the next month.
Because if anything happens to her, the US figure skating team may
well get blanked at the world championships in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, who hasn't lost since last year's Olympics, will be
odds-on to win her third crown in four years. But unless Michael
Weiss can crack the Russian troika that has ruled men's skating all
winter, the rest of the squad will be going overseas purely for the
sauna and the experience.
</P>
<P>
   The post-Olympic season is always a reconstruction project for
the Americans, but this time they're rebuilding from Ground Zero.
When the US championships were done inside the Delta Center
Saturday night, everybody was thumbing through the biography
binders to see who these people were. Trifun Zivanovic? Sarah
Hughes? Laura Handy and J. Paul Binnebose?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not since 1962, the year after the squad was wiped out
in a plane crash en route to Prague, has the US sent such an
inexperienced team to the worlds. Only six of the 16-member roster
have ever competed there, and only Kwan has come close to the
awards podium.
</P>
<P>
   Zivanovic, a 23-year-old from Los Angeles who played hockey
until he was 18, was pinching himself after finishing second to
Weiss. ``I've never been in this position before,'' exulted
Zivanovic, who never had been higher than seventh at nationals.
``I'm totally psyched.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, a 13-year-old from Great Neck, N.Y., whose father John
is a former Cornell hockey captain, was making her senior debut.
``I can't believe I'm sitting at a press table with Michelle
Kwan,'' Hughes marveled.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes never dreamed about making it to worlds. But she got a
ticket to Helsinki because 13-year-old Naomi Nari Nam, who finished
second, is too young. Hughes gets her pass because she's a world
junior medalist.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew there would be end-of-quadrennium turnover, with
champions moving on and pairs and dance couples breaking up.
</P>
<P>
   Then five-time titleist Todd Eldredge took the amateur season
off. Kyoko Ina-Jason Dungjen and Jessica Joseph-Charles Butler, the
top returning pair and dance couple, went pfffft. Four-time
medalist Nicole Bobek pulled out because of endometriosis. Anyone
want a week in Finland?
</P>
<P>
   The men's and women's champions here were completely
predictable. Kwan breezed to her third title in four years, which
no woman had done since Jill Trenary nearly a decade ago.
``Everyone predicted I wouldn't be here,'' said Kwan, who'll start
college in the fall but plans to keep competing. ``Well, I'm here _
and I won.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, believed to be the first father to win the men's title
since Roger Turner in the '30s, inherited Eldredge's crown after
two years as runner-up. ``A lot of international judges take you
more seriously,'' mused Weiss, ``when they see the national title
under your name.''
</P>
<P>
   How seriously the judges will take the new pairs and dance
champions is another matter. Danielle and Steve Hartsell, the
youngest US pair (at 18 and 21) since Melissa and Mark Militano in
1973, literally were the only entry to stand up in the free skate.
And Naomi Lang and Peter Tchernyshev topped a dance event that had
only eight entries _ and none of the men among the top three
finishers are US citizens.
</P>
<P>
   So unless Weiss can elbow his way past a group that includes two
world titlists (Alexei Yagudin and Elvis Stojko), an Olympic gold
medalist (Alexei Urmanov), and a global medalist (Evgeni
Plushenko), it'll be up to Kwan to prevent the first star-spangled
wash-out since 1994. She'd better button up her overcoat, wear a
surgical mask, and megadose on vitamin C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
