<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WOMEN KICK OFF AGAINST DENMARK 
</HEADLINE>
 WORLD CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ FIFA president Sepp Blatter predicted Sunday that ``the
future of football is feminine'' during the draw for the third
Women's World Cup. If so, the tournament, scheduled June 19-July 10
at seven United States sites, will be a milestone event.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 tickets have been sold for the tournament, and
the championship match is expected to be sold out at the Rose Bowl
in Pasadena, Calif., making this the most popular women's sporting
event ever.
</P>
<P>
   The US will kick off against Denmark at 3 p.m. Saturday, June
19, at Giants Stadium. US coach Tony DiCicco called Group A the
``unknown group'' because of Nigeria, the Americans' foe June 24 in
Chicago, and North Korea, their opponent June 27 at Foxboro
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is mystery about many of the teams, since the
women's sport is in the early stages of development. Only China and
Norway have rivaled the US in previous tournaments. The US won the
first Women's World Cup in China in 1991, the Norwegians prevailed
in 1995 in Sweden, and the US captured the first Olympic women's
event in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   What is known is that if the Americans qualify for the second
round, their opponent will be difficult, since the US would meet a
Group B team _ Germany, Brazil, Italy, or Mexico _ at Jack Kent
Cooke Stadium July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Foxboro Stadium will host doubleheaders involving
Australia-Ghana and Norway-Russia June 20, and Mexico-Italy and
US-North Korea June 27; and a semifinal match, which will be part
of a Revolution-MetroStars doubleheader July 4.
</P>
<P>
   Teams likely will choose training sites in the area of their
opening match. Norway, which twice has defeated the US in
exhibitions in the Boston area, likely will set up its camp in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Per-Mathias Hogmo said Norway is developing ``a new
generation'' of players. The Norwegians are led by captain Linda
Medalen, now a defender, the nation's all-time leading scorer with
61 goals, and striker Marianne Pettersen.
</P>
<P>
   Norway gave the US its only defeat of 1998, a 4-1 decision at
the Algarve Cup in Portugal as Pettersen scored twice. The US edged
the Norwegians, 2-1, in the first Women's World Cup final and
Norway eliminated the US, 1-0, in the 1995 semifinals before
blanking Germany, 2-0, in the title match.
</P>
<P>
   Since the defending champion does not automatically qualify for
the finals, Norway was placed in European qualifying, and had to
rally with victories over Germany and England in its final two
matches. Ragnild Gulbrandsen scored twice in the 3-2 victory over
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The draw prevents the US and Norway from meeting until the final
day of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The US was 22-1-2 in 1998 and is 9-1-1 in World Cup finals play.
The US began the 1995 finals with a 3-3 draw against China as
Michelle Akers was injured in an early collision.
</P>
<P>
   Akers was injured early in Sunday night's US-FIFA World
All-Stars game in San Jose, Calif., while contesting a cross with
Medalen. The World All-Star team won, 2-1, on goals by Canada's
Charmaine Hooper.
</P>
<P>
   The US has the most experienced team in the world, with seven
players with more than 100 international appearances. Julie Foudy,
who scored for the US Sunday night, leads the midfield. The top
scoring threats are Akers, Mia Hamm, and Kristine Lilly, and
goalkeeper Briana Scurry guides defenders Brandi Chastain, Lorrie
Fair, captain Carla Overbeck, and Kate Sobrero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 0217EST &QL; 
