<HEADER>
A5507 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAIPAN-APPAREL-SFCHRO     02-15 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIPAN-APPAREL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PRESSURE MOUNTS ON APPAREL INDUSTRY IN SAIPAN  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAIPAN, Northern Mariana Islands _ Last month, some of America's
biggest clothing companies were caught with their pants _ and
shirts and dresses _ down by a sudden public-relations nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   A breaking scandal over rampant labor abuses on this tiny
Pacific island cast a pall over the publicity-conscious companies,
which spend billions each year on advertising to create a glamorous
image.
</P>
<P>
   A $1 billion series of class-action lawsuits against the
clothing firms was the newest gambit in a corporate reform movement
stretching from the nation's streets and college campuses to
Fortune 500 boardrooms.
</P>
<P>
   At stake in Saipan and elsewhere is the creation of a 21st
century rule book for U.S. industries, such as apparel, that have
moved much of their domestic production to low-wage havens
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than seeking reform through government regulation, this
new movement emphasizes consumer pressure and boardroom lobbying to
create ``codes of conduct'' barring labor and environmental abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Even governments are starting to act as informed consumers. In
San Francisco and elsewhere, local governments are using their
power as purchaser and investor to press corporations to end
sweatshop practices and old-growth logging. Institutions such as
the University of California are joining in.
</P>
<P>
   The movement is deeply divided over goals and tactics. Many of
its leaders are from the Bay Area, ranging from companies such as
Levi Strauss Co. and private-sector alliances such as Business for
Social Responsibility to liberal activist groups such as Global
Exchange and lawmakers such as Rep. George Miller, D-Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were filed in California and federal courts by
Global Exchange, two other groups and a labor union. The suits
charged The Gap, Gymboree of Burlingame, Tommy Hilfiger, J. Crew,
Nordstrom, Sears and nine other apparel corporations, along with
their Saipan contractors, of creating a system of indentured
servitude on U.S. soil to avoid $200 million in annual customs
duties.
</P>
<P>
   But compared with garment factories in neighboring Asian
countries, which churn out billions of dollars of clothing each
year for the U.S. market, Saipan's manufacturers are would-be
reformers.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the Saipan garment makers adopted a voluntary set
of rules to prevent labor abuses. The code of conduct was based on
the Apparel Industry Partnership, a landmark agreement sponsored by
the White House and signed in 1997 by leading apparel corporations,
human-rights groups and labor unions. The Saipan plan requires
local clothing factories to respect labor rights and safety
standards and to open their plants for regular inspection by
independent monitors.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Saipan contractors quickly found, declarations of
goodwill often are too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Miller and the Clinton administration renewed a
campaign to remove Saipan's longtime exemption from federal minimum
wage, immigration and customs laws. And after the class-action
lawsuit was filed, several large apparel corporations _ jittery
from the bad publicity and the push from Washington _ canceled or
reduced their contracts on the island.
</P>
<P>
   The Saipan Garment Manufacturers Association, which represents
the island's 33 garment makers, tried in vain to head off the
pressure by suspending two of its member factories after the U.S.
Department of Labor found them liable for an array of labor abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Charron, chairman and chief executive officer of Liz
Claiborne Inc., flew to Saipan last week to warn that the island
``could be a ghost town'' unless sweatshop abuses are eradicated.
</P>
<P>
   Charron urged Saipan's garment contractors, which provide about
10 percent of his company's global production, to speed up
enforcement of their code of conduct. ``If we take action now, we
can be an example to the rest of the world and remove the cloud
hanging over Saipan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, for Liz Claiborne, like many corporations that have
adopted codes of conduct, reform doesn't necessarily mean pay
raises.
</P>
<P>
   Charron urged Saipan's contractors and government officials to
fight attempts to end the island's exemption from federal minimum
wage. If the local minimum wage of $3.05 is raised to the federal
level of $5.15 per hour, he said, ``it begins to price (Saipan's
garment industry) out of the competitive global economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The garment industry is one of America's most globalized and
hyper-competitive sectors. Many apparel corporations manufacture
little or none of their clothes, instead contracting out the work
to firms in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 percent of men's apparel and 60 percent of women's
apparel sold in the United States is imported, mostly from
low-wage, developing nations. For example, the Gap and Levi Strauss
each have their garments produced by more than 1,000 contractors in
several dozen nations simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, several scandals have linked major corporations
_ clothing brands such as the Gap, Kathie Lee Gifford and Nike, and
coffee outlets such as Starbucks _ to child labor and horrific
sweatshop abuses by their contractors.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, these firms and dozens of Fortune 500 corporations
have created and adopted their own codes of conduct banning labor
abuses, and the Clinton administration has spearheaded the Apparel
Industry Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many economic reasons why companies have adopted
codes of conduct, but helping prevent bad publicity like this
Saipan controversy is clearly a motivator,'' said Aron Cramer, vice
president of Business for Social Responsibility, a San
Francisco-based corporate coalition of Fortune 500 giants and
smaller firms that has taken a key role in the Apparel Industry
Partnership and is advising the Saipan garment manufacturers on
implementation of their reform plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporations are realizing that socially responsible business
practices have real bottom-line benefits'' such as improved quality
control and higher worker motivation, Cramer said.
</P>
<P>
   But many industry leaders say that despite the economic benefits
of reform, sweatshop-style cost-cutting remains more profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a shark-feeding frenzy in this industry in the past
30 years,'' said Paul Gill, executive director of Made By the Bay,
a San Francisco-based coalition of garment factory owners, labor
unions and government that is trying to help the Bay Area's apparel
industry _ with 20,000 local manufacturing jobs _ survive against
foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``As trade barriers go down, work gets sent overseas and the
cost of labor becomes the variable. So abuses become all too
common, and that's what we're competing against,'' Gill said.
</P>
<P>
   Codes of conduct are a great idea, most observers agree. The
only problem is that almost no one agrees on what they should cover
or how they should be enforced. For example, disagreement is
widespread over whether codes should require corporations to do the
following:
</P>
<P>
   --Publicly disclose the identities and locations of all their
contractors. No codes do.
</P>
<P>
   --Ensure freedom of organization for workers, even in nations
such as China where the government bans independent unions and
jails their leaders. Most codes don't.
</P>
<P>
   --Require contractors to pay the nation's prevailing
garment-industry wage or a higher ``living wage'' _ a level defined
as covering the total basic needs of an average-size family,
divided by the average numbers of wage earners in a family. Most
codes require only the prevailing wage.
</P>
<P>
   --Require contractors on Saipan to prohibit their labor
recruiters in China, the Philippines, Bangladesh and other nations
from charging workers exorbitant recruitment fees, effectively
creating a system of indentured servitude in Saipan. (No overseas
locations have a similar system.) No codes do.
</P>
<P>
   Between the high-sounding rhetoric and the dog-eat-dog
international competition, there is often little room for
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   In Saipan, industry leaders say consumers had better take what
they get and not demand too much from a fashion label.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working conditions here are far better than in any of the
countries we compete with,'' said Richard Pierce, executive
director of the Saipan Garment Manufacturers' Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the apparel companies leave Saipan because of this bad
publicity, they'll just go to Mexico or China. Now tell me, would
that make things better?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 0338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 03:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETFILES-SFCHRON-NETF     02-15 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - NET FILES  
 THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ  &HT;     Amazon _ Read at Your Own Risk 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Amazon.com misled the public and paid the price with a public
relations shellacking. But did it commit an unpardonable sin on the
wild, wild Web, where the lines between advertising and editorial
content are frequently fuzzy? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   To one degree or another, most commercial Web sites intersperse
paid ads with news, feature stories and opinion pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, e-commerce giant Amazon.com admitted that it charges
book publishers for premium placement of certain recommendations on
its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   While a lot of people interpreted that as charging advertisers
for positive reviews, Amazon says it doesn't cross that line.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; You be the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing visitors encounter when they enter Amazon.com is
a feature titled, ``What We're Reading,'' that features books
selected by its staff reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon insists that an advertiser cannot pay to have its book
recommended in this section though it can pay to have it placed
prominently or for an extended period of time.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity storm prompted Amazon to adopt a new policy:
Beginning in March, it will identify which featured placements have
been paid for and which haven't. The Seattle company also offered a
full refund to anyone who bought a book that was recommended on the
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Amazon incident gave the company a black eye and temporarily
could bruise e-commerce sales. But the real issue is this: Who
should be responsible for differentiating between editorial and
advertising content on the Web _ the site operator or the consumer?
Experts are divided over the question.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Online vendors _ not consumers _ should be responsible for
clearly identifying what is editorial content and what is paid,
says Paul Grabowicz, coordinator of the New Media program in the
Graduate School of Journalism at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you charge (for placement of) recommendations and claim
they're objective, that creates a credibility gap between you and
your customers,'' Grabowicz said. ``You have to come clean, or it
blows up. Hopefully, (the Amazon disclosure) will get others in
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Or will it?
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Vanderbilt, who tracks e-commerce for Jupiter
Communications in New York, argues that Amazon.com is a classic
merchandiser that is simply abiding by well-established retail
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no coincidence that Budweiser gets an end (display) in a
grocery store instead of Miller. That's because they paid for it,''
Vanderbilt says.
</P>
<P>
   Grocery stores don't place a sign on their end displays saying
that Bud paid for the space. So why should Amazon?
</P>
<P>
   ``If consumers don't understand the same thing is happening
online, then they're being foolish,'' Vanderbilt adds. ``Like
brick-and-mortar booksellers, Amazon.com and others are not
promoting certain titles out of the editorial kindness of their
hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   A major difference between the Web and traditional media is that
retailers usually don't own newspapers or magazines or TV stations.
Through years of experience with these media, consumers usually
know what is an ad and what is independent news and opinion. No one
would ever confuse a Target store and Time magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But many retailers do own their own Web sites and create them to
look a lot like online newspapers and magazines. The rules _ for ad
placement and disclosure _ still are being written.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, ``clearly, it is up to consumers to take
responsibility because there is no government authority over the
Net. They need to embrace self discipline,'' agreed Bob Rucker, a
former CNN correspondent and journalism professor at San Jose State
University.
</P>
<P>
   Rucker said he looks at hundreds of commercial Web sites but
can't remember any that clearly differentiate between editorial
content and sales pitches. ``That's probably by design,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One exception is BabyCenter.com. The San Francisco Web site says
it provides ``guidance and gear for expectant parents'' and has
stories on topics such as twins and toilet training.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of its site is a section labeled, ``Featured Areas
from Our Sponsors,'' that includes about a dozen articles such as
``A Safer Ride brought to you by General Motors'' and ``College
Savings brought to you by Charles Schwab.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is to never violate the trust of our readers,''
BabyCenter CEO Matt Glickman said. ``It's easy to be tempted to
cash in in the short term, which is what happened to Amazon, but it
undermines the long-term credibility you're trying to build with
customers. We will accept money for ad placements, and we will make
that clear to our users.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has adopted a hands-off policy toward
the Internet, encouraging self regulation that so far has put few
limits on what and how things are sold online. Although that has
fueled an explosion in e-commerce sales and helped the overall
economy, it also has led to many misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as online retailers are under the gun to sell ads to
survive, don't expect the rest of the industry to turn virtuous
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE FORGOTTEN &QL; 
When you're a fledgling startup in the go-go Internet industry,
forget about trifling details like sales, profits and long-range
plans. The cardinal rule is: Cash in with a jaw-dropping stock
offering while the market is hot.
</P>
<P>
   Before there was an eBay, industry wags were drooling over
Marimba, which once was touted as the Next Big Thing on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, however, the onetime ``push'' company has yet
to cash in. Kim Polese, the Marimba CEO who once graced the pages
of Time magazine, has all but vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes word that Marimba is preparing an initial public
offering for the spring. Company officials aren't talking.
</P>
<P>
   Marimba has spent the past year trying to distance itself from
push technology, which broadcasts custom-tailored information over
the Internet directly to a PC.
</P>
<P>
   The Menlo Park company has repositioned its products and now
distributes software updates and content over corporate networks.
It boasts more than 800 customers, including Federal Express and
Ford Motor.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't pull off an IPO soon, however, it runs the risk of
gaining an asterisk in Internet history as one of the biggest
busts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BLACK HISTORY MONTH &QL; 
February commemorates the people, places and events that shaped
African American history. Among the notable Web sites on the topic,
several bear viewing:  &LR; harlem.eb.com &LR;  explores black culture in
1920s New York, and  &LR; www.imdb.com &LR;  celebrates contributions to the
silver screen, including the groundbreaking ``Sweet, Sweetback's
Baadasssss Song'' (1971) and Oscar-winning ``When We Were Kings''
(1996). For an illuminating look at the underground railroad that
ushered slaves to freedom, check out  &LR; www.nationalgeographic.com &LR; 
 &LR; /railroad &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Warning: The following is not for the squeamish. Only would-be
medical students and mad scientists need apply at  &LR; www.pathguy.com &LR; 
 &LR; /autopsy.htm &LR;  and  &LR; www.lacoroner.com &LR;  for ghoulish delights.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
