 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2520 - February 15, 1999   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2520 -- Feb. 15, 1999 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. LEARNING TO FORECAST THE MYSTERIOUS EL NINO El Nino helped
make 1998 the hottest year ever recorded. Its dramatic weather
changes have been linked to an upsurge of diseases such as cholera,
malaria and dengue fever around the globe, as well as a brutal
drought in Texas, wildfires in Indonesia and Brazil, marine mammal
deaths in the western Pacific and a host of other woes. Scientists
are hard at work trying to improve their ability to predict El Nino
so we can prepare for the extremes of weather. Meanwhile, there is
speculation that global warming may be compounding El Nino's
effect. By Carl Zimmer. From Discover magazine. 1,000 words +
photos. 2. DEAD IN THE WATER Two dozen Pakistani sailors aboard the
Delta Pride have been abandoned in the Gulf of Mexico for more than
six months. The merchant marine, even now the lifeblood of
international commerce, is still a hazardous calling. By Thomas
Hackett. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (3,500
words) and edited article available. 3. EXPERIMENTAL TREATMENT
SHOWS PROMISE FOR CHILDHOOD ARTHRITIS Rheumatoid arthritis is an
auto-immune disease that affects millions of people worldwide. It
occurs when, for unknown reasons, a person's immune cells begin to
attack their joints. In many cases, the disease causes severe
disability. In a new study, Dutch researchers report they have been
able to curb the autoimmune attack in four children with a severe
form of childhood arthritis that could not be controlled with drugs
by giving the children bone marrow transplants. By Michael
McCarthy. The Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
KOSOVO GIMMICKS, NOT THREATS, MAY BUY TIME The new element in the
Kosovo talks now going on at Rambouillet near Paris was underlined
by President Jacques Chirac in his formal welcoming speech. It is
that Europe can no longer tolerate war on its continent. By Flora
Lewis. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
CREATING COLETTE In our time, when authors and biographers debate
the morality of plundering other peoples' lives, it is a guilty
pleasure to plunge into a world where everyone's life was fair
game. No sooner was a liaison begun or ended than it appeared
thinly disguised in a gossip column, humorous essay or novel. No
writer has plundered her own life and the lives of those around her
so successfully as the French writer Colette. The first volume of a
biography of Colette effectively destroys the old myth that she was
an innocent, inexperienced girl from Burgundy exploited by a
no-talent husband 13 years her senior who locked her in her room to
write and published the ``Claudine'' novels under his name. Julie
Martin reviews ``Creating Colette'' by Claude Francis and Fernande
Gontier. From The New York Times Book Review. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
From New York Times Science Times :
</P>
<P>
   A. Despite Misgivings, Herbal Medicine Flourishes Herbal
medicine, the mainstay of therapeutics for centuries before modern
purified drugs relegated it to the status of near-quackery, has in
the last five years emerged from the fringes of health care with an
astonishing flourish and now shows clear signs of joining the
medical mainstream. By Jane E. Brody. 3,000 words + graphic.
</P>
<P>
   B. In Nepal, Arranged Marriage Gives Way to Courtship by Missive
In an isolated village in Nepal, ancient traditions are changing --
foremost among them, the ritual of courtship. Young people are now
writing love letters, for a reason. The practice of parental
matchmaking is being abandoned, and in its place come love letters
that reach out to grab the future. By Erica Goode. 1,300 words. 7.
ON THE LATIN EMPIRE Frangoise Waquet has written a cultural history
of Latin in the modern era. She looks at why Latin continued to
play a key role in the education of elites at a time when it had
ceased to be professionally useful. The practice of Latin became
not only a criterion of exclusion for women, who were regarded as
``illiterate'' since, with very few exceptions, Latin was omitted
from their education, but also an instrument of domination over
peoples. Latin was a vehicle not only of ostentation and authority,
but of ``forbidden'' knowledge. As Gustave Flaubert put it:
``Beware of quotations in Latin; they always conceal something
risqui.'' By Roger Chartier. Le Monde. 1,500 words. (English
translation available.)
</P>
