<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-BASEBALL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENOUGH OF IMPEACHMENT, IT'S TIME FOR SOMETHING CRUCIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The end of the Clinton impeachment trial, which did not begin
with a bang and has not ended with a whimper, means we finally can
get on to something more important. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For you that may mean the Academy Awards or how to make up to
your sweetheart for buying her an ironing board for Valentine's
Day. My focus will be more substantial. I intend to revel in the
opening of baseball spring training. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the pitchers and catchers show up and begin to work
out muscles made sore by a winter of punching adding machines to
keep track of their money, it's time to think about the evolving
language of our national pastime. For there's no question that it's
changing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When I was a boy listening to the likes of Jack Brickhouse
broadcast Chicago Cubs' games, I heard about fastballs and curves.
It was not until I was well along in my own young-adult baseball
ineptitude that sliders first came to my attention. Later, I
learned about slurves, a term now almost as extinct as bunts by a
clean-up hitters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays the language of pitching has become even more technical
and abstruse. We hear, for instance, about cut fastballs and
four-seam fastballs and circle change-ups and other bizarre
deliveries whose meaning is, quite simply, beyond my ability to
grasp. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's as if the people who invent the recondite language of
high-tech systems analysis have bled the stifling complexity of
their enterprise onto the baseball diamond. My-oh-my-oh-my. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for us I know a man who can help us through this maddening
morass. The mortal Paul Dickson, who began watching major league
baseball as a child in 1946 at Yankee Stadium, has just published a
revised edition of a baseball word book he first released 10 years
ago. This is ``The New Dickson Baseball Dictionary,'' and its
(arguably impossible) task is to offer a compendium of terms used
in baseball along with a guess as to their meaning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This new edition, as Dickson says, acknowledges that ``the game
has continued to change, occasioning the need for terms like `wild
card,' `realignment,' `Executive Council,' `interleague play' and
`acting commissioner.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One helpful thing about Dickson's collection is that now and
then he helps us see how and when the evolution of baseball's
jargon occurred. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, under the entry ``hit for the cycle'' _ which
means a batter in one game has singled, doubled, tripled and
homered (though not necessarily in that order) _ Dickson quotes
slugger Dave Kingman after he accomplished this rare feat in 1972:
``When Chris Speier mentioned it to me in the dugout, I didn't know
what it meant. I had never done it, and I had never even heard of
it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the same entry, we learn the wonderful story that former
umpire Ron Luciano told about Lou Piniella, whom Luciano described
as the worst baserunner in history: ``He ran for the cycle. In a
single game he managed to get himself thrown out at every base.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There also are lots of references in Dickson's book to the
changing financial realities of major league baseball. For
instance, there's an entry for ``small market club,'' meaning a
low-revenue team in a relatively thinly populated area, such as the
Kansas City Royals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the real surprise of the new book is that this is not found
among the meanings of ``foul ball'': First pitch thrown out by a
disgraced president. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
