<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN17-COX     02-15 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Wounded and enraged, Clinton-zilla lurches left!
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a delicious new thrill running through conservatives,
who sometimes seem to like nothing more than scaring themselves
with lurid frights. This one has President Clinton veering to the
far left after escaping the impeachment posse.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario figures that the president owes his survival to the
Democratic Party's base, which is defined by conservatives as
left-wing, and so must now do whatever the Democratic left wants.
There are a couple of things amiss with this.
</P>
<P>
   One is that the GOP right has spent six years denouncing Clinton
as a crazed left-winger already. His first budget was going to
bankrupt the country and make bag ladies out of stock-club ladies.
Actually, it boosted bag ladies into the market. His national
health care plan was going to ``socialize'' medicine. Instead, the
private sector is socializing it through HMOs. Some leftism.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in order to have their scare, conservatives have to recast
Clinton as moderate after all, so they can fear his leftward turn.
Awkward.
</P>
<P>
   A somewhat larger problem is the simple fact that there is no
left-wing in this country. (Keep that to yourself. Talk radio
couldn't stand the shock.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Democratic left''? What on Earth would that be? It turns out,
upon inspection, to be folks who want to raise the minimum wage,
think well of Social Security and fret, almost always futilely,
that the rich-poor gap in this country leaves some of our people
living in a sort of in-house Third World.
</P>
<P>
   For a left wing, we have only environmental groups that may
feather toward the fringe at their edges but in the main reflect a
national consensus; Planned Parenthood, whose support of lawful
abortion mirrors majority opinion; the American Civil Liberties
Union, a zealot about the Constitution; outfits like People for the
American Way, keen for anything even vaguely liberal but
particularly vivacious on behalf of church-state separation, as
were our Founding Fathers.
</P>
<P>
   And that hoary bugaboo, the AFL-CIO, although unions go back
more than a century and are as often conservative _ currently, for
instance, in fighting free trade _ as liberal. And maybe
gun-control advocates, who hold _ again as the Founders did, most
citizens do and as the courts always have _ that the Second
Amendment isn't absolute.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, radical characters from left to right,
from ranters like Louis Farrakhan to the woodsy militia creeps, but
neither fringe has standing in either party.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in the late '60s and early '70s were benumbed by their
outres _ Animal-Rights Hysterics for Free Love and Unilateral
Disarmament, or some such. They paid a political price. Now it is
Republicans' turn, as their party cozies with would-be theocrats
and loopy divines. The Rev. Jerry Falwell has it that one of kid
TV's ``Teletubbies'' is a gay stalker. The GOP is beginning to pay,
too.
</P>
<P>
   As ever, the natural gravity of American politics still pulls
toward the middle. Bill Clinton _ the ol' triangulator, splitter of
all differences _ is of all people almost laughable as a looming
left-wing bogeyman.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
