<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MARDI-GRAS-REVIEW-N     02-15 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MARDI-GRAS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CHICKENS IN A POT? NO, MARDI GRAS FOR EVERYONE! 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(bl) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Ron Kelly would probably be depressed by the
impeachment trial of President Clinton if he did not have a parade
to go to. He would probably be troubled by last week's denouement,
or mad about shameless partisan politics, if he were not so busy
trying to snag some beads.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we worry about that when we're trying to figure what
day the parade is, and what time it starts, and what the route is,
and, when it's all over, who's gonna be making the gumbo,'' said
Kelly, 32, a valet at the Pontchartrain Hotel here who, like most
everybody else, is consumed with Carnival, the robust countdown to
Mardi Gras on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the country can march in step to the funeral
procession of its own national spirit, fretting, cursing and
wondering, now that all the salaciousness has been wrung out of the
Monica Lewinsky affair, whether there is nothing left but shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not us; we got a party to worry about,'' Kelly said. ``We'll
worry about Clinton on Ash Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if Mardi Gras, the last pagan rout before the
abstinence of Lent, were not unique to New Orleans and places like
Mobile, Ala., and Galveston, Texas, where the celebrations are
smaller? What if, in the midst of all the embarrassment, anger and
creeping numbness caused by the Clinton scandal, the whole country
put on a feathered mask, draped some worthless beads around its
neck and, as one New Orleans band sings, ``party till the money run
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even a hangover would be better than what we're going
through,'' said Dan T. Carter, a historian at Emory University in
Atlanta and author of ``The Politics of Rage'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
1995), about the late Alabama Gov. George Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   What if the notion consuming talk down at the health club was
not the constant claims by Republican lawmakers that they are only
doing what's best for the country but who would be crowned King of
the Zulus? What if, instead of watching Democrats on CNN still
quibbling over exactly what sexual relations are _ people in New
Orleans know _ all some folks really cared about was the ball or
showering the crowd with glittering doubloons. While elsewhere
pundits were analyzing the 50-to-50 vote on the second article of
impeachment, crowds were gathering on Bourbon Street to watch women
flash their breasts in exchange for cheap plastic beads.
</P>
<P>
   What if America just threw down, as they say here, and had a big
ol' wooly Carnival?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need it,'' said Kirk Strang, a lawyer from Madison, Wis.,
who will soak up Carnival until Monday, and then, loaded down with
beads and King Cakes, fly home to Wisconsin where the Carnival
tradition has been going on for years.
</P>
<P>
   If Cheeseheads can eat crawfish, oysters and jambalaya and wash
it all down with liquid Hurricanes, why can't everybody?
</P>
<P>
   Mardi Gras is not simply parades and drunken revelry but a
sequined, satin cloak that settles over this old city's shoulders
around this time every year. People with a lot of money and people
with just a little bit join secret societies and attend masked
balls, put on sometimes lavish, sometimes skimpy parades, and crown
each other King This and Queen That. Men wear tights.
</P>
<P>
   There is still crime, poverty, potholes and late car payments
here. There is still the Lewinsky affair and all that it implies.
Just nobody gives a damn. With no such distractions, the rest of
the country languishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need it,'' Carter said. ``We need to cut loose and yell and
shout, `Throw me somethin', mister.'''
</P>
<P>
   What if, say, Atlanta had Carnival? Atlanta could use one. The
night before its Falcons were to play Denver in the Super Bowl, a
star player was arrested for trying to solicit a prostitute on
Miami's Biscayne Boulevard. Later, after Denver beat the Falcons
like an ugly red-headed stepchild, another player was charged with
laundering money for a drug dealer. Then, in the wake of the
accusation that Salt Lake City bought the 2002 Winter Games,
leaders of Atlanta's own bid for the 1996 Olympic Summer Games had
to explain their own lavish treatment of Olympic dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   What if New York had one? Or even Washington?
</P>
<P>
   Mardi Gras in America's political epicenter might be asking too
much, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea, but I just don't think it would
work,'' he said. ``You'd have to tie some of those people down and
pour the booze in them with a funnel, to get them to loosen up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
