<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-VINCE-GILL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO BASICS: VINCE GILL LOOKS FOR HIS COUNTRY ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of country singer Vince Gill. 
 By BETH TORROLL  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He may be the poster boy for today's emerging traditional
country music, but don't say it to Vince Gill's face.
 &HT;    The singer/songwriter, whose personal artistic style has run the
gamut from bluegrass to country/pop, looked back to his country
roots for his latest studio album, ``The Key'' (1998), a salute to
the style of classic country.
 &HT;    But Gill insists that he recorded this particular set of songs
for himself, not intending to lead any parade back to what he
interprets country music to be.
 &HT;    ``It's really a very traditional country record, what I find
country music is to me,'' he says. ``I don't think what is on the
majority of country radio these days is country music. I don't say
that with my fingers crossed behind my back, because I've made a
lot of records that I don't think are country music.''
 &HT;    Certainly Gill has recorded more than a few songs that have
riled the country-music establishment, building his career on the
emotional pop/country ballad alongside his trademark,
sometimes-giddy uptempo numbers, featuring Gill's crystal-clear,
high-tenor voice and masterful guitar work.
 &HT;    Gill is a pretty casual guy, with a passion for fast food, a
quick wit and a mean golf game. He is what he is with no apologies,
he says, and when he hears something in his head, he goes with it.
This time around it was a classic-country voice that he heard, so
that's what he recorded.
 &HT;    It's no wonder that the sad sound of classic country came
naturally to Gill, because his year leading up to the August 1998
release of ``The Key'' was a rough one. His divorce from wife Janis
Gill, herself a performer with Sweethearts of the Rodeo, was
compounded by the loss of his father, Stan Gill, to cancer.
 &HT;    Together, the two blows rocked Gill's emotional foundation,
driving him from the stage for a nine-month rest in 1997 and early
1998. During this time, he continued to write, record, golf, spend
time with Jenny, his teen-age daughter, staying close to his
Nashville home much of the time.
 &HT;    ``I don't know that I did a lot of soul searching or did a lot
of in-depth looking at my life or any of that,'' Gill says. ``I'm
not that deep.''
 &HT;    But the loss of his father caused the singer to reflect on the
songs he was raised on, classic country that helped to shape the
tone of ``The Key.''
 &HT;    ``Me losing my dad made me remember old songs,'' the 41-year-old
musician recalls. ``It made me really remember what I love about
country music. It's not me trying to say, `OK, country music has
gone way too far' _ that was not the exercise of this record in the
least.
 &HT;    ``All it was is me missing, personally, that style of country
music. I missed recording it, and I wanted to make a record that
never strayed from it.''
 &HT;    Not only did Gill's father inspire the tone of the project, but
his lessons inspired the singer to write a particularly emotional
song for the album.
 &HT;    ``The most poignant song, to me, is the song about my father
that I wrote called `The Key To Life,''' he says. ``That one is
really the heart-on-the-sleeve of the songs.''
 &HT;    An Oklahoma native, Gill began in bluegrass as a member of the
Bluegrass Alliance and Byron Berline's Sundance. He branched out in
1979 as the lead singer for the pop/country group Pure Prairie
League, rendering lead vocals on several hits, including ``Let Me
Love You Tonight.''
 &HT;    The young musician spent most of the 1980s as a sideman, joining
Rodney Crowell's Cherry Bombs and touring with Emmylou Harris, as
well as singing and playing guitar on numerous Nashville
recordings.
 &HT;    He had signed his first solo recording deal, with RCA executive
Tony Brown _ formerly a Cherry Bombs piano player _ as early as
1983. But his solo career didn't lift off until he followed Brown
to MCA in 1989. ``When I Call Your Name'' (1990), a tailor-made
showcase for Gill's talents, earned a Grammy and two Academy of
Country Music awards.
 &HT;    Thereafter one hit led to another _ ``Pocket Full of Gold'' to
``Look At Us'' to ``Go Rest High on That Mountain'' to ``When I
Call Your Name'' _ and Vince Gill became a household name. Along
the way, he earned a shelf of trophies, including 11 Grammy awards,
20 BMI Songwriter awards and 17 Country Music Association awards _
more CMAs than any other performer has ever won.
 &HT;    Gill insists that popularity isn't an issue for him. He makes
music because it's in his soul, he says, and he gives the
impression that, even if his spotlight fades, he'll continue down
his own artistic path regardless, stretching and exploring.
 &HT;    So when he had to piece together ``The Key'' during a period
when his personal world was askew, Gill naturally turned to artists
who had inspired the generation before him, artists whose music had
helped form the foundation of music as he knew it.
 &HT;    ``The records of Ray Price were inspirational, but also the
record that Ray Charles made in the early '60s (``Modern Sounds In
Country and Western Music'') was a very beautiful, orchestrated way
of doing really traditional country songs. It wasn't all edgy and
up tempo and all of that, so that's where I started, that's what I
heard in my head.
 &HT;    ``I'm not trying to be retro,'' he adds. ``I'm not trying to be
anything that I haven't been. It's just inspired my music.''
 &HT;    Gill invited friends such as Patty Loveless, Faith Hill, LeAnn
Womack and Alison Krauss to sing on the album, and when ``The Key''
was released it debuted at No. 1 on Billboard's Country Albums
chart.
 &HT;    In addition to ``The Key,'' 1998 also brought ``Breath of
Heaven,'' Gill's second Christmas album, featuring a collection of
holiday standards.
 &HT;    ``That's my opportunity to step out of my country career, so to
speak,'' he says, ``and try to be Nat `King' Cole and try to be
Johnny Mathis or Bing Crosby or Frank Sinatra.''
 &HT;    The latter resonance was particularly noteworthy, because the
album was recorded on the day after Sinatra's death, at the Capitol
Records studio in Los Angeles that Sinatra made famous and with
famed arranger Patrick Williams using several of Sinatra's band
members.
 &HT;    The new year began with Gill's Jan. 30 appearance on A&AMP;E's
popular concert show, ``Live By Request.'' Next up is a major tour
that will begin March 4 at the Houston Livestock and Rodeo Show.
 &HT;    He'll even stretch his wings as a producer when new artist Sonya
Issacs releases her debut album later in the year. Producing is
more than just a lark for him, the singer adds.
 &HT;    ``It's a lot of fun,'' he says. ``Something for me to do when I
get old, instead of riding buses!''
 &HT;    Gill's turn toward the traditional side of country is no
about-face, merely a shift in emphasis for an artist who has always
leaned toward the classic sound.
 &HT;    ``I'm not out to be the new Roy Acuff,'' he says. ``I'm not out
to save the Opry. I'm not out to make a traditional record and say
`Hey, everybody, we're going too far.'
 &HT;    ``I'm just doing what I do, what moves me.''
 c.1999 Beth Torroll  
