<HEADER>
A5621 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEPATITIS-LIFEBEAT-AR     02-15 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEPATITIS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUIET STRUGGLE AGAINST HEPATITIS C
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a vertical color photo of a woman standing by an open door
with syringes and medication in the close foreground. The JPEG
image is available within minutes by e-mail. Call William Gonzalez
at 212-499-3355.) 
 By BEN STEELMAN 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call her Pat.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, she thought she had pulled her life together.
After years of heavy drinking and drug abuse, she was clean and
sober, ``and I had just met the man of my dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, mindful of her past, she asked for an AIDS test. The
results came back negative for the HIV virus, but the lab work
detected something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I had been exposed to the hepatitis C antibody, but
I was OK,'' she said. ``I wasn't actively sick from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, six months later, Pat returned to her home in Wilmington,
N.C., after a trip, ``and I was just literally struck down. I
couldn't get out of bed. I couldn't eat. I couldn't sleep. I had no
idea what was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat had become the victim of a little-known disease that is
nearing epidemic proportions. According to the National Institutes
of Health, some 4 million Americans are infected with hepatitis C,
a virus that affects the liver. Estimates of new infections each
year vary from 30,000 to 150,000 cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the trouble is, the therapies are not very good yet,''
said Dr. John W. Sanders, an infectious-disease specialist in
Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Most victims don't realize they have it. Perhaps 15 percent of
those infected clear the virus from their systems within six months
or so, according to the NIH. Most of the rest show no symptoms at
all, at least at first. Perhaps one in five develops mild symptoms,
such as fatigue or a general malaise.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Pat now remembers ``feeling tired a lot'' for a
number of years. ``I told my mom, TI feel like I have mono.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet hepatitis C _ or HCV, as doctors abbreviate it _ works
slowly and insidiously.
</P>
<P>
   After two decades or more, perhaps 20 percent of those infected
will develop cirrhosis, a scarring of the liver. HCV has replaced
chronic alcoholism as the most frequent cause of cirrhosis.
</P>
<P>
   As scar tissue replaces the normal, spongy tissue of the liver,
this organ is less able to perform its functions, such as making
key proteins or filtering the blood. Excess fluids might build up
in the abdomen, causing swelling. Internal bleeding might result.
In severe cases, ``either you have a liver transplant or you die,''
said Saunders. At least 8,000 to 10,000 people die from HCV each
year, according to federal statistics.
</P>
<P>
   HCV is also associated with hepatoma or hepatocellular carcinoma
(HCC), a form of cancer that is usually fatal. It typically appears
only after years of cirrhosis, although a tiny minority of HCV
victims may develop the cancer early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was something you had and got over,'' said Pat.
But many patients will carry the HCV virus for the rest of their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is, ``It's not a death sentence,'' said Steven
Zacks, a clinical assistant professor of medicine at the University
of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In most patients, the disease can be controlled. Yet it can be a
complex, and costly, process.
</P>
<P>
   First detected in the 1970s, HCV is unlike hepatitis A, which is
spread by human wastes in contaminated food or water. It is also
different from hepatitis B, which is more infectious and can easily
be spread by sexual contact.
</P>
<P>
   HCV is carried from victim to victim primarily by blood. At
first, hemophiliacs, kidney dialysis patients and others who had
transfusions were at risk. Since 1992, however, doctors and the Red
Cross have had a reliable test to screen for HCV. Today,
transfusions and blood donations are considered safe.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the virus is spread mainly by intravenous drug use
and the sharing of needles or by tattooing and body piercing with
unsterilized equipment. The use of internasal cocaine _
``snorting'' the drug _ also seems to be an infection route, said
Zacks. Veterans who collected tattoos as a souvenir of military
service overseas may be especially at risk, Saunders said. Health
professionals who prick themselves with infected needles can also
contract HCV. A small number of infants may get the virus before
birth if their mothers are infected.
</P>
<P>
   Data ``have been conflicting'' on the links between HCV and sex,
according to the NIH; however, the risk of giving the disease to a
monogamous sexual partner ``is thought to be minimal,'' according
to the agency's 1997 consensus statement on the disease.
Prostitutes and others who have sex frequently with different
partners may face a slightly greater risk, Saunders said.
</P>
<P>
   Drs. Willis C. Maddrey and Eugene R. Schiff, authors of a
standard manual for patients, even urge spouses to use condoms if
one of them is HCV-positive. Zacks counsels partners to seek
testing for the virus, but in the case of monogamous couples, he
thinks that condom use can be optional.
</P>
<P>
   The disease's course can be sped up by heavy alcohol
consumption. Patients with a chronic infection should not drink,
Zacks said.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis C can be worsened further if one takes acetaminophen,
an ingredient in Tylenol and other headache and cold remedies,
while drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the treatment of choice for HCV is the drug
interferon. Patients take up to three injections a week, and some
of them can give themselves the shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit like taking insulin for diabetes,'' said Saunders.
</P>
<P>
   Yet interferon has drawbacks. Only about half of the patients
treated with it will have normal liver function restored after six
months. Of these, about half will suffer a relapse within a year or
so. In other words, its effectiveness rate is only about 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration recently approved a combination
treatment of interferon injections together with Ribavarin, which
can be taken in pill form.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the treatments are expensive. A supply of
interferon can cost between $300 and $600 per month; with
Ribavarin, the cost of care can range from $1,200 to $1,500 per
month.
</P>
<P>
   HCV patients will need to revisit their doctor _ generally a
gastroenterologist or infectious disease specialist _ for regular
blood tests. One will measure alanine aminotransferase, ALT for
short, a liver enzyme. The higher the levels of ALT in the
bloodstream, the more inflamed one's liver is likely to be. Another
test measures the ``viral load,'' the amount of HCV virus in the
bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   There is hope for new drugs now in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a lot of progress in the last couple of years,''
Zacks said. ``There's a lot of potential for new drugs in the
pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, doctors focus on suppressing or reducing the virus
and delaying the onset of cirrhosis for as long as possible.
</P>
<P>
   For Pat, the disease has taken its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from being an outgoing person, always out, talking to
people, doing things constantly, to being a recluse,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She no longer has the energy to ride her bicycle or to dash off
on the cross-country road trips which she loved. The former night
owl now often goes to bed, exhausted, by 8 o'clock.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, she'll still walk past the bars and night spots she
used to like. ``But everything seems so empty, all the partying. I
want to yell at those kids, if you only knew . . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``People had better wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   The American Liver Foundation operates a hepatitis and liver
disease hotline at (800) 465-4837. The Hepatitis C Foundation of
Warminster, Pa., (800) 324-1518, and the Hep C Connection of
Denver, (800) 522-4372 coordinate networks of support groups and
offer information.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ben Steelman writes for the Wilmington, N.C., Star-News.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
