<HEADER>
A5622 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLYCHILD-LIFEBEAT-NY     02-15 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLYCHILD-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAS THERE LOVE ENOUGH FOR ANOTHER BABY?
</HEADLINE>
  By LEAH INGRAM 
 c.1999 Leah Ingram 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing up as an only child, I was determined not to have only
one child. So imagine my surprise when halfway through my second
pregnancy, I started having doubts about having another child.
</P>
<P>
   I loved my firstborn Jane, now 3, so fiercely that simply
looking at her brought tears to my eyes. How could I possible love
another child as I love Jane?
</P>
<P>
   My husband, Bill, ever the pragmatic thinker and the second of
two children, knew fully well that a parent could love both kids.
He kept telling me, ``Love isn't finite. You will be able to love
both children.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bill wasn't the one feeling ambivalent -- I was. Turns out I
wasn't alone. Ask almost any woman who is mother to more than one
child, and she'll tell you about her own, albeit fleeting, feelings
of ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   These feelings are quite normal during pregnancy, says Dr.
Monica Reed, an obstetrician and gynecologist and medical director
of the women's center at Celebration Health in Celebration, Fla. In
fact, Reed, a mother of two, shares with her patients her own
long-ago feelings of ambivalence. ``I tell my patients, 'The love I
had for my first child exceeded anything, and I was unsure I could
love a second child in the same way. I discovered that the love I
have for my second is just as great as it is for my first.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed's words of assurance probably would have fallen on deaf
ears had she told them to Andrea Hessekiel of Rye, N.Y., who says
she momentarily regretted getting pregnant again only after
daughter Sophie, now 4, was born. ``It was Sophie's second day of
life, I'd had my second C-section, and as I hobbled into the
bathroom to use the toilet, I began to cry. I said, 'What have I
done? I had this perfect life, this adorable child, and I've gone
and messed everything up,'' she recalls thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Hessekiel says she felt so intensely connected to her first
born, Kira, now 7, that she wasn't sure how she could have the same
kind of relationship with her new daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, you can't have the same relationship with your
second child as you did with your first, says Kim Dell'Angela, a
psychologist at Chicago's Loyola Medical Center, mostly because you
won't have as much time. In fact, ``time is one of a mother's
biggest concerns,'' says Hilory Wagner, author of ``And Baby Makes
Four'' (Avon Books, 1998), a book about welcoming the second baby
to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   But worrying about time management issues while you're pregnant
can cause more stress than relief. Instead, talk about your
feelings, especially with your spouse. ``If you have concerns that
your partner won't pull his share of child care with this baby,
address that before the baby gets there,'' Wagner adds. Getting
your husband involved will benefit you -- and your kids, too. If
your husband becomes the primary caregiver for one child, as my
husband did with Jane, after her sister, Anne, now 1 1/2, was born,
he may discover a newer and deeper relationship with his first
born.
</P>
<P>
   A number of factors contributed to my feelings of ambivalence.
Just weeks before I'd gotten pregnant with Anne, I'd finally lost
all my prepregnancy weight, and here I was packing on the pounds
again. I was also concerned about the already diminished time I had
with Bill. ``You need to budget your time with every one,'' says
Lillian Glass, a New York City marriage/family counselor in private
practice, and plan ways that you and your spouse can get time
alone, even if it means staying up later at night, after the kids
have gone to bed, just so you can talk uninterrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Another cause of ambivalence is the issue of going back to work,
something Dell'Angela blames on the media. ``Women are always
hearing, 'If you love your children, you'll spend more time with
them.' Or people may say to women who work outside of the home,
'Well now that you're going to have two kids, you'll be staying
home now, right?' We lump love with time,'' but time does not equal
love.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of things you can do to bid your ambivalent
feelings farewell. First, don't listen to what anyone else has to
say about your decision to have another child. ``Sometimes, it can
feel like open season on your parenting,'' says Dell'Angela. Also,
don't stress yourself out worrying that your first child will be
permanently scarred by the birth of his sibling. Instead, prepare
him for the new baby by taking him to sibling classes and reading
books about the new baby, Wagner suggests. And remember: you're
giving your child a brother or sister whom he will grow to love and
cherish. Furthermore, your younger child will benefit from the love
and companionship of his older sibling -- something your first born
did not have.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, talk to other parents about how they handle having two
children. ``You'll hear others tell you that your feelings are
normal and that you should trust that everything is going to be
OK,'' says Dell'Angela. However, if your feelings of uncertainty
about your pregnancy become so intense that you fear you might hurt
yourself or your unborn child, speak to your healthcare
practitioner immediately.
</P>
<P>
   After Anne was born, my feelings of ambivalence faded along with
the memory of labor pain. It's hard to remember how freaked out I
was about become a mother of two. The best part for me now is not
only loving two children, but seeing my daughters becoming friends
and growing to love one another.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Leah Ingram is a free-lance writer based in Ewing, N.J.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
