<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AN-ODE-TO-FRIENDS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ONLY WE COULD ALL BE `FRIENDS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jennifer Aniston, Courteney Cox and Lisa
Kudrow in a scene from ``Friends.'' 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 From TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In many ways, ``Friends'' is like a fast-and-funny soap opera:
All of the cast are attractive, all have interesting lives, great
clothes and cool apartments. And, just like on a soap, the six
``Friends'' players interact only with each other, whether on a
romantic or platonic level.
</P>
<P>
   In its sixth season, the slick formula still works. In fact,
it's propelled ``Friends'' to its highest ratings ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only real challenge now,'' deadpans David Schwimmer, who
plays Ross, ``is coming up with new hairstyles every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: It's never dull. And, if you're a fan, you
literally have to watch every week to keep up on who's sleeping
together or breaking up.
</P>
<P>
   Take this current, eventful season: Chandler (Matthew Perry) and
Monica (Courteney Cox) spent the early stages furtively trying to
hide their steamy love trysts. Rachel (Jennifer Aniston) and Ross
called it quits _ again _ prompting Ross' current midlife crisis,
while Phoebe (Lisa Kudrow) was busy playing surrogate mother to her
sister's twins. As for slow-witted Joey (Matt LeBlanc), well, he's
been occupied enough just being Joey.
</P>
<P>
   It's not often you get the entire cast of ``Friends'' to
assemble for an interview, but when it does happen, you realize
just how good-looking they are. And how levelheaded they are about
their success, as Perry demonstrates when asked about their
characters' glamorous-if-hectic lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I kind of like that Chandler is finally getting a little
less neurotic this season,'' Perry says jokingly. ``Plus he's in a
relationship with Monica _ I love that I get to kiss Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   On the breakup front, Aniston is grateful that the long,
drawn-out affair between Rachel and Ross apparently has finally
reached a finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest thing was that Rachel had the ability to let Ross
go when she finally saw what was at stake for him,'' she says. ``As
painful as that was, it was also a wonderful thing for her as a
woman in terms of self-growth and being selfless.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, it's not unusual for any of the ``Friends'' cast
to talk about their characters as if they were real people. In some
ways they are, since each performer was cast directly to type and
has varied little over five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   They may live in a fanciful sitcom world, in short, but to
Aniston there's a lot of realism in the friendships played out on
the show. For example, she doesn't see any comparison between the
soulful, supportive female relationships on ``Friends'' and those
combative, business-suit-clad babes on ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean, with girls at each other's throats?'' Aniston says
with a grimace. ``I don't think that's real life. It exists, I'm
sure, but not with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the show's creators/executive producers,
Marta Kauffman, David Crane and Kevin Bright, always planned to
keep things hopping on ``Friends.'' That explains why the story
lines bounce back and forth between the six pals in equal
proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have six characters,'' Kauffman says, ``they all have
lives of equal importance, but the variations are endless. We have
to keep pushing ourselves to keep it different, fresh and funny ...
In an odd way, these six are our children. We love them all
equally.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helps, of course, that those children are all still
extremely attractive and have collectively kept out of any
career-ending tabloid scandals. Their dating lives may occasionally
turn up in the gossip columns _ with veiled whispers of Aniston
dating Brad Pitt or Perry getting cozy with ``Party of Five'' star
Neve Campbell _ but they wear their success quite well.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, they've come a long way from the histrionics
of their first breakout season, when each went from relative
unknown to magazine covers in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first year, we got some undergarments in the mail,''
Schwimmer says sheepishly. ``Uh, a marriage proposal. That was
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The sextet nod as a group when asked if these days they're more
comfortable about going out in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all in your attitude,'' Aniston says. ``If you want to go
to the store, you go to the store. There's always going to be
someone who recognizes you. But it's not like you can't leave the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact we all live and work in Los Angeles, which is full of
actors and celebrities, makes it easier,'' he says. ``It's easier
to go to the supermarket here than if we lived somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears extremely unlikely that the show will be leaving the
Warner soundstage in Burbank for another road trip in the near
future. Last season finished with a three-episode arc that had the
entire cast _ except Kudrow, who was pregnant _ on location in
London for Ross' ultimately disastrous wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a few personal highlights, including their meeting
quasi-royal Sarah Ferguson _ a.k.a. the Duchess of York _ when she
made a cameo appearance, the trip was a one-shot deal, the actors
agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just too hard,'' Aniston says with a sigh. ``We were
exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides uprooting the cast and crew and shooting in a
different time zone,'' Kauffman adds, ``we were in a foreign
country in unfamiliar surroundings. It took a lot longer than it
would have if we did it here. That was our one time.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Friends'' forecast for the immediate future is, no
surprise, that we'll see the six stars in constant contact with
each other, no outsiders allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show always works best when we have the six of them
involved with each other,'' Kauffman says. ``When you bring someone
in from outside, it's never as successful as what we have between
them. These are the people viewers care about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, they bug us all the time to let them kiss each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Since each of the six are also contractually obligated for two
more seasons _ and each received a cool $250,000 bonus from NBC
this past Christmas _ ``Friends'' isn't going anywhere soon.
</P>
<P>
   It does pose an interesting question, though: How could you ever
pull the plug on a show with such beloved characters?
</P>
<P>
   The previously silent Kudrow speaks up: ``What ending other than
a happy one could you want for these people? Oh! A tragic fire!''
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, is there any cast member brave enough to
hazard a guess as to where the chaotic lives of Ross, Rachel,
Monica, Joey, Phoebe and Chandler will be, let's say, 10 years down
the road?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we'll all be married,'' Perry offers helpfully.
``Not to each other, you know, but married by then. We will have
each learned a lot _ and probably our hair will be even more
different.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor for TV Guide Canada, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
