<SLUG> BC-MARK-WAHLBERG-IN-THE-CORRUPTOR-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING HIS MARK: MARK WAHLBERG BIDS FOR ACTION STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Mark Wahlberg in a scene from ``The
Corruptor.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Alma Wahlberg wants to see less of her son Mark.
 &HT;    It was bad enough when he was modeling Calvin Klein underwear,
but in ``Boogie Nights'' (1997) he often wore nothing at all, and
in fact prominently displayed his ... well, his endowment for the
arts. And for the past few months the movie has been playing around
the clock on cable.
 &HT;    ``I can already hear the message on my answering machine,''
Wahlberg says. ``It will go something like, `Honey, Aunt Gertrude
saw ``Boogie Nights'' on HBO and she passed out. What are we going
to do?'''
 &HT;    Just one more complication of life post ``Boogie Nights'':
 &HT;    ``I've been very busy,'' the actor sums up. ``I get bothered.
People ask me about my private parts. A lot.''
 &HT;    The organ in question was artificial, Wahlberg adds, a fact
which he's stressed in interviews any number of times.
 &HT;    ``But just the other day a journalist asked me if it was real. I
said, `Look, ask the director.' The journalist said, `No, I'm
talking about Burt Reynolds' hair in the film.'
 &HT;    ``I was like, `Hey, I really have no idea.''' He laughs. ``Now,
that's a tough question!''
 &HT;    Wahlberg can afford to laugh. The former Marky Mark has left his
rap days behind, and finds himself suddenly famous _ if not quite
as much so as his buddy Leonardo DiCaprio, with whom he co-starred
in ``The Basketball Diaries'' (1995), certainly enough to change
his life.
 &HT;    ``Fame is such a scary proposition,'' Wahlberg says. ``I talk to
Leo about the pressure of having everyone suddenly love you. I was
in a similar situation when I first started in music ... The weird
thing is that one day you're the poster on some girl's wall, and
the next she's ripping you down to put up Marilyn Manson.
 &HT;    ``It's all about survival for me now,'' Wahlberg says. ``For me
the `Boogie Nights' years represent a time to stop dealing in the
b---sh-t and just do good work.''
 &HT;    The 27-year-old is working even now, despite appearing relaxed
in jeans and a sweater in a suite at New York's Regency Hotel. He's
there to do interviews about ``The Corruptor,'' opening March 5.
It's an action movie in which a Los Angeles police officer
(Wahlberg) with a canny Chinatown cop (Chow Yun-Fat) team up to
combat some vicious ganglords.
 &HT;    ``Chow is amazing, man,'' Wahlberg says of the legendary Hong
Kong star. ``He's a different type of action hero in this movie.''
 &HT;    Wahlberg signed on to do ``The Corruptor'' after turning down a
role _ eventually taken by Joaquin Phoenix _ in Joel Schumacher's
upcoming sleazefest, ``8 mm.''
 &HT;    ``It was a great script, but they wanted me to play Dirk Diggler
Part Two, and I couldn't do it,'' he says. ``I would have loved to
have worked with Nic Cage, but the minute I read in the cript that
my character would be introduced in a porn shop and that he knows
everything about porn and S&AMP;M, I said `Nah.' I just couldn't get up
the energy to do it.
 &HT;    ``They told me, `Kevin Costner did two baseball films.' I said,
`Yeah, but that's America's pastime. We're talking about porn here,
and I don't even like porn, man.'''
 &HT;    That same reaction almost caused him to reject ``Boogie
Nights,'' he recalls. Though such previous films as ``Renaissance
Man'' (1995), ``The Basketball Diaries'' and ``Fear'' (1997) hadn't
set the box office on fire, and he really couldn't afford to turn
down high-profile roles, he nonetheless hesitated.
 &HT;    ``When I started acting,'' he explains, ``I vowed there would be
three things I would never do in a film: sing, dance and take my
clothes off. In one film, I broke every rule.''
 &HT;    Wahlberg is used to breaking the rules, though. He grew up in
Dorchester, Mass., son of a nurse and a trucker who divorced when
Wahlberg was 11. As a child of a working single parent, the young
man had plenty of time to get into trouble, and he usually did.
 &HT;    ``Every day I had this routine: Wake up, go outside, make money,
get into something bad,'' Wahlberg recalls. ``I knew it was just a
matter of time before I would be locked up and somebody would just
throw the key away.''
 &HT;    In 1988 it happened. The 15-year-old Wahlberg did a 45-day jail
stint for assaulting a man over a bottle of beer.
 &HT;    ``It was a real wakeup call,'' he recalls. ``I convinced myself
during those 45 days that I was never coming back.''
 &HT;    At the time of his release, his brother Donnie had just become a
teen idol with the band New Kids on the Block. Inspired, Wahlberg
became the front man for his own group, Marky Mark and The Funky
Bunch.
 &HT;    Their 1991 album went platinum. And one night on stage, on a
dare, Wahlberg dropped his drawers _ and hit paydirt. He landed a
lucrative contract as the official Calvin Klein underwear model.
 &HT;    Those were raucous years for a young man who loved to cause a
stir. He loomed over Times Square on a billboard, virtually naked.
He dedicated his 1993 autobiographical photo book to his penis.
Gossip columnists buzzed about public brawls.
 &HT;    As the initial hype died down, Wahlberg reassessed his life and
decided to take control of things. He said goodbye to rap and to
modeling, and declared that Marky Mark was dead _ long live Mark
Wahlberg, the actor.
 &HT;    ``I'm not totally knocking it, but once I did those ads, I
started to feel like my voice was being taken away from me,''
Wahlberg says. ``I started to feel like I was just this body. I
knew I had to totally turn things around so I would be heard.''
 &HT;    Hollywood laughed, but Wahlberg stuck with it and, with ``Boogie
Nights,'' his efforts paid off. Now he has boxloads of scripts to
consider, and he can turn down anything which doesn't strike his
fancy.
 &HT;    Next up may be a boxing film, ``Out On My Feet.'' It's a drama
about a young man being trained by an aging boxer, a role to be
played by none other than the ``Raging Bull'' himself, Robert De
Niro.
 &HT;    Working with a Hollywood heavyweight such as De Niro was
inspiring, the younger actor says.
 &HT;    ``We're doing these fight scenes together,'' he recalls, ``and I
didn't want to hit hard. But De Niro is like, `Go, go, go, kid!' So
I had to hit him. I couldn't be scared. I had to go for it.''
 &HT;    He's also got a new album in the works _ but don't expect it to
be more of the same old thing.
 &HT;    ``Marky Mark is retired,'' he says flatly. ``I love to make
music. But as far as going out, pulling down my pants and running
around in my underwear, well, I don't think I could do that
anymore.''
 &HT;    At least not right now.
 &HT;    ``Maybe I'll do a 20th-anniversary reunion tour,'' he says
jokingly. ``I'll come out with my big beer belly, pull my pants
down and listen to the people groan.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
