<HEADER>
A5612 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENE-WILDER-IN-ALICE-     02-15 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENE-WILDER-IN-ALICE-IN-WONDERLAND-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILDER WILDER: A MORE THOUGHTFUL GENE WILDER RETURNS TO THE SMALL
SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Gene Wilder in a scene from ``Alice in
Wonderland.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He may be playing the Mock Turtle in the upcoming
television-movie version of ``Alice in Wonderland,'' but he's
mocking no one today. In fact, the comic actor Gene Wilder may be
open, talkative and friendly, but he's a distinctly serious man.
 &HT;    That's understandable, since he's know his share of unhappiness
along with the laughter, most notably the 1989 death from ovarian
cancer of his wife, comedian Gilda Radner.
 &HT;    ``My early life was a combination of sadness and hilarity,'' the
63-year-old Wilder says, relaxing on a couch at a
satellite-television studio in Manhattan. ``There was a lot of
sadness in my life. My mother was so ill, and I was told not to
ever argue with her, because it might kill her. But I was told to
make her laugh.
 &HT;    ``So there was always an underpinning of sadness around, lurking
in the shadows,'' he says. ``In my actual life, especially now, I'm
the happiest man I know.
 &HT;    ``I'm very fortunate to have found love again after Gilda died.
I'm very fortunate to live a wonderful, quiet life in the country,
to write and paint and act, really, when I want to act.''
 &HT;    For a long while, Wilder _ who starred in such memorable films
as ``Bonnie &AMP; Clyde'' (1967), ``The Producers'' (1968), ``Willy
Wonka and the Chocolate Factory'' (1971), ``Young Frankenstein''
(1974) and ``Stir Crazy'' (1980), as well as the lamentable 1995
television sitcom, ``Something Wilder'' _ simply didn't feel the
urge to act.
 &HT;    But lately he's been increasingly visible. He wrote and starred
in ``Murder in a Small Town'' (1999), a cable movie which aired on
the Arts &AMP; Entertainment Network in January, and on Feb. 28 he'll
turn up as the Mock Turtle in NBC's three-hour-long retelling of
Lewis Carroll's ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland.''
 &HT;    The special-effects-driven movie, directed by Nick Willing,
stars Tina Majorino as Alice, along with an all-star cast that
includes Whoopi Goldberg, Martin Short, Ben Kingsley and Miranda
Richardson. To play the singing, dancing and 2-inch-tall Mock
Turtle, Wilder sported shells and hair extensions, performing in
front of a blue screen and interacting only with Majorino.
 &HT;    It was a revelatory experience for the actor, who had never
liked ``Alice in Wonderland,'' either the book or the classic
Disney animated film.
 &HT;    ``I started performing at 13, and that was about the time I
became inquisitive about literature, about Dostoevski, Carroll and
Dickens,'' Wilder recalls. ``I just didn't get `Alice,' though. It
went by me _ I enjoyed some parts, but didn't understand what the
whole thing was about.
 &HT;    ``Later I understood more,'' he adds, ``but I never quite got
the meat of it, the heart and soul. And I never wanted to see the
cartoon version.
 &HT;    ``Then I received the script for the television movie last
summer,'' Wilder says, ``and I read it from beginning to end. It
was magnificent. It captured the essence of Carroll's story, and I
think I got what he was going for.
 &HT;    ``Let me put it in terms of Mock Turtle and Alice,'' he says
with a smile. ``Nick Willing told me that the fears we all have of
abandoning our childhood and venturing out into adulthood can be so
terrifying that sometimes we don't want to let go.
 &HT;    ``In Alice's case,'' he says, ``it was her fear of singing a
song in public. I related to that in a very personal way _ not
about singing, not about acting, but about getting up and speaking
to people.
 &HT;    ``I can perform before 2,500 people, but ask me to make a speech
at a banquet and it's still as hard for me as giving an oral book
report was at school,'' Wilder admits. ``I related that to Alice.''
 &HT;    In a sense, he says, the encounter between Alice and the Mock
Turtle represents a coming-of-age for Alice.
 &HT;    ``By the time she gets to Mock Turtle and the Gryphon, she can
say `This isn't right' or `I don't believe this,''' he says. ``I
put her through all kinds of tests, nudging her on to be brave, to
try singing with me. When we're done I've made her laugh and sing.
I've exposed my emotions to her, and I see that she's ready to move
on.
 &HT;    ``I tell her, `Dear, you're ready to go on,' and what I'm really
saying is that she's ready to become a woman and to let her fears
drop.''
 &HT;    Wilder is even more pleased with ``Murder in a Small Town.''
Based on its solid reviews and ratings, A&AMP;E has already
commissioned Wilder and director Joyce Chopra for a follow-up.
 &HT;    ```Murder' was everything I set out to do as a writer and an
actor,'' he says proudly. ``There was a particularly huge sense of
satisfaction at having written it.
 &HT;    ``I'm on page 70 of the next one, which won't be a sequel,'' he
adds. ``Four characters are the same, and Joyce Chopra and I are
hoping to form a repertory company of sorts, using the same actors,
even if their characters died, in different roles in the next one.
 &HT;    ``If we're lucky, we'll do one movie every 10 or 12 months.''
 &HT;    It's no accident that both ``Alice'' and ``Murder'' are
small-screen projects, or that Wilder hasn't made a theatrical film
since the abysmal ``Another You'' (1991).
 &HT;    ``The world of film has changed,'' he says matter-of-factly. ``I
took some time off, and when I came back I didn't like what I was
being offered.
 &HT;    ``At this point I don't want to do anything I don't like, don't
want to see, that I think might disappoint an audience,'' he says.
``Why do it? I'd rather wait until the bell goes off in my head.''
 &HT;    Wilder has never been a prototypical movie star, anyway. In
fact, he notes, most of the films for which he's best known
originally flopped.
 &HT;    ```The Producers' failed,'' he says. ``It was sold down the
river to television so the producer could make his money back. Now
it's a cult film.
 &HT;    ```Willy Wonka' failed at the box office,'' he continues. ```The
Frisco Kid' (1979) failed at the box office. My three favorite
films are `The Producers,' `Young Frankenstein' _ which did not
fail at the box office _ and `Frisco Kid.'
 &HT;    ```Blazing Saddles' was great fun, too, and very popular,''
Wilder adds, ``but it amazes me that two out of my favorite three
films were failures initially. Then again, so was `The Wizard of
Oz' (1939).''
 &HT;    Wilder currently lives in Connecticut with his second wife,
Karen, in a home left to him by Radner. The actor spends a good
deal of time raising funds for cancer causes, and says he often
thinks of Radner.
 &HT;    ``Her spirit is the first thing that comes to mind,'' he says
wistfully. ``She was a firefly, and if you knew her you saw that
her flame didn't go off very often.
 &HT;    ``Gilda just had a great spirit.''
 &HT;    Though he's experienced his ups and downs, the actor isn't
complaining. All in all, he thinks Jerry Silberman, the Milwaukee
boy who grew up to be Gene Wilder, would be impressed by Gene
Wilder's life and career.
 &HT;    ``If you talked about that with Jerry when he was Jerry, he'd be
tickled to death _ or tickled to life,'' Wilder says. ``He'd be
very happy.
 &HT;    ``It's scary when you want to be an actor and you're just a
little pipsqueak from Milwaukee,'' he says thoughtfully. ``You
don't know if you'll make it or not, and things like eating and
surviving don't even enter your mind.
 &HT;    ``I just wanted to get roles in plays. It may have been ignorant
intuition, but I thought that if I got parts in plays, everything
would eventually take care of itself.
 &HT;    ``And it did.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
