<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3492 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TA     02-15 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 The Week in Review  
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Secret View From the Top
</P>
<P>
   If every union member's apartment were half as nice as Gus
Bevona's penthouse atop the headquarters of the janitors' union,
class tensions would disappear. But there isn't enough marble in
the world for everyone to have such a place. Bevona, who headed New
York City's main union for janitors and doormen for 18 years,
designed the penthouse in lower Manhattan. Union dues _ $500 a year
from each of 55,000 members _ helped finance his 23rd-floor spread.
</P>
<P>
   The penthouse has green marble in its floors and wainscoting.
Thick slabs of black marble went into the conference tables and the
dressing room counters. Creamy white and grey marble climbs from
floor to ceiling in the bathrooms. There is rosewood galore _
illuminated built-in rosewood display cases, a rosewood liquor
cabinet and built-in rosewood entertainment centers. There were his
and her's bathrooms and his and her's dressing rooms (each with
three cedar closets.) There were two terraces with spectacular
views and an immense kitchen chock full of the finest German
appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Bevona's parent union, the Service Employees International
Union, got so fed up with his high salary ($450,000), princely
lifestyle and dictatorial ways, that it pushed him out of his job
two weeks ago. Until the parent union opened the penthouse last
week, union members had no idea of the treasures inside. Bevona,
who insisted that he did not use the penthouse as an apartment,
said he deserved his pay and penthouse because his members were the
nation's highest paid janitors.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVEN GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Where Jeans Are A Rape Defense
</P>
<P>
   The signs held by five female legislators in front of the
Italian Parliament read, ``Jeans, an alibi for rape.'' The women,
all wearing jeans, were protesting a decision last week by Italy's
highest appeals court that a woman's claim that she was raped must
be untrue because she had been wearing jeans.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Carmine Cristiano, a 45-year-old driving
instructor, had argued not that the jeans were provocative, but
that they were difficult to take off, and therefore the woman, an
18-year-old student, must have consented. The appeals court agreed,
overturning a 1996 verdict in which a lower court had found
Cristiano guilty and sentenced him to two years and eight months in
prison. The appeals court said it was ``common knowledge'' that
jeans ``cannot even be partly removed without the effective help of
the person wearing them,'' and that it is ``impossible, if the
victim is struggling with all her force.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision drew expressions of outrage. Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema of the Democratic Party of the Left said he was
``indignant, as a citizen.'' The female legislators pledged to
continue wearing jeans to Parliament until the decision is
reversed. Alessandra Mussolini, the granddaughter of the Fascist
dictator, who represents the conservative National Alliance in
Parliament, called the ruling ``shameful'' and said, ``Women are
already afraid to report rapes _ this just makes it worse.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN TAGLIABUE
</P>
<P>
   No Chemical Threat Found At Bombed Plant in Sudan
</P>
<P>
   More evidence emerged that raised questions about the Clinton
administration's cruise missile attack on a Sudanese pharmaceutical
plant last August. Scientists hired by lawyers for the owner of the
plant examined 13 soil, sludge and debris samples from the wrecked
factory, but found no trace of chemical weapon compounds.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the National Security Council stood by their
forensic evidence that the plant was targeted only after a soil
sample obtained clandestinely by the CIA indicated the presence of
a precursor chemical used to produce the deadly VX nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tripp on Tough Love
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tripp, the woman whose secret recordings of Monica
Lewinsky led to President Clinton's impeachment, broke a long
silence, saying in an interview that her deepest regret is the pain
she caused her former friend.
</P>
<P>
   She betrayed Ms. Lewinsky, she said, to save her from being
abused by the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always saw Monica as a kid, I always saw her as a lost
soul,'' Mrs. Tripp told The New York Times. ``I believe she and the
country will never understand that I believed this was in her best
interest, and that makes me very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DON VAN NATTA Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Push to Temper Mandatory Sentences
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter-century that drug laws requiring mandatory
sentencing have been in place in New York and other states, critics
have repeatedly denounced them as Draconian.
</P>
<P>
   Now a powerful voice has been added to that criticism, as New
York State Chief Judge Judith Kaye, proposed softening the laws to
allow judges to temper the 15-year mandatory sentences when such a
punishment seemed a ``miscarriage of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   She also suggested that those accused of possessing small
quantities could be given drug treatment, not prison _ a plan that
could keep 10,000 low-level offenders a year free. The plan, Gov.
George Pataki said, ``warrants further review.''
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City Blues
</P>
<P>
   An ethics panel working for the Salt Lake Olympic Organizing
Committee issued a scathing report about that city's desperate
campaign to win the 2002 Winter Games. Officials showered Olympic
delegates with cash and an array of gifts, from free trips to the
