<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN16-COX     02-15 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frequent fliers fume for fairness
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ One way for Congress to regain a few of
the approval points it squandered on the impeachment debacle would
be to do something about air travel. To talk to a frequent flier is
to open yourself to hair-raising tales of hardy souls braving
discomfort, dislocation and airline treatment that can border on
false imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Ron Wyden (D-Ore.) and John McCain (R-Ariz.) have taken
such action in proposing a Passenger Bill of Rights. I would give
up my aisle seat to them. The bill would force airlines to admit
when they overbook and give the real reasons they bumped you. It
would also make it easier and faster for passengers to get refunds
of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   These things are good as far as they go, but something more is
called for. We don't need a few more regulations. We need a
movement. We need a stirring document setting forth the basic
rights that Nature's God bestows on anyone with an airline ticket.
We need a real statement on passenger rights to which travelers can
rally as they storm the ticket counters and barricade themselves
behind vinyl chairs in terminal lounges.
</P>
<P>
   Something like this:
</P>
<P>
   The Passenger Bill of Rights
</P>
<P>
   Preamble: We, the airline passengers of North America, are not
animals, we are human beings. Most of us, at least. Many of us
don't want to be on your stupid ol' airplane, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   1. We have the right to the entire can of soda. Don't you try to
pour that Coke into three cups for three passengers. We demand the
cup and the rest of the can, too. With ice.
</P>
<P>
   2. We have the right to breathe air that is 20 percent oxygen.
Nothing less. Canaries in cages should be posted in conspicuous
locations so passengers can note when they keel over for lack of
breathable air.
</P>
<P>
   3. We have the right to remain silent. Don't even try to wake us
up before we land.
</P>
<P>
   4. We have the right to eat peanuts. Crackers and stale pretzels
are not valid substitutes. On long flights, mystery meat will be
provided for all carnivorous passengers.
</P>
<P>
   5. We have the right to confront ticket agents. Announcing
flight cancellations and then clearing out all employees is an
invitation to civil insurrection. Passengers are due a living,
breathing human face to yell at.
</P>
<P>
   6. We are three-dimensional beings with the right to take up
space. We may be taller than average, we may be wider than average,
we may even wear overcoats: it's not our fault. Roller coasters,
vintage spacecraft and many swing-sets have bigger seats than
today's airliners.
</P>
<P>
   7. Anyone under 6 must get a plastic pilot's-wings badge. Girls,
too. No exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   8. No airport hot dog should ever cost more than $5.00. Even
with chili on top.
</P>
<P>
   9. We have the right to bring on as many things as we can stuff
into one overhead compartment, no matter how hard we have to push
to get it all in. If the door closes, it's legal.
</P>
<P>
   10. We have the inalienable right to a decent cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   11. Detroit Airport will be razed and salt will be sown into the
soil where the terminal used to be. It is necessary as a warning to
others.
</P>
<P>
   12. We have the right to television-free sections in all
terminals, no matter what the contract with CNN says.
</P>
<P>
   13. Each terminal in a major metropolitan area shall have at
least one (1) dimly lit bar that will be open late, staffed by a
sympathetic bartender who speaks in a thick accent associated with
that airport's geographic region. On a bad trip, it might be our
only feeling having been somewhere away from home.
</P>
<P>
   14. We have the right to air-terminal phone booths with seats.
</P>
<P>
   15. Passengers stuck on the runway for long periods of time have
the right to receive mail and packages from home. International
humanitarian agencies have the right to inspect conditions.
</P>
<P>
   16. We have the right to see our suitcases again, or any parts
of them that might be handy.
</P>
<P>
   These are not outrageous requests, but throughout history,
revolutions have been founded on people's more basic expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Things are getting ugly near the baggage-claim area. And even
extra peanuts may no longer quell the angry masses.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
