<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5637 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN16-COX     02-15 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stumbling into a fine young man
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The first crash jolts me awake.
Instinctively, I open my eyes and glance at the bedside clock. It's
3:37. I lie motionless in the dark _ waiting, listening, trying not
to breathe. Then I hear movement outside the bedroom door.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief, terrifying moment, I'm a little kid again,
scrunched under my flowered chenille spread, hiding from the
alligators that I always knew were living under the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Thud! Bump! Something slams into the bathroom door.
</P>
<P>
   In a flash I eliminate the impossibilities. A storm? Not
tonight. The cats? Nope. They don't use the upstairs bathroom.
Theirs is in the basement. Then I hear an ominous squeak and a
click, followed closely by a hollow, Thunk! Oh Lordy, I'm gonna'
die at the hands of a hired gun. Then I remember report cards went
out last week.
</P>
<P>
   Resigned to my fate, I decide to go with dignity. I'll not die
cringing under the comforter. Whatever is after me is going to have
to look me straight in the eye first. I fling back the covers,
plant my bare feet firmly on the carpet, and head for the bedroom
door.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, I manipulate the knob and ease into the hall. Nearby,
much too close for comfort, I hear a metallic rattle followed by
... the sound of rushing water? I make like a statue just outside
the bathroom ... listening. Clunk! Shuffle (or was that, Sniffle?)!
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, I'm wide awake. It's the damnedest thing I've ever
heard of. A burglar has broken in to use my toilet. His towering
shadow is outlined by the night light. Omigosh! I'm being stalked
by a behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   Then the giant spoke. ``Hi, Mom, guess I wasn't as quiet as I
thought. Sorry I woke you up.'' Just like that. The kid has almost
given me the ``big one'' that Fred Sanford was always threatening
when he assured his dead wife, ``I'm coming, Elizabeth! This is the
big one!'' and all he has to say for himself is, ``Sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   My first instinct is to threaten to pull his inheritance. But
quickly that thought is replaced with a strong urge to take a swing
at him. ``You have scared me to death and now I'm going to hurt
you,'' I warn as I move in on him. My threats are met with a
giggle, for obvious reasons. He's a foot taller and a whole people
bigger than I am. My son, home for the weekend, picks me up, tucks
me under one arm, and hauls me back to bed, assuring me he'll be
``quiet as a little mouse'' and will see me in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   As I slide back under the covers, I'm thinking how good it is to
have him home and wondering how, with his crashing and banging, I
ever managed to get any sleep when we were housemates. Guess I just
got used to it.
</P>
<P>
   Kristofor was not a quiet kid. He was cautious, but
uncoordinated. By the time he was 2, he was running into the
furniture, tripping over the cats, and toppling unwary visitors.
Walls were little more than sideboards of the giant carom board he
called home. I began to worry so I set up an appointment for an eye
exam.
</P>
<P>
   Kindly old Dr. Patrick was our neighbor. Often, he'd stop out
front and tell me what a handsome boy I had there. He packed
Kristofor into the little booster chair and they discussed what the
boy was seeing and how many. I held my breath. No one wants to hear
her child is less than A-1 Perfecto. I wasn't disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   When the exam was over, he helped Kristofor crawl down and told
him the disappointing news. ``You don't need glasses, son. You saw
all of the duckies just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So I don't get a lollipop?'' Kristofor asked, brokenhearted.
Doc assured him his eyes were so good he deserved two, and sent him
to the receptionist to collect. We watched as he toddled down the
hall, bouncing from a wall here and tripping over an imaginary
something or other there. I grimaced but Dr. Patrick chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth, don't worry,'' he said reassuringly. ``The boy will
be fine _ once''he grows into those feet of his.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he never has. He's 6'4'' and still stumbling. But it's OK.
He's finally found the lady of his dreams. She's almost his size
and equally as graceful. Their affectionate gestures remind me of
the bears I used to
</P>
<P>
   watch in Chicago's Brookfield Zoo. All paws.
</P>
<P>
   And the reason he's banging around the house in the middle of
the night? He's come home to break the official news. ``Amy and I
are going to be married.'' He's glowing and I couldn't be happier _
although I do fear for their children. But I won't mention it
because I get to play with the cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail to: 320 East
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
