<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-COOK     02-15 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-COOKIES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How the cookie crumbles
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ People love cookies and milk. People hate cookies and
computers.
</P>
<P>
   In case you don't have your ``Internet for Dummies'' handbook
nearby, a computer ``cookie'' is a file that Web sites install on
your computer's hard drive when you visit a site that offers
cookies. They are very small files, never more than 225 characters
or 4K of disk space. Not all sites send cookies to your computer,
but an increasing number do.
</P>
<P>
   Harmless though they might be, most Internet users have a
knee-jerk reaction to anyone or anything trying to gather
information about them. The notion that merely typing in a Web
address opens up the opportunity for companies to find out anything
at all about them is distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an advertiser might set a cookie on your computer
to track how many people have viewed an online advertisement. Web
sites also send cookies to monitor how many users might view a
particular page or section. The folks who send these cookies say
they do it to help determine which parts of their Web sites get the
most traffic so they can add or subtract content accordingly and to
keep users from looking at the same advertisements over and over
again.
</P>
<P>
   Cookies, for the most part, are harmless both to your computer
and your privacy. There's really no harm in sites such as ESPN
SportZone sending baseball-related ads to users browsing the
baseball section. In fact, some users may find the products and
services being offered to them useful.
</P>
<P>
   However, cookies can also be used to track your password, user
name, credit card numbers and any other information you have
provided via an online form. Sites like The New York Times, which
require user ID and passwords, store this information as a cookie
in your hard disk, so registered users won't have to keep filling
out forms every time they go to the site.
</P>
<P>
   Search engines use cookies to ``remember'' individual user
habits and deliver customized news and services targeted to them.
</P>
<P>
   Online vendors, such as Amazon.com, can read the user's cookie
and match it with a stored profile that would contain credit card
information, so the user won't have to enter the information each
time.
</P>
<P>
   Given what cookies do, it won't come as a surprise that Internet
advertisers love cookies _ all kinds and any kind. Cookies with
news, with entertainment, with sports, with search engines. If you
can put it on the Web and you can advertise there, you can bet
there's a marketing department somewhere making sure every Web ad
comes with cookies. Most cookies are active only during a single
Web surfing session and disappear after users log off.
</P>
<P>
   However, the sheer vastness of the Internet and the complexity
of home PCs make many Web users wary of cookies. There are concerns
that cookies can be used to lift personal information from your PC
or perhaps something more insidious. A special Web site called
Cookie Central (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .cookiecentral.com) explains the various uses and potential
misuses of cookies. Ironically, the site uses cookies itself to
deliver its own banner ads to subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concerns, the U.S. government says it likes cookies.
A report issued last March from the Energy Department's Computer
Incident Advisory Capability (CIAC) said, despite the fear and
loathing some users have, ``the hype about cookies has far
outweighed the actual hazards of the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The popular concepts and rumors about what a cookie can do has
reached almost mystical proportions,'' the report stated. ``It is
not an executable program and cannot do anything to your machine.''
</P>
<P>
   The report helped quiet rumors that America Online planned to
use cookies to gather private information from its members' hard
drives.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing consultants such as DoubleClick
(http://www.doubleclick
</P>
<P>
   .com) use cookies to increase the efficiency of the placing of
advertisements on Web sites and deliver ads to the people most
likely to be interested in a particular company's products and
services.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick addresses the issue of cookies and Internet privacy
directly at its Web site. The company reassures all Web surfers
that any user information gleaned from cookies remains completely
anonymous. ``We do not sell or rent any information to third
parties,'' the company says.
</P>
<P>
   Since the information is anonymous, DoubleClick maintains, only
the sites themselves and advertisers could benefit from the
information the company gathers.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick believes cookies make the Web a better place. ``We
believe that cookies enhance the Web experience for the user by
limiting the repetitiveness of advertising and increasing the level
of relevant content on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   While DoubleClick might paint too rosy a picture of cookies,
there really isn't anything dangerous about them. There are ways
you can monitor what sites are sending you cookies and/or stop them
altogether, and you can read about them below.
</P>
<P>
   There are people who will abuse cookies _ unscrupulous Web sites
might take your information and sell it to offline marketers, but
as Electronic Frontier Foundation director Stanton McCandlish told
CNet last year, ``It's really difficulty to imagine a technology
that can't be abused.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT COOKIES DO ...
</P>
<P>
   1. Web site tracking: It's a way to help Web designers and
developers keep tabs on which areas of their sites are most
popular. It also provides more accurate accounts of how many people
have actually visited a Web site and what pages they viewed.
</P>
<P>
   2. Marketing: Cookies deliver targeted advertisements for
products consumers might want _ for example, advertising sporting
equipment to users who visit the sports area of a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   3. Storing IDs: Cookies can store passwords and user IDs, so
subscribers to The New York Times, The Wall Street Journal, Slate
or any site that requires a user ID and password won't have to keep
filling out registration forms everytime the visit the site. Online
retailers like Amazon.com and others use cookies to streamline
their online ordering process, remembering what orders have been
placed, or items that have been selected but not yet purchased.
Users can return weeks later and find the items still in their
``online shopping baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Personalization: Even the most anti-cookie contingent agrees
this is one of the best uses of cookies. Microsoft and Netscape
browsers use cookies to create personal start pages. Users can come
to a large site such as CNN, MSNBC or Excite and select which areas
of the site they want to view and which areas they don't. The
cookie stores that information and uses it on the next visit.
</P>
<P>
   5. Target marketing: Cookies can be used to build a profile of
you _ where you surf, and what advertisements you click on. This
information is used to send ads to you that supposedly will be of
interest to you based on your Web surfing history.
</P>
<P>
   COOKIES DON'T ...
</P>
<P>
   1. Mine your PC and gather information about you from other
programs such as letters, spreadsheets or e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   2. Send information to any other sites you surf.
</P>
<P>
   3. Make changes to any information you've supplied previously.
</P>
<P>
   4. Damage your computer or your hard drive in any way.
</P>
<P>
   5. Taste good dunked in milk or purchased from a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
