<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cuff monitors average blood pressure
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Mark of Fitness Inc. wristwatch-style blood
pressure and pulse monitor can store data about two people and
sells for around $100 at selected health product and electronic
stores.
</P>
<P>
   To use the MF-72, as the unit is called, you strap it over your
wrist and push the start button. A cuff inflates, and the device
automatically measures your pulse and blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The reading is comfortable and takes less than a minute. And
because the unit is portable, a person needing to monitor his blood
pressure can keep it with him at all times. It runs on two AAA
batteries and comes shipped in a clamshell carrying case.
</P>
<P>
   The MF-72 holds records for two people and gives current
readings plus averages of the past seven readings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your blood pressure can be up at one reading just because you
were walking around,'' said Wayne Baker, sales manager for Mark of
Fitness. ``An average of seven readings gives your doctor a much
clearer picture of where you really are.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the MF-72 won an innovation award at the recent
International Consumer Electronics Show, the product is not yet
widely distributed. If you can't find it, call the company at (732)
842-7200 for information.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
