<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5641 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-TAXES16-COX     02-15 2001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TAXES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tax software: They're not like putting an accountant in your PC,
but programs make unpleasant task easier
 &HT;    WITH GRAPHIC
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Back in the Dark Ages before home computers,
anyone preparing his income tax returns had to sit down with
pencil, paper and a calculator and shuffle through a box of records
for hours to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   Now that person can sit down in front of his computer screen and
accomplish the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   It will still take hours, and he'll have to shuffle through the
same box of records, but at least his return will look neater.
</P>
<P>
   A review of three tax preparation software products, two online
tax assistance services and the Internal Revenue Service's taxpayer
assistance Web site showed basically that the pencil, paper and
calculator method aren't that bad after all.
</P>
<P>
   One rule seems to apply: If you don't have your records in order
and you can't figure out the meaning of the applicable tax
regulations, filling out your tax returns will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Teri Dixon, public affairs officer for the Internal Revenue
Service office in Cincinnati, said tax software reduces the chance
of math errors. And if you file electronically _ more on that later
_ you'll get a quick acknowledgement that your return has been
received, and you'll get a quicker refund.
</P>
<P>
   But Dixon said, ``The best software can't help you if you don't
have good records. That's our No. 1 tip.''
</P>
<P>
   The software packages may help walk you through the process of
filling in a tax return, but they're generally only a bit more
helpful than the tax preparation books you can pick up for free at
the local post office or library.
</P>
<P>
   And while flipping back and forth through a booklet is fairly
easy, trying to navigate through an online help index can be
frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Tax-preparation software takes care of all the adding,
subtracting and dividing. It also checks the charts to fill in the
blanks on how much tax you owe or what your standard deduction
would be.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it. The reason some people go to an accountant or a
professional tax preparer is that they hope the professional will
know some tricks to reduce their taxes. They don't want to break
the law, but they want to twist it a little to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The software packages are good about pointing out tax savings an
inexperienced private citizen might miss, but they seem to stick
very close to the rules and language found in official Internal
Revenue Service tax booklets.
</P>
<P>
   TAX SOFTWARE
</P>
<P>
   Most programs follow a similar pattern: The program flashes
interview questions across the computer screen, and the user types
answers into little boxes. The questions range from ``What's your
first name?'' to ``How much did you receive in rent from your
tenants in out-of-state rental property?''
</P>
<P>
   Alongside the questions, most programs offer one or more
``help'' options. Some have a list of frequently asked questions
related to the information the program is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the program might ask if you earned any tax-exempt
interest in the past year. The nearby help option explains what
types of interest are taxed and which are tax-exempt.
</P>
<P>
   A major shortcut is available if you have kept accurate,
up-to-date records on a computerized personal accounting program
such as Quicken. The software packages claim to be able to import
information directly from your financial records, greatly reducing
the time required to fill out the return.
</P>
<P>
   One annoying and time-consuming feature in tax-preparation
software is that users must type in everything on their W-2 forms.
Each W-2 has about 25 boxes, and the programs usually ask questions
about each box on each W-2.
</P>
<P>
   With traditional paper filing, you just copy numbers from the
W-2s and enter them on the tax forms, then put a copy of the W-2 in
the envelope when you mail the return.
</P>
<P>
   The software programs reviewed were all designed for individual
taxpayers and they all were fairly flexible. They easily handled
simple returns where the taxpayer took the standard deduction and
had no unusual sources of income.
</P>
<P>
   They also did fine with more complicated returns involving home
businesses and self-employment taxes.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the software did not do well was answer specific
questions that often come up during a typical tax-preparation
session.
</P>
<P>
   They have answers for frequently asked questions, of course, but
what if your question isn't that frequently asked? The help subject
indexes within the programs are often difficult to use.
</P>
<P>
   After you have answered all the questions in the federal tax
interview, the programs calculate your taxes and tell you how much
you owe or how big of a refund you should receive.
</P>
<P>
   Some programs offer the option of completing a state income tax
return. In most cases, you must pay extra for a separate program
capable of handling your state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The state tax return is completed much like the federal return;
the program interviews you, you type in answers and the program
plugs the answers into the forms.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy a tax-preparation software package now, it should be
useful well into the future. The packages are designed to be
updated by linking them to their manufacturers through the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   FILING
</P>
<P>
   The traditional way to file taxes is to fill out paper forms,
put them in an envelope along with W-2s and mail them to the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   All the tax software packages and online services we tested
allow filers to print out completed forms and send them to federal
and state tax authorities by mail.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the IRS also has been accepting various
forms of electronic filing.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers with the simplest returns can file their returns
directly with the Internal Revenue Service with the TeleFile
system. The taxpayer follows instructions and types tax information
using a telephone keypad, which leads to a quicker refund than
paper filing.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers with more complicated returns generally must pay a
third party such as a tax-preparation service to file their taxes
electronically. You can't log onto an IRS Web site and file your
taxes directly.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon said the IRS uses third parties because it has certified
that its approved third-party providers know what they're doing and
won't send through a lot of improperly filed forms.
</P>
<P>
   But she also said security is a concern. The Internal Revenue
Service doesn't want an unlimited number of people tying into the
service's computers.
</P>
<P>
   And she said she doesn't know if the IRS will ever allow direct
electronic filings from individuals. ``I can't see that far into
the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Charges of $10 to $15 are common for electronic filing. A few
online service providers also offer free electronic filing to
low-income filers.
</P>
<P>
   The methods for electronic filing are set by the software or
online service you choose, but they all promise a quicker refund
than filing by mail.
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAMS AND ONLINE TAX HELP
</P>
<P>
   _ MacIntax (Intuit Inc.): Intuit is the clear leader in the
tax-preparation software business with its MacIntax and TurboTax
products accounting for 73 percent of the market, according to
figures from the company. MacIntax is the basic version of Intuit's
tax software for use on Macintosh computers. The program is very
similar to TurboTax for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Data entry was quick and easy and users should have no trouble
navigating from one form to another. The more sophisticated
programs have more built-in help features, but MacIntax was more
than adequate for simple returns. It also can import information
from Quicken financial management programs. One drawback that
MacIntax shares with TurboTax is that it doesn't come with software
to complete state tax returns. That state software costs $27.95
through Intuit's online store. MacIntax has a suggested retail
price of $34.95, but you should be able to find it cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kiplinger TaxCut Deluxe Multimedia (Block Financial): Block
apparently is trying to cut into Intuit's market by offering
products very similar to TurboTax and MacIntax at reduced prices.
Unlike the Intuit products, for example, TaxCut downloaded an Ohio
income tax program from the Internet for free. The state form was
not very sophisticated, however, and required the user to check a
state tax booklet for several questions.
</P>
<P>
   TaxCut's language and graphics have a homey feel. Online help
items say things like ``Congress just loves to change tax laws, and
you can be sure that new rules that can save you money are built
into TaxCut.'' The software is simply organized under three
headings: prepare, review and file, and it's easy to navigate.
TaxCut has multimedia features such as little video movies in which
tax advisers pop up on the screen to explain new tax rules.
</P>
<P>
   TaxCut says it can import information from Quicken, Microsoft
Money and other management software. The tested version offered the
first year's electronic filing free after a mail-in rebate, and
fees for electronic filing were slightly less for TaxCut than for
Intuit products. Most stores carry the Deluxe version for about
$40. Basic versions and Macintosh versions are available.
</P>
<P>
   _ TurboTax Deluxe (Intuit): This product has all the bells and
whistles of TaxCut Deluxe Multimedia plus a few extras. In addition
to video tax advisers, TurboTax Deluxe has a built-in library of
tax books such as Money magazine's ``Income Tax Handbook.'' Turbo
Tax Deluxe also has a planner to help you plot tax strategy for the
current year. The program is clear and easy to use, but if you want
to complete a state income tax form, you have to buy a separate
program for $27.95. The suggested retail price for TurboTax Deluxe
is $49.95, including electronic filing, and you should be able to
find significant discounts on that price.
</P>
<P>
   _ TaxACT 98 Standard Edition (2nd Story Software Inc.): If you
just want the experience of filling in a simple tax return on your
computer, you can download TaxACT 98 Standard Edition from the
Internet for free. The software doesn't offer much help with
complicated tax situations, but if you already know which number
goes in which box, TaxACT works just fine. Log on at taxact.com and
follow the instructions to download the standard program. It took
about 15 minutes to download using a 56 bps modem. All the time the
free program was downloading and during its use, 2nd Story is
lobbying to sell you the more sophisticated TaxACT 98 Deluxe for
$9.95. The company also offers a state tax program for $12.95.
Electronic filing on the TaxAct site costs $7.95 per return.
</P>
<P>
   _ OneTax.com (Thomson Investor Network): This service at
onetax.com seems to be working out some bugs and is not recommended
at this time. It offers an attractive price _ federal and state
returns prepared and filed electronically for $9.95 _ but the
system is prone to problems. Three times while attempting to
prepare a return the reviewer was logged off the site. Also
OneTax.com delayed filing a federal return electronically several
times and failed completely to electronically file a state return.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Digital Daily (Internal Revenue Service): This is the main
online help site for the IRS, and it contains links to just about
everything you need to file your federal taxes. It has forms and
publications on most subjects that can be viewed online or
downloaded to your home computer.
</P>
<P>
   You can find the Digital Daily at www.irs.ustreas.gov, and one
page on the site claims to offer tax regulations in plain English.
Don't be surprised if their idea of plain English doesn't match
yours, however. You can't use this site to file your taxes
electronically, but from the home page you can navigate to the IRS
e-file page that links you to TaxACT and other online tax services,
including the online versions of TurboTax and Taxcut.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
