<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't replace that slow computer until you have to
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You'd think _ judging from the computers my friends
own _ that many people of my personal acquaintance are spending
their evenings designing nuclear submarines and figuring ways to
control the Hubble Space Telescope from home.
</P>
<P>
   It's created a weird sort of modern neurosis. I think of it as
PC envy. People who have relatively low-powered computers at home
spend a huge amount of time fretting they don't have a powerful
enough computer. After all, they're bombarded with ads and articles
that discuss the merits of having a super computer.
</P>
<P>
   This morning's e-mail brought me a note from a reader who uses
an old Mac Classic computer. She said she was really happy with it
and wondered if she should buy a new iMac.
</P>
<P>
   The answer isn't exactly what you might think. There's nothing
wrong with replacing an old computer, even one you're happy with,
because newer and more powerful computers do things faster (that's
convenient and less frustrating) and can run more-powerful programs
(some of the best new programs won't run on old machines).
</P>
<P>
   If you have plenty of money and want a new computer, then there
are good reasons for buying one. But if you are one of those people
who have to count pennies, and who have to make decisions between
buying a new computer and going to New Orleans on vacation, or
paying the mortgage, then don't feel blue or compelled to buy just
because you have this vague notion that you need more.
</P>
<P>
   Among my power-hungry friends, the most common uses for a home
computer (besides games, and we'll get to that by and by) are
e-mail, using the Web, writing old-fashioned paper letters and
running Quicken or some other money management program. It doesn't
take a super computer to do all that. And if the machine you have
at home now does it all for you, then you won't hurt yourself in
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Here comes Husted's Rule of Computer Replacement: Unless you
have plenty of money to spare, only buy a new machine when the one
you own won't run a program you truly need to use, or when it runs
the program so slowly you just about can't stand it (put in
scientific terms).
</P>
<P>
   The benefit of following that rule is that you're taking
advantage of a computer world truth: The computers on sale next
month are always more powerful and cost less than the ones last
month. So, when you do buy, you'll get the very most bang for your
buck.
</P>
<P>
   OK. I said I would come back to the topic of games.
</P>
<P>
   If playing computer games is a big part of your computing life
(and it isn't necessarily a sin to actually have fun with that
expensive piece of hardware that sits ugly and beige on your desk
at home), then Husted's Rule still holds true. But you will find
the games you most want to play require enormous computing power.
And the demands from the games don't stop there.
</P>
<P>
   You'll soon find out that games push every component. That
designers _ stretching to get the most realistic video and the most
powerful sound _ write the games with rich folks in mind. You'll
find the latest video card is important to the hottest games and,
if you want to hear the crunching sound just right when the Alien
Creature From the Third Grade eats your hero, you'll need a hot
sound card and the latest in speakers.
</P>
<P>
   There is one small gleam of hope, however, that I can offer even
the game players in the crowd. In a calculated way, I stay two
generations behind on the games I play. That way, I save money
twice. I find games that are new to me in the bargain bin at the
software store, and I also postpone the day when I enrich the
credit card people by dropping big money on a new machine.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 1027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE16-COX     02-15 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web world also blankets local entertainment events
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sure, they call it the World Wide Web. And, yes
indeed, you can zip from Paris, France, to Paris, Ark. Click your
mouse button and you can visit almost any spot on the globe within
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes down to real life, most of us find that the
happenings in our neighborhood and city occupy most of our time.
While you can get the schedule for almost any subway train system
in the world from the Web, folks in Atlanta probably have more
interest in the fact that local MARTA schedules, fare information
and parking information can be found at http://www.itsmarta
</P>
<P>
   .com/.
</P>
<P>
   Most particularly, we'd like something fun to do over the
weekend. And that's where the Web really shines.
</P>
<P>
   So, for today, let's let the world wait and take a look inside
how to find that type of local information using the World Wide
Web. We'll concentrate on Atlanta. But as we explore some of the
sites, we'll also spend a little time talking about how you can
adapt what we learn to your home city.
</P>
<P>
   One good place to start is with Yahoo!. Set your browser to
visit http://localevents.yahoo.com
</P>
<P>
   /events/metro/atlanta/index
</P>
<P>
   .html. (There are similar Yahoo! locations for other major
cities.)
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, this is a pretty clunky way to find out stuff
(although you can use the standard Yahoo! search method if you are
looking for a specific event or topic in Atlanta). I'll show you
what I mean by clunky. It's not bizarre to think you might be using
this Yahoo! feature to find something fun to do for the weekend.
You'd like to know what's available.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can click on your choice of ``Arts and
Entertainment,'' ``Industry Events,'' ``Music'' or ``Recreation and
Sports.'' So, you might start by clicking on ``Music.'' You'd then
be given a sub-menu for different types of music, and you'd have to
click on each sub-menu to find out what's cooking. Meantime, you
wouldn't find theater performances that way, so you'd need to go
through the same winnowing process by starting with ``Arts and
Entertainment'' to get to theater. By the time it got to be
Saturday night, you'd have a sore mouse finger. However, the
listings _ once you get to all of them _ seem fairly complete.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take the same problem _ finding something to do for the
weekend _ to another site. You need to know, as you weigh the
opinion you'll read, that this site is owned by Cox Interactive
Media, which is owned by Cox Enterprises. Cox Enterprises also owns
The Atlanta-Journal Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The site I'm talking about is Access Atlanta. The main site is
at http://www.accessatlanta
</P>
<P>
   .com but, to duplicate our search for weekend entertainment
we'll go to http://www
</P>
<P>
   .accessatlanta.com
</P>
<P>
   /entertainment/calendars. You'll still find various
entertainment events divided in categories: ``Theater,'' ``Dance,''
``Visual Arts,'' ``Classical Music,'' and, among other things,
``Pop Music.'' But there's a shortcut here. Just click on the link
for ``Weekend's Best Bets'' and you'll get a selection of various
events planned for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also be able to choose links for upcoming events _ if you
tend to plan far into the future _ as well as events outside
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's drop in over at Digitalcity Atlanta. (If you live in
another area and it's big enough, there may be a digital city for
you, too.) But we are headed for http://home.digitalcity.com
</P>
<P>
   /atlanta/events/, where the method of finding an event is pretty
nifty. Just use the drop-down menus to select a category, date and
the area (in the case of Atlanta you get two choices: ``Downtown''
or ``North and East'') and press the Find Events button. You can
set the categories for all, if you just want something to do and
don't care if it's a movie or ice skating or a museum exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day, the search engine will return 50 or more
events. Then, you'll be able to click on each event listed to get
more detail.
</P>
<P>
   So, now you know how to find out what to do next weekend. Now
all you have to do is find the time and the money to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
