<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCHER16-COX     02-15 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCHER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once a novelty, now big business
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Netwatchers are not necessarily Net geeks.
</P>
<P>
   What I know about the Windows 98 operating system you could put
into half of a very small thimble, and I will never understand why
``King's Quest VII'' crashes every time I'm ready to fight the evil
wizards.
</P>
<P>
   But I am a Web surfer from way back _ all the way back to 1994,
to be exact. I read an article about all these neat things you
could see on your computer if you had this gizmo called a
``browser.'' So I got myself one at the local software joint and
installed it on my dumpy little Compaq Presario 486. I ventured out
into the wilds of cyberspace all by myself, with no map, no search
engine and certainly no technical support.
</P>
<P>
   There really wasn't much to look at then, and with a 2,400 bps
modem, if you wanted to look at the cool sites of those days _
HotWired, Pathfinder or the Louve museum _ you needed time, and
plenty of it. My friend Janet called me up after I had sold her on
the virtues of ``that Internet thing'' to complain. ``In the time
it takes me to download Time magazine, I can sit down on my couch
and read Time magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   And you know what? In those days, she was right.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling somewhat guilty, I felt compelled to help my friends and
fellow Web surfers get the most out of the Web. After all, it was
at my suggestion they were forking over $19.95 of their hard-earned
money each month to stare at their computers and wait for the magic
of the Web to appear before them. In my quest for Web knowledge, I
did the only thing I could think of at the time.
</P>
<P>
   I got a subscription to Wired magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Reading between the lines _ which was pretty much how you had to
read Wired in those days _ I found out that you could get better
computers with faster modems, and there were books that could help
you find Web sites to give you Tarot card readings, Emily
Dickinson's poetry and the contents of a Coke machine in some
building at Stanford University. Not that I had any need to know if
there was any Diet Coke left in some vending machine at Stanford
University, but it was kind of cool to be sitting on the other side
of the country gathering up this kind of information.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the days of wandering aimlessly through cyberspace are
gone. More and more users are logging on every day from home and
work. Portals such as Yahoo! and Excite promise to take you to
every Web site worth seeing, and the number of sites grows
exponentially every day.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more retailers, banks, and airlines pour onto the
Web, it's becoming more of a utility than an amusing little hobby.
Everyone wants a piece of your valuable online time and your
valuable off-line money. Web powerhouses like CNN and Amazon.com
would love it if you spent all your online time just visiting their
sites and nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Although I have spent more than my fair share of time at Amazon
_ the travel mug/thank you note last Christmas from Amazon's
marketing department was a real wake-up call for me and my credit
limit _ there are other things to do online that are useful and
just plain fun. To miss them is to miss the creativity and
innovation that made the Web worth looking at to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   The Web of the 21st century is big business. Everyone from
Disney to Martha Stewart has their own Web page, and newcomers to
the Web are lost even before they start. Companies like Peapod now
will deliver groceries to your front door, and the cable and phone
companies are promising a future filled with ``always on'' Net
access that will eliminate busy signals and the endless downloads
of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, the Web is going to change your life. You may
become a devotee of online shopping, hourly news updates from MSNBC
or sending e-mail to your friends and co-workers. Even if you never
log on, the Web isn't going to go away. You watch your kids bounce
from Web site to Web site from a nervous distance or look at Web
addresses constantly being flashed across your TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a novice Web surfer, the Web was filled with novice
Web surfers. People built Web pages with lists of sites because it
was fun, not to make money, go public, get into mergers and
acquisition or land on the covers of business magazines. In the
last six years the Web has become a business. As consumers we need
to know what's going on out there and how it's going to change how
we use the Web and how we fit it into our lives.
</P>
<P>
   While we try to figure it all out for you, there's lots to do in
the meantime. Why not see how the Coke machines are stocked in New
York and Denmark? (http://www.cc.columbia.edu/(tilde)cocacola/ and
http://
</P>
<P>
   amigos12.diku.dk/currentstatus.html, respectively).
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz covers the Internet for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. She comments on Internet issues and trends as
the Netw(at)tcher. She has been covering the Internet and its major
players since 1995 as an online editor for a New York business news
service. She also has contributed to Wired News and The New York
Times CyberTimes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
