<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN16-CO     02-15 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PCs too cheap to pass up
 &HT;    By Gerry Yandel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Decisions, decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Charlie Partana says in ``Prizzi's Honor'': Do I ice her?
Do I marry her?
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with computers. Now that the holiday dust has
settled, a question still hangs in the air: Should you trash that
vintage Pentium that's served you so well and buy a newer, faster
machine now that the prices have leveled out a little? Or are you
in it for better or for worse and need to upgrade?
</P>
<P>
   With all the new models on the market creating a glut of
hardware, there's never been a better time to upgrade. I just took
my P166 off life support by adding 48 MB of RAM, a U.S. Robotics
56k modem and a Matrox 8-gigabyte hard drive for $380. (It would
have been cheaper, but I had to pay more than I should have for EDO
RAM because only one store that I could locate had any.)
</P>
<P>
   The result is like getting a new machine _ with a customized OS
and software bundle _ that has a whole bunch of space and memory
and will do anything I need it to do: play the newest games, create
CPU-intensive graphics or use six programs at once.
</P>
<P>
   So, now I don't need to go buy a new machine anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But, I'm gonna get one anyway ... they're just too darn cheap to
ignore.
</P>
<P>
   How's this for a price from the ads on these very pages: A
400-MHz computer with all the trimmings for $650? Add another $200
for a 17-inch monitor, and you've got one heck of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is, the most inexpensive computers don't use Pentium
chips.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares?
</P>
<P>
   AMD's K6 series of chips benchmark as fast as or nearly as fast
as _ and in some cases faster than _ Pentiums do. Intel's own
Celeron chip is another good alternative to spending an extra
couple of hundred dollars to get the Pentium brand, and all three
flavors are more CPU power than most home users will ever need.
</P>
<P>
   Wait, it gets better. AMD has a K7 at 500 MHz on the horizon,
and Intel is about to offer the Pentium III _ albeit a
controversial chip currently being boycotted by some in the Net
community. (But that's another column.)
</P>
<P>
   The point is that prices on K6s, Celerons and PIIs will probably
drop even lower.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm not saying Pentium isn't a good chip to buy _ not at
all. There's no denying that Pentium connotes reliability, well,
except for that little floating point unit screw-up a few years
back. But they are the team to beat on the semiconductor playing
field.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the K6 chips aren't worth considering, either.
In fact, big-name manufacturers _ like Compaq, Hewlett-Packard and
others _ have been selling AMD's K6s for a while, and a hot rumor
around the 'Net is that Gateway 2000 is in talks with AMD about
using its chips in some Gateway systems.
</P>
<P>
   Don't rule out Celeron, either. Initially, these Intel chips
were essentially Pentium IIs without a Level 2 cache created to
counter AMD's cheaper prices. New Celerons _ Celeron (A) _ however,
have an L2 cache and are equal to Pentium IIs running at 66-MHz bus
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   For many people, upgradeability is a factor. Chances are,
though, that by the time you're ready to trade in one of these
300-400 MHz uber-machines, you won't be able to use what's
available then anyway. Your best strategy these days is to approach
buying a new computer as if it were disposable and forget about
upgrading the chip and motherboard down the line. Need a machine
for e-mail and letter-writing? Get a 266-MHz K6-2 and a 15-inch
monitor for slightly more than $500. Need some real power for
graphics and gaming? Go for a 400-MHz Celeron (A) or the new,
speedier PC100 bus with a K6-2 chip and a 17-inch monitor for
around $750.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, you can't go wrong spending the extra money to
buy a Pentium II.
</P>
<P>
   It's just about impossible to go wrong with any of these new
boxes, and the dogfight brewing between Intel and AMD can only make
it better.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if I didn't know better, I'd say the buyer is in the
driver's seat these days.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: pcajc(at)yahoo.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
