<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta No. 5 city in Net use
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The City Too Busy To Hate apparently spends a lot of
its free time on the Internet. A study by Inteco, a Connecticut
market research firm, found metro Atlanta the fifth most wired
community in America.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of metro Atlanta adults regularly access the
Internet, according to the study. Oakland, Calif.; Orange County,
Calif.; Seattle; and Washington, D.C., placed first through fourth.
After Atlanta come Dallas, Houston, San Diego, Phoenix and
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The company sampled 16,500 American households in December. The
study found about 55 percent of the adult U.S. population _ 108
million people _ had hopped on the Internet at least once in the
previous 30 days. The December numbers were up 38 percent from May
1998 and 71 percent from September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 study of Internet use, Atlanta placed seventh behind
San Jose, Calif., Boston, Denver, Dallas, New York and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Of those who use the Internet, 76 million have access from home,
51 million from work, 22 million from a friend's or relative's
house, and 24 million use computers at a school, library or
community center. The bulk of Internet users, 77 percent, are
between 18 and 49 years of age, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   OFF-BRAND CAN BE OK
</P>
<P>
   We are, increasingly, a nation of billboards. Clothes with
company names are considered cooler than those without. FamilyPC
magazine, in its March 1999 issue, takes a look at the issue of
brand names as related to technology products. It attempts to
answer this question: When it comes to computers, is
label-consciousness anything more than simple vanity?
</P>
<P>
   The article looked at a Compaq PC and a computer from Comtrade.
Compaq is a well-known brand, Comtrade lesser known. The comparison
looked at comparably priced systems. Both were about $2,100.
</P>
<P>
   The Compaq was considered far easier to set up and use. It comes
complete with a poster detailing the set-up procedures, and the
article gave the poster high marks. Compaq's system comes with
color-coded ports and cables, so matching cable and port is no
tougher than plugging a blue into a blue. The software that came
with the Compaq was rated better, and the service supporting the
computer and reliability of the system was rated higher. The
Comtrade machine got rave reviews for its core components, its
multimedia parts and its performance.
</P>
<P>
   The study concluded that off-brand systems offer more
performance and better features than similarly priced name-brand
machines. But big-name machines offer more attention to detail and
polish. If you are someone who is comfortable with computers and
not afraid of risk, the no-name machines would be a safe buy. If
you're a PC novice, a more user-friendly name-brand system might be
the best option.
</P>
<P>
   No-name brands included in the article are Comtrade, http://
</P>
<P>
   comtrade.com; emachines, http://www.e4me.com; Gazelle computer,
www
</P>
<P>
   .gazelle-computer.com; iDOT.computers, http://www
</P>
<P>
   .idot.com; MidWest Micro, http://mwmicro.com; and Quantex,
http://www.quantex
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMIZED TICKETMASTER
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster is trying to get into the Internet portal business.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket broker launched a customizable Web site that lets
users create profiles, at http://
</P>
<P>
   my.ticketmaster.com. The profiles, in turn, are used to provide
a listing of the concerts and sporting events that should appeal to
you.
</P>
<P>
   The new site lets you see the view you'd have from any seat in
75 different venues, in virtual reality 3-D images. The site also
offers event times, directions to the venue and information about
parking.
</P>
<P>
   The site works best with Intel Pentium II-class processors. A
400-megahertz processor is recommended, but a 200-MHz machine will
work as well.
</P>
<P>
   My Ticketmaster is part of the regular Ticketmaster site,
http://www
</P>
<P>
   .ticketmaster.com. The company said online ticket sales have
averaged more than $10 million per month the past 21 months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
