</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Sickly pilots a plague on labor movement
 &HT;    For release Feb. 17, 1999
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As I sat down to write this, I intentionally placed my late
father's timeworn, quarter-sized green union button on the desk in
front of me, not only as a reminder of where I came from, but as a
notation of my personal lifelong support of the American labor
movement.
</P>
<P>
   I put the pin of Local 133 of the Club and Restaurant Employees
Union _ dad once had been a bartender _ so that I wouldn't go off
the deep end in what I had to say about the sick-out against
American Airlines and the paying public by the Allied Pilots
Association _ so arrogant that it initially ignored a federal
judge's demand that the pilots return to work.
</P>
<P>
   There is good argument that what the pilots were seeking, equal
pay for the Reno Airlines pilots just brought aboard by an American
Airlines buyout, was a legitimate labor-management issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the labor side handled it abysmally. It gave the public no
warning. The sick-out was not the result of a long, drawn-out
negotiation that failed. It just happened because the pilots wanted
their message to get across quickly.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, it was a lie. The pilots were not sick, just
circumventing the rightful course of labor negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Nevermind that it more than inconvenienced hundreds of thousands
of passengers and their families; the pilots's goal was to double
the pay of a scant few other pilots and to hell with whomever
suffered as a result.
</P>
<P>
   When a strike is imminent, the public has an opportunity to seek
other means. In the case of a package delivery strike, there was a
negotiation period where the public was alerted to send things
early, or by other means. The same is true of an airline strike.
When American Airlines pilots threatened to strike several years
ago over another matter, the public still had time to purchase
tickets on other airlines, or to take a train, bus or car.
</P>
<P>
   But not this time. Suddenly there was a sick-out. People were
trapped in the midst of their travels in Europe, in the Caribbean,
in the United States. Television feasted on pictures of stranded
travelers in airline terminals trying to get some sleep against
their luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Weddings and funerals were missed, honeymoons shattered,
business trips canceled at the gate. That the management of
American Airlines made no significant attempt to address or correct
the reason why the pilots were dishonestly sick cannot go
unnoticed. But, what the pilots did was far more callous.
</P>
<P>
   There always has and will continue to be a need for organized
labor. Unfortunately, our premier view of that today is through six
figure salaried pilots and seven to eight figure salaried athletes
who walk off the job.
</P>
<P>
   Where we need to be looking is where there has been historic
abuse of the American worker struggling to pay his and her bills.
They are the people who work in assembly plants, mines, clothing
and shoe factories and the like. That's where the American labor
movement began and where it still has the biggest job to do.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, labor has been its own worst enemy in recent
decades. Between corruption and arrogance, it repositioned itself
from the heart of the American public to its hind quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This sick-out is an example of labor at its ugliest.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with meaningful debate between management
and labor. And, if they can't agree, a strike is warranted. And the
public gets to observe and contemplate its options.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots did not let this happen. The pilots got a sickness
that became a plaque on the traveling public.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't what my father's union button was all about.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
