<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web world also blankets local entertainment events
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sure, they call it the World Wide Web. And, yes
indeed, you can zip from Paris, France, to Paris, Ark. Click your
mouse button and you can visit almost any spot on the globe within
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes down to real life, most of us find that the
happenings in our neighborhood and city occupy most of our time.
While you can get the schedule for almost any subway train system
in the world from the Web, folks in Atlanta probably have more
interest in the fact that local MARTA schedules, fare information
and parking information can be found at http://www.itsmarta
</P>
<P>
   .com/.
</P>
<P>
   Most particularly, we'd like something fun to do over the
weekend. And that's where the Web really shines.
</P>
<P>
   So, for today, let's let the world wait and take a look inside
how to find that type of local information using the World Wide
Web. We'll concentrate on Atlanta. But as we explore some of the
sites, we'll also spend a little time talking about how you can
adapt what we learn to your home city.
</P>
<P>
   One good place to start is with Yahoo!. Set your browser to
visit http://localevents.yahoo.com
</P>
<P>
   /events/metro/atlanta/index
</P>
<P>
   .html. (There are similar Yahoo! locations for other major
cities.)
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, this is a pretty clunky way to find out stuff
(although you can use the standard Yahoo! search method if you are
looking for a specific event or topic in Atlanta). I'll show you
what I mean by clunky. It's not bizarre to think you might be using
this Yahoo! feature to find something fun to do for the weekend.
You'd like to know what's available.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can click on your choice of ``Arts and
Entertainment,'' ``Industry Events,'' ``Music'' or ``Recreation and
Sports.'' So, you might start by clicking on ``Music.'' You'd then
be given a sub-menu for different types of music, and you'd have to
click on each sub-menu to find out what's cooking. Meantime, you
wouldn't find theater performances that way, so you'd need to go
through the same winnowing process by starting with ``Arts and
Entertainment'' to get to theater. By the time it got to be
Saturday night, you'd have a sore mouse finger. However, the
listings _ once you get to all of them _ seem fairly complete.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take the same problem _ finding something to do for the
weekend _ to another site. You need to know, as you weigh the
opinion you'll read, that this site is owned by Cox Interactive
Media, which is owned by Cox Enterprises. Cox Enterprises also owns
The Atlanta-Journal Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The site I'm talking about is Access Atlanta. The main site is
at http://www.accessatlanta
</P>
<P>
   .com but, to duplicate our search for weekend entertainment
we'll go to http://www
</P>
<P>
   .accessatlanta.com
</P>
<P>
   /entertainment/calendars. You'll still find various
entertainment events divided in categories: ``Theater,'' ``Dance,''
``Visual Arts,'' ``Classical Music,'' and, among other things,
``Pop Music.'' But there's a shortcut here. Just click on the link
for ``Weekend's Best Bets'' and you'll get a selection of various
events planned for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also be able to choose links for upcoming events _ if you
tend to plan far into the future _ as well as events outside
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's drop in over at Digitalcity Atlanta. (If you live in
another area and it's big enough, there may be a digital city for
you, too.) But we are headed for http://home.digitalcity.com
</P>
<P>
   /atlanta/events/, where the method of finding an event is pretty
nifty. Just use the drop-down menus to select a category, date and
the area (in the case of Atlanta you get two choices: ``Downtown''
or ``North and East'') and press the Find Events button. You can
set the categories for all, if you just want something to do and
don't care if it's a movie or ice skating or a museum exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day, the search engine will return 50 or more
events. Then, you'll be able to click on each event listed to get
more detail.
</P>
<P>
   So, now you know how to find out what to do next weekend. Now
all you have to do is find the time and the money to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
