<HEADER>
A5662 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENEAOLOGY16-COX     02-15 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENEAOLOGY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Embracing our past
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Alfred Texeira's parents were part African, part
Portuguese. Both he and his mother could ``pass'' for white. So
when Texeira was drafted into the Army during World War II, he
thought he'd try for a slot in an all-white unit.
</P>
<P>
   But when he was assigned to a post in the Jim Crow South, he
figured he needed to take a safer route.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid of being put up on an oak tree,'' he says. ``So I
switched over to black. It upset my mother because she thought I'd
have better opportunities in a white outfit.''
</P>
<P>
   One day as Marlo Smith listened to Texeira's war stories, and
noticed the astonishment on her 10-year-old son's face, she had an
epiphany. She began taking notes, then recording her grandfather's
musings on audiotape or video whenever he got into the mood to
reminisce.
</P>
<P>
   With her first surreptitious scribble, she joined the exploding
ranks of America's family historians, people who've become driven
to make sure stories of ordinary folks like her grandfather don't
die when they do.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired in part by Tom Brokaw's book, ``The Greatest
Generation,'' and a host of other best-selling personal memoirs _
such as ``Angela's Ashes,'' ``The Liars' Club'' and ``Having Our
Say: The Delany Sisters' First 100 Years'' _ many people have
embarked on a quest to preserve their own family histories in a
user-friendly fashion.
</P>
<P>
   They are going beyond the more traditional, but
difficult-to-read genealogical charts in favor of self-published
books and audio- and videotapes they hope will bring their
ancestors to life after the old folks are all dead and gone. Smith
and like-minded others have become writers and moviemakers, even
though their books usually are printed in limited numbers and their
films will be seen only on their families' own TVs.
</P>
<P>
   Many are aging baby boomers _ only now trying to appreciate what
their parents and grandparents endured in the Great Depression and
World War II; many are younger, like Smith, who is 30.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure what's behind this ``outbreak of memoir
fever,'' as the American Association of Retired Persons puts it,
but it may be that families feel compelled to record their unique
histories as an antidote to the anonymity and lack of connectedness
in a crowded, mobile world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the enormous economic changes in the 19th and 20th
centuries, each generation is experiencing a different world, and
there's a lot of displacement,'' says Stephen A. Kowalewski, head
of anthropology at the University of Georgia. ``We move around a
lot, lose our sense of who we are. People seem to find that what
their parents and grandparents have to say is a particularly new
experience, a world we have lost.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``I had a great aunt who died in her 90s, and her
children did one of these living histories. It was really
eye-opening about her way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Kopper, owner of Posterity Press in Bethesda, Md.,
publishes family histories. His take on the new interest in the
field: ``Our values and culture have become so neon that people are
looking for more real, more vital, more humane lives than our own.
People tend to candy-coat the past. These histories tell it like it
was. People perceive now that the real past isn't what we were
taught by TV and the movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Emily Wheeler, 52, began taping aunts, uncles and her parents to
find out about her grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told how my grandmother would take them out and wash
their hair in cold water. I learned the day my grandparents got
married, they got a horse and buggy as a wedding gift. My
grandfather went out and cut down a tree and made a rolling pin,
and I have it today, and it's 75 years old. And it's all on tape.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds: ``I want my grandchildren to know where they came from
when they get my age and will tell their grandchildren. I don't
want these things forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Family histories have become such a hot topic that courses are
being taught in colleges and high schools, offering tips to
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Galex of Atlanta, co-owner of Roots &AMP; Wings Life Stories,
which produces family-history videos, teaches occasionally at Emory
University's program for elders on interviewing and recording
techniques. Martha Blow, an instructor at R.D. Head Elementary in
Lilburn, Ga., was recently named the school's teacher of the year,
in part because she requires pupils to interview their elders to
preserve history.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Wearn, 10, son of Mary and James Wearn, earned a 100 on an
assignment from Blow that required him to interview his
grandparents about the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was astonished to learn things like movies cost 25 cents,
popcorn a nickel, and what food they ate and games they played when
they were young,'' says his mother. ``It's very important because
times are changing so rapidly now, so much is lost along the way.
Our children's lives are so filled with video games and TV and
things that are transitory, and sometimes we lose sight of the
history that made us who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy was enthralled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised everything was so cheap,'' he says. ``They
told me they rode on trolleys, and I've never even seen one.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are individuals compiling books, audiotapes and videos
to pass along to descendants, but the movement has spawned a
fast-growing cottage industry of entrepreneurs who will interview
relatives on tape and put together family history books. Scores
have joined the Association of Personal Historians, a group formed
in 1995, says APH President Bob Joyce of Santa Ana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with a few and now have 120 members,'' he says.
``But our membership doesn't reflect the numbers involved. It's far
more. The market is just huge. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are hundreds of thousands of people doing this,
most on their own,'' he says. ``Most don't even know there's help
out there, and we can save them a lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
   The price for such help isn't always cheap, however. Personal
historians who interview relatives of clients charge a few hundred
dollars to $10,000 or more. And those who want books published or
elaborate video productions made can spend many times that much.
</P>
<P>
   Family historians aren't genealogists, says Joyce. ``What we try
to do is capture the real person in his or her own words. We don't
want to change the intent or the meaning. We are careful to try to
keep the voice, spirit, tone and personality of that human being,
so future generations will know them as a real person.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Flowers, a professional family historian and genealogist
with homes in Florida and metro Atlanta, charges $40 an hour for
her work. She says ``family history has become a major hobby,'' and
she is hired by people who ``don't have the patience or have run
into a brick wall they can't knock down.''
</P>
<P>
   She collected information on her own family by interviewing old
relatives, often on videotape, and found out that many older folks
talk about an ``Indian princess'' _ a euphemism used by whites for
``African-American'' _ in their ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father talked about living through the 1926 hurricane in
Miami, crawling out of the house as it collapsed around him, his
time in WWII on Iwo Jima. My mother talked about life on a farm
during the Depression with seven brothers and sisters, how her
father would measure their feet on newspaper and go to town for
shoes before school started.''
</P>
<P>
   Such stories, she adds, are hard to imagine for today, but
they're easier to believe when ancestors _ living or dead _ come to
life on a TV screen. ``I think that passing down the true story of
who my ancestors were, and what they had to say, is the greatest
gift I can leave for future generations,'' Flowers says.
</P>
<P>
   Kopper's Posterity Press prints family histories in varying
quantities. They can cost from ``the price of a used Honda,
$10,000, all the way up to a bloody Maserati,'' Kopper said. ``I
have done some in six figures. We do printings of 250 on up to
about 5,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Galex, a CNN reporter before starting her business in 1992, says
demand for her services has never been higher.
</P>
<P>
   Many people want a book and a video history, and some people are
asking for CD-ROMs. Her rates start at $600 and go up from there
for videos. Workshops aimed at teaching people how to do their own
cost about $75 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit people down and get the family stories. We produce the
family-history videos that weave in the stories of many
generations, with the photos and other images to help illustrate
the stories as they unfold, one generation to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlo Smith hopes to finish her book and videos in time for her
grandfather's 80th birthday around Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stories are so remarkable,'' she says. ``He tells it like
it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The memories Smith is recording, he says, aren't bitter ones,
just signs of the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got back, I tried to change my discharge papers to say
I was white and not in the black transportation company I was in,''
he says. ``My mother was very prejudiced, and she didn't want me to
be called a Negro. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were white, you had a better chance; if you were black
or Negro or whatever, it was different.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Smith: ``This is important for the kids coming up to know
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
