</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Power Mac stands out in crowd, distinguished by minitower, speed
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From the side, it looks like a pillowcase with
handles. This latest desktop computer from Apple continues the
company's renewed emphasis on design.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, this model is called simply (and boringly) the Power
Mac G3. Apple has abandoned, for now at least, giving jazzy new
names to every new model of the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   But the Power Mac G3 is geeky in name only. It looks like no
other computer you've seen before, except for the Apple's runaway
hit, the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Like the iMac, the Power Mac G3's color scheme is iridescent
blue and white. The Power Mac, however, is a minitower and doesn't
include a built-in monitor like the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   And the Power Mac is the fastest Mac yet, offering processing
speeds up to 400 megahertz. There's also 1 megabyte of something
called backside cache, a chunk of memory designed to speed up the
processing power of the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   With the Power Mac, Apple has added a new design concept for
desktop computers. There are four handles atop the minitower, which
give this computer the pillowcase look from the side.
</P>
<P>
   The Power Mac continues other design changes begun with the iMac
last August.
</P>
<P>
   For one, there's no built-in floppy drive. You can, however,
easily add one in any of the Power Mac's five bays for internal
storage devices. Two of these slots also support Zip drives, CD-ROM
drives and DVD drives.
</P>
<P>
   The Power Mac is also designed to support USB, the new standard
already in use in PCs for connecting peripheral devices such as
mice and monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the iMac, though, the Power Mac is built for transition.
One slot supports the previous connection standard, so you can use
a current mouse, keyboard or monitor. The Power Mac does come with
the same USB iridescent blue mouse and keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Power Mac is also the first Apple computer to come equipped
with a new technology called FireWire. This is another peripheral
connection technology, and it vastly enhances the ability to
transfer video and audio files to your Mac. You'd use a FireWire
port, for example, to transfer to your Mac images from your
camcorder.
</P>
<P>
   The price of these latest Power Macs ranges between $1,600 and
$3,500, depending on the options you choose. Features such as
internal modems are optional.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
