<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tips offered for speedier 'Net connections
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No matter how fast your connection, the Internet can
move like molasses. It's one of the major frustrations holding back
the development of the 'Net as a commonplace utility.
</P>
<P>
   There are, though, ways to speed up your connection. Read about
them in the March issue of PC World.
</P>
<P>
   The article also compares the benefits of various new connection
technologies, such as the telephone company's digital subscriber
lines and cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   The March issue of PC World also includes a list of what it
considers the top PCs. It offers several lists of 10.
</P>
<P>
   There's the top 10 desktop computers, the top 10 laptops and the
top 10 home PCs. For example, as the top home PC, the magazine
names Dell's Dimension XPS R450.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Well, at long last it's here. Maxis has finally released the
next version of its popular ``SimCity'' game.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``SimCity 3000,'' the game offers better graphics, more
complexity and more control over your urban simulation. ``SimCity
3000'' was more than two years in the making. Maxis had originally
planned to give the game a 3-D perspective and let users view their
cities from street level. But that approach was abandoned midway
because it demanded more computer firepower than most home
computers could muster.
</P>
<P>
   For younger kids, there's a series of four new education games
released by Knowledge Adventure. The titles, part of the
``JumpStart'' series, are ``Reading for Second Graders,'' ``Learn
to Read,'' ``Math for Kindergartners'' and ``Math Mystery.'' These
games are designed to help kids master reading and math skills. The
games are all available for both Macs and PCs, if they have Windows
95 or Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Scuba diving enthusiasts can now read the popular magazine of
the sport, Skin Diver. The online version of the magazine offers
most of the same content as its printed counterpart. You'll also
find some games and the opportunity to buy scuba equipment and
trips online. This site is at http://www.skin-diver
</P>
<P>
   .com/LEindex2.asp.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
