<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virtual birds, dating tips come courtesy of e-mail
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a moment of abject stupidity, which is several
degrees dumber than my normal state of simple stupidity, I allowed
the whole world of public relations agents to access my e-mail
address.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, my mailbox is constantly stuffed with rubbish that
I never read past the first paragraph; at times the subject heading
is enough to prompt erasure.
</P>
<P>
   But every so often come gems of such surpassing brilliance that
I cannot but share them with you. The first came from an
all-purpose flack, or public relations agent, from whom I hear
several times weekly. Now, I did not make up what follows; I
haven't changed a word of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you can have a personal computer valet,'' he writes. ``For
under $100, you can command an animated parrot with built-in speech
recognition to navigate PC programs, monitor stocks, call friends
and associates over the Internet via a built-in Internet phone,
issue meeting reminders, warn of unexpected events on the stock
market and report news and weather. It is called Prody. If you
don't have a best friend, this is the closest thing to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can arrange a demo.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for me, you can't. I've had parrots. Parrots have large,
cruel beaks. They have voices, equaled only by those of a couple of
White House reporters I once knew, capable of cutting through a
quartet of jackhammers. I once observed a parrot clamber down from
its perch, work its way to the top of our breakfast table, sidle up
to my father's dinner plate and seize his hamburger steak. Dragged
that ground beef all the way back to the edge of the table and was
about to heave it over the side when Dad caught on.
</P>
<P>
   My computer gives me enough trouble now. I sure don't need it
coming on with a virtual parrot screeching, ``Prody wants a
megabyte!'' I don't have many friends, and I doubt I would keep
them by having my virtual parrot call them up at odd hours.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do I want ornithological hysteria the next time my 401(k)
takes a torpedo amidships.
</P>
<P>
   The same day I was offered a parrot demo, I got a book
announcement. The book is entitled ``How To Juggle Women,'' and
that intrigued me, because even after a year on the Internet this
is a fetish I'd never discovered.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, I misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This book is an essential guide for the seasoned dating man
who needs help organizing the women in his life,'' the announcement
said. ``Women are constantly grabbing your interest and attention.
Do you have to choose one over the other? Of course not! Stop
letting opportunities like these go to waste. Why not date them
all?
</P>
<P>
   ``You will learn time-saving techniques that will maximize your
availability, and allow you to spend time with several ladies a
day. The author details scheduling methods so you never have two
dates at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, women are certainly grabbing my interest and attention all
the time, and I could use some help organizing the women in my
life, chiefly my wife. My daughters and my granddaughters seem
pretty well organized.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the book will be of little use, since my dating
days ended 42 years ago this week, and I was scarcely what you'd
call seasoned. I manage to spend time with several ladies a day,
usually without making any of them mad, and without having to get
involved in tedious things like dating. They're friends, and as
long as I don't unleash virtual parrots upon them or buy books on
girl-juggling, they may remain so.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
