<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: We have a visually impaired student at our
middle school for whom we would like to borrow a three-dimensional
model of both the male and female reproductive systems to aid with
her instruction during the Human Growth and Development course. Can
you help us find a source? _ Mary Beth Huba, librarian
</P>
<P>
   A: The best I could do is the HEALTH EDCO catalog from WRS
Group, which makes the models. Call (800) 299-3366 for a catalog.
The ones I did locate must stay on premises, but perhaps your
student could make a field trip.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My dishwasher is apparently turning my new stainless
tableware dark. This is Oneida stainless, not the cheap stuff. Any
suggestions? _Georgia Reed
</P>
<P>
   A: Stainless, not stain-proof. The discoloration could be caused
by any number of things _ tea, coffee, vinegar, salt, etc. Pitting
and spotting may also be caused by hard water. Oneida recommends a
stainless cleaner to keep the flatware looking its best. One note
of caution regarding dishwashers and stainless steel: Oneida
advises customers to avoid detergents containing lemon. For more
information call (800) 877-6667. Q: Could you help me find the
elusive owner of a business that owes me compensation? _M. Baker
</P>
<P>
   A: The secretary of state's office, corporate division, provides
such information at 463-5555 or via e-mail, at
corpinfo(at)sos.state.tx.us. You may obtain the company's
registered agent, directors, addresses, date of incorporation, etc.
You may not be given the owner's name but you will have the name of
the president _ often the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our baby sitter went home to Venezuela for Christmas. There
has been some problem with her student visa and she can't return to
the states now. How does one go about becoming a sponsor for
someone to be a citizen? _S.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``There is no way for a nonrelative U.S. citizen to 'sponsor'
a foreign national for U.S. resident status or citizenship,'' says
Paul Parsons, an attorney board-certified in immigration and
nationality law. As part of the student visa application, a student
must convince a U.S. consular official that she can afford to study
in the United States without working unlawfully and that she
intends to return to the home country upon completion of the
studies. Reliance on U.S.-citizen friends for financial support
undermines both assertions.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news? ``Baby-sitting and other off-campus work is
normally unauthorized employment and a violation of student
status,'' says Parsons. Exceptions are made for changed
circumstances (currency devaluation, parent's loss of employment,
etc.). To seek U.S. citizenship, a foreign national must first
qualify for U.S. resident status and then wait five years to apply
through a process known as naturalization (only three years if
married to and residing with a U.S.-citizen spouse). Q: I'm
interested in learning how to draw like they do in Marvel-like
comic books. I have called comic book stores, commercial artists,
but none of them has what I'm looking for. _Zack Schenkkan
</P>
<P>
   A: Pick up a copy of ``Draw the Marvel Comics Super Heroes''
from Klutz Press _ that should give you a place to start. Local
classes are often given in the summer by cartoonists. Q: Why are
all the Subway sandwich shops that awful shade of yellow? Either
someone got ahold of some really cheap paint or they want you to
get out of there real fast. _Erin R.
</P>
<P>
   A: That yellow obviously works for Subway, which grew from Fred
DeLuca's one shop in Bridgeport, Conn., 30-plus years ago to nearly
13,600 worldwide now. In the QSR world (restaurant speak for
``quick service restaurant''), identification with the original is
the key to success. Hard to miss that yellow. Jim Huntley, local
Subway representative, says inspectors drop by to make sure each
franchise has not deviated from the prescribed decor. And yes, some
commercial designers admit colors are chosen to get the customer in
and out of fast food restaurants quickly. Q: What is the correct
Roman numeral for 1999? ESPN shows ``MCMXCIX,'' which is 1,000
followed by 100 less than 1,000, then 10 less than 100, then 1 less
than 10. What is wrong with ``MIM,'' which is 1,000 followed by 1
less than 1,000? _N. McConnell and K. Meyer
</P>
<P>
   A: MIM is acceptable today, according to Roger Osborn, professor
emeritus of mathematics at the University of Texas. Not always so.
In Julius Caesar's day, Roman numerals were strictly additive.
(Here's a primer for the novices: M &QC; 1,000, D &QC; 500, C &QC; 100, L &QC; 50,
X &QC; 10, V &QC; 5, I &QC; 1. Bonus: a bar over a Roman numeral multiplies it by
1,000.) So 1999 would have been correctly written MDCCCCLXXXXVIIII.
In the Middle Ages, convention allowed for the subtractive
principle, so nine could be written IX (one from 10) instead of
VIIII. Subtraction was permitted as long as numbers were within two
Roman numerals of each other _ i.e., you could subtract X (10) from
L (50) and C (100), but not from D (500). In the past 50 years or
so, subtracting any Roman numeral from another has been accepted.
``Only an absolute purist would disagree with MIM,'' notes Osborn.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was Bluegrass Roy? As a youngster I used to tune in to a
powerful little five-watter station from Nashville ( I believe) and
listen to this country-western singer. _Jaim Barr
</P>
<P>
   A: Bluegrass Roy was born Edward Leroy Freeman, according to
Skip Ogden of iBluegrass Magazine. The singer started his radio
career in Kentucky and traveled wherever his sponsor, Hamlin Oil,
sent him. Hamlin was a medicinal oil. For information on iBluegrass
Magazine, check out www.ibluegrass.com or call (252) 243-8700. Q:
We have a great view of the University of Texas Tower and
especially enjoy seeing it bathed in orange. Is there a key to
understanding what excites the tower light person to make that
happen? _Ed Nichols
</P>
<P>
   A: The complete tower turns orange with the number 1 lighted
when a Longhorn team wins an NCAA championship and to mark
achievement as determined by the university president. Variations?
Completely orange tower: a Big 12 team championship, defeat of
Texas A&AMP;M in football, an NIT championship, commencement, March 2
and July 4. Tower shaft white, observation and column decks orange:
football victories other than A&AMP;M, Big 12 tournament victories in
basketball and baseball, other postseason tournament wins, and on
Easter, Memorial Day, Thanksgiving and Christmas. White tower,
alternately orange and white observation and column decks: ties for
an NCAA team title, Big 12 championship or football game. Does your
view include the Erwin Center? It's orange after basketball
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ Here's a product that solves a travel problem for families,
hunters and campers. The Bumper Dumper hooks onto a trailer hitch
receiver and provides an instant restroom. No more poison ivy when
nature calls. Order by calling (818) 364-8242 or online at
www.bumperdumper.com.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
