fear that the memories of their parents' and grandparents'
generation will die with them, baby boomers are taking steps to
preserve their family histories. They're writing family memoirs,
taping parents telling favorite stories, and other measures to hold
onto a piece of their past. Many employ entrepreneurs who've tapped
onto a gold mine - a growing market for family stories, legends and
geneologies, many of which turn into books. There's even a
``roots'' service in Atlanta with its own web site. (Hendrick,
