<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5745 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     02-15 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND YOU THOUGHT IT WAS ALL OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The End.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK. It's not the end.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate's acquittal of President Clinton on two articles
of impeachment voted by the House of Representatives means that
Clinton will not be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   It does not mean, however, that we have heard the last of the
scandal that led to impeachment _ not by a long shot. The saga of
Monica and Bill is an industry, a self-sustaining media/political
phenomenon that has yet to run its course.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, independent counsel Ken Starr is still in
business. He reportedly believes that he has the authority to
indict Clinton before the president leaves office. A criminal
prosecution could keep the scandal fires burning until January 2001
_ and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   For another: Does anyone imagine that the many all-Monica
all-the-time TV programs will just turn off the lights and close up
shop? Is there any reason to suppose that anyone involved with the
scandal will resist the urge to write a book?
</P>
<P>
   Why, Monica Lewinsky's ex-friend Linda Tripp celebrated the end
of the impeachment trial by sitting down for an interview with The
New York Times and launching a tour of the TV talk-show circuit.
Tripp turned up Friday on ``Today.'' Next up: ``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   And everywhere that Linda goes, James Carville is sure to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'''s Katie Couric asked Carville _ Clinton's star
defender and chief Starr antagonist _ if he would bury the hatchet
after the president's acquittal in the Senate. Carville said sure,
he'd be glad to bury the hatchet _ bury it in Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Figuratively speaking, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melrose Place'' might be on its way to the TV graveyard, but
the soap opera in Washington is going strong. Maybe Geraldo Rivera
will add Heather Locklear to his stable of sassy blond
commentators.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed the scandal's latest episode, Clinton
prevailed by plenty in Friday's Senate vote. The first article of
impeachment prompted only 45 guilty votes as 10 Republicans joined
the Senate's 45 Democrats to give Clinton a walk on perjury
charges. On the second article, obstruction of justice, all 45
Democrats and five Republicans voted not guilty for a 50-50 tie
that deprived prosecutors of the simple majority they desperately
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The ``House managers,'' as the prosecutors were called, knew all
along that they would never drum up the 67 votes they needed for
conviction. But they could have claimed a moral victory if at least
51 senators had voted to remove the president.
</P>
<P>
   With the votes finally counted, some senators wanted to
``censure'' Clinton _ which means that even though they let him
keep the keys to the Oval Office, they wanted to adopt a formal
resolution expressing their disapproval of the president's behavior
during and after his fling with Lewinsky. Texas Sen. Phil Gramm
scuttled that effort by moving to table the censure proposal
``indefinitely'' _ which means ``forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm believes that censure is unconstitutional and a waste of
time. He has a point.
</P>
<P>
   The time to censure the president would have been late last year
when many members of the House _ Republicans as well as Democrats _
were eager to avoid impeachment proceedings. At that point, Clinton
probably would have signed on to a harshly worded rebuke, and all
concerned could have washed their hands of the whole deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton-haters in the House and their Clinton-hating
constituents back home wanted no part of censure. They wanted
impeachment _ and they had the votes to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   What they didn't have the votes to do was convict Clinton and
remove him from office once the impeachment moved to the Senate for
trial. The president needed 34 votes to beat the rap; it was
obvious to anyone with half a brain that he had them.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was pointless. The outcome was predetermined.
</P>
<P>
   But the outcome was valid. Most Americans didn't want Clinton
removed from office, and he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's get back to the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
