<HEADLINE>
BIG SUR'S ULTIMATE HILLSIDE HIDEAWAY
</HEADLINE>
 - INN-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG SUR _ If Valentine's Day has gotten you in the mood for a
romantic escape _ and if cost is not a pressing issue at the moment
_ the posh Ventana Inn has a lodging option that might be difficult
to resist.
</P>
<P>
   It's called the Sur House.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't heard of it before? Don't be embarrassed. That's by
design.
</P>
<P>
   You're not likely to find the Sur House while casually strolling
the 243 acres of Ventana's hillside resort on California's Central
Coast; no sign, no markers have been constructed to provide
direction to it. Neither will you locate it on the map that is
given to guests at check-in; this place is so exclusive it has been
left off the map.
</P>
<P>
   If you book it, you're shown the way to it, and thereafter it's
your own little secret.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a free-standing, two-story structure of rough cedar,
with polished knotty-pine floors. About 1,000 square feet. With a
fireplace in the open-beam living room, a full kitchen, and a king
bed in the loft bedroom. Its west-facing windows offer commanding
views of the Pacific Ocean. And on its very own redwood deck, there
is a hammock, chaise lounges for sunbathing ... and a swirling,
104-degree spa that would comfortably seat eight.
</P>
<P>
   Secluded? You can't imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people who come here basically to disengage, to relax,
to rejuvenate,'' said Sal Abaunza, general manager of the Ventana
Inn. ``Two days will restore that. We're very sensitive to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The resort _ with its Japanese baths, clothing-optional sun
decks, four-star restaurant and brochures that strongly and
unrepentantly urge you to leave your kids at home _ has a
well-earned reputation for providing delicious tranquillity for
those who have been worn to a nub by their big-city jobs. But the
Sur House carries the concept to a lavish extreme.
</P>
<P>
   It might be advisable to clear some room under your credit-card
ceiling, though. The Sur House rents for $725 a night, compared
with $340 for a standard room at the Ventana.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you get for that.
</P>
<P>
   After check-in, a bellman hops into a golf cart and asks you to
follow him in your car. After a while, he turns up a winding,
unmarked road and pulls to a stop at what appears to be a townhouse
in the woods. After showing you around _ the ready-to-light
firewood stack in the fireplace, the control for the jets in the
spa, the dimmer switches for just about every light in the place _
he takes off, and you're on your own. Delightfully so.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they'll bring breakfast to you in the morning, so you can
sip coffee and work on the standard Big Sur fare (granola, fruit,
plain yogurt, muffins) while the sun streams onto your deck. And if
you're not up to walking in the dark to the restaurant for dinner,
they'll send a golf cart to shuttle you.
</P>
<P>
   Words most commonly uttered in the Sur House: !ital!I could get
used to this.!off!
</P>
<P>
   Before long, you're mentally calculating what it would set you
back to lounge here for a week. Perhaps because it takes so little
time to feel settled in.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the deck, about a third of a cord of firewood is neatly
stacked, eagerly waiting to attack the damp coastal chill. Next to
the hearth, a bookcase holds a generous supply of Book of the Month
Club hardbacks, from romance novels to Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn and
James Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The interior decor is more rugged than rustic: overstuffed
couches, rattan chairs, casement windows, foot-square ceramic tiles
in buckskin hues.
</P>
<P>
   A vine, planted long ago at the corner of the house, has had its
tendrils trained to grow just beneath the upstairs windows, so that
when you look out on the ocean it is framed by a riot of
bright-green, waxy leaves. Even from the bathroom basins, the view
is breathtaking (which can be a bit perilous when you're brushing
your teeth).
</P>
<P>
   About the only drawback to the Sur House is its proximity to the
only road into the resort. A tall hedge shields you from prying
eyes, but the sound of vehicles climbing the mountain penetrates
this divider without much difficulty _ especially at about 7:45
a.m. when the resort employees come streaming onto the job.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not likely to be too great a nuisance, since the
eyelids tend to get heavy early in the evening in such environs.
</P>
<P>
   The place has the general feel of an exotic treehouse.
</P>
<P>
   On the final morning of a recent stay, when a deer wandered to
within 20 feet of the front gate, it became obvious the impression
is a universal one.
</P>
</TEXT>
