21 YEARS, 21 BEERS: HOW FOOLISH CAN YOU GET? (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By JACK Z. SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On my 21st birthday, I did something I would never do now.
</P>
<P>
   I drank 21 beers.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, I hadn't heard the term ``alcohol poisoning.'' I
didn't realize the danger in drinking so much. Fortunately, I drank
the beer over a long period, probably 10 hours or more, while
attending a college journalism conference.
</P>
<P>
   Why did I drink 21 beers? Perhaps to impress my peers with what
a macho, swinging guy I was. Perhaps to squelch my social
insecurities and fit in with other imbibing students. Perhaps to
see if I could drink that much.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, it was incredibly stupid, as I realized the next
morning when a fierce hangover laid me low. I didn't comprehend how
lucky I was. Had I drunk a little harder and faster, I could have
been dead.
</P>
<P>
   These days, on the cusp of 50 and eagerly awaiting my AARP card,
I'm Mr. Moderation. Nine days out of 10, I have a single cold one
after I get home from another brutal day at the keyboard. A
drinking binge is now two beers.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't thought about that 21st birthday for years. But tragic
events of recent days dredged up memories.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas A&AMP;M University in College Station, an 18-year-old
student died from head injuries after falling three stories in a
school parking garage. Police said he had more than twice the legal
limit of alcohol in his system.
</P>
<P>
   At Southwest Texas State University in San Marcos,
administrators suspended 12 fraternities after out-of-control
drinking at weekend frat parties. One student, an 18-year-old
graduate of Fort Worth's Paschal High School, was hospitalized for
severe alcohol poisoning and ``almost died,'' said Jim Studer,
Southwest's vice president of student affairs.
</P>
<P>
   A 21-year-old fraternity pledge was beaten to death at a frat
house in the wake of another party that included heavy drinking.
The prime murder suspect, a 21-year-old former Southwest student,
shortly thereafter committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the nation, binge drinking on college campuses is a
chronic problem, as documented in studies by the Harvard School of
Public Health. The consequences can be disastrous _ students
killing themselves or others in car wrecks, students engaging in
unprotected sex or becoming victims of date rape, or students
flunking school because drinking becomes a bigger priority than
hitting the books.
</P>
<P>
   How do you stop the problem?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the $64 million question,'' said Angie Taylor, director
of alcohol and drug education at Texas Christian University in Fort
Worth. ``If we knew the answer, everyone would be doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor and Southwest's Studer say colleges can reduce the
problem by various means. There can be tough punishment for
fraternities or other organizations that foster unbridled drinking;
education programs to inform students about alcohol's dangers; and
individual counseling for problem drinkers wanting help.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can help by setting ``some real clear expectations as to
what's acceptable and unacceptable behavior,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   For parents, being a good role model ``is more important than
anything,'' she said. If Dad gets smashed every weekend, he'll have
much less credibility in admonishing Junior not to drink
excessively at college.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has been dismayed to learn of some parents asking
resident assistants in dormitories where their newly enrolling son
or daughter can get fake IDs to buy booze.
</P>
<P>
   A major contributor to runaway student drinking is a ``cultural
perception'' that ``that's what you do when you're in college,''
Taylor said. ``We call that the `Animal House' mentality,'' she
said, in reference to the 1978 John Belushi comedy featuring
raucous frat boys.
</P>
<P>
   TCU is launching a new program that will utilize student
athletes to warn against heavy drinking and help counter the idea
that it's cool to get plastered.
</P>
<P>
   After the 18-year-old Aggie student fell to his death on Jan.
30, my oldest daughter, Amanda, a junior at A&AMP;M, reported on the
tragedy for the school newspaper. She has friends who drink but has
always personally shunned alcohol and seems acutely aware of its
perils.
</P>
<P>
   She turns 21 this year. I'm thankful that she's smarter than her
old man.
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Z. Smith is an editorial writer and columnist for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7724, or e-mail:
jzsmith(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
