<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5843 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AWARDS-SITES-LADN     02-15 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AWARDS-SITES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR.COM LEADS THE PARADE OF AWARD SITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Editors: CalArts Web address in 11th graf requires a tilde).  
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I'd like to thank my information agent ...
</P>
<P>
   Just as in Hollywood, it's award season in the worlds of new
media, though unlike the movie biz, there's no clear must-get
honor.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to see what some folks think are the best sites
around, there are a couple of places to start. But first something
for the awards-show traditionalist. Last week, the ABC Internet
Group and the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences launched
Oscar.com to track all the events leading up to the big show March
21.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers such goodies for movie buffs as a complete list
of nominees, synopses of nominated films, academy history, and
photo galleries of past winners, Oscar fashions and splashy
arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   ABC and the academy also promise to add trivia games, a database
of past winners and nominees, a producer's journal of show
preparations and much more.
</P>
<P>
   The site also will carry a live Webcast of the Oscars on awards
night, though as the recent Victoria's Secret fashion show
demonstrated, it'll still be a while before you willingly choose
the Webcast over the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   And if Oscar just isn't enough for your awards-night jones, try
these Web award sites:
</P>
<P>
   You can start with the Webbies, which used to be sponsored by a
really fine little magazine called the Web. But the Web (the
magazine) had as much trouble devising a viable economic model as
any of the sites it wrote about. And without the insanely large
stock-market valuations keeping those sites afloat, it died an
untimely death.
</P>
<P>
   The Webbies live on, however, at www.webbyawards.com, thanks to
the good folks over at the International Academy of Digital Arts
and Sciences, which has already announced 110 nominees. The awards
will be handed out March 18 in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Webbies, among the best art site nominees is one
by Amy Alexander, a film and video professor at the California
Institute for the Arts in Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's Multi-Cultural Recycler (at
shoko.calarts.edu/(tilde)alex/recycler.html) cuts and pastes
together instant collages based on images from the dozens of
Webcams that show everything from naked homebodies to the Hollywood
sign to coffeemakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cameras provide documentation, surveillance and a very
specific representation of the camera owners and their
surroundings,'' Alexander said. ``Ordinary people and places around
the world are instantly subject to becoming part of the mass
culture and are potentially also subject to cultural recycling.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, once you have the machine create a collage from the
images taken from randomly selected Webcams, the site is posted in
a gallery, where it, too, can be further recycled by the next
visitor.
</P>
<P>
   If the Webbies and Alexander's work aren't enough to elevate
your appreciation for the World Wide Web, the folks at Cool Site of
the Day (www.coolsiteoftheday.com) not only hand out daily
recognition categories, they also have an annual best-of contest.
</P>
<P>
   The Cool Sites staff pick the nominees, then Web denizens do the
actual final voting. Check 'em out at
http://www.coolsiteoftheday.com.
</P>
<P>
   In the video-gaming business, the Flights of Fantasy awards have
already gone out, spotlighting the best games on consoles such as
Sony PlayStation, Nintendo 64 and Sega Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   Konami's Metal Gear Solid was the biggest winner, pulling down
awards for game of the year, best adventure game, story development
and sound. Two of the game's creative talents, Hideo Kahima and
David Hayter, were honored for individual achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Other big awards included Capcom's Resident Evil 2 for best
action game; THQ's Rugrats Adventure for best children's game;
Namco's Tekken 3 for best fighting game; THQ's Devil Dice (a
personal favorite) for best puzzle game; Sega's Panzer Dragoon Saga
(the only Saturn title of recent note) as best role-playing game;
and EA Sports' Madden NFL 99 for best sports game.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo's Pokemon (which still consumes my children's attention
almost six months after its release) proved to be no pocket monster
on the Game Boy, getting honored for innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo also scored an award for game design for the great
Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time, which otherwise was shut out
despite nine nominations, the most of any title. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
