<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Feb. 16:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WARM-AGES (Undated) _ New evidence has caused scientists to
change their minds about the next ice age. They now suspect that
the present warm period could last much longer that originally
believed _ another 10,000 to 20,000 years, or even longer, citing
new evidence, in the form of chemical tracers of past climates
contained in deep-ocean sediments. By William K. Stevens. (1850
words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ICELAND-GENES (Reykjavik) _ In a brave new experiment that
is being closely watched around the world, Iceland's 270,000
residents are poised to share the genealogical, genetic and medical
information that makes them who they are for the goal of advancing
science. Their homogenous nature makes the experiment even more
important. But the audacity of the plan _ and what it bodes for the
future _ has provoked a bitter battle both within and outside of
Iceland and put the nation at the forefront of a world debate over
the ethics and uses of genetic research. (2100 words) By Sarah
Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EMOTIONAL-FORECASTS (Undated) _ People make emotional
forecasts every day in routine decision-making, deciding whether an
action with will make them happier. But often, scientists report,
those forecasts are wrong. By Philip J. Hilts. (1690 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NSF-COLWELL (Undated) _ A conversation with Dr. Rita
Colwell, the first woman and the first biological scientist to head
the National Science Foundation. She discusses her education in the
'50s, her achievements in fighting cholera in developing nations,
and possible research at the foundation. By Claudia Dreifus. (1675
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTARCTIC-BIKE (Undated) _ Students and researchers are
working to design a bicycle for conditions on Antarctica, where
winter temperatures average minus 76. Their efforts are part of a
bigger project to create a more pleasing and productive work
environment on the ice. By Warren E. Leary. (950 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EYE-SURGERY (Undated) _ In recent years, after the
pioneering work of Dr. Relya Zivojnovic in Belgium, surgery has
brought back sight to people with more and more extreme injuries.
Eyes once written off as hopeless now are functioning. By Philip J.
Hilts. (475 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ In recent decades, families and
physicians have begun to discuss the subject of death and dying
more openly, but wide gaps remain between what patients want for
their last days and what doctors and other health professionals
think they want. By Jane E. Brody. (1225 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MIDLIFE (Undated) _ Far from being a time of turmoil, for
many people the midlife years appear to be a time of psychic
equanimity, good health, productive activity and community
involvement, a team of MacArthur researchers found. The years
between 35 and 65, and in particular the decades between 40 and 60,
the defining period of midlife, are a time when people report
increased feelings of well-being, and a greater sense of control
over many parts of their lives. By Erica Goode. (1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Women's upright posture may be responsible for for their high
rate of injuries in sports like soccer. A study showed the tended
to crouch less, causing ligament strain. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pro and con: Do all post-menopausal women need a cervical Pap
smear every year? (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Car surfing, standing on the top of a car of hooking on with
skates, is killing young people. Safety authorities are trying to
get the word out. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Italian researchers believe sleep deprivation may lead to
heart attacks and strokes. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STRESS (Undated) _ The chemistry of anxiety and
pharmaceuticals remains a mystery to professionals, who ponder just
which one has the greater effect on a patient. By Abigail Zuger,
M.D. (880 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-SNOWBOARDING (Undated) _ The dangers and techniques
of snowboarding. By Gary Taubes. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHAIN-LETTER (Undated) _ An Internet chain letter tells
faculty of the fast track to tenure. By David DeMers. (450 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: On sleeping with
one eye open, as birds do; overestimating the danger of radon and
some termites' capacity to eat lots of fiber and produce little
methane.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Will I grow up
to be short like my mother or tall like my father? Your adult
height will probably be somewhere in between; some formulas for
calculating it. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
