 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, Feb. 16,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEXICO _ MEXICO CITY _ Covering the president in Mexico.
(Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-GENOCIDE _ PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ Sitting on a
bamboo-slatted bench, widow But Lin crumbled dried lumps of cooked
rice in a basket and talked about what she wants to happen to the
Khmer Rouge leaders who brutalized her country. Twenty years after
the Khmer Rouge fell from power, a day of judging them approaches.
But Lin hopes it will put her anger to rest. A United Nations team
of three legal experts is scheduled this month to recommend to
Secretary General Kofi Annan whether to start action against the
remaining Khmer Rouge leaders living openly in Cambodia. Some form
of international tribunal likely will be proposed to hear evidence
against the men who masterminded the madness that left as many as
two million Cambodians dead in less than four years, from 1975 to
1979.
</P>
<P>
   (Kunstel-Albright, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: ETA: Noon.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-SENATE _ WASHINGTON _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, seriously
considering a run for the U.S. Senate in New York next year, will
have to consult more than public opinion polls. The first lady's
first-of-its-kind candidacy would raise novel legal questions for
attorneys to sort out. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JASPERDEATH-TRIAL _ JASPER, Texas _ Testimony begins Tuesday in
the Jasper dragging death. This story focuses on pre-trial
developments. (Brooks, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MARDIGRAS-BANDS _ NEW ORLEANS _ High school bands are a major
part of the Mardi Gras parades. Some have become important parts of
modern Mardi Gras history and have demanding training programs to
prepare them for the annual six-mile hike. We focus on a
predominantly black band that was the first to march in the once
all-white Rex parade. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATURES
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS SKOLVOUCHERS _ The push is on, once again, for a
voucher plan in Texas. But the politics are trickier, and perhaps
more treacherous, than ever before. Pete Laney, Speaker of the
House, has become more vocal about his criticism, and some say he
stacked the House Public Education Committee to reflect his
stronger and more public stance against vouchers. (Keyed to
pro-voucher rally Tuesday.) (Brooks, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-JUDICIALELECTIONS _ A bill lobbied by Chief Justice
Tom Phillips would make judicial elections nonpartisan and publicly
finance top judicial posts _ a radical isea not just in Texas but
for most states. Phillips' proposal answers criticism brought by
the latest 60 Minutes scrutiny of the Texas judicial selection
process. (McCarthy, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
