u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-SENATE16-COX-     02-15 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SENATE16-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRST LADY AS CANDIDATE RAISES LEGAL ISSUES
 &HT;    Eds: Adds 2nd graf with Clinton comment; other minor editing.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, seriously considering a run
for the U.S. Senate in New York next year, will have to consult
more than public opinion polls. The first lady's first-of-its-kind
candidacy would raise novel legal questions for attorneys to sort
out.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of a race gained steam Monday when President Clinton
said, ``I think she would be terrific in the Senate ... but it's
her decision to make. I will support whatever decision she makes
enthusiastically.'' Clinton was speaking during a break in a
meeting with President Ernesto Zedillo in Merida, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   If she hits the campaign trail, would Mrs. Clinton take her
usual entourage of White House staff and Secret Service agents,
whose traveling expenses would be charged to taxpayers? If so,
would her campaign have to defray some of the costs?
</P>
<P>
   Already, Mrs. Clinton is planning extensive travel on behalf of
the president's Social Security and Medicare proposals and to
promote historic preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Could she shuttle to and from New York aboard her Air Force jet,
and from speech to speech in a motorcade of government cars? And
could she justify the public costs by adding non-partisan ``first
lady'' appearances to her campaign travels?
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be pretty much new territory,'' said Ian Stirton,
spokesman for the Federal Election Commission, which oversees
campaign election laws and financing. ``I imagine a lot of lawyers
will be working on that.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has begun that work yet, according to the first lady's
press secretary Marsha Berry, who agreed that the legal research
would be needed if Mrs. Clinton decides to become a candidate. But
``none of that has happened,'' said Berry, because ``she's not
there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, which is urging
the first lady to seek a Democratic seat being vacated by Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, spokeswoman Kerin Polla also acknowledged
the unanswered legal points. ``It's never been done before,'' she
said of having a first lady as candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of a president running for re-election, the rules
are fairly well established, said the FEC's Stirton. The taxpayers
get the bill for the security, the limousines and the jet
designated Air Force One that always accompany the chief executive.
Political parties pay a small portion of the enormous costs of a
president's fund raising or political travels.
</P>
<P>
   But the first lady's situation is less clear, since she holds no
constitutional position, Stirton said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other potential issues, the Clintons have built up an
extensive list of well-wishers and others on a White House computer
database. Could the first lady use that information to raise money
or build support for her Senate campaign?
</P>
<P>
   ``If some of the cost was generated by taxpayer dollars, there
could be problems,'' Stirton said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the fact that Mrs. Clinton does not live in New York
is hardly a problem at all. The residency requirement for Senate
candidates in the state is so lenient that she need only establish
an address there by election day. In recent decades, New Yorkers
have elected two senators, Robert F. Kennedy and James Buckley, who
had very shallow roots in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Published news reports already have Mrs. Clinton's agents
scouring Manhattan's posh West Side for an apartment, amid denials
from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Berry has offered no hints on what her boss will do. ``Everybody
just needs to relax,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   White House chief of staff John Podesta said Sunday on ABC-TV's
``This Week'' that Mrs. Clinton is ``going to talk to the people
who have been urging her to run, think about it. But I will tell
you one thing: I think that if she does run, she will win.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
