<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5931 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTIMACY-AZR &LR;      02-15 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTIMACY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTIMACY: RELATIONSHIPS CAN'T BE BUILT ON SEX ALONE  
 (WITH INTIMACY-SIDE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUG CARROLL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It is one of the great ironies of our culture.
Approximately 30 years after the sexual revolution in America, we
claim to be so enlightened about sex, yet we remain so ignorant
about intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Our national obsession with sex has resurfaced all over again in
the past few months with the Clinton-Lewinsky affair in full view.
For something we still find so difficult to talk about in private,
sex continues to receive very public preoccupation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton thing has raised awareness,'' says therapist
Marilyn Murray of Psychological Counseling Services in Scottsdale,
Ariz. ``People are re-evaluating what they thought about
sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, perhaps intimacy finally will receive sufficient
discourse. Murray says that a relationship's cord consists of four
strands of intimacy _ intellectual, emotional, spiritual and
physical _ and if any one of the strands is damaged, so, too, is
the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this is more complex than we've been willing to admit
to ourselves. If sex is a sprint, then intimacy is a marathon for
which our society of instant gratification seems to have little
interest in training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexuality is an incredibly complicated area,'' says Murray's
colleague, Ralph Earle, who estimates that the Psychological
Counseling Services practice he founded is ``more than 50 percent''
devoted to sexual issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible for a couple to have good emotional intercourse
and not have a satisfying sex life, just as it's possible to have
lots of physical intercourse and not have a good relationship.
Those things have stayed the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, described by Earle as an ``emotional heart surgeon,''
conducts programs that have drawn intimacy-challenged clients to
the Valley from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``intensives,'' these typically require a couple's
participation in what amounts to a jump-start for a faltering
relationship for a full week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always start out by saying that as human beings, one of our
greatest desires is for intimacy,'' Murray says. ``We're made that
way. The physical part often comes along as a result of the other
three being very good. The lifelong successes are those who've
developed the other three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex alone usually doesn't do it. When we get any couple in
here, I almost never start at the physical. I say, `Tell me where
you are in these other three areas.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotional intimacy is the one we end up working the most on.
Often they're not sharing what they think or feel, even about the
average, everyday types of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The renowned sex therapists William Masters and Virginia Johnson
addressed this deeper level of love almost 25 years ago in their
book ``The Pleasure Bond: A New Look at Sexuality and
Commitment.'' &QL; 
GROW OR DIE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Intimacy must be nourished by a mutuality between a man and a
woman that may include, but must go beyond, the physical fact of
intercourse,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intimacy, like any other emotion, must either grow and become
deeper or it must wither and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Men and women often define intimacy quite differently, says
Earle, a former minister who trained with Masters and Johnson
before going into private practice in 1970. He is considered a
national expert on sexual addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men usually use the word `intimacy' for `sex,' '' Earle says.
``Women will not use it that way. The problem is that a person may
think he is being intimate when he's not being intimate at all. It
happens in many, many situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to get a couple to define what would be satisfying in
(begin ital) emotional (end ital) intercourse. It can be tough to
get men to work through those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Murray has observed a shift in traditional roles in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a person who's more analytical, they'll be the
person who is less emotional _ male or female,'' she says. ``The
one who's more artistic, freer with emotion, that's the one who
wants and demands a lot more intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we see men saying `I'm the one who talks about feelings.'
That's kind of exciting, to see men step up to the plate and be
initiators.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve and Terri, an East Valley couple in their 40s, discovered
that they were in an unhealthy relationship shortly after they
married in 1991. &QL; 
BREAKING DOWN BARRIERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After three years of struggling for some semblance of intimacy,
they found themselves in one of Murray's intensives.
</P>
<P>
   When Murray first met Steve and Terri, she had them sized up
within minutes. Steve's difficult relationship with his mother and
his two previous marriages had convinced him that love equals pain.
</P>
<P>
   He was battle-weary, and it was obvious that his barriers were
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terri was trying to break down my walls, and I'm sitting there
throwing hand grenades at her,'' says Steve, who had a pattern of
verbally abusing his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to realize that this stuff wasn't about her, and I had
to quit trying to bring it into the relationship. I learned that,
yes, there are some people in life who've hurt me. But she's not
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked at how she loved me, (I saw that) she loved me
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray and the Psychological Counseling Services staff also
worked with Terri, who had been married once before, on learning to
set boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   A classic pleaser, she always pursued Steve whenever he
retreated from her. Their come-here, go-away pas de deux was
maddening for both of them.
</P>
<P>
   Over time _ ``They needed a forklift for our file,'' Terri said,
joking _ the work done in therapy began to take hold. Steve
realized that it was safe to let Terri love him and that intimacy
was his responsibility as well as hers.
</P>
<P>
   But their marriage still wasn't good enough for the newly
emboldened Terri, who says the couple existed as roommates for so
long that she was about to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The abuse had stopped, but I had to say `I know we can do
better than this,' '' she recalls. ``The marriage was bland, it was
boring for both of us. We were stuck in a flat, boring,
not-terrible marriage _ like a lot of people.'' &QL; 
A WAKE-UP CALL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Terri's threat to leave Steve for good _ they had separated
before for a brief period _ was the wake-up call he needed to put
forth an extra effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I discovered this was what I wanted and that there was a
huge danger of losing it,'' he says, ``I began to get real serious
that something had to change.''
</P>
<P>
   What kept them going through the ordeal, they say, was the
belief of Murray and the other counselors that they truly loved
each other. Through it all, even the worst parts, the couple
managed to faithfully schedule their weekly date night, getting
away from their blended family of three children to spend time
together.
</P>
<P>
   Terri says she made the important discovery that intimacy must
work first on an individual level before it can have a chance in a
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a single mom,'' she says, ``I was (begin ital)
doing (end ital) instead of (begin ital) being. (end ital) How can
you develop intimacy with another if you don't have time to spend
with yourself?
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to know yourself takes time. You need to create those
quiet spaces in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray says it's possible for our society to get intimacy right
if we want to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope for healing is greater today than it's ever been,''
she insists, saying that advances in counseling have paralleled
those in medicine. ``The knowledge is there, but are people willing
to take advantage of it?''
</P>
<P>
   A good start might be a radical change in our orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the mystique of seeing sex as special or intimate has
been lost,'' Murray says. ``People take sex for granted, rather
than seeing it as something beautiful, designed to bring a couple
together in the deepest way.
</P>
<P>
   ``A healthy sexual relationship starts in the mind. What have
you done to build a good, healthy relationship all the way around?
It's being sensitive and caring in all these other areas, that's
what ends up making sex good. Then it's making love instead of just
having sex.''
</P>
<P>
   What's holding us back, then?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are afraid to risk revealing ourselves,'' says
Terri, looking back on her own experience. ``We're so
self-protective. We've had all this exposure to sex, but we've also
been inundated with a type of psychology where we just protect
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're too afraid to say, `Here's who I really, truly am. This
is the pain I've been through. This is what I love. This is what I
think about when I'm alone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody sells intimacy,'' Steve says. ``But everybody sells sex
_ we're inundated by it. Where do you see modeled a good intimate
relationship?''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Steve and Terri, it seems that we just did. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
