<SLUG> BC-INTIMACY-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY I'M COMMITTED TO BEING CELIBATE  
 (SIDEBAR TO INTIMACY) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUG CARROLL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I am a 42-year-old divorced man. I'm not having sex
with anyone, nor will I until I remarry. That's (begin ital) if
(end ital) I remarry.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this means there's a chance I will not have sex for the
rest of my life.
</P>
<P>
   You probably think I'm strange, and you'd better believe I feel
that way sometimes. The celibate lifestyle I've chosen for myself
is a struggle, but obviously I'm convinced it's right for me or I
wouldn't be committed to it.
</P>
<P>
   And I certainly wouldn't be sharing it with 600,000 of my
closest friends, as I am here.
</P>
<P>
   Why should you care?
</P>
<P>
   You should if you've had trouble building true intimacy in
relationships. I'm talking about getting to know someone from the
inside out, soul to soul, no shortcuts. Isn't that what we all long
for _ someone with whom we connect on the deepest possible level?
</P>
<P>
   Sex often gets in the way of that, if we're telling ourselves
the truth. Sex can arrest the development of a relationship, giving
us a false sense of closeness to someone. Just because we're close
physically doesn't mean we're in even the same area code
emotionally or spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   In a mate, I want intimacy in (begin ital) all (end ital)
respects and won't settle for less. Can't have that? The bar's too
high? Fine, I'll stay single and celibate.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I know what you're thinking: ``This guy is a geek! He's
probably just a nerd who can't get a woman!''
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, I could be having sex. Women enjoy my company _ and
I enjoy theirs. In fact, knowing that I won't be having sex unless
I'm married again frees me to really get to know women as people,
not as mere objects of desire.
</P>
<P>
   Do women think this is weird? I'm sure some of them do. And I'm
equally sure some do not, agreeing that it's worth the wait. For
the right woman, this would be the best wedding gift I could give
her. If that sounds quaint, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   You see, it's not that sex isn't important to me. On the
contrary, it's important enough that I want to protect my heart and
the heart of someone special. Once this bridge is crossed in a
relationship, there's no turning back without considerable pain.
</P>
<P>
   I've learned some difficult lessons there; I'm sure many of us
have. It's our own fault if we don't apply what we've learned.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, how can I instruct my son, now 9, to abstain if I'm
not doing so myself? He will see right through me and would be
correct in calling me a hypocrite. If he is to become a man of
integrity, it must begin with me.
</P>
<P>
   Do I miss having sex? Are you nuts? Of course I do! How could
anyone (begin ital) not (end ital) miss such a profound expression
of human emotion? I do my best to channel that energy into other
areas. Daily exercise, for one, helps in easing the tension. So
does meditation. It's a challenge, and I won't pretend that it's
not.
</P>
<P>
   If you still think I'm strange, I understand. Clearly, this is a
road less traveled in our sex-saturated society.
</P>
<P>
   However, one of the best things I've discovered about midlife is
that I don't care so much anymore about what others may think. I'm
me _ and I like it. I'm through with apologizing for who I am.
</P>
<P>
   If your conscience is telling you to wait on sex, then its voice
is the only one you should listen to. It doesn't matter where
you've been; this is about where you're going.
</P>
<P>
   Now you know you're not going there alone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Doug Carroll can be reached at doug.carroll(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
