<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT MADE THE DIFFERENCE FOR THE '98 S&AMP;P 500 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: If you peruse Tuesday's stock tables regularly, you may
wonder how in the world the market's major indicators turned in
such magnificent performances last year.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Dow Jones industrial average, which had a respectable
gain of 16.1 percent. This venerable group of 30 blue-chip stocks
is really too narrow a gauge to be a good proxy for the overall
market.
</P>
<P>
   The 26.7 percent surge by the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, on
the other hand, would seem a much better measure of how the market
fared. The same goes for the Nasdaq composite, which was up 39.6
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Given the impressive performance of the S&AMP;P 500 and Nasdaq
composite, the annual-return numbers in the right-hand column of
Tuesday's stock tables are a puzzlement. Those columns in recent
weeks reveal at least as many losers as winners, which might lead
casual observers to wonder how aggregate performances could have
been so strong given all the apparent individual weakness.
</P>
<P>
   A recent analysis by Dean Investment Associates sheds some light
on how misleading the S&AMP;P 500 performance was last year.
</P>
<P>
   Only slightly more than 56 percent of the S&AMP;P 500 stocks
recorded gains in share price last year. Many of the stocks that
were either flat or losers weren't dogs, either. They included such
corporate luminaries as Allstate, BankAmerica, Coca-Cola, Delta Air
Lines, Disney, DuPont, Gillette, Marriott, Merrill Lynch, 3M, J.P.
Morgan and Sears.
</P>
<P>
   Given the disappointing performance of these top-drawer
companies, the obvious question is how the S&AMP;P 500 managed an
increase that was far better than its average gains since the late
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, the Dean analysis explains, has to do with the way
the S&AMP;P 500 is weighted by market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Although the index itself rose 26.7 percent last year, the
average increase for an S&AMP;P 500 stock was only 10.9 percent. More
tellingly, the median stock was up only 4.3 percent. This means
half rose more and half rose less (or declined).
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit for the overall index's spectacular showing
goes to Microsoft. Its market value more than doubled, and the
resulting $170 billion gain more than covered the slippage of 165
S&AMP;P 500 stocks with market values of under $10 billion that
declined in value last year.
</P>
<P>
   Although a universe of 500 stocks implies a broad-based
measurement, just over 44 percent of the S&AMP;P's return last year was
accounted for by Microsoft, Wal-Mart, GE, Lucent, Cisco, IBM,
Intel, Dell, Pfizer and Merck.
</P>
<P>
   Without the value gains of those companies, which make up only 2
percent of the 500 components, Dean notes, the
capitalization-weighted return for the index is less than 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   What's the lesson here for investors? If you buy a mutual fund
structured to track the S&AMP;P 500, you're not as diversified as you
may imagine. Your index fund is, as a practical matter, excessively
dependent on the stock performance of a relatively small number of
giant companies. Those companies in recent years, fortunately, have
been going like gangbusters.
</P>
<P>
   If this trend peters out, however, many index fund investors
will discover they're a lot more vulnerable to stock market
downdrafts than they realized.
</P>
</TEXT>
