<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIO GRANDE AREA IS HARD ON HUMANS, BUT FINE FOR FOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH TEXAS _ At half past 5 o'clock, the sun still is an hour
from setting, but already, as shadows grow longer, there's a touch
of evening coolness in the air.
</P>
<P>
   In the basin of a dry pond, ringed close around by mesquite and
scrub, we come upon another transient camp with scattered papers,
the stubs of smokes, empty five-gallon plastic water jugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio Grande is just 100 straight-line miles to the south.
From the air, we're told, one actually can see paths beaten not by
the hooves of animals but by the feet of people pouring north
across the border in relentless waves, driven by need, drawn by
hope.
</P>
<P>
   Their way leads through this area we've been hunting. And the
hidden resting places _ of which we've run across a dozen or more,
all abandoned _ are squalid way stations on a journey that must
come, in many cases, to a desperate end.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of quail hunters from the Middle West, the
experience in this harsh and prickly piece of country has been a
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everything here,'' said our host, John Howe, ``will
either stick you, scrape you, sting you or bite you.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's true, the first impression is mainly of dust and
thorns. Yet the variety and abundance of wildlife the land supports
is amazing.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, when we came back from lunch and our
heat-of-midday break, we found that one of John's friends had taken
a feral pig, a great coal-black, bristly brute.
</P>
<P>
   Armadillos, faster afoot than you'd imagine from their shape,
scampered away to the side of the hunting car and disappeared
behind cactus clumps.
</P>
<P>
   Peccaries, the pig's native relative, could be seen ghosting
through the thickets ahead. In the bright sky turned a white-headed
hawklike bird that John called a Mexican eagle. Deer were
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   And such quail!
</P>
<P>
   By this day's end we'll have seen 14 coveys. In all, in one full
day and parts of two others, there'll have been 25 coveys. It's the
kind of hunting that in many regions is barely remembered.
</P>
<P>
   John's wife, Linda, has driven out from town to spend this last
hour with us.
</P>
<P>
   She and their friend Conley Juban ride together in Conley's
Jeep. John leads the way in his magnificent wheeled schooner, the
open hunting vehicle he himself designed and built for following
the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Low to the west, the sun paints red the undersides of the
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more covey,'' John says. ``Just one to end the day.''
</P>
<P>
   The light begins to fail. Then, at the very last, there's a dog
on point ahead, and another backing. We walk in behind them, and
the birds come up _ fine big covey of 15 or more.
</P>
<P>
   But the quail are only quick things half-seen, twisting through
mesquite branches in the blue of evening. And no one shoots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd better dress our birds here in the field,'' John says.
</P>
<P>
   Unfastening a latch on the side of the vehicle, he lowers a
hinged panel to create a working table. In doing so, he reveals the
wheeled schooner's final miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we've put the guns away, maybe somebody would care
for a refreshment. Bring the ice, Conley,'' John Howe says.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the hinged panel is a well-stocked bar.
</P>
<P>
   After Texas, quail hunting may never seem the same again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
