NYT-02-15-99 1634EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5952 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLINGS-SEARCH-2NDTA     02-15 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLINGS-SEARCH-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ gun, Fern says.
</P>
<P>
   He never pulled a gun. Instead, he began sharpening the butcher
knife.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going after Nettie and Jake,'' Fern says, referring to
Nettie's beau. ``He was going to kill that S.O.B.''
</P>
<P>
   Fern, then 11, huddled with sister Norma, 13. They decided Norma
should go for help. She slipped out the kitchen door and called
police about 11 p.m. from a neighbor's house. Feigning calm, Fern
took Linda to a rocking chair and fed her milk from a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   When the police walked in with Norma, Oldham was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   One of the officers asked: ``What's going on here, Mr. Oldham?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' he answered. ``I'm just sharpening a knife here for
the girls to use in the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   He sure could think fast on his feet, Ed says.
</P>
<P>
   The officers checked the kitchen cupboards and found them bare.
A former neighbor says Oldham took off running through the woods
behind the house. Fern doesn't remember that. She remembers that
they handcuffed her dad.
</P>
<P>
   The children rode in a police car to the juvenile detention
center, where each received fresh clothes.
</P>
<P>
   According to newspaper accounts, Oldham refused to answer police
questions the next morning. Police considered sending him to a
hospital for observation but instead released him to the custody of
two brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Losing her mother, and then being isolated from her family in an
orphanage, was especially hard on Fern, a mama's girl. She lived on
the second floor while Norma was housed on the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't allowed to visit back and forth,'' Fern said. ``The
only time we got to visit was if we saw each other out in the yard.
That just about killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the knife incident, their father cared enough to visit
the children occasionally at their foster homes and orphanages.
</P>
<P>
   One year _ Fern thinks it was 1947 _ most of the family shared
Easter at an aunt and uncle's house. That's the last time Fern
remembers seeing Linda, who had a burn on her bottom from sitting
on a hot furnace grate.
</P>
<P>
   Ed's last memory of Linda is different. He is unsure of the
date. His father picked up him and his brother, Bud, at their
orphanage and took them to Linda's foster home. That's where Ed
remembers Linda crawling down stairs backward.
</P>
<P>
   The memories are so old, and Linda was so young, that neither
Fern nor Ed is certain of the color of her eyes or hair.
</P>
<P>
   One day Fern and Norma were taken from their orphanage to see
their caseworker. Her message was short: Linda had been adopted by
a well-to-do Kansas City area family.
</P>
<P>
   Fern remembers thinking: ``Gee, she's gone. We'll never find
her.''
</P>
<P>
   She believes Linda was between 2 and 3 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Their father opposed the adoption because he didn't want to lose
Linda, Fern says. He died at a Kansas City boarding house in 1953,
when he was 50. No one performed an autopsy, so the cause of death
was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Fern and Norma discussed finding Linda in the mid-1960s but
didn't know where to turn. Older sister Nettie opposed their
search. Fern is unsure why.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Fern enlisted help from her children and her
husband. They searched records, wrote the courts, drove through the
old neighborhood. But they turned up nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Ed called the family's former caseworker in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are calling to ask me any questions about Linda,'' she
said, ``I can't tell you anything, and I won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed told her, ``Have a good life,'' and hung up.
</P>
<P>
   Most early searching was wasted, Fern says, because they had
Linda's birth date and foster family name wrong.
</P>
<P>
   An aunt thought Linda had stayed with someone named Bybee, not
McBee. Not until Nettie died in 1995 did Fern find that photograph
with the correct name on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Even that avenue appears to be of little help.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Scott and Estaline McBee cared for Linda, first on Quincy
and later in Independence. A phone call to a McBee in the current
Kansas City phone book helped unravel the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Estaline McBee liked Linda so much she kept three pictures of
the baby until she died in 1987. One is a 5-by-7-inch enlargement
hand-tinted to show Linda with blue eyes and a pink smock. McBee's
youngest daughter discovered the pictures in a box of her mother's
belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked in with the photographs was a yellowed newspaper clipping
from Jan. 11, 1946. It shows the six Oldham children the morning
after they were taken from their father.
</P>
<P>
   So Estaline McBee, who kept many foster children over the years,
had known Linda's background.
</P>
<P>
   But if she knew who adopted Linda, she left no clues.
</P>
<P>
   After Nettie died three years ago, Fern discovered Linda's
original birth certificate in Nettie's possessions. At last they
had Linda's correct birth date: May 25, 1945.
</P>
<P>
   It was a key clue, says Fern, who already knew Linda was born at
General Hospital No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has helped, too, Ed says. Many people are searching
online for relatives, and some offered suggestions. One told Judith
to get a list of people born on Linda's birth date from the
Missouri Bureau of Vital Records.
</P>
<P>
   Because the state created a new birth certificate in Linda's
adopted name, that name _ not her original name _ appears on the
list.
</P>
<P>
   But which one of nearly 100 females is she?
</P>
<P>
   A way to find out is to eliminate girls whose birth names never
changed. It's simply a matter of cross-checking the list against
birth announcements published 54 years ago in Missouri newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Ed and Fern recently scoured newspapers on microfilm at the
Kansas City Public Library. In two hours they eliminated 14 names.
More than 80 remain.
</P>
<P>
   It will be easier if Linda is looking for them, too. One recent
clue provides Ed and Fern hope. It comes from Mary Grizzle, who
grew up across the street from the Oldhams and still lives in the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago _ perhaps in the 1970s or 1980s _ someone knocked
on Grizzle's door and asked about the Oldham family. She cannot
remember the person's name or whether a man, a woman or a couple
knocked.
</P>
<P>
   Ed and Fern exchanged glances. They pushed Grizzle for more
details, but the memory was too faint.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was Linda.
</P>
<P>
   Their prayer is that Linda will read this article and respond.
</P>
<P>
   If not, they will keep searching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to get desperate,'' Ed said. ``We feel as if
we do not have much time, and it seems that all doors are closed.''
</P>
<P>
   They realize Linda may be dead, may not know she is adopted or
may not care. Fern says her brother, Bud, is worried that Linda
won't want a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she doesn't want to be involved with us, that's OK,'' Fern
said. ``We'll know she's OK, and we can live with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
