<SLUG> BC-CARNIVAL-TOWN-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSLEY, Kan. _ until the snow blew.
</P>
<P>
   In good years, they made money. In bad years, it was nip and
tuck.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what they got they gave back to generations of people in the
form of vivid memories. Maybe it wasn't the circus that came to the
bigger towns. But in the backwater communities the carnival was
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we had this legacy all around us,'' Ploger said. ``And
about 10 years ago we starting putting it together.''
</P>
<P>
   People made donations of carnival items they'd squirreled away
over the years. Children and grandchildren of the Brodbeck family
pitched in, finding old stuff out in barns, stuff packed away in
attics. Donations came from all over _ swords from a sword
swallower, old carnival ``joints'' (booths), brasswork from rides,
even a scale from a guy who for 52 years made a comfortable living
guessing people's weight.
</P>
<P>
   Money was raised locally. Plus, Kinsley acquired a $60,000
community development grant from the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only one in the country,'' Ploger said of the
museum. ``We've heard of other groups who want to start museums,
but they just can't seem to get off the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinsley has never really had that problem. But then maybe it had
an edge because carnivals and circuses have one thing in common _ a
midway.
</P>
<P>
   And what's the sign here say, almost serendipitously? ``Midway
U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of fits. Even if here is ``out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
