r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRAIRIE-RANCH-KAN &LR;      02-15 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAIRIE-RANCH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FEAR NEW TALLGRASS PRAIRIE PRESERVE MAY WIND UP AS A CATTLE
RANCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Advocates of a tallgrass prairie park in Kansas
envisioned a vast expanse of waving grasses with elk, bison and
antelope. Now, some fear that what they will get is just another
cattle ranch.
</P>
<P>
   At least one prairie advocate is concerned that that's what is
in store for the new 10,894-acre National Tallgrass Prairie
Preserve in the Flint Hills of Chase County.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan being proposed by the (National) Park Service would
obligate 9,000 to 10,000 acres to pasture management with cattle,''
Ron Klataske said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service last month released its preferred plan
for the park's operation. It took public comments on the plan in
special open houses last week in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Klataske, a longtime advocate of a national tallgrass park,
represents the Kansas Audubon Council and is on the 13-member
advisory committee set up by Congress to help plan the park's
management. To him, cattle grazing is more appropriate for private
land than for a tallgrass prairie preserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tallgrass prairie national preserve, not a federal
grazing allotment,'' Klataske said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Miller, the park's superintendent, said Friday that he
thought the place would live up to its expectations as the nation's
outstanding example of a tallgrass preserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is going to expect the tallgrass, and there's going
to be areas very accessible where people can see it and get into
that tallgrass,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The major influences on the tallgrass are grazing and fire,
Miller said. And there's little scientific data to prove that bison
are better for the health or diversity of a tallgrass ecosystem
than cattle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only 70 percent to 80 percent of the preserve will be grazed by
cattle, Miller said. About 1,000 acres will be set aside for 25 to
30 bison. But that does not mean the park will be mostly about
cattle ranching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under this plan, the majority of the land would continue to be
grazed by cattle, but I think you need to look at cattle as a
grazer to manage the tallgrass prairie.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pritchard of the National Park Trust, a nonprofit private
group established to purchase land for conservation, agrees with
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to manage this for the tallgrass prairie,''
Pritchard said. ``And tallgrass prairie and bison are not
necessarily synonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the bison park. And it's not a cattle park. It's a
grass park, a tallgrass prairie park.''
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard said the planning included discussions with many
scientists who convinced him and the National Park Service that a
tallgrass ecosystem could be just as healthy grazed by cattle as by
native ungulates such as bison or elk.
</P>
<P>
   But if they are equal, Klataske asked, why not use bison as the
dominant grazers?
</P>
<P>
   ``If cattle were the same as bison, and livestock are the same
as wildlife, why wouldn't the National Park Service manage the
Yellowstone National Park with cattle, sheep and horses rather than
manage bison and elk and other wildlife that aren't as easily
managed?'' Klataske asked.
</P>
<P>
   Klataske suggested that cattle had been chosen because of
intense lobbying from the livestock industry and the restrictions
of a cattle-grazing lease that governs most of the park's land.
</P>
<P>
   The park is an unusual public-private arrangement in which the
National Park Trust will own all but 180 acres, a compromise worked
out in Congress to appease Kansas interests concerned about federal
ownership of the land, once operated as the Spring Hill or Z Bar
ranch.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 the National Park Trust sold the cattle-grazing rights
to Ed Bass, a Texas millionaire, for 35 years as part of a lease
that was little- publicized.
</P>
<P>
   It would cost about $2 million to buy back the lease rights to
all of the property, Pritchard said.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard and Miller said that no one had exerted any political
pressure and that the planners were told not to consider the lease
as a barrier to any of their plans.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, there are practical reasons for not quickly
populating the park with many bison, Pritchard said. They take a
long time to socialize, and the park is probably too small for a
large herd of bison, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The way cattle are grazed on the land under the lease, Miller
said, will have to be altered to allow a more diverse prairie
ecosystem to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Miller stresses that much progress has been made in the last few
years, especially in light of the controversy over federal
ownership and other issues that dogged the park proposal for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hope people will look at this plan and see a lot of things
in it that they really support,'' Miller said. ``In order to do
this, we're going to need a lot of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be exciting to see this unfold.''
</P>
<P>
   To obtain a copy of the National Park Service's plan, contact
the agency in Cottonwood Falls at (316) 273-6034. Public comments
will be accepted until March 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
