<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARNIVAL-TOWN-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS TOWN IS PERMANENT HOME FOR THE CARNIVAL, AND ALL ITS
TRADITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES J. FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSLEY, Kan. _ For years, about the only thing that's ever
stirred folks to pause here on a seemingly endless trip across the
high plains is the big sign at the junction of U.S. 50, 56 and 183.
</P>
<P>
   One arrow points west, reading, ``San Francisco, 1561 miles,''
and another points opposite, advising, ``New York, 1561 miles.'' As
the sign says, Kinsley is ``Midway U.S.A,'' where travelers,
relieved to be this far, pose for a snapshot.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsley is also ``out there,'' halfway between Dodge City and
Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. In a couple of years, folks here predict that tour
buses will pull in with regularity and swarms will fill Main
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction? Simple.
</P>
<P>
   The carnival has come to town. Permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past couple of years, Kinsley has set itself up as the
country's carnival capital by establishing headquarters for the
National Foundation for Carnival Heritage and its Carnival Heritage
Museum, which occupies an abandoned downtown department store.
</P>
<P>
   And next to the museum is what for millions of youngsters in
tens of thousands of small towns was a consummation of their dreams
_ a merry-go-round.
</P>
<P>
   Remember? On a hot summer night, one end of prairie town would
literally come ablaze with light. That glow would illuminate
unimagined sights _ snake handlers and sword swallowers, games of
chance and shooting galleries, gravel-voiced barkers and even
scantily dressed women.
</P>
<P>
   The carnival became part of small-town America's mythology. For
a brief moment, a whistle stop, a tank town, a wide place in the
road was transformed. For a night a Ferris wheel, freaks and cotton
candy replaced the unrelieved sameness of rural America.
</P>
<P>
   This past year, evidence of what's ahead for Kinsley was easy to
spot _ 10,000 tourists showed up. The enthusiasts were people for
whom a brass (actually steel) ring, a hand-painted broadside or the
third-oldest Ferris wheel in the country are akin to heaven on
Earth. They came in cars, pickup trucks, motor homes and even a few
tour buses.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials say 1998 was just the beginning. In the next
couple of years the museum will expand into three other buildings
down the street so it can house its steadily growing collection of
carnival memorabilia. More old performers will be initiated into an
adjunct carnival Hall of Fame. And in November 2000, there'll be
the unveiling of Kinsley's piece de resistance _ a Heyn
double-decker carousel, built in Germany in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   John Ploger, a member of the museum board, said the Heyn would
be the only operating double-decker carousel with original overhead
panels in North America. There was another Heyn double-decker
without the panels, but Ploger said he understood it had been sold
and returned to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rarity of the Heyn should bring people out of the
woodwork,'' he said. ``We expect our yearly numbers to go to 50,000
or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the ancient carousel is in storage. It was brought to
the United States in the mid-1980s, its ornate wooden horses sold
off to collectors for cumulative million-plus dollars, and then was
rescued by Frank Trainer, a Floridian who couldn't bear seeing the
frame and innards of the old machine dumped in a landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer overhauled the carousel's machinery, then sold it to
Kinsley for $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of horses is no problem. Providentially, Kinsley has in
its midst a nationally known carver of wooden carousel horses,
Bruce White, whose creations grace many Applebee's restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids ride merry-go-rounds,'' Ploger said. ``Kids don't care if
that horse moving them up or down is new or old. But then it really
doesn't matter. Bruce's horses are as good or better than the
originals.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinsley's journey to becoming a town celebrating carnivals has
taken some time. For decades, community leaders sought industry _
jobs, manufacturing, plants.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, said Dick Darling, a specialist in community
economic development for the Kansas State University Research and
Extension service, is that there aren't that many factories looking
to relocate, what few are likely to wouldn't choose rural Kansas
and, even if those obstacles were overcome, the recent good times
have all but guaranteed the absence of an adequate labor force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hodgeman County is northwest of Kinsley,'' Darling said. ``Its
unemployment rate is currently 1.4 percent. That means there are a
total of 14 people in that county looking for work. I doubt if any
employer would move a plant there. You get the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   With its pursuit of industry at a standstill, Kinsley looked
within. What was here?
</P>
<P>
   Well, there had been a big Indian fight near here. And there was
once a jim-dandy train robbery. Yet what people really remembered
was that Kinsley, of all places, had been the home of six carnivals
from the turn of the century until the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It started about 1901, when Charlie Brodbeck traded some cows
for a small merry-go-round. Charlie noticed that folks coming to
where he had set up the contraption would ride a horse or come in a
horse-drawn wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Then they'd get on a wooden horse. And pay a nickel to boot.
</P>
<P>
   The proverbial light bulb went on over Brodbeck's head. He, his
sons and the men who married into the family left their
hardscrabble farms for the carnival business.
</P>
<P>
   In all, that first merry-go-round birthed six carnival companies
that every spring would leave Kinsley and travel all over the
Midwest and the Rocky Mountains until the snow blew. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
