</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLINGS-SEARCH-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIBLINGS HAVE SEARCHED 50 YEARS FOR BABY SISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONNA McGUIRE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ On a frosty night 53 years ago, a father's
drunken rage tore Ed Oldham's family apart.
</P>
<P>
   The father, an unemployed widower, stormed into the kitchen of
his home, grabbed a 10-inch butcher knife and began sharpening it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children Flee A Knife,'' blared a headline in The Kansas City
Times the next morning, Jan. 11, 1946.
</P>
<P>
   His six children _ ages 7 months to 16 years _ spent the night
locked in the juvenile detention center downtown. As wards of the
state, they later shuffled between foster homes and orphanages,
spending only rare moments together.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years the baby was gone _ separated from the Oldhams
under the secrecy of Missouri's adoption laws.
</P>
<P>
   Her name was Linda.
</P>
<P>
   For decades her siblings have ached to know what happened to
her. For decades they've searched for her.
</P>
<P>
   For decades they've come up empty.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Oldham, 59, is a rail-thin, 6-foot Texan who likes
cigarettes, cracking jokes and doing remodeling work for real
estate companies.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Judith, is a genealogy buff adept at researching
family history on the Internet. About a year ago Judith got the
idea that perhaps they could find Linda on the Internet, too.
</P>
<P>
   Judith added Linda's name to online adoption registries,
subscribed to an adoption e-mail list and created a Web page called
``Looking for Linda.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point she turned up a Missourian named Linda seeking her
birth family. For a few days Ed thought they had found his Linda.
But she had the wrong birthday.
</P>
<P>
   And so the search has gone. More dead ends than headway, more
disappointment than elation.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's adoption records are closed _ especially tight to
inquiring siblings. The Oldhams' rented house in the 4300 block of
East 10th Street no longer exists. Neither does the neighborhood
police station. Memories have faded. People involved have moved,
married and died.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ed refuses to give up.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Plano, Texas, resident flew to Kansas City to
rendezvous with Fern Cates, 64, an older sister who lives in
Syracuse, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference room at The Kansas City Star, they spread out
old family photographs, Linda's birth certificate, their mother's
death certificate and other clues collected over the decades.
</P>
<P>
   Among their artifacts was a small, black-and-white photo,
slightly curled at the edges. It showed a woman in a short-sleeved
dress holding a round-faced infant in a bonnet. An afternoon sun
warmed their faces and stretched a shadow on cracked concrete
beneath them. A small, one-story house with a porch and two
chimneys stood in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Ed and Fern believe the woman was Linda's foster mother.
</P>
<P>
   Scribbled in pencil across the back of the picture were ``Linda
Joyce Oldham,'' a partial address on Quincy and the name ``McBee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go to that neighborhood,'' Ed said, tapping the
photograph. ``I want to see if I can find that house.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph C. Oldham painted houses, delivered coal, worked some for
Sheffield Steel and held various odd jobs. But at times he was
unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Fern remembers her father as strict, mean and unaffectionate. If
he got mad at one of the children, he was mad at them all. He hid
whiskey and wine bottles in the house and ran a tab at a
neighborhood tavern.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Mary Belle Oldham, used a treadle-powered machine to
sew the family clothes: dresses from seed sacks and boys' pants
from used adult overalls.
</P>
<P>
   Any Christmas gifts usually came from the Salvation Army _ or
from an aunt who once gave Fern a doll.
</P>
<P>
   The house lacked electricity, running water and telephone
service. Old newspapers served as wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   The rats were awful. They bit everyone in the family except Fern
and her mother. One night Ed awoke crying after a rat gnawed his
left thumb. Another time his mother killed a rat in the bathtub. To
this day, rats terrify Fern.
</P>
<P>
   One late-summer day in 1945, Fern and the other children spotted
an ambulance at the house as they walked home from school. Their
mother was sick. The hospital sent her home in a taxi, but she got
sicker.
</P>
<P>
   The next day she had gallbladder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later she died of post-operative shock, two weeks short
of her 36th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday afternoon, Ed uncurled his long body from the
back of a car and stepped onto Quincy Drive in Kansas City. Fern
exited the other side and reached into the trunk for that photo of
a woman holding an infant.
</P>
<P>
   According to an old city directory, Estaline and Scott McBee
lived at 2223 Quincy Drive in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   No such address exists today _ only an empty lot. A mail carrier
on his rounds shook his head. He didn't know when the house was
torn down.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a house next door looked suspiciously like the one in the
picture. Ed paced the street, searching for the right angle. Yes,
it had two chimneys. Yes, the front porch matched. But the angle
wasn't right.
</P>
<P>
   Finally they found the right spot across the street, in a sloped
driveway. Someone took the picture here, Ed and Fern agreed.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor had lived on Quincy since 1948. No, he didn't
recognize the woman in the picture. He didn't recognize the name
McBee, either.
</P>
<P>
   Shivering, Ed and Fern retreated to the car, sure they had the
right street. But it was another dead end.
</P>
<P>
   After mother Oldham died in 1945, 16-year-old Nettie tended to
her five younger siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated with the family's living conditions, she plotted to
marry a neighbor and take in her brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Her father found out and stormed home. As usual, he had been
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Grandpa, who had leaked Nettie's plans, huffed a mile to the
Oldham house and attempted to reason with the furious father. But
no words could soothe that anger. Grandpa gave up and hiked home.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers reported the next day that Oldham threatened to
shoot his children. He had brass knuckles in his pants pocket that
he tried to make them think was a gun, Fern says. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
