<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5959 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOWA-BUSH-TEX     02-15 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-BUSH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA ISN'T WORTH WHAT IT'LL DO TO A GOOD TEXAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some Iowa Republicans visited Austin last week to beg our Gov.
George W. Bush to enter their presidential caucuses next February.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trap, George. Don't do it.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowans probably didn't mention it, but one can be elected
president without winning the Iowa caucuses. Ronald Reagan did it,
and so did Bill Clinton. George W.'s dad won the Iowa caucuses, but
not in the year he made it to the White House. Later, the senior
George lost the caucuses but was elected president. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another reason for George W. to stay away from
Iowa. Iowans are wonderfully tolerant and intelligent people, but
in their hearts they harbor a hearty dislike of Texas and all
things Texan.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists can argue until the virtual cows come home about
why Iowans feel the way they do about Texas. But take it from a
former Iowa resident _ they do. The differences between the states
are stark.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa is Frost Belt; Texas is Sun Belt. Iowans consume energy;
Texans sell it. Iowa grows corn; Texas, wheat. Iowans love
government; Texans loathe it. Iowans sprinkle at baptisms; Texans
immerse. Iowans are modest; Texans boast. Texans love the Dallas
Cowboys; Iowans despised even the Landry/Staubach-era team. Iowa
fought for the Union; Texas flew the Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed in Iowa's caucuses, Texans must renounce their native
state and all its works and ways. Two who didn't, John Connally and
Phil Gramm, were sent packing from Iowa in wintry defeats every bit
as forlorn as Napoleon Bonaparte's retreat from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Although he looked and acted like a president, Big John lost the
1980 caucuses to Bush. The elder George camouflaged himself by (a)
not wearing cowboy boots and Stetson or speaking in a Texas twang,
(b) noting as his credentials his work in places like the United
Nations and China rather than in the Texas oilfields, and (c)
having never been a governor or senator from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Few Iowans were aware at the time that George the Elder actually
was a Houston resident. Bush shrewdly hung back as the candidate
from Somewhere East and let Connally, proudly wearing boots and
Stetson, be the designated Texan. Big John never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his Iowa victory, Bush later lost the 1980 GOP
nomination to a former Des Moines resident, Ronald Reagan. The
Gipper intelligently sat out the caucuses that winter for the
warmth of Santa Barbara, Calif. The Reagan Revolution happened
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, the now-Vice President Bush returned to Iowa
and was stuffed by that dynamo campaigner, Bob Dole. The reason: In
1988, Bush was the only Texan in the race, and Dole made sure
Iowans knew it. Even so, George the Elder went on to get the
nomination and win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Phil Gramm bravely sallied north to Iowa. The Texan
said all the right things for Iowa ears. He was for the family
farm, corn-additive gasoline, price supports and eradication of the
corn borer. He praised small-town schools and kissed every pig he
could find.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm hung out for a while with Iowa football coach Hayden Fry,
an expatriate Texan. (More about Fry in a minute.) But Gramm, like
Connally, suffered a caucus rear-kicking.
</P>
<P>
   Fry must not have told Phil that when Hayden left Texas for Iowa
in 1979, the new coach spent two years in a serious funk of
unpopularity with a state that saw him as a relative of J.R. Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden got off to a bad start in Iowa when, in the nation's No.
1 pork-producing state, he called such animals by their Southern
name of ``hogs'' rather than the Iowa preference for ``pigs.''
Hayden drawled Texanisms like ``dance with the one that brung ya''
and ``scratch where it itches.'' Those lines had worked for Darrell
Royal, but in Iowa they prompted talk-show callers to snicker about
Fry's Texas accent.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden eventually promised to set aside his Texas ways. But not
until Fry took the Iowa Hawkeyes to the Rose Bowl did Iowans decide
that Hayden could be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's antipathy to Texas isn't a North-South thing. Jimmy
Carter of Georgia, who is as Southern as they come, won the Iowa
caucuses in 1976. But Carter was out of office then, and he
literally took up residence in Iowa for an entire year to persuade
Iowans that he was deserving of their votes.
</P>
<P>
   For most of 1975, Jimmy C. was everywhere in Iowa. He slept on
Iowans' couches. He appeared on local TV cooking shows. He went to
as many county fairs (Iowa has 99 of them) as he could schedule. He
got himself wedged in breaks in the noon livestock reports on
countless Iowa radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Robert Waller made anybody think of the Bridges of
Madison County as a scene for adultery, Jimmy was there. He lusted
only in his heart, and Iowans returned his affection.
</P>
<P>
   So the message to Governor Doubleyew from one who knows is this:
To win in Iowa, you must resign from the governorship of Texas
immediately and renounce your Texas heritage. Then spend 350 of the
next 365 days in Iowa. Leave your boots and Stetson home, and talk
like somebody from National Public Radio. Do that, and you might
have an outside chance of beating Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Ask your dad: Is a victory in the Iowa caucuses really worth all
that?
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Piller is a business writer for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at (817) 390-7719 or
danpil(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
