<HEADLINE>
`EVEN SEEMINGLY SMALL ERRORS FEED PUBLIC SKEPTICISM'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL K. HARRAL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago I gave a quick overview of the findings of
the American Society of Newspaper Editors' study of newspaper
credibility. I promised that I would visit each of the study's six
major findings in separate columns during the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   We have long argued internally in the business that there is no
such thing as a minor error. Some errors get you in really deep
trouble and some don't, but all chip away at credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Most of you may not know whether I'm accurate if I'm writing
about nuclear physics _ some of you will, of course, because you
possess specific knowledge _ but you do know I've made a mistake
when I say that streets cross when they actually run parallel, or
when I use the wrong location for a well-known landmark.
</P>
<P>
   A reader who didn't leave his name made this point for me on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wish that the people who write articles would get
their geography right,'' he said, complaining that we were wrong in
identifying a city in which a store was closing. ``I sure wish your
people would check their geography before they write stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of you have had the unfortunate experience of showing up
for something only to find that the time or location in the
newspaper was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of this is our fault, because sometimes we are simply
passing on errors that other people made when they gave us the
information. But you don't really care who made the error or why.
And there's no reason you should.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what the ASNE study labeled as ``Major Finding No. 1'':
</P>
<P>
   ``The public sees too many factual errors and spelling or
grammar mistakes in newspapers. Even seemingly small errors feed
public skepticism about a newspaper's credibility. Each misspelled
word, bad apostrophe, garbled grammatical construction, weird
cutline and mislabeled map erodes public confidence in a
newspaper's ability to get anything right. One focus group even
laughed out loud when asked whether mistakes ever appeared in their
paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, readers don't care whether the reporter was
rushed, or that the staff was down three people, or if the copy
editor was too busy laying out pages to catch misuses of the common
language.''
</P>
<P>
   I want to say this nicely and not too defensively, but I deal
with many such complaints in letters and e-mails in which the
writer makes numerous spelling and grammar mistakes. And sometimes
you are simply wrong when you criticize our use of words.
</P>
<P>
   That only means that you hold us to a higher standard. Fine. So
be it.
</P>
<P>
   The study said that even though ``almost half of the public
believes that mistakes and errors occur in the rush to meet
deadlines, 27 percent attribute them to sloppiness, carelessness,
laziness or a lack of caring, and an additional 5 percent suggest
that the journalists just don't know any better.''
</P>
<P>
   That hurts. There are sloppy, careless, lazy and uncaring
journalists. (You can say that about any group of workers.) But
that has not been the general rule with the journalists I have
worked beside for more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Readers can be unforgiving, and for a very good reason: The
newspaper becomes personal to them. Many callers to my office begin
by telling me how long they have subscribed to the Star-Telegram,
establishing that they have a right to criticize the newspaper or
its performance.
</P>
<P>
   When I had a child at home, my wife and I used a little verbal
cue to indicate our level of distress. The indicator of a high
degree of dissatisfaction was whether the conversation referred to
``our child'' or ``your child.'' ``Our child'' had just won an
award in school. ``Your child'' just drew a picture on the wall
with finger paint.
</P>
<P>
   I find that same speech pattern in readers. If they are about to
praise us or indicate some minor dissatisfaction, they'll refer to
``the newspaper'' or sometimes ``my newspaper.'' If they are really
upset, it becomes ``your newspaper,'' and I settle in for a long
and sometimes not very pleasant discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The study said that 23 percent of adults say they find factual
errors in their daily paper at least once a week beyond
typographical and grammar errors. Of those, only 21 percent think
that mistakes are becoming more frequent, but 60 percent believe
that there are just as many errors as there always have been.
</P>
<P>
   As when dealing with children, honesty and directness are
appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   The ASNE study found that 19 percent of readers say they always
see a correction when there has been a factual error; 40 percent
say they ``sometimes'' see one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also clear that admitting mistakes and errors is not only
a wise practice, but a very desirable one among readers _ 63
percent said they `felt better' about the quality of the news
coverage they get when they see corrections,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   We correct errors on Page 2 of the newspaper, and it sometimes
is depressing to all of us to read that section.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is reader advocate for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. His e-mail address is harral(at)star-telegram.com.
You may telephone him at (817) 390-7692 or write him at P.O. Box
1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
