</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CENTRALSTATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CENTRAL STATION' TAKES US ON AN HONEST JOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After watching Sharon Stone very carefully re-create Gena
Rowlands' performance in the remake of ``Gloria'' _ or rather,
judging by its lackluster box office returns, after NOT watching
Stone attempt the role _ you may be in the mood for a more
emotionally honest film with a suspicious older woman taking in a
young boy.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, ``Central Station,'' with a moving
performance by Fernanda Montenegro in the lead, could be just what
you're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro plays Dora, a former teacher who writes letters for
the unschooled, and she has set herself up at the central train
station in Rio de Janeiro. She's contemptuous of the banal
sentiments that the needy illiterates pass through her, which of
course sets her up for a comeuppance.
</P>
<P>
   It comes in the form of Josue (Vinicius de Oliveira), a
10-year-old she has to take care of. Dora is asked by Josue's
mother to write a letter, and shortly after she does, the boy's
mother dies in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Central Station'' takes a turn into a different kind of
picture when we learn that Dora's affection for Josue has a less
than altruistic motivation. He's not exactly winning her over; she
essentially wants to sell him off so she can get a TV. When her
scheme doesn't work out as she planned, she's again forced to care
for the boy, holding out so that she can deliver him to his father
(against whom his mother railed in her letter).
</P>
<P>
   Once Dora and Josue are on the road, and she has to depend on
the people whose easy sentiments she ridiculed, layers of her
crustiness dissolve and flake away in the country breezes. But it's
the determination that Montenegro shows as an actress that keeps
your attention.
</P>
<P>
   Director Walter Salles may move the movie into territory that's
too sweet, but at least he isn't being facile, either. Even though
we've all seen this story before, the simplicity that Montenegro
brings opens the windows and clears out some of the stale air. De
Oliveira's crankiness is enjoyable, too. He's not really an actor,
so he seems to be figuring out what to do as the camera is rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Many may be surprised that ``Central Station'' took the Golden
Globe for Best Foreign Film over ``Life Is Beautiful.'' But after
you take in the rich performance of Montenegro, you'll be convinced
that the Globe voters can occasionally be right.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, ``Central Station'' is filled with obvious ironies that
produce more sniffles than hay fever season. Incredibly, though,
the biggest one is unintentional; it's probably a story that Dora
would find laughable.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Central Station'' (in Portuguese with English
subtitles) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Walter Salles &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Fernanda Montenegro, Vinicius de Oliveira &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 115 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and situations &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
