<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV17-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBIE FACES BIG 4-0 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday Feb. 17)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barbie, the world's most famous anatomically incorrect doll,
turns 40 in March.
</P>
<P>
   While one might hope that Barbie would ease gracefully into
middle age _perhaps trade in the hot-pink Mustang for a nice,
sensible Volvo station wagon and start worrying less about her
makeup and more about her arthritis pains - Barbie, instead, seems
to be using her birthday as an excuse for a gigantic mid-life
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   While others her age might worry that their birthday cake will
set off the smoke alarm, Barbie is celebrating her 40th birthday by
getting a butterfly tattoo on her stomach and hanging out with a
new set of friends, including one who sports a nose ring.
</P>
<P>
   Although Barbie has never been your average woman, unless your
definition of an average woman is a clone of Dolly Parton and Olive
Oyl, she needs to think twice before she goes chasing after her
fading youth.
</P>
<P>
   The world is filled with sad, pathetic people who cannot accept
that they're not as young as they used to be. It is one thing for
Barbie to watch what she eats and exercise regularly; it is another
thing entirely for her to dye her hair purple and stick sharp
things through parts of her body that sharp things should never be
stuck through.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie's at a stage in her life when she should be making
appointments with her periodontist, not slam dancing at Offspring
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course, one has to wonder how popular a sagging, wrinkling,
nearsighted doll would be with little girls, assuming there are
little girls out there who would rather play with Barbie dolls than
chat with each other over the Internet.)
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, but not certain, that Barbie would have aged
more gracefully if she had married and had kids instead of wasting
the best years of her life hanging around that loser Ken. Besides
having the vacant, light's-on-but-nobody's-home look of someone
who's been dropped on his head as a baby, Ken had no visible means
of support, leading everyone (except the bubble-headed Barbie) to
assume that he was a either a drug dealer, a pimp or a vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   (Is it any coincidence that Ken bears a striking resemblance to
Dan Quayle? I don't think so.)
</P>
<P>
   Ken, of course, gave the impression that he was more interested
in looking at himself in the mirror than settling down with Barbie,
a rejection that may have lowered Barbie's self-esteem to the point
that she felt a need to get a butterfly tattooed on her stomach and
hang around with people with rings in their nose.
</P>
<P>
   If things had turned out differently for Barbie and she had had
kids (though not with Ken, God forbid), Barbie would have been much
too tired and/or stressed out to worry about a mid-life crisis,
much less have time for one. Instead of bemoaning her lost youth,
Barbie could drive her kids to soccer practice and help them with
their algebra homework. (This should be a real challenge for a doll
who got in hot water with teachers for uttering the message ``Math
is hard.'')
</P>
<P>
   Instead of tagging along with her slacker friends to rock
concerts, she could make frantic calls to the pediatrician at 4
o'clock in the morning because her daughter had a 104-degree fever.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no need to decorate her body with tattoos because
her kids would satisfy her artistic needs by writing on the walls
with laundry markers and grinding bubble gum into their hair.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie clearly has a lot of issues she needs to work out at this
stage in her life, but one thing she should be extremely happy
about is that she's just a doll.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
