<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIFFULTIES THE CENSUS BUREAU ENCOUNTERS IN COUNTING NOSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CLAASSEN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   World War II showed the Census Bureau how hard it can be to
count each American.
</P>
<P>
   Needing every potential soldier, leaders of the Selective
Service System asked the Census Bureau in 1942 for the number of
young, single men in the country who were old enough to fight.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, Navy and other services prepared to handle the
millions of men counted during the 1940 Census. They were caught
off guard, however, when 15 percent more young black men showed up
to fight than the census knew existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time the Census Bureau really got a wakeup
call about how many people it was able to count,'' said Frank
Newton, spokesman for the agency's Dallas regional office.
</P>
<P>
   In black communities struggling with overt, institutional
discrimination in the 1940s, there was little incentive to
cooperate with a federal government that turned a blind eye to Jim
Crow laws.
</P>
<P>
   Other neighborhoods of racial or ethnic minorities were also
wary of census-takers. Some had to be watchful around government
workers _ sometimes census workers in particular _ in their home
countries. Others sensed only a tenuous connection to their new,
adopted country and its government.
</P>
<P>
   Although relations have improved and statistics for ethnic
groups are more accurate now, other communities in the United
States seem to have become as leery of the government as minority
communities were in the 1940s, Newton said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that wariness, apathy and other problems, the 1990
Census, according to the Census Bureau, was the first in more than
40 years to be less accurate than the previous one.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, only 65 percent of households returned their surveys,
down from 74 percent in 1970. Next year, that figure is expected to
drop to 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For local governments, uncounted people mean lost money.
According to the U.S. Conference of Mayors, each uncounted person
equals $1,230 in lost federal grants during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   To improve accuracy, the bureau's statisticians proposed a head
count with mathematical models, or ``statistical sampling,'' to
fill in for uncounted people. The National Academy of Sciences and
the American Statistical Association encouraged the change.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1950s, the bureau has conducted post-census accuracy
checks through surveys and telephone polls.
</P>
<P>
   Those reviews suggested that post-census phone surveys were more
accurate than door-to-door interviews in accounting for the 2 to 5
percent of Americans who are hard to reach, said Barbara Bryant,
the census director under President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out of the 1990 Census, we really realized we can't
count them all,'' Bryant said. ``We knew it would be the last
census where we tried to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's plan, however, was too ambitious for congressional
Republicans and other critics.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Census was at first designed to count 90 percent of
Americans through surveys and in person, and use statistical
sampling for the remainder, which census statisticians considered
the most conservative approach.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans and some others said that sampling should only
be used for the 2 to 5 percent who can't be counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The methodology was unproven, and there would have been no
full-count number to fall back on, since they would have counted
only 90 percent the traditional way,'' said Chip Walker, spokesman
for the House Subcommittee on the Census.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Republicans, meanwhile, said that GOP members
merely feared a higher population count for young people with
modest incomes and minorities, who tend to vote for Democrats. So
far, however, demographic studies show only that statistical
sampling could cause Indiana to lose a seat in Congress and
Mississippi to gain one.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the challengers won a partial victory in the Supreme
Court. Federal law requires that population counts used to assign
seats in Congress for each state must be based on surveys and
in-person interviews, the justices ruled.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruling left open the chance for a second official count
based on statistical sampling to steer federal grants and other
work. The White House and congressional Democrats are gearing up to
fight for that.
</P>
<P>
   During the next several months, congressional Democrats and
Republicans, who control funding for the census, are expected to
feud over the possibility for two official censuses. One Democratic
bill and two Republican bills are already on file.
</P>
<P>
   A two-headed census, however, could lead to more political
infighting.
</P>
<P>
   After the census calculated an adjusted 1990 figure through
statistical sampling, the state of Texas, the city of Los Angeles
and others filed suit to use the adjusted figures.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a federal judge ruled that former Commerce Secretary
Rob Mosbacher had the authority to reject the adjusted figures. The
ruling focused on Mosbacher's authority and did not involve issues
of statistical accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-headed 2000 Census, legal fights over voting rights
are likely to erupt if states fail to use adjusted counts to draw
local political districts, said Brian Currey, a Los Angeles lawyer
who represented Texas, Los Angeles and others in their census suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are enterprising lawyers out there who would say the
census has the numbers and the methodology is sound,'' Currey said.
``It would be an uphill fight, but that challenge would be made.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Claassen is a computer-assisted-reporting specialist for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at (817) 390-7710
or via e-mail at jeff(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
