u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     02-15 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, Feb. 15. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-ECON-II (Undated) _ Part 2 of the series: How the United
States, seeking freer capital flow, knocked on poorer nations'
doors and got a warm welcome. By Nicholas D. Kristof with David E.
Sanger. (7000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Rambouillet, France) _ The broad shape of the
peace deal that the two sides in the Kosovo conflict are being
compelled to accept emerged, with Russia playing a key role in
trying to persuade the Serbs to allow NATO-led troops on their
territory. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-POLITICS (Abidjan) _ Nigeria's leading political party
chooses Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, the country's military ruler in the
late 1970s, as its candidate for the Feb. 27 presidential
elections. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-THREAT (Washington) _ Iraq's vice president threatens to
attack U.S. air bases in Turkey after U.S. carries out another air
strike in Iraq this morning. Reaction from Washington. By Steven
Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   with map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-LOTT (Warren, Mich.) _ At the town meeting in Warren,
Mich., where Trent Lott, Gov. Engler and other Republicans are
