<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5974 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASSING-GLORY-LADN &LR;      02-15 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSING-GLORY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
` PASSING GLORY' SHOWS DIFFERENT HOOP DREAMS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ In 1965, Jesuit High School's boys basketball
team in New Orleans was 29-1 and being called the ``Team of the
Century.''
</P>
<P>
   But just across town, St. Augustine High School's team was 30-0.
No one talked about the Purple Knights' record, however, nor
whether the school would play Jesuit to see who really was the team
of the century.
</P>
<P>
   That's because even though both schools were run by the Catholic
Church and were located in the same city, Jesuit was all white, and
St. Augustine was all black. And in 1965, in New Orleans, white
high schools didn't play against black high schools.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where Father Joseph Verrett (Andre Braugher) enters
in the TNT movie ``Passing Glory,'' which airs Sunday during Black
History Month.
</P>
<P>
   Kicked out of the Baltimore parish where he'd been working, the
black priest returns to his hometown to teach at St. Augustine
under a white mentor, Father Robert Grant (played by Rip Torn).
</P>
<P>
   Soon Verrett is pressed into service as the basketball team's
coach, clashes with its star (played by Sean Squire) and with Grant
and inspires the team to challenge the Jesuit players to an
informal game.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, the resulting match is decided with a last-second
shot, of course, and you can guess how it turns out. But in
reality, the St. Augustine team walloped Jesuit by 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was (a blowout), but drama being what drama is ...''
acknowledged a laughing Harold Sylvester, who wrote the script and
starred in the original game. He went on to be the first black
athlete at Tulane University before becoming an actor and
screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   The film's script takes other dramatic license, such as
Verrett's role as a coach and his squabbles with Grant, but
otherwise is a relatively faithful telling of a Tale of Two
Basketball Teams and their city in a time of transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South, I think, is a wonderful place,'' said Sylvester.
``But it certainly was a bit behind the times. (The game) was just
the beginning of us coming to terms with the fact that sometimes
things aren't always the way that people tell you they are, which
was the value for me in doing this story.''
</P>
<P>
   But the story struggled to get made. It was first optioned by
Disney back in 1992, and later Denzel Washington was slated to star
in and direct it. Writer-director John Sayles took a crack at
rewriting the screenplay for film, as did others.
</P>
<P>
   But then the project ended up in the limbo of turnaround for a
time before its executive producers, Quincy Jones and Magic
Johnson, persuaded TNT to make it for television.
</P>
<P>
   They stuck with a pared-down script that was closer to
Sylvester's original and brought in Steve James as director. James
is best-known for the brilliant 1994 documentary ``Hoop Dreams,''
which followed the lives of two Chicago youths trying to escape the
inner city through their basketball skills.
</P>
<P>
   James said he was willing to do another basketball film because
``sports in general can be a great backdrop to deal with most
anything dramatically; it's inherently dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Hoop Dreams,'' where he and his team shot more than 250
hours of footage over three years in the boys' lives, ``Passing
Glory'' involved different challenges, James said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make a good documentary, you have to get complete access to
really show what happens as it happens,'' James said. ``In
``Passing Glory,'' the challenge is to re-create something with the
same kind of nuance, detail and truth as the actual event.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the former Los Angeles Lakers basketball star, said he
was attracted to the tale because ``it's a story I lived. I went
through this myself, and I think a lot of people will relate to it.
And it's a true story that helped stop segregation. This historic
game helped change the way we think in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Johnson said the story isn't just about black vs. white.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't cheer for the black team, you don't cheer for the
white team; you cheer for all that both teams overcame to play as
athletes,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he was attracted to the project because the truth
behind it startled him, despite his own many years as a jazz
musician traipsing across the Jim Crow South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go back to being on the road with Lionel Hampton in the
early '50s, when it was seriously rough, traveling on band buses
and no hotels to stay in,'' Jones said. ``You couldn't eat in the
restaurants. We had to have white drivers so we could eat on the
road, or (we'd) starve to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years later, when Jones' band played in Las Vegas with
Count Basie's band, host Frank Sinatra told bodyguards, ``If
anybody looks at the band funny, break their legs. Relating to
that, and not understanding (what was still going on in New
Orleans) ... I was so surprised. And I immediately got sucked into
what the story was about.''
</P>
<P>
   It also sucked in Braugher, who was looking for new dramatic
challenges after leaving his much-lauded role as Detective Frank
Pembleton on ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful material, very heartwarming,'' said Braugher.
``It has a very interesting message about preparing yourself to
exploit the things that happen to you. These kids are at a breaking
point. To me, it's a message that's most powerful: Finally, the
losers believe in themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Braugher also was attracted to the moral ambiguities in what
literally could have been a black-and-white film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always turned off by films where the heroes are too good
and the villains are too evil,'' Braugher said. ``Especially when
you're doing historical pieces, there's a tendency to artificially
enoble or drag down the participants. But if there's any message
about history, it must be that it is nuanced and complex.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Passing Glory'' is indeed nuanced. Most characters have at
least a few flaws, and some of the more interesting byplay comes
between Squire's character and a junkie older brother, and between
the Jesuit team's star and his racist father.
</P>
<P>
   Braugher said the junkie brother is emblematic of what happened
for many black youths who turned to drugs and alcohol because they
felt they had no future.
</P>
<P>
   That's changing, in part because the game that Sylvester and
others played did far more than just settle who was better at
shooting a ball through a round rim of metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of weight on our shoulders because we knew
that, regardless, we had something to prove _ and not only about
basketball,'' Sylvester said. ``Because if we couldn't measure it
in terms of basketball, then how in the hell are we going to
measure it in terms of poetry and philosophy and math? We just had
no idea where we stood in the world order.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 1705EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
