<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STRESS-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN STRESS ENTERS THE GERM EQUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(kd) 
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A patient I'll call Mario sat down opposite me with the look
that meant we were about to have a fight. During our three-year
acquaintance we have had many _ mostly split decisions, which is
why we are still on the friendliest of terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do any blood tests today,'' he said. ``I've been too
stressed out. I know my immune system is way down.'' He stopped and
glared at me.
</P>
<P>
   Mario thinks that I don't put much stock in the stress theory of
disease, at least the way it shakes out in the average examining
room, where stress is seldom triggered by an earthquake or
holocaust but is usually a smaller-scale affair. Mario thinks that
I have cast my lot entirely in with the competing germ theory,
ascribing his past health problems to several debilitating
HIV-related infections and his current good health to a handful of
strong medications. Mario thinks that I pooh-pooh the importance of
his innumerable relaxation techniques in keeping him whole. And he
knows that the last time stress loomed I made him do his blood
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But what Mario doesn't know is that any thoughtful adherent of
the germ theory of disease can only be impressed with how
remarkably little it sometimes winds up actually explaining about
infectious diseases. Not infection in the laboratory, among
carefully selected populations of cells and animals, but infectious
disease out here in the wild, where stressed-out humans often
respond to germs in a way that defies the germ theory's simple
axioms.
</P>
<P>
   The unfolding story of the bacteria associated with peptic ulcer
disease is a prime example. For much of this century ulcers were
considered to be a paradigm of stress-induced disease, clear
evidence of mental anguish turning physical. Then in the early
1980s a bacterium called Helicobacter pylori was found to be
associated with most ulcers, and the science swung around. Ulcers
were only an infection after all. Psychology dropped out of the
picture; relaxation was out for ulcer treatment, and antibiotics
were in.
</P>
<P>
   But strangely, the question of what causes ulcers remains almost
as murky as ever. Many people carry H. pylori from childhood on,
but more than 80 percent never get ulcers. Between 10 percent and
30 percent of ulcer patients never carry the bacteria. Meanwhile,
scientific studies that convincingly associate ulcers with
psychological stress remain to be dealt with. The German blitz of
London in World War II and the 1995 Kobe earthquake in Japan both
precipitated local outbreaks of ulcer disease. Studies have shown
that ulcers heal more slowly in anxious people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reports of the death of ulcer psychosomatics have been greatly
exaggerated,'' experts concluded in the Journal of the American
Medical Association last month.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkably similar ambiguity already exists for many other
infections: Germs both explain them and do not. Scientists still
puzzle over why some people exposed to a cold virus get sick, while
many others do not. Among the factors that seem to produce colds:
long-term psychological stress, like losing a job. Among the
factors that seem to protect against them: the social support of
many friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Before Robert Koch discovered the tubercle bacillus in 1882,
theories ascribed tuberculosis to everything from stress to genes
to bad air. The bacillus seemed to void them all, but only
temporarily: For every 100 people exposed to the tubercle bacillus
and infected by it, it turned out that only 10 got sick. Scientists
have spent most of this century trying to make sense of why that is
so; genes, luck or stress.
</P>
<P>
   A nascent germ theory of heart disease is now making headlines.
Traces of an organism called Chlamydia pneumoniae have been found
in the sludge within diseased coronary arteries; when rabbits and
even some humans with heart disease are treated with antibiotics
active against chlamydia, their heart disease appears to improve.
</P>
<P>
   But the discovery of a heart germ is unlikely to resolve the
many mysteries of heart disease, or erase the strong evidence that
stress, depression and personality type appear to be cardiac risk
factors, just like cigarette smoking and blood lipids. Heart
medications may come to include antibiotics some day, but the
endless jostling of the psychosomatic and the orthodox theories of
disease will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Acolyte of the germ theory that I am, I almost bet Mario $20
last month that the stresses of a new job were not somehow going to
inactivate his medications and give his infections the upper hand.
Fortunately, I restrained myself. The blood tests I made him take
came back completely out of whack. I was not looking forward to
seeing him again and admitting defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But Mario, stressed no more after passing probation at his job,
synthesized it all a few weeks later with elegant simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you I was stressed,'' he said. He paused. ``I was
really stressed.'' He paused again. ``I was kind of too stressed to
take my medicines for a while.'' He smiled sheepishly. It was
another split decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
