<SLUG> BC-SCI-ANTARCTIC-BIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BICYCLE BUILT FOR BRUTAL SOUTH POLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Ill., Wis., Calif.)   (af)  
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If you want to bicycle to work, finding a good bike
for your commute is hardly a problem. But if you work in Antarctica
and the commute is around the South Pole, things get a little
trickier.
</P>
<P>
   Bicycle manufacturers, catering to the sport of extreme biking,
make rugged two-wheelers for traveling along mountain trails,
through snowy hills or across desert flats. However, not one of
these machines is up to conditions found at the pole, where in
winter temperatures average minus 76 degrees Fahrenheit, the sun
never rises and drifting snow piles up several feet.
</P>
<P>
   Students at the Art Institute of Pittsburgh, working with
researchers and technicians who stay at the South Pole, hope to
change this with a new type of bicycle designed for Antarctic
conditions. If all goes as planned, one or two of the cycles will
go to the pole this year for testing.
</P>
<P>
   The program is part of a collaboration among several technical
schools and the Center for Astrophysical Research in Antarctica
(CARA), a consortium of universities that build and operate
telescopes at the South Pole. Working with a $575,000 grant from
the National Science Foundation, CARA is trying to use the
students' classroom work and technical skills to improve quality of
life at the South Pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want something functional at the end because we are trying
to create a more aesthetically pleasing and productive work
environment at the South Pole,'' said Randall H. Landsberg, CARA's
education coordinator at the University of Chicago, ``But it's also
a great experience for the students.''
</P>
<P>
   The students in Pittsburgh, and others at Gateway Technical
Institute in Elkhorn, Wis., and Triton College in Rivergrove, Ill.,
are engaged in projects including planning interior space in new
buildings at the pole and designing a portable enclosure for
researchers in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen M. Butler, assistant director of the design school at
the Art Institute of Pittsburgh, said students earning associate
and technical degrees there are enthusiastic about problem-based
learning. ``It fosters a relationship between science and art and
design,'' he said, ``The projects come from discussions with people
who have worked at the South Pole and the students get the
satisfaction of coming up with solutions that make people's lives
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The school launched its first project with CARA five years ago
when students set out to improve the cold-weather gear researchers
wore. One invented a two-piece glove that kept researchers' hands
warm while working with small objects by allowing them to
temporarily pull back a heavy, outer mitten to expose a hand
covered in an inner glove.
</P>
<P>
   The bicycle project has proved even more challenging.
Researchers have taken bikes to the pole for more than a decade,
but success has been limited. The cycles, usually mountain bikes
with 2.5-inch-wide tires, work during the summer. But riders say
that during the winter, extreme cold and drifting snow, a granular
variety with the consistency of sand, render the bikes useless.
</P>
<P>
   ``In places that are not well traveled, the tires sink into the
snow and you're stuck,'' said John Kovac, a biker and University of
Chicago graduate student. ``Also, bikes there often end up with
their brakes and gearshifts disabled because plastic parts crack
and cables snap because of the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   CARA's observatories at the South Pole are about three-quarters
of a mile from the main station and living quarters, isolated in an
area called the Dark Sector to keep light pollution and stray
electromagnetic radiation from polluting their observations.
Workers usually walk to and from the observatories several times a
day. Carrying equipment, a person makes the trek at about 3 miles
an hour, experts said, and a bike could triple that speed.
</P>
<P>
   Under industrial design instructors Bill Farrell and Paul
Jordan, students have worked on the project for 18 months. The
initial proposal was for a pedal-powered vehicle in a plastic
shell, but the design was discarded as too complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The current design is built around aluminum mountain bike frames
donated by Hanebrink Bicycles of Big Bear Lake, Calif. Using these
as models, Farrell said students also are making lighter, carbon
fiber frames. They have added adjustable handlebars and seat poles
with quick-release switches that can be operated with a gloved
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Students designed wide metal pedals with toothed edges to
accommodate insulated boots and have decided on a single-speed,
rear-gear drive for simplicity. The group discarded the idea of
using an old-style coaster brake operated from the pedals and will
use an all-metal disc brake on the rear wheel controlled by a lever
on the handlebar.
</P>
<P>
   The test bikes will try three wheel and tire designs, all about
20-inches in diameter with a tread section about 7-inches wide. One
wheel has vulcanized rubber tires while another has an aluminum
frame with a stainless steel mesh making up the tire portion. The
third is a hollow, polycarbonate resin wheel molded in two pieces
that are fused together at the center, a design so buoyant that it
helps the bike ``float'' above the snow, its creators say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a lot of planning and now it's time to build the
hardware and test it at the South Pole,'' Farrell said, ``By the
end of the year, we'll know what works. And if it doesn't, we'll
change it until it does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
