<HEADLINE>
MACBILL: AN AMERICAN TRAGICOMEDY IN THREE ACTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PUNCH SHAW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new political drama, ``The Senate Impeachment Proceedings,''
opened recently in the nation's capital to great fanfare and
anticipation. But not only did this turgid and sordid melodrama
fail to live up to its hype _ it established a new low in the
annals of American theater.
</P>
<P>
   This show had the warmth and kindness of ``Who's Afraid of
Virginia Woolf?''; the wit of ``Long Day's Journey into Night'';
and the intelligence of ``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the
Forum.'' You have to wonder why this production was even done,
given the largely negative reaction to an earlier (and cruder)
version that was staged late last year in the House Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of this extremely lengthy political soap opera dealt
with a president caught in the endgame of a sexual and legal
scandal. The action (and never was a word more inappropriate)
played out over three acts, with each one somehow managing to be
even more tedious and distasteful than the last.
</P>
<P>
   Act I, ``The Impeachment Vote,'' featured a number of
overwrought performances by actors portraying members of Congress,
who for the purposes of this drama were divided into two rival
bands, much like the Sharks and the Jets in ``West Side Story.'' (I
forget the names of the respective gangs.)
</P>
<P>
   What little dramatic potential the act had was completely robbed
by the shrill chatterings of a kind of Greek chorus composed of
players identified only by their initials (ABC, CBS, NBC, C-SPAN,
ESPN, WWF, etc.) who interrupted throughout the play to tell us
what had happened and what would happen next. Indeed, once this
annoying chorus made it clear that the lawmakers intended to remain
loyal to their gangs on every vote, without regard to law,
conscious or reason, the work as a whole collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Act II, ``Testimony and Trial,'' promised to breathe new life
into the piece by playing the sex card that had been prominent in
the 1998 version of the show. But even some contrived multimedia _
for no reason at all, the players were seen on videotape instead of
live on the stage _ could not add any sizzle to this disappointing
act.
</P>
<P>
   Although the characters in the House version had been clever
enough to stay focused on sex by repeatedly reminding us that
``it's not about sex,'' the grandfatherly types created for the
Senate version were far too polite to raise the subject at all.
</P>
<P>
   The final act, ``The Debate,'' was the most perplexing of all.
The entire act took place behind a closed curtain! The chorus
assured us that the players were earnestly acting away behind the
curtain, but the audience was not allowed to see them! We were
never told why, but I suspect it might have been the work of a
shadowy group of underlords called the Managers, who came out of
nowhere and somehow took control of the play early in the second
act without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen some strange avant-garde theater before, but not even
Samuel Beckett or Eugene Ionesco would have tried anything this
stupid. When the hysterical chorus finally let us know it was over,
the whole experience added a meaning to the term ``anticlimax.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the performances, there was hardly a credible acting job
in the bunch. Bill Clinton, as the president, was only sporadically
convincing in his role. The actors playing the
too-numerous-to-mention lawmakers (there must have been hundreds of
those clowns!) came across as more believable _ if only because we
assume that real politicians would also be boring.
</P>
<P>
   The only interesting performance in the entire drama, in fact,
was delivered by newcomer Monica Lewinsky, who did a fine job in
the piece's ingenue role. Although never seen in the House Theater
version, her character had triggered the action by confessing to
indelicacies with the married chief executive that would have made
a hooker blush.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
