<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5985 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACHMENT-PLAY-2ndT     02-15 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-PLAY-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: made a hooker blush. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the character finally made her long-anticipated appearance
in the second act, Lewinsky delivered one of the show's few
surprises by portraying her as composed and complex. The script, to
this point, had painted her as either a predatory slut or an abused
victim. Rather than settle the debate, Lewinsky's subtle
performance cast the issue in a new shade of exquisitely tailored
gray. Unlike the rest of this enormous cast, you expect that we may
be seeing Lewinsky again.
</P>
<P>
   Other roles, though, were just terribly miscast. The president's
lawyer, for example, was played by David Kendall, a caricature of a
whiny, grimly sincere, Ivy League mouthpiece. How could they have
cast this inexperienced nobody in such a pivotal role when Johnnie
Cochran was available?
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, this funeral dirge could have used a little comic
relief. Cochran stomping around the Senate chambers raving, ``If
the dress doesn't fit, you must acquit!'' might have given the play
the jolt it so desperately needed.
</P>
<P>
   The lighting was flat and, in many cases, unflattering. The set
design and costuming were more suited to the production of yawns
than drama. And never has the lack of music and special effects
been more keenly felt.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, the work failed on the issue of credibility.
Fiction is one thing, but this piece of fantasy would have us
believe that, first, a married president would risk everything for
a sordid liaison with a White House intern barely out of her teens;
and, second, that the government's response to this would be to
spend tens of millions of our tax dollars to deal with the mess so
that everybody in government could look bad, not just the
president. Come on.
</P>
<P>
   What a relief it is that no revivals of this work are expected.
I have never seen a performance in which both the audience and the
players seemed so universally disgusted with every aspect of the
work at hand.
</P>
<P>
   The only comfort to be found during this endlessly long drama
was this thought: At least it was only a play. Punch Shaw
contributes theater reviews and other arts pieces to the
``Star-Telegram'' and does not pay much attention to politics. We
didn't have the heart to tell him.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   THE PLAYERS
</P>
<P>
   Henry Hyde: This grandfatherly House manager made several strong
and powerful speeches during the presentation.
</P>
<P>
   William Rehnquist: The Supreme Court justice portrayed the judge
with the stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lewsinky: ``That woman, Miss Lewinsky'' made a surprise
videotape appearance late in the saga.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr: The independent counsel offered the threat of
action late in the drama.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton: Our Lady MacBeth says, ``Out, out, damn
(vast right-wing conspiracy) plot.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Peachees
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has its Oscars. Broadway has its Tonys. So shouldn't
the players in the impeachment drama also have an award? Here are
the Peachees.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest and Best Hair: Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison
</P>
<P>
   Best Monica-on-''Friends''-Update Hair: Monica Lewinsky
</P>
<P>
   Best Costume: Supreme Court Justice Rehnquist, portraying That
Guy Who Swears In the Senate, had yellow strips added to judicial
robes after seeing such a costume in a Gilbert and Sullivan
production.
</P>
<P>
   Best Comic Line: ``That depends on what your definition of `is'
is.'' President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Worst Blown Line: Again, President Clinton. Early on, he shakes
his finger at the audience and declares, ``I did not have sexual
relations with that woman, Miss Lewinsky,'' when clearly the script
must have read just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Best Imitation of a Backwoods Preacher with a Grudge: Sen. Stom
Thurmond
</P>
<P>
   Worst Make-up or Worst Lighting?: In her video deposition,
Monica Lewinsky's upper lip was not the same color as her lower
lip.
</P>
<P>
   Special ``Revenge of the Nerds'' Award: Kenneth Starr
</P>
<P>
   Best No-Show: Rep. Newt Gingrich
</P>
<P>
   Best Imitation of Your Grandfather: Rep. Henry Hyde
</P>
<P>
   Best Live Commentary: The spectator in the Senate gallery who
shouted out, ``God almighty, take the vote and get it over with!''
</P>
<P>
   _
