<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-MARY-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ITALIAN FILM CRITICS HAVE VERY CATHOLIC TASTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ ``This is a comedy that offers absolutely nothing new and
is typical of a certain genre of American cinema that seeks to make
audiences laugh by mocking everything, from simple
misunderstandings (disguises, lies, identity switches) to jokes
that are heavier and in questionable taste (the handicapped.)''
</P>
<P>
   But this Italian review of the hit comedy ``Something About
Mary'' does offer something new: it is an online assessment by the
Roman Catholic Church. And it is not all negative. ``The film is
not mean, offensive or blasphemous,'' the review said, though it
dismissed the movie nonetheless as ``superficial.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet movie review site, at
http://www.chiesacattolica.it./acec, is prepared by a film
commission of the Italian Bishops Conference and went online at the
beginning of the year. It is a glaring example of how the church
has changed its attitude toward the dominant cultural medium of the
age.
</P>
<P>
   That shift became evident in 1996, when the Vatican marked the
100th anniversary of film by issuing its own list of the 45 best
movies of the century. There were films with spiritual themes, like
``Gandhi'' and ``Ben-Hur,'' but also ``Citizen Kane,'' ``The Wizard
of Oz,'' ``The Bicycle Thief'' and ``La Strada.'' Since then
Catholic bishops around the world have weighed in with their own
assessments of contemporary cinema, with some intriguing cultural
differences.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the Office of Film and Broadcasting of the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops introduced a more limited
movie review Web site two years ago. There are only two reviewers,
both laymen, and their site only discusses a handful of current
films (Web address: http://www.nccbuscc.org/movies/index.htm).
</P>
<P>
   The Italian bishops' Web site carries reviews of most current
films as well as movies dating back to 1991. By next year it plans
to have its entire archive on the Internet. In cinephiliac Europe,
moreover, the Catholic Church takes an unusually nuanced and
broad-minded approach to its reviews. ``We watch everything, even
R-rated films,'' said the Rev. Dario Vigano, a professor of ethics
at the Catholic University of Milan who sits on the church's
32-member film review board. ``We don't watch X-rated films, but
you can't really call those movies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We exist to give moral, not aesthetic, opinions,'' Vigano
added. ``If you look at our reviews of the soft-porn films of Tinto
Brass,'' a well-known Italian director, ``you will see why we
reject them. They aren't embarrassing to watch. After all, we are
adults.''
</P>
<P>
   The church long ago gave up the practice of blackballing films.
In 1934 Italian bishops began regularly vetting new releases to
guide church-run parish theaters, but there are only 600 of those
left in Italy. Nowadays, with families deluged by movies in
theaters, on cable and on videocasette, the church seeks to promote
those that uphold moral values.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas the American church's version has four basic ratings,
from A-1 (``general patronage'') to O (``morally offensive''), the
Italian ratings range from ``acceptable'' to ``unacceptable,'' with
a broad palette of gradations, including ``dubious'' and
``fatuous.'' The bishops add a second and sometimes third
description after a slash to further assist viewers. ``Something
About Mary,'' for example, was rated ``inconsistent/vulgar.''
</P>
<P>
   A recently released Italian sex farce, ``Paparazzi,'' was rated
``futile.'' Massimo Giraldi, a layman who is chief reviewer at the
church's National Commission of Film Evaluation, explained that
while the movie was sexually explicit and thoroughly offensive, his
committee deemed it ``too stupid'' to merit a rating of
unacceptable. ``That would give the film too much importance,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the church's online reviews are succinct
and prosaic, not unlike a Siskel and Ebert snippet; in Italy they
tend to be more in sync with the French journal Cahiers du Cinema,
with considered esthetic judgments, acid commentary on American
culture and erudite film references. Scenes from ``The Truman
Show,'' for example, are likened to moments in Fritz Lang's
``Metropolis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Meet Joe Black,'' in which Brad Pitt plays the force of death,
recently opened in Italy and won a ``questionable/ambiguous''
rating, but the review focused on its intellectual flaws. ``The
life-death relationship moves within the usual pseudo-religious and
pseudo-philosophical systems that get lost in New Age trends,'' the
review said. ``It confirms a certain confusion that American
culture cannot shake when it deals with issues tied to the
supernatural.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Such assessments are a far cry from the rigid and terse
condemnations the Roman Catholic Church once issued in Europe and
the United States. In 1934 the American bishops instituted the
Legion of Decency, which lobbied Hollywood studios steadily, and
often successfully, to tailor movies to their own moral standards.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, where Catholicism was the state religion until 1984,
the church had an even closer relationship with the film industry.
Some of the first movies made in Europe at the turn of the century
were accounts of the life of Jesus; in Italy these were shown only
in churches. The Vatican banned church screenings after directors
began turning to secular topics, and instead allowed bishops to set
up parish theaters. There were some 6,000 church-run cinemas, half
of all the movie theaters in Italy, until the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   To guide those theaters, Italian bishops started a journal of
their own reviews in 1934, Segnalazioni Cinematografiche, covering
even the most obscure movies; bound hardcover volumes are still
coveted by film buffs. ``Those old reviews are an important
reference point,'' said Serge Toubiana, editor in chief of Cahiers
du Cinema. ``They saw everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The church reviews gave a thumbs down to ``Dames,'' a 1934
musical starring Ruby Keeler and Dick Powell, because it ``mocked
efforts to impose moral standards on show business.'' The same year
the church declared ``It Happened One Night,'' starring Clark Gable
and Claudette Colbert, ``wholesome'' but recommended that certain
scenes be omitted for young audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The church does not ban films, mainly because it has no
authority in Italy to approve what goes into commercial theaters.
But it does speak out against films it considers insulting, from
Fellini's 1960 classic ``La Dolce Vita,'' which mocked bourgeois
families loyal to the church, to Martin Scorsese's 1987 film ``The
Last Temptation of Christ,'' deemed too racy to be reverent.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, a former theater actor and playwright, is not
much of a film enthusiast and does not watch television. But he
recently attended a Vatican screening of ``Life Is Beautiful,'' the
Italian comedy by Roberto Benigni that is set in the Holocaust and
has been nominated for seven Academy Awards. The animated film
``The Prince of Egypt'' was also shown recently at the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Vigano, who attends international film festivals, said that
``Life Is Beautiful'' (``recommendable/poetic'') and ``The Truman
Show'' (``recommendable/difficult/good for debate'') were among his
favorites last year. He added that he was thrilled by the seven
Oscar nominations for the Benigni film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The panorama of Italian cinema is so flat, we welcome
Benigni,'' he said. ``His success confirms all the hopes of our
commission.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
