<SLUG> BC-SCI-EYE-SURGERY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE OFFERS NEW HOPE FOR SAVING INJURED EYES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Mass.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By PHILIPS J. HILTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the summer of 1996, a supervisor at a soft-drink factory in
Ghana, West Africa, angered some of the men working under him, and
during the fight that followed, lye was thrown in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, his vision would be declared an irreparable loss, and
doctors would not attempt treatment.
</P>
<P>
   His corneas, the windows over the pupil, had turned thick, white
and opaque. The globe of each eye had lost its fluid and deflated
like a limp balloon to less than half size. And the man's eyelids
had fused together.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, after the pioneering work of Dr. Relya
Zivojnovic in Belgium, surgery has brought back sight to people
with more and more extreme injuries. And now, according to a report
in last month's issue of Archives of Ophthalmology, the man from
Ghana has had vision restored to 20/60 in his right eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is tremendously interesting,'' said Dr. Halal Lewis,
director of the Eye Institute at the Cleveland Clinic. ``It
suggests that maybe some eyes that we thought would continue to
deteriorate can be saved, at least temporarily.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a loss of pressure inside the eye has occurred, the eye
usually deteriorates steadily into complete collapse. But in the
case of the man from Ghana, that has not happened, though his
doctors are not sure why. And by using an artificial cornea, Dr.
Claes Dohlman at the Massachusetts Eye and Ear Infirmary was able
to restore vision to the patient's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John D. Gottsch, of the Wilmer Eye Institute at Johns
Hopkins Medical Center, noted: ``Eyes in as bad shape as this are
generally written off as hopeless. But this work by Dr. Dohlman is
very encouraging; it may teach us that even eyes like these have
the potential to see again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Ghanaian man, Dohlman believed that enough of
the eye was still working _ the retina was intact and the glands
that make fluid in the eye were not completely lost _ that a
transplant might work. He used a clear plastic cornea to replace
the injured one. Because of the extensive tissue damage, he first
had to sew a patch of healthy eye tissue to the plastic cornea, and
then he transplanted both together onto the man's eye.
</P>
<P>
   The operation occurred in 1997, and the man's eye has retained
good vision for more than a year. It is not yet clear whether his
good vision will continue or deteriorate again over time.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known how many cases of injury leading ultimately to
complete collapse of the eye occur in the United States, but
researchers say the number is in the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   And they say that the case of the man from Ghana suggests that
some people now counted as untreatable may be able to have vision
restored for a time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 1722EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
