<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5993 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENVIRONMENTAL-ACTIVIS     02-15 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENTAL-ACTIVIST-4000(7Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUSADE AGAINST PESTICIDES COSTS COMPANY LOTS, BUT ACTIVIST MORE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by ENVIRONMENTAL-ELFATOCHEM) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   This is the story of Mark O'Connor, a Texas environmental
activist whose little-known crusade against a company for arsenic
contamination in Bryan-College Station mirrors the high-profile
story of Jan Schlichtmann, played by John Travolta in the current
hit movie ``A Civil Action.'' O'Connor's story, though, is the tale
of a brilliant but deeply disillusioned man who spent much of his
adult life wasting his talent, drowning himself in alcohol and
drugs. His whistle-blowing work paved the road to his redemption,
led to the closure of the pesticide plant Elf Atochem and initiated
one of the largest environmental settlements in state history. For
O'Connor, it was a solitary fight, one that for the most part paid
him nothing and tore apart his family life. This story was
constructed after examining legal documents and hundreds of
newspaper stories, talking to O'Connor's friends and family and
examining more than 300 E-mails and personal documents that
belonged to Mark O'Connor, who died of a heart attack five months
ago at age 41.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PROLOGUE
</P>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ The cold rain came down hard, as it had for
weeks. Mark O'Connor walked along the fence line of the Elf Atochem
herbicides/pesticides plant, in search of arsenic. Actually, he was
looking for a pile of dirt, one contaminated with deadly inorganic
arsenic. He stamped out his cigarette and put his chin to his chest
to keep his glasses dry.
</P>
<P>
   His mood was dour. It wasn't the winter storms that he cussed.
He loved rainwater; it was pure. Rain was not the problem. People
were the problem. He had spent the past few days vehemently arguing
with Elf Atochem managers, the same higher-ups who six months
earlier had asked Mark's hazardous-waste cleanup company to help
the plant dispose of its arsenic-contaminated waste water. A
relationship with Elf Atochem could have led to a long-term
contract worth millions. But he couldn't keep quiet. The pesticide
plant's carelessness in disposing of its hazardous waste threatened
the surrounding lakes and soil.
</P>
<P>
   Mark's anger had peaked a few nights earlier, when he was
working past midnight at the plant, filtering and disposing of
chemically tainted rainwater. He stumbled across a scene that
horrified him: a plant worker dumping contaminated water into a
waterstream, through a pipe drilled into the dike. The stream ran
to ``No-Name Lake,'' which turned into a creek, which poured into
Finfeather Lake, which ran through the city of Bryan to Bryan
Municipal Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing?'' Mark asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pumping water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I can,'' he said. ``Supervisor said I'm supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what he said, Mark thought. ``I'm supposed to.'' He's
supposed to what, poison the water? Thinking about it now, marching
along the fence line in his search for arsenic-contaminated dirt,
Mark became angry again. The managers hadn't flinched when I told
them that story, he thought. Said it was no big deal, they'd take
care of it. It was obvious to him they didn't care. That was even
clearer when he talked to the plant workers and shared his rage.
Many of them rolled their eyes or chuckled, as if what he talked
about was standard operating procedure. ``If you think that's
bad,'' one said, ``you should see the pile.''
</P>
<P>
   So the pile was where Mark headed. When he reached it, he was at
the property's edge, staring at a heap of arsenic-contaminated dirt
that had been dug up and deposited near the shoreline of Finfeather
Lake to make room for Elf Atochem's newly paved parking lot. It was
large, about 5,000 cubic yards' worth of bulldozed earth. It was
uncovered. If it was severely arsenic-contaminated, Mark thought,
this was bad. Rain and wind could cause the arsenic to ``leach''
into the nearby lake and land, despite the fence surrounding it. At
least the gate was secure; he counted three padlocks. There were
spirals of razor wire atop the tall fence. Mark walked the fence
line clear back behind the pile, off the road, toward the lake.
Mark was shocked at what he found: The fence ended. It did not
connect. It was three-sided.
</P>
<P>
   As he neared the pile of dirt that day in January 1991, he had
no way of knowing that it was fully 1 percent arsenic _ enough to
``kill an elephant,'' as his father would later say. He did not
foresee that this mound of earth would eventually cost Elf Atochem
$2.5 million, a bargain compared with the hundreds of millions the
company would eventually be committed to paying in fines and
settlements.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   As well, Mark had no idea that this discovery and others like it
would consume him for the rest of the decade, giving his life
purpose and a sense of redemption, even as they ripped apart his
family. He did not know how his crusade against environmental
complacency and injustice would rouse his friends, anger powerful
corporations and give hope to a handful of families whose children
were born with fatal diseases.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way he or anyone else could understand how the
victories and ultimate tragedy that would befall Mark O'Connor
would nevertheless sow seeds of hope for people he did not know and
for the son he would eventually inspire.
</P>
<P>
   All Mark O'Connor knew then was that he spotted tricycle tire
tracks in the soil. He was not sure whether the tracks had any
connection to the children's plastic toy pail someone had left atop
the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rod O'Connor set his tray down on one of the long picnic
tables inside the Tony DeMaria Bar B Q restaurant in Waco in
Central Texas. It was November 1998, and the environmental
chemistry classes he taught at Baylor University were preparing for
Thanksgiving break.
</P>
<P>
   It was warm out, more than 70 degrees, but Dr. Rod said he
wanted hot barbecue, never mind the weather. He was retirement age,
64, like most of the customers in Tony's. Unlike most, he was
white.
</P>
<P>
   He surveyed the poor-side barbecue dive as he dipped one of four
thick slices of white bread into the gravy/drippings that came with
his skin-on chicken. ``I worked at a place like this in high
school,'' he said, smiling. ``There was a poster on the wall that
said, `The Lord does not subtract from your three score and ten the
days you spent fishing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rod hadn't been fishing in a long time. He and his son,
Mark, used to cast often _ fishing in Montana, Missouri-style, none
of that over-romanticized fly-fishing stuff. They hiked in Arizona,
walked the plains of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   That was before their relationship changed, before the teen-age
Mark embraced fully the hippie vibe of the '70s. Mark still carried
a slide rule _ he was an excellent student _ but his increasing use
of drugs and alcohol began to affect his desire to excel. He grew
his hair long. He fought often with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rod didn't understand. Rod O'Connor was born in a small
Missouri town. Growing up, he had done as his father, a school
superintendent, had told him to do. ``I was a goody two-shoes,''
Dr. Rod says. When he and his wife saw ``Rebel Without a Cause'' in
1955, he says, he ``never did figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   When the offer came to teach at Texas A&AMP;M in 1973, Dr. Rod was
happy to move from Spokane, Wash. He thought that perhaps the
conservative nature of the Bible Belt would help straighten Mark
out. Any town surrounded by places like Snook and Madisonville, as
Bryan-College Station is, must be a good influence.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The lake had a strong, unpleasant odor, even in 1973. The Texas
Water Quality Board found that Lake Finfeather and the lake it fed,
Bryan Municipal Lake, contained levels of arsenic 50 times higher
than the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency allowed. A few years
earlier, the state had blamed Pennwalt Corp.'s herbicide/pesticide
plant _ later Elf Atochem _ that sat adjacent to Finfeather, and
ordered the plant to clean up the mess. But Pennwalt's treatment of
the lake proved hazardous as well: The chemical added to disperse
the arsenic instead made it collect on the lake's floor.
</P>
<P>
   No one was surprised, then, in 1973 when a Bryan-College Station
lawyer filed suit against Pennwalt in the 85th State District
Court, asking that the company stop discharging dangerous chemicals
into the water and that it be made responsible for its cleanup. It
was estimated then that there were between 300,000 and 700,000
pounds of arsenic-contaminated sludge at the lakes' bases.
</P>
<P>
   That so much contaminant could collect in a freshwater lake was
understandable, given the plant site's history. In 1940, the Bryan
company Cotton Poisons began producing calcium arsenate, used since
the turn of the century to kill pests on cotton crops.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental health concerns during this time were almost
nonexistent. There were pictures taken by the plant of workers
covered in white arsenic powder; piles of calcium arsenate would be
left outside to dry so they could be ground into powder and sold.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, the company was bought by Pennsylvania Salt
Manufacturing Co. (eventually known as Pennwalt Corp.), which later
also manufactured arsenic acid-based cotton desiccants used to
defoliate cotton. (The arsenic dried the cotton, which made it
easier to pick.)
</P>
<P>
   For the next few decades, the company would continue producing
arsenic-based materials. Pennwalt would later acknowledge that the
sins of these decades undoubtedly contributed to the problem that
came to be known locally as ``Lake Arsenic.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1975, Texas regulators were convinced that waste water from
Pennwalt had seeped into the lake and caused the environmental
hazard. A plant official told a group of concerned citizens that
the company would work to clean up the lake, but that ``as long as
arsenic is in demand, we will keep making it.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   One year later, the lawsuit against the company ended in a
consent judgment: Pennwalt would drain Lake Finfeather and remove
the arsenic-contaminated sediment. Although it agreed to fix the
problem, Pennwalt did not admit any wrongdoing. ``In this kind of
judgment,'' an attorney fighting Pennwalt said after the decision,
``we don't expect a defendant to admit that he is guilty as hell.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Connor was well on his way to drunkenness most nights in
1987, often bringing a 12-pack of Miller Lite to comfort him
through his dreary job as a technical vice president/gopher for his
dad's company, Texas Romec.
</P>
<P>
   Mark had undergone a steady slide into depression and
drug-induced escape since his arrival in Bryan. His SAT scores
allowed him to skip his senior year of high school and get admitted
early to Texas A&AMP;M, but Mark was chafed by the school's
``ultraconservative, stodgy mindset.'' As he would later write in
E-mails to friends:
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember the looks and comments I got as a 17-year-old
freshman with hair down to my (rear) in 1974 _ right around the
time the Corps was rabidly resisting integration of women into
their ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   He was equally disillusioned with the faculty, believing they
were more concerned with grant money and corporate-funded research
than teaching and new ideas:
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent my summers doing construction work and soon decided
that many of the men shoveling beside me in ditches seemed far
wiser than most of my professors at A&AMP;M. ... After a year and a
half, I ... chose to embark on the noble mission of being an honest
working man. I had also started developing the unfortunate habit of
trying to hide from myself, my dissatisfactions and my increasingly
cynical view of the world with beer and drugs. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked job after job: ditch-digger, telephone lineman,
oilfield, construction, electrician, cable lineman. ... By the time
I reached 30, I discovered that I had obtained no real skills and
that the drinking and drugging had reached the point to where I was
practically unemployable anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The only semi-steady work he could find was with his father, Dr.
Rod, who had co-founded Texas Romec in 1980 while still teaching.
Texas Romec developed new technologies for toxic waste treatments,
specifically to filter and purify waste water at oilfield sites.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mark built the company's signature piece of equipment:
a patented reverse-osmosis filtration system inside an 18-wheeler
for use in oilfields and other hazardous-water cleanup sites. The
job offered some travel, and an opportunity to bond with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Money troubles forced them to sell the patent on the
reverse-osmosis system. But by the mid- to late-'80s, the company
had discovered an unlikely source of income: flea combs. Mark and
Dr. Rod had designed combs that contained flea medicine, so pets
could be treated by combing them. It became Texas Romec's chief
source of income by 1987. But it didn't make Mark enjoy work any
more.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mark fell in love. Her name was Shannon, a high school
student hired by his dad, a pretty blond girl who talked into the
night about his dreams and overlooked his addictions. She moved in
with Mark, her older man, the flea-comb-magnate-turned-dreamer with
bad credit.
</P>
<P>
   When, in 1989, they had a son, Kyle, Mark left his last Miller
Lite can, half-consumed, in the parking lot of his first Alcoholics
Anonymous meeting. The program took. Mark and Shannon reveled in
his new-found sobriety, going to AA dances, to the beach, camping.
With Mark's drug-induced haze gone, he and Dr. Rod tried to
re-establish communication by writing poetry to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there were still problems to overcome. Mark slept during
the day and stayed up at night, as he'd conditioned his body, which
wasn't conducive to the typical family life Shannon wanted. But for
now, it seemed as if the clouds were parting. And it stayed that
way, until Mark's obsession with Elf Atochem.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 7, 1989, a Bryan Utilities transformer blew. The power
outage lasted three hours. Included in the buildings that went
powerless was Elf Atochem, which had merged one month earlier with
Pennwalt to form the new company.
</P>
<P>
   For those three hours, there was a scrubber system shutdown. The
scrubbers are like filters that catch hazardous materials in the
air that are produced during the acid-manufacturing process. There
was no catching now. Billows of yellow-orange acid fumes containing
nitric oxide and nitrogen dioxide filled the plant.
</P>
<P>
   As was standard procedure by this time, the employees of the
plant with the new $10 billion French-owned parent company ran from
the building as fast as they could.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The weed never made him this high, Mark thought as he unlocked a
door at the Elf Atochem plant in January 1991, shortly after his
discovery of the arsenic-loaded dirt pile. ``Breaking and
entering'' was such a nasty, bureaucratic term, he thought.
Besides, he had his own set of keys. He preferred to call it
``trespassing for a higher cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark took pictures of the things he would later claim proved Elf
Atochem's unsafe practices. He photographed open drums of
chemicals, leaky tanks, flooded areas. He photographed the dirt
pile, which now comically had a mostly torn tarp draped over it.
The photographs would eventually prove critical in getting
regulatory agencies to take notice of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Dr. Rod called his patent attorney, the only
one he knew well. ``I told him that we were in a quandary. We
wanted to finish the job initially, but we knew they were breaking
the law. He told me that we had better call it in, or we'd be
culpable.'' Dr. Rod made a call to the Texas Air Control Board and
Texas Water Commission. (These would later become the Texas Natural
Resource Conservation Commission, or TNRCC.) They asked Mark and
Dr. Rod to write down everything they had heard or seen.
</P>
<P>
   They had heard a lot, because Mark's inquiry didn't stop with
picture-taking. During the next several months, he would play
investigative reporter, quizzing the workers and anyone with
knowledge of the plant's operations. There were many horrific
stories, several of which would be documented by the local media
and government agencies, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``disastrous spill'' in 1982 of 1,000 to 1,500 pounds of
arsenic trioxide, which created an arsenic dust cloud that sent the
plant workers fleeing into the streets, warning others to get away.
</P>
<P>
   _ Numerous ``boilovers,'' such as one reported in 1988 when a
``reactor'' vat of arsenic trioxide overflowed during the
manufacturing process, again causing a mass exodus. During a
boilover, nitric oxide fumes and arsenic smokes were released
through the smokestacks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Air and soil samplings that showed high levels of arsenic in
the air, dust and soil in a two-mile area surrounding the plant.
There were also stories about what seemed an unusual number of
babies born with partially formed brains who died shortly after
birth.
</P>
<P>
   _ A reaction of methyl parathion and cement caused a 55-gallon
drum to rupture and catch fire, which in turn inflamed adjacent
drums, sending smoke throughout the building. Afterward, a fire
department test noted levels of hydrogen sulfide in excess of 1
percent inside the building, a potentially hazardous level.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employee allegations that someone was jamming the alarms so
that they would not sound if such accidents occurred.
</P>
<P>
   To Mark's chagrin, the company's problems were well-known to the
agencies _ for example, a dust sampling taken by the Texas Air
Control Board in a day-care center near the plant in 1988 contained
arsenic levels at 1,900 parts per million. The average level in the
United States was about 5 parts per million. Mark was dumbfounded.
Governmental agencies had fined and monitored the plant, but to
Mark it wasn't enough. He wanted to know, ``Why hadn't more been
done?''
</P>
<P>
   For the next few years, Mark continued to gather as much
information as possible. Elf Atochem became his life. His only
income was from Texas Romec; the help he gave regulators and law
firms paid him little or nothing. He worked with the regulatory
agencies and helped law enforcement groups gather information in
hopes of prompting criminal charges against the plant.
</P>
<P>
   But the time spent working against Elf Atochem did not help
Mark's personal life. As Shannon put it, ``It seemed like I woke up
one day, and all THIS was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Mark spent much of his time investigating the plant's
operations. He wandered up and down the railroad tracks that
bordered the plant to the east, looking for any sign of
improprieties. He walked the fence line on the west side as well,
standing on the hood of his truck, taking pictures with Kodak
disposable cameras, enduring the jeers of the workers who spotted
him.
</P>
<P>
   Home life became chaotic. Mark kept scores of legal note pads
scattered about, each one scribbled and doodled on; hundreds of
newspaper clippings littered the house. Phone bills regularly ran
from $400 to $600 because of the calls Mark made to activists,
writers, agencies, officials and aggrieved parties throughout the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The strong hint of danger was always present. Clicking sounds
and strange noises led Mark and Shannon to believe that their phone
was tapped. Shannon would come home and find FBI agents or Texas
Rangers at her table, talking to Mark. The agencies suggested that
Mark get a remote-ignition switch for his truck, just in case,
which he never did. Mark bought Shannon a snub-nosed .38-caliber
handgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't normal,'' Shannon would say later. ``It was not
the way I wanted to live. The danger somewhat intrigued him, but I
hated the whole situation. He was the best father he knew how to
be, but he wasn't always there to begin with. Then this came along.
He had time for everybody but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the work clearly paid off for him in one respect: In
December 1992, after months of wrangling over Elf Atochem's ground
water and lake cleanup efforts, the company and the Texas Water
Commission agreed on an $11 million payout, the largest
environmental settlement to that point in state history.
</P>
<P>
   Included was $2.5 million for environmental violations _
including the now-famous dirt pile _ and $6.6 million to buy out or
compensate affected property owners. This was in addition to the
$14 million the company estimated it would have to spend to clean
up the plant site. All told, it was estimated the company would pay
$26 million.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   The company told the Houston Chronicle that it didn't want to go
to court with the commission, which had estimated that Elf Atochem
had allowed 4,000 gallons of arsenic-laced ground water daily to
seep into the nearby creek and lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Mark felt his first twinge of vindication. It was an important
triumph, Mark believed, but he hoped for more than a monetary
punishment. By summer 1993, he thought that would come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The newly formed Texas Environmental Task Force executed search
warrants at the Bryan plant and Atochem North America's corporate
offices in Pennsylvania. They were hoping to find evidence of
criminal negligence in the company's handling of the Bryan plant.
</P>
<P>
   They found little that was useful. Months later, a high-level
company executive, on condition of anonymity, would tell the
Bryan-College Station Eagle, ``These files were cleaned not only
this spring, but several times the last year or so. The
(incriminating) information is not here anymore _ gone.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   After the first year of investigating Elf Atochem, Mark and Dr.
Rod were convinced that, although the contaminated ground water and
its seepage into the lakes were important, the real hazard was
airborne chemicals carried from the plant to the surrounding
neighborhoods. It didn't take long for Mark to test that theory.
</P>
<P>
   Three law firms had descended upon the town, signing up
residents to class-action and property lawsuits against Elf
Atochem. To prove the hazardous levels of arsenic in the
surrounding area, Mark was overseeing testing for various lawyers
and firms.
</P>
<P>
   There was no problem in finding arsenic. On ceiling fans, in
doorways, on air-conditioning units _ the dust had arsenic levels
ranging from 80 to 2,000 parts per million, when 5 parts per
million was average. But the company argued that such findings in
no way implicated it. Arsenic can be found in rat poison. It could
have been blown there by various means.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rod and Mark provided the way to overcome that argument. A
few years earlier, the Texas Air Control Board had conducted a test
of the dust in the air being emitted from the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The key was not the arsenic in the air samples, but the other
chemicals for which it tested: zinc and manganese, which were also
used in the plant's product manufacturing. Because the ratio of
arsenic to zinc to manganese in the houses matched the ratio found
in the plant's dust emissions, it was a fingerprint, one that
pointed toward Elf Atochem.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Cynthia and Neal Coates moved to a house six-tenths of
a mile from the Elf Atochem plant. In 1992, their son, Samuel, was
born with a partially formed brain, a small portion of which
protruded from the back of his head. As with most anencephalic
babies, he struggled to breathe and to suckle for most of his short
life.
</P>
<P>
   The Coateses knew Samuel was dying one night in October, the
same night they attended the home birth of Neal's sister's child.
While his sister labored, Neal and Cynthia took turns holding
Samuel, taking pictures, telling him he was loved. The baby cousin
arrived at 11:30 p.m. Samuel died three hours later. He had lived
one day short of two months.
</P>
<P>
   Initial newspaper reports said Samuel was the first anencephalic
child born in the area in eight years. But Mark found others in his
door-to-door searching, poorer families who weren't counted,
stories later verified by the law firms. Each case was more
painful, more touching, than the last. Mark found that many studies
linked arsenic contamination and neural-tube birth defects, such as
anencephaly and spina bifida.
</P>
<P>
   Mark wanted to be sure these cases weren't lost in the large
class-action lawsuits that were brewing. Firms had come in and
signed up homeowners for lawsuits, but Mark wasn't convinced they
were passionate enough to do what was right by the 12 families who
had 13 children with such defects, all of whom lived near the
plant.
</P>
<P>
   With Mark's help, these families got their big gun: famed
Houston attorney Joe Jamail, who had helped Pennzoil win one of the
largest civil settlements in history in a contract dispute with
Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1995, Jamail walked into a meeting with the lawyers
for Elf Atochem and several other chemical companies now involved
in the suit. He carefully laid out 13 graphic pictures of
anencephalic babies, showing their deformities to everyone in the
room. As one version of the story goes, he then addressed the
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today and today only,'' Jamail said, ``one hundred thirty
million dollars to settle. Otherwise, the parents get on the stand
and tell their stories.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers settled, although Elf Atochem did not admit guilt.
Newspaper reports put the figure at ``more than $100 million.'' Elf
Atochem's lawyers dispute this, but cite confidentiality portions
of the agreement in declining to detail the actual amount.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   There was no reaction at the Elf Atochem plant to the news. The
company had been closed for more than a year; Elf Atochem shuttered
its Bryan operations in October 1993 because, it said, the
operations were no longer profitable.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the company settled a class-action suit for $55
million. The settlement ensured that no additional similar claims
could be made against the company, no matter what health problems
residents developed in the future. Mark felt this amount wasn't
enough. Concerned that more arsenic-caused illnesses would show up
years from now, he led a successful effort to appeal the case _
including going to the Texas A&AMP;M library to learn how to write a
brief himself, which he submitted on behalf of contesting
litigants. The settlement is currently before the 5th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for Mark,'' says the Sierra Club's Neil Carman,
``I think it (the plant) would still be running.'' All that is left
behind at the Elf Atochem site now are ground-water treatment
facilities to continue the plant's cleanup of contaminated ground
water and soil.
</P>
<P>
   The day the plant closed, Mark allowed himself a small moment of
satisfaction. Although he felt bad for the 30 or so workers who
lost their jobs, he knew the larger wrong had been righted, at
least partially. I've finally done good, he thought. His life had
been given purpose, importance. The water was turning pure. It
tasted good.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Shannon left Mark in 1996. The separation came as a shock to
Mark. Although the split was relatively amicable _ they would share
time with Kyle equally _ Mark still didn't understand what he'd
done wrong. He told himself and Shannon that by helping the
community, he was helping his family.
</P>
<P>
   To help deal with the pain, Mark wrote often of his travails to
an E-mail list known as ``Bobwahred,'' composed of journalists,
lawyers and others of like interests. He usually signed his notes
or E-mails as a variation of ``Rainman'': a person who turned water
pure as rain.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote of his ongoing battles in East Texas that occupied him
through the latter '90s: He was now fighting chicken-processing
plants, searching for mercury dumps, doing various investigations
for lawyers in other suits. But his role as environmental watchdog
became increasingly difficult. As he wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these fights, especially the inexcusable resistance
offered by the environmental regulatory agencies, wear on me. I
know ... about the loss of hope, the meaninglessness of trying to
change a system that can't be changed. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I'll get up tomorrow morning, put on my pants
and try to get by one more day. If I'm accomplishing nothing else,
at least I didn't cop out today, at least I tried, and as fruitless
as it may all end up, it is that that I choose to try to pass on to
my son _ Rain.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Mark was huffing. It was mid-September 1998, a Thursday evening,
two years after the separation, eight years after he first set foot
on Elf Atochem grounds, and he was the assistant coach for Kyle's
soccer team. He was running up and down the field, playing goalie.
He was thin, looked to be in good shape, had only turned 41. But a
lifetime of Benson &AMP; Hedges didn't help his on-field stamina.
</P>
<P>
   Mark had much to be excited about. His relationship with Shannon
was very amicable. His 9-year-old son was healthy and doing well in
school. Work was good, too. Mark had spent the year as an
investigator for an environmental law firm in East Texas, rounding
up information on another hazardous waste site near Caddo Lake.
</P>
<P>
   His personal life was ... well, he finally had prospects of
having a personal life. He had recently hit it off with a young
woman, and the next night would be their first official date.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon told him he looked pale. ``I don't feel well,'' he said.
``I need to eat.'' Mark and Kyle returned to his house. Mark put
Kyle to bed between 9 and 9:30 p.m. He kissed him good night.
</P>
<P>
   Between 10 and 10:30 p.m., Dr. Rod called with good news: A new
job was calling them to southern Asia, to clean up
arsenic-contaminated drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Mark hung up and lay down on the couch. The television was on.
He still didn't feel right. Tired. Maybe he should just crash on
the couch. He often slept there, anyway. Time for adventures
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   A few days earlier, Mark had E-mailed friends about the purest
water he'd ever sipped. His words seemed a fitting dream:
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all talkin' about smells and light and corn bread ... brings
back so many memories of visiting my maternal grandparents in
Gordonville, Missouri, population 99 back then ... Pappo and
Grandma Mienie. They had no plumbing, just an outside cistern with
a hand pump on it so every time I stumble into a filthy Exxon
station restroom in Buffalo or Dime Box I'm reminded once again of
their old outhouse. Every night Grandma Mienie would go out and
fill a huge kettle at the pump and put it on the coal-burning stove
to heat up and make us a bath in a big old tin tub. In the winter
the house was heated with coal stoves and in the summer you
languished in the heat and humidity, listening to the cacophony of
crickets and cicadas until you could finally fall asleep. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I hold those times close to my heart because I know I'll never
see anything remotely like that again. I've never tasted water so
damn good as what came out of that cistern. The smells of that old
house, the utter satisfaction of just sitting in that porch swing
with an old man smoking a pipe and not saying a word while he
listened to his ballgame, the sky lit up with fireflies, the clinks
and clanks coming from the kitchen at sun-up as Grandma Mienie
stoked the stoves and got some scrambled eggs going for everyone. I
honest to God could live like that if I can ever figure out a way
to get back there _ Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Mark's alarm went off in his bedroom and woke Kyle up.
Sleepy-eyed, he turned the alarm off and saw his dad in the living
room, on the couch, hands on his chest. The television was still
on. Kyle went to the kitchen and started a pot of coffee for his
dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad, get up.''
</P>
<P>
   He walked over to the couch and pushed his dad. He felt cold.
Kyle put a blanket over him. Kyle checked his breathing. He
immediately ran to the phone. He called his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom,'' he said calmly, ``something's not right. Daddy's not
breathing. I think he's dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Shannon burst through the door. Peaceful as he
looked, Shannon could tell immediately that Mark was dead. She
found Kyle crying in a fetal position in his bedroom. She picked
him up and took him to a neighbor's house, ran back and called 911.
Shannon thought of Kyle, and she asked that the ambulance please
not turn on its siren.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   EPILOGUE
</P>
<P>
   No one would have guessed that Mark O'Connor would die of a
heart attack at age 41 _ or that he would die a hero, or that his
funeral would be packed with people from all over the state.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled with demons his whole life, with stubbornness and
disillusionment. Yet it was these traits that gave him the strength
to battle through the environmental crusades that defined his life.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he could thank his parents for his zealous outlook,
even though he had trouble communicating with them until late in
his life. As Mark wrote: ``I was raised to know right from wrong
... I was taught that the guy in the white hat always wins, good
triumphs over evil and justice in my country was sure, swift and
true.'' He wrote these words sarcastically, but it's obvious he
never stopped believing that such was the way life should be.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their troubles communicating, Dr. Rod takes pride in how
Mark finally squared his life with his passions. ``Mark and I could
talk about technical stuff, but not about the stuff that was
hurting him or me. But his work and writings helped close any old
wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the inheritance he leaves for the son who admired him.
Shannon tells about the time years ago when she went into the
garage and saw that Kyle had erected an elaborate system of hoses,
pipes, buckets and valves. He was playing Dad, making water run
from bucket to bucket. Like Mark O'Connor, she says, Kyle will make
waters pure.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
