<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Periodicals on the newstand this week
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a cover story on Bill Clinton's successful dodging of the
impeachment bullet, Newsweek ($3.50) sets the stage with this blunt
summation: ``Born with brute stamina and lacking the gene that
produces embarassment in the human soul, Clinton had once again
outlasted his enemies.'' Newsweek also offers excerpts from
Lawrence Schiller's 621-page investigation into the JonBenet Ramsey
murder, ``Perfect Murder _ Perfect Town.'' Though Schiller doesn't
reach a strong conclusion, he implicates the family, saying that
only someone familiar with the house could have been responsible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Writer's block: Joseph Mitchell turned in his last story for
the New Yorker ($3.95), a piece called ``Joe Gould's Secret,'' in
1964. Though he kept showing up for work, Mitchell didn't publish
another article between then and his death in 1996. Mitchell's
32-year dry spell became something of a legend at the magazine (he
was caricatured in Jay McInerny's ``Bright Lights, Big City'') but
writer Mark Singer insists in the current issue of the New Yorker
that it was the excellence of his pre-1964 writing that really made
Mitchell heroic, and an equal of such colleagues as A.J. Liebling.
Singer revisits the ghostly Mitchell, as actor and director Stanley
Tucci plans a new movie based on Mitchell's last story.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Loser: In his novel ``Bob the Gambler,'' Mississippi novelist
Frederick Barthelme wrote convincingly of an average Joe who stakes
his life on a turn of the cards and loses. Now Barthelme and his
brother Steve are charged with conspiring with a blackjack dealer
to rig games at a Mississippi casino. People ($2.99) updates this
instance of life imitating art. Attorney Boyce Holleman notes that
in 1996 the Barthelmes lost more than $150,000, and that if they
were cheating, they weren't very good at it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't blink: Dossier ($3.95) reports on 29 junior
movers-and-shakers in Atlanta business and the arts, blurbing a
``new breed'' of record producers, club owners, PR entrepreneurs
and internet mini-moguls to watch. ``Soon-to-be supermodel'' Kate
Thompson shares the cover with consultant Marc Adler and gallery
owner Pui Panich.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More people to watch: There's no cross-over between Dossier's
list and a (shorter) list of 20 ``intriguing'' people from Atlanta
($3.50). ``Intriguing,'' we suppose, is a term that lets Patsy
Ramsey (mother of the murdered JonBenet) into the list. Atlanta
also profiles humorist Lewis Grizzard, and demonstrates that the
former Atlanta Constitution sportswriter and columnist can still
raise hackles and generate chuckles five years after his death.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The green blazer: Created in 1931 by golfer Bobby Jones and
Wall Street stockbroker Clifford Roberts, the Augusta National golf
club has become sacred ground, but at the beginning of the
Depression, its success was hardly assured. When the first Masters
was held in 1934, the club couldn't afford to pay any of the
winners until a handful of members chipped in for the $5,000 purse.
In Vanity Fair ($3.95), David Owen tells of the parlous economic
climate that forced the owners to try raising cattle and turkeys on
the fairways to help generate income, and of the fortuitous
partnership of Jones and Roberts that brought the Augusta National
into existence. The story is excerpted from ``The Making of the
Masters: Clifford Roberts, August National and Golf's Most
Prestigious Tournament'' by David Owen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bottled passion: Though it wasn't a heartfelt paean to a dead
love, Amanda Poor, a 13-year-old from Ipswich, Mass., sent out a
real-life message in a bottle in 1996, essentially saying ``Hi!''
Life ($3.99) reports that Amanda was answered years later by a boy
from the Azores, a string of islands near Portugal, 2,286 miles
from Ipswich. If you want to visit the real beach house used in
Kevin Costner's movie ``Message in a Bottle,'' check out Coastal
Living ($3.95) for a pictorial on the Bath, Maine beach house
renovated for the film.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't call her Mrs. Babyface: Tracey Edmonds, president and
CEO of the $5 million Edmonds Entertainment Group, has a hand in
the music, management and movie businesses, and also happens to be
married to Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds, co-creator of LaFace
Records. Essence ($2.75) features the 32-year-old exec who met her
future husband when she auditioned for a part in his video, ``Whip
Appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
