<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Herrera's new line is all about brown
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The question style-conscious women will be asking
when it's time to update their fall/winter wardrobes is ``How
now?''
</P>
<P>
   And the answer, from Carolina Herrera's standpoint, is ``Brown
cow.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown leather jackets, pants, blouses, skirts and gloves served
as the catalysts for the cold weather collection Herrera unveiled
Monday under the Tent at Bryant Park. Herrera's supple, shiny,
form-fitting leather pieces were rendered in mouthwatering shades
of butterscotch, chocolate and (eggplanty) auburgine.
</P>
<P>
   Since brown's already been noted as a dominant factor in the
collections showing this week, Herrera's brown-out came as no
surprise. What did raise eyebrows along the runway, however, was
how bold and clever she was to insist that, yes, brown and pale
blue or pink or red or magenta can go together.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Herrera's designs were for the mature woman blessed
with a youthful spirit. Her collection looked ladylike and fun to
wear and included her signature A-line silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   Jackets were cut close to the torso and stopped just below the
hip or fell all the way to the ankles. Most tops (pullovers in
leather, silk, mink and woolens) featured cowl or ``portrait''
necklines and were short-sleeved or sleeveless to emphasize the
elbow-length gloves. Both the skirts and the pants rode low on the
hips, with zippers hidden discreetly on the sides or in back. The
skirts were hemmed below the knee, and the pants flared from the
knee down.
</P>
<P>
   Besides leather, Herrera's collection was rooted in other such
luxury fabrics as double-faced cashmere, mink, moire silk and
mohair. For evening, she showed halter top-feathered skirt
combinations and color-blocked satin gowns.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera's collection was free of that premillennial mind-set
that so many other designers are fostering. She exudes an
infectious ``Let them eat cake'' attitude. Clothiers at every price
level would do well to latch on to Herrera's leather look and milk
it for all it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   Coming Wednesday: Nicole Miller, Mark Eisen and Badgley Mischka.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
