<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Niggardly' describes something `stingy' can't
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On National Public Radio's ``Morning Edition''
recently a free-lance writer named Cecilie Berry offered her two
cents' worth in the flap over a bureaucrat shamed by his
vocabulary. I didn't hear it, but a friend insisted that I call for
a transcript. It was more proof, she said with amusement, that
Americans are committed to the lowest common denominator.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I wouldn't know Cecilie Berry from Chuck Berry, only that
``Morning Edition'' host Bob Edwards identified her as ``a
free-lance writer who lives in Montclair, N.J.'' As tag lines go,
that doesn't bring much heft to the table. But then, no one knew
who the unfortunate David Howard was either.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, you'll recall, was the aide to Washington Mayor Anthony
Williams, who injudiciously spoke of having to be ``niggardly''
with the district's budget. The word had no sooner left his lips,
hitting the streets not with a clunk but a tremendous clatter, than
he was on the apology stand. You'd have thought the man, in the
midst of a talk about a budget, had uttered the N-word.
</P>
<P>
   How that would fit into the context of revenue projections ought
have seemed puzzling, but no one pondered it for long. It sounded
close enough, and within 24 hours Howard had dutifully resigned. He
offered his head because other people had nothing in theirs.
</P>
<P>
   It's beside the point that the mayor accepted the resignation
and then changed his mind after someone provided him the benefit of
a dictionary. Howard was acquitted on the first count _ racism _
but not on the second. If he had not used the N-word, he
unquestionably had used a big word, and damn him for it.
</P>
<P>
   As Cecilie Berry told ``Morning Edition's'' audience, ``I would
not have chastised Howard for racism, but I would have accused him
of grandiloquence, pedantry and being a pain in the butt, not a
crime against humanity, surely, but the more common misdemeanor of
putting on airs.''
</P>
<P>
   Why don't we add to that charge the more serious one of being an
``elitist''? Then we can put the man in stocks and display him on
Dupont Circle for all to see, an example of what happens when you
risk rising above the lowest common denominator.
</P>
<P>
   We're not going to allow it in this society. On one level, we
embrace vulgarity everywhere (remember when the Braves went to the
National League playoffs against the Dodgers and vendors were
hawking T-shirts that said ``LA Sucks''?). On another, we nod
solemn assent at the pretentious and pseudoscientific
(``paradigm,'' ``parameters.'')
</P>
<P>
   We even let the sportswriters limber up their tired
vocabularies. It's not enough that an athlete has torn a ligament.
They let us know if it is, perchance, the anterior cruciate
ligament.
</P>
<P>
   But a hapless budget official uses a legitimate word that
predates Chaucer and we're all over him. Bailiff Berry, trying hard
to be charming, told of her own teenage fling with big words and of
what a snob she used to be. In her case, she never quite learned
what they meant. Somewhere she came upon ``hoi polloi,'' and ``for
months anything that wasn't interesting to me was strictly for the
hoi polloi.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be pedantic or a pain in Berry's backside, but if she
knew what it meant she'd have known that ``hoi'' was Greek for
``the.'' So it was redundant, and a bit ignorant, to speak of ``the
hoi polloi.''
</P>
<P>
   With any word, the question is not its size but its rightness.
Does it express our meaning precisely, and how does it play upon
the ear? Does it have zip or force? (Does it have euphony? There's
another two-bit word Berry can add to her collection.)
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, ``niggardly'' is closer to what Howard meant than
``stingy'' or ``miserly,'' alternatives Berry would have preferred.
Even among synonyms there are shadings of difference. The American
Heritage Dictionary tells us that ``stingy'' implies ``an
inclination toward meanness of spirit,'' and ``miserly'' a greedy
``hoarding of wealth for its own sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard meant something else, and in his mind the word for it was
``niggardly.'' If it was unfamiliar to some, well, let them learn
something. They need to. It was not a pretentious word, but
neither, perhaps, was it the most precise word. As a synonym for
stinginess, it implies a grudging pettiness in spending.
</P>
<P>
   What Howard meant was frugality in the extreme, and there is a
word for that, too. The word is parsimonious. But in the
know-nothing culture that would be showing off, and the Cecilie
Berrys would be giving us their two pennies' worth. Pinch 'em,
Cecilie, and you'll know what it means.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
