</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-SNOWBOARDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SNOWBOARDING SECRET: THINK UPRIGHT THOUGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
 (fb) 
 By GARY TAUBES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I last went skiing in 1985, when I took a two-week break from
researching my first book and rented a chalet in the Swiss Alps. I
could afford it because the dollar was strong. Bottles of Dom
Perignon cost $18, which is why I cannot honestly say I remember
the skiing.
</P>
<P>
   But I do recall using two skis, one on each foot. Since then,
snowboarding has come into vogue, a sport that not only
exhilarates, but also reveals the wisdom of buying stock in a
trauma center near a ski resort.
</P>
<P>
   Because snowboarding looked like fun _ and because I have no
dependents _ I decided to try it. I was given plenty of cautionary
advice, most of it along the lines of ``get used to falling down,''
and suggestions on how best to limit my first-day injuries.
</P>
<P>
   I went to Big Bear Mountain Resort, a three-hour drive east of
Los Angeles at an elevation of about 7,000 feet, and hired a
private instructor for three hours at $60 an hour and rented boots
and a board for $30. The lift ticket cost another $30.
</P>
<P>
   I wore long underwear and flannel-lined blue jeans under ski
pants, for padding as well as warmth. Special snowboarding pants
are a good idea, though, because they are both insulated and
padded, and will take the pounding, which traditional ski pants may
not. I also wore wrist braces and the kind of braces rollerbladers
wear to prevent broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   My instructor, a jovial ex-Angelino named Eric Floyd,
acknowledged that the braces were a good idea. Eric was wearing a
helmet.
</P>
<P>
   When you rent the equipment, or buy it, you will be asked
whether you are ``regular'' or ``goofy foot,'' which is snowboard
lingo for how you stand on the board. The snowboard position is
akin to that of surfing or skateboarding: Your feet are shoulder
width apart; your lead foot points slightly forward, while your
rear foot is perpendicular to the board. ``Regular'' means your
left foot is in front, and ``goofy foot'' means your right foot
leads. Your weight goes over your leading leg, and your knees are
slightly bent.
</P>
<P>
   An instructor, I learned, will give you encouragement, but keep
you from attempting the impossible. Eric started me off with a
lecture on the value of positive thinking and self-realization.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think you'll fall,'' he said, ``you will.''
</P>
<P>
   I ignored this because I live in Southern California, where
lectures on self-realization are only slightly less ubiquitous than
cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on flat ground, where I fell only occasionally, we
moved one small step at a time. Eric showed me the correct stance,
then had me lock my front foot into the binding, keeping my rear
foot free. I practiced sliding the board back and forth on the
snow, then pushing it like a skateboard, which is the way one gets
around when not going downhill. Eric had me slide with my back foot
on the board, but not locked in, then with the foot locked in, and
so on.
</P>
<P>
   When I was comfortable, we went to the bunny slope, a three- or
four-degree incline, which seemed plenty steep once I got going.
Eric told me to ski down the slope without attempting to turn, and
after a couple of times I was able to cover 30 yards or so before
falling.
</P>
<P>
   After learning how to go forward, you learn how to brake or
turn. The latter is accomplished by turning your body slightly and
leaning in the direction you want to go. Theoretically, this will
bring the board up on its edge, which is what makes it turn. A left
turn, for example, is made by leaning back on your heels and onto
the heel edge of the board. The right turn is made by leaning
forward on your toes and the toe edge of the board. As in ice
skating and conventional skiing, braking is accomplished by turning
abruptly and letting your edge bring you to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   Both turning and braking require finding the balance point _
that point at which you are just balanced on the edge rather than
continuing blissfully ahead, or, of course, falling. If you go
beyond your balance point, you will ``catch an edge,'' and the
snowboard pivots upward and vigorously slams you face down or rear
first into the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Snowboarding, regrettably, has no equivalent of conventional
skiing's snow plow. Until you find your balance point and learn to
turn and brake correctly _ which is what takes three days unless
you are blessed with freakish physical coordination _ you will
spend the intervening time being repeatedly body slammed. Large
doses of Advil and a bath of Epsom salts helped me return to
partial functioning within a week.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, I graduated _ unwillingly but at Eric's
insistence _ from the bunny slope to the beginner slope. This
required taking a chairlift, which is wonderfully relaxing once you
master getting on and getting off without falling. From the vantage
of the chairlift, beginner snow board slopes look like alpine
battlefields: bodies scattered everywhere, some of them moving
slowly, and some motionless, the latter, I would learn, being
content to remain prostrate while their pain subsided.
</P>
<P>
   On the beginner slope, my first few runs proceeded roughly like
this: ski for 10 yards, and try to turn. Fall. Get up. Fall. Rest.
Try to get up. Fall. Ski for 10 yards, and try to turn. Fall. Ski
straight, gather speed, panic, and fall.
</P>
<P>
   By my fourth or fifth run, I started to get the hang of it,
finally implementing the secret of snow-boarding success: leaning
my rear knee into my front knee. This kept my weight over my front
leg, where it needed to be. I still could not turn, but was able to
go downhill for 100 breath-taking yards at a clip until an imminent
collision with another skier _ or the lift line, or a tree _
brought the run to an abrupt end.
</P>
<P>
   Falling is a surprisingly efficient method of braking, although
not necessarily the best. And then, much to my surprise, positive
thinking made a difference. When I talked myself into relaxing and
assumed I could snowboard without falling, I could. Learning to
relax is crucial to success.
</P>
<P>
   The truly frightening aspect of snowboarding _ more than the
constant pain _ is its addictive nature. After five or six runs, I
was hooked and having fun. When I made it down the hill, I was
eager to get back on the lift and try again. I stopped only because
I had to get back to Los Angeles before rush hour, snow was falling
heavily, and, as far as I could tell, my knee and ankle ligaments
were still connected. I was quitting while ahead, but planning to
return in two weeks _ provided I regained sensation in my left arm
by then.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Ski Areas Association, only six
resorts in the United States do not accommodate snowboarders. For
specifics, check the organization's Web site at www.snowblast.com.
Another site to try: Snowboarding Online at www.twsnow.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
