<HEADER>
A6027 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     02-15 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A PLAN TO MOVE THE NEW YEAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One very inconvenient problem about New Year's 2000 is that New
Year's Eve falls on a Friday night, and New Year's Day, a holiday,
falls on Saturday. So how will anyone know, or begin to deal with,
all the business problems likely to arise when computers
malfunction and all sorts of services are interrupted?
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of this dilemma, Representatives  &UR; John Linder &LR; , R-Ga.,
and  &UR; David Dreier &LR; , R-San Dimas, have introduced House Joint
Resolution 14: ``In order to provide the public and technology
professionals with an additional day, prior to the start of the
workweek, to begin repairs on failed computer systems ... the New
Year's Day holiday ..shall be deemed to occur on January 3, 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, when to wear one's party hat will be the subject of
future legislation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CRITICS DECRY KAZAN OSCAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The ad hoc Committee Against Silence is hoping that hundreds of
protesters will show up at the Oscars on March 21 to demonstrate
against director &UR; Elia Kazan &LR; 's lifetime achievement Oscar. Kazan,
89, has been a Hollywood pariah since the '50s, when he named names
to the House Un-American Activities Committee. Kazan, who took out
ads in Variety and the New York Times urging others to name names,
too, is considered responsible for many studios' blacklists.
</P>
<P>
   Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences president  &UR; Karl &LR; 
 &UR; Malden &LR;  nominated Kazan for the award, saying, ``There's no place
for politics in any art form.'' Among those who share his views &LR; 
are  &UR; Charlton Heston &LR;  and  &UR; Nora Ephron &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   But other members of the Hollywood community are less forgiving.
 &UR; Rod Steiger &LR; , who found out about Kazan's naming names just as
``On the Waterfront'' finished shooting, said, ``It was like I
found my father was sleeping with my sister. The passing of time
can do nothing to ease the pain of those who suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Director  &UR; Stanley Donen &LR; , who won last year's lifetime
achievement award, told the New York Post that Kazan deserves
applause for ``some wonderful pictures. ... But his activities, as
a person, were deplorable. That just comes down to who he is, and
whether or not he gets an Oscar doesn't change who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Meanwhile, MSNBC says that the hottest Oscar issue this
year is which designer will dress  &UR; Gwyneth Paltrow &LR; . Furthermore,
there's a buzz about Miramax's willingness to pay her $4,500-a-day
make- &LR; up artist,  &UR; Kevin Aucoin &LR; . ``If he charges that much for
Gwyneth,'' an observer told MSNBC, ``imagine how much he charges
for ugly people?''
</P>
<P>
   Miramax, which made ``Shakespeare in Love,'' denies that it's
being stingy. ``Gwyneth always uses Kevin,'' said a studio
spokeswoman. ``If she doesn't it won't be because of price.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - The Postal Service reports that Californians have bought one
in five of the 65.5 million breast cancer fund-raising stamps sold
since their first offering on July 30. Seven cents a stamp goes
goes to research.
</P>
<P>
   - Last week's item about  &UR; Jane Seymour &LR;  testifying before a
House committee chaired by Representative  &UR; Joe Barton &LR;  was
erroneous. The committee is Government Reform and Oversight; its
chairman is  &UR; Dan Burton &LR; , R-Ind.; and Seymour is testifying _ as
private citizen, not Dr. Quinn _ because her father had cancer and
she is an activist in behalf of alternative medicine.
</P>
<P>
   - Names are named in  &UR; Linda Grekin &LR; 's new book, ``I'll Never Get
Lost Again: The Complete Guide to Improving Your Sense of
Direction'' (RDR Books; $12.95).  &UR; Ann Landers &LR; ,  &UR; Joan Baez  &LR; and
 &UR; Beverly Sills &LR;  are three celebrities with perfectly terrible senses
of direction.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The latter part of 1999 to the year 2000 promises to be a &LR; 
 &UR; lively time for parties. ... By painting their faces and hands &LR; 
 &UR; silver, performers become Hi-Tech Gals and Guys. Add `Star &LR; 
 &UR; Trek'-like shoulder pads, ray guns and neon `glow in the dark' &LR; 
 &UR; necklaces for that science fiction look. ... To set the tone for &LR; 
 &UR; entertainment, substitute confetti decorations for computer &LR; 
 &UR; chips, mouse pads for place mats and mock computers for &LR; 
 &UR; centerpieces.'' &LR;  - Getting ready for Y2K events, from a story by
 &UR; Stan Heimowitz &LR;  of Celebrity Gems in Meeting Manager magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
