<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRS.CLINTON-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS FIRST LADY WOULD MAKE A `TERRIFIC' N.Y. SENATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDA, Mexico _ President Clinton, publicly commenting for the
first time about the possibility that his wife might seek the
Senate seat from New York in 2000, said Monday: ``I think she would
be terrific in the Senate but that's a decision that she'll have to
make.''
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is considering whether to seek
the seat that will open up with the retirement of Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, according to White House aides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``I will support whatever decision she makes,
enthusiastically.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that Mrs. Clinton has not had ``anything like
adequate time'' to talk with Democrats in New York, adding: ``I
don't think it had ever occurred to her before a lot of people
started calling and asking her to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, asked about Mrs.
Clinton's possible Senate bid, replied: ``I think Mrs. Clinton is a
fantastic human being and anybody who knows her knows that she
would be a great public servant.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Moynihan said New York could use some of Mrs.
Clinton's ``magnificent, young, bright, able, Illinois-Arkansas
enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd be welcome and she'd win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About all Mrs. Clinton has said about running for the Senate in
2000 is that she hasn't had time to think about it _ and she said
that through a spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters during his summit meeting here with
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, Clinton replied to question
about his wife's possible political career and said: ``It's her
decision to make. I will support whatever decision she makes
enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a lot of other opportunities for public service that
will be out there. She and I both would like to continue to be
useful in public affairs when we leave office. But it's a decision
she'll have to make. She'd be great if she did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is expected to visit New York City in early March
for a women's leadership forum and her comments will be watched
closely for any clue about her intentions.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani is a possible Republican
candidate for the Moynihan seat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
