<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Feb. 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, the temperature fell to a record minimum of
25 degrees at Myrtle Beach, S.C., as clear skies and light winds
promoted unusually chilly conditions over the Southeast. Another
cool start will occur across the region Tuesday, though abundant
sunshine will cause temperatures to rapidly rebound into the 60s
and lower 70s by midafternoon. Ample sunshine will also cover the
Middle Atlantic states and Northeast, with slightly above normal
temperatures expected.
</P>
<P>
   Areas of snow will accompany low pressure crossing the upper
Middle West Tuesday. Several inches of snow are possible from
northern Minnesota to the northern peninsula of Michigan where air
moistening in transit over Lake Superior could enhance snowfall
accumulations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, showers will occur farther south as a cold front
attendant to the low lifts humid air positioned over the Ohio and
Tennessee Valleys. Isolated thunderstorms may erupt later Tuesday
afternoon as a jet stream disturbance passes overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain will batter much of northern California Tuesday as a
steady stream of moist air arrives from the Pacific Ocean. As the
damp air is lifted and cooled by the interior mountains, very heavy
snow will blanket the Sierras above 6,000 feet where total snowfall
may exceed 40 inches by Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, scattered showers and mountain snow will affect
western Washington and Oregon. Wet weather will spread into the
interior West later Tuesday, reaching western Montana and Wyoming
by late in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: European Blizzard
</P>
<P>
   Heavy snow and frigid winds have battered eastern Europe over
the past several days. Protracted and extreme wintry weather has
been a consequence of a low pressure system at high altitudes that
stalled over Hungary, Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, Ukraine, Poland
and other neighboring countries. The cold upper-level storm has
become separated from the steering winds of the jet stream,
accounting for its lethargy. Moreover, a sprawling high pressure
system centered over Siberia's Arctic coast continues to block the
path of the upper-level low, allowing wintry weather to persist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
