<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6032 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEXICO-HNS &LR;      02-15 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND MEXICO MAP CLOSER COOPERATION TO COMBAT DRUG TRAFFICKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDA, Mexico _ President Clinton and Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo tried to ease nagging U.S.-Mexican irritations Monday with
an agreement setting benchmarks to measure the nations' campaigns
against narcotics trafficking and consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, wrapping up a 23-hour summit in this one-time center of
Mayan civilization, headed back to Washington late Monday vowing to
work with the Republican Congress in the aftermath of the
impeachment struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he was heartened that four Republican members
of Congress had joined 20 Democrats to take part in meetings here
with members of the Mexican parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a time for reconciliation and renewal,''
Clinton said during a photo session. ``I think what we have to do
is to serve the American people. And if we keep that in mind, I
think everything will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Mexico accord on drug cooperation set a yardstick to
enable the two countries to measure progress and identify areas
that need further effort.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the 16 measures will enable the two
countries to ``ensure a greater degree of accountability and
scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said winning the drug war ``won't
happen overnight,'' but added that Mexico and the United States can
do it over time.
</P>
<P>
   Some 70 percent of the illegal narcotics in the United States _
mostly cocaine, heroine and marijuana _ are either cultivated in
Mexico or transit across Mexico to reach the United States where
Americans consume an estimated $57 billion worth of illegal drugs
each year.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmarks incorporated the priorities of both countries.
The United States won Mexico's agreement to accept specific
yardsticks for eradication, extradition of drug traffickers, asset
forfeiture, money laundering, control of precursor chemicals and
efforts to stem corruption within law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico won U.S. agreement to yardsticks measuring progress in
efforts to stem consumption, boost interdiction, train Mexican
agencies and provide technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The 91-page accord stipulates actions, a baseline, a target and
measurement criteria.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement comes two weeks before the Clinton
administration's expected decision to certify to Congress that
Mexico is cooperating with joint counternarcotics efforts. Congress
requires annual certification by the administration. Mexico has
never failed to achieve that status under three American presidents
over 12 years, despite congressional criticism that Mexico should
be doing much more.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's cooperation has ``clearly improved'' under Zedillo's
leadership, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in remarks to Merida business leaders after signing the
agreements with Zedillo, noted the change in atmosphere from an era
when the nations' leaders could not even touch upon the subject
``without falling into an unwinnable argument about who is to
blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declared: ``That has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk candidly about this now because we have started to
talk the same language _ the language of parents who love their
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo told the same audience: Mexicans are ``convinced and
determined to keep up the fight against drugs until we win.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo declared ``total war'' against narcotics on Feb. 4 with
a $400 million blueprint to purchase ships, aircraft, radar, X-ray
equipment and other equipment to help combat narcotics production
and trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities often express resentment at the annual U.S.
review of Mexico's anti-drug campaign, criticizing the effort as an
infringement on Mexican sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Zedillo also announced agreements designed to
protect crossborder undercover operations by law enforcement
agencies and to stem law enforcement violence against Mexicans
trying to cross the U.S.-Mexico border without documentation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said U.S. border protection must be enforced ``with
justice, fairness and sensitivity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
