<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY WOMEN OFTEN TAKE IT ON THE SHIN 
FOR PAP SMEARS, THE MATTER OF TIMING 
KICKS THAT CAN KILL 
FOR SLEEPLESS NIGHTS, A PERILOUS PENALTY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Ga., Calif., N.Y., Iowa, Italy)  (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   That upright posture so dear to mothers and governesses may
contribute to women's high rate of injuries to the anterior
cruciate ligaments (ACLs) that crisscross the knee and help keep it
stable.
</P>
<P>
   Three-dimensional motion analysis of 20 recreational athletes
found that women run and perform some other athletic movements in a
much less crouched position than men, causing the quadricep muscles
in the fronts of the thighs to generate a great deal of power. In
an awkward movement, like landing on uneven ground, the highly
activated quadriceps have enough force to pull the tibia, or shin
bone, forward and tear the ACL, said Dr. William Garrett Jr.,
chairman of the department of orthopedic surgery at the University
of North Carolina School of Medicine and an author of a study
presented recently to the American Academy of Orthopedic Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   In pivoting movements, videotaped for the study, women crouched
less than men at the moment of impact with the ground. Similar
differences were found for forward and sideways running, movements
that are common in soccer and basketball. At the college level, ACL
injuries are two to three times more common among women than men in
soccer and three to four times more common in basketball, according
to the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are studying the biomechanics that explain why women
crouch less, said Dr. Letha Griffin, a team physician for Georgia
State University. ``Possibly it feels more natural because women
have a lower center or gravity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett said women can be retrained to bend more and thus
protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Torn ACLs are often repaired by grafting tendons from elsewhere
in the body. ``The graft acts like a scaffold on which new
connective tissue grows,'' Dr. Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   _ NANCY STEDMAN
</P>
<P>
   PRO &AMP; CON: Debating the Pap Smears Intervals
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do all postmenopausal women need a cervical Pap smear every
year?
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   Telling all postmenopausal women that they do not need a Pap
smear every year could be a dangerous recommendation. One problem
is that a recommendation to decrease the frequency of Pap smears
has been construed as a recommendation to decrease the frequency of
visits to the doctor for routine examinations, including a pelvic
examination.
</P>
<P>
   Also, though the Pap smear is not perfect, it is the best cancer
detector available. Since its introduction, there has been about a
70 percent reduction in the mortality rate. Sixty-two percent of
women who die of cervical cancer in the United States either have
never had a Pap smear or have not had one in five years.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, in postmenopausal women, the site at which most of
the cervical cancers arise is usually where they cannot be readily
seen. If a woman has a history of sexually transmitted diseases,
multiple sex partners or smoking, she may need them more
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   _ DR. JONATHAN BEREK, professor and vice chairman, department of
obstetrics and gynecology, University of California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Postmenopausal women who have never been sexually active, have
never had abnormal yearly Pap smears or have had normal Pap smears
in the last three consecutive years are candidates to have Pap
smears less frequently. The practice, however, does not apply to
women who have not had regular screening in the past or those who
have had biopsy-confirmed high-grade precancerous changes.
</P>
<P>
   Cervical cancer and its precursors are strongly associated with
the sexual transmission of viral infections. In the absence of
sexual activity, heredity and other life habits are rarely, if
ever, associated with cervical cancer by themselves. The
development of cervical cancer can be traced through its
precancerous stages by regular Pap smear screening.
</P>
<P>
   If a woman has a normal cumulative Pap smear history prior to
menopause, her risk of acquiring new precancerous lesions is
probably sufficiently low to allow screening at longer intervals.
</P>
<P>
   _ DR. AUSTIN CHEN, gynecologist, St. Vincent's Medical Center
and Hospital, New York; assistant professor, New York University.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   AT RISK: A Deadly Game, and How to Kill It
</P>
<P>
   Car surfing is a dangerous game that participants play by
standing on moving vehicles and pretending to surf or by hooking
onto the backs of cars, trucks or buses while rollerblading,
skateboarding or sliding on ice. While not all that common, it can
be very deadly, according to a report in this month's issue of the
Annals of Emergency Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The report, written by doctors in the departments of emergency
medicine, trauma services and surgery education at Iowa Methodist
Medical Center in Des Moines, was prompted by a small but alarming
rise in car-surfing injuries. The doctors cited five cases treated
by emergency room doctors at the medical center in 1996 and 1997;
three were fatal.
</P>
<P>
   While there are no national statistics for car-surfing injuries,
a search of newspaper articles in the United States undertaken by
the researchers found a total of 29 cases since 1989, involving 20
young men and nine young women with 15 of the cases reported as
fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's typically 14- to 20-year-olds who are at the greatest
risk of injury,'' said Dr. Timothy Peterson, medical director of
the Bureau of Emergency Medical Services with the Iowa Department
of Public Health and lead author of the report. ``They have just
gotten their licenses and along with their friends they're going to
go out there and have a good time even if it kills them. Sometimes
it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopping the dangerous car surfing involves education and
enforcement, Peterson said. ``In some states, car surfing is a
crime, and if a driver allows someone to stand on the car and that
person falls off, then the driver is held accountable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: Sleepless Nights, Dangerous Mornings
</P>
<P>
   The usual penalty for a bad night's sleep is feeling tired and
irritable, but Italian researchers believe sleep deprivation may
also lead to heart attacks and strokes the next morning, according
to a recent article in the American Journal of Hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring 20 men and 16 women, all mild to moderate
hypertensive patients who had never been treated, Dr. Paola Lusardi
of the University of Pavia found blood pressures and heart rates
were higher on mornings after the patients were deprived of sleep
than when patients slept undisturbed from 11 p.m. to 7 a.m. All
were administrative workers at the university and nonsmokers with
no major sleep complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Data suggest that lack of sleep in hypertensive patients may
increase sympathetic nervous system activity during the night and
the following morning, leading to increased blood pressure and
heart rate. This effect might represent an increased risk for both
organ damage and acute cardiovascular diseases, Dr. Lusardi and her
colleagues reported.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians have noted that heart attacks and strokes occur more
frequently from early morning to noon, but this study suggests
there may be a medical penalty for sleepless nights, said Dr.
Michael Weber, president of the American Society of Hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   Among hypertensive patients, sleepless nights may be part of a
cycle of stress, but it is a cycle that can be broken, Weber said.
``One thing we can control is sleep,'' he said, suggesting that
patients discuss their sleep patterns with their physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may require as little as four or five hours of sleep
a night instead of the eight-hours norm in the Italian study, but
anything under four hours would be considered sleep deprivation,
Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   _ NANCY BETH JACKSON
</P>
</TEXT>
