<HEADLINE>
SURVIVING FIRES, CRASHES AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are art end of review)  
 (af)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For viewers who don't have enough to worry about, ``Nova''
delivers a heavy dose of disaster Tuesday night and Wednesday, four
hours' worth of mankind's propensity for perishing in fires, car
accidents, plane crashes and ship sinkings.
</P>
<P>
   Documented by dire descriptions of the consequences of bad luck
and bad judgment, ``Escape! Because Accidents Happen'' is leavened
by attention to counterattacks against menaces down the decades.
</P>
<P>
   The cautionary mini-series begins Tuesday night with fire,
citing such famous examples as the one that destroyed three-fifths
of metropolitan London in 1666; the fire in that city at the Kings
Cross station, which killed 31 people in 1987; the 1911 blaze at
the Triangle Shirtwaist factory in New York, in which 146 people
died, and the 1942 Cocoanut Grove nightclub fire in Boston, which
killed 492 merrymakers.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes of confusion and pain, suffocation and suffering
leave no doubt of fire's power to kill and kill fast: ``You either
burn to death alive inside of an inferno,'' a Triangle historian
says, ``or you make an effort to jump to safety out of the
window.'' But jumping out the garment-factory window meant a fall
of eight or nine stories.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the hour is given to the lessons learned down through
the centuries and the techniques for fighting back, like water
pumps and hoses, computer systems for alarms, automatic sprinklers
and helmets that enable their wearers to see through the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Having emerged unscathed from all that, you can look forward in
Tuesday night's second hour to car accidents, which we are reminded
have taken the lives of more Americans in the last century than all
the country's wars. The good news here includes safety glass, seat
belts and air cushions.
</P>
<P>
   But the real breakthrough awaits taking the human being,
responsible for 90 percent of traffic deaths, out of the driver's
seat. If substituting computers to create an automated highway
system smacks of Big Brother, well, take your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night brings perils in the air and on the sea, with
the emphasis on getting out alive. But what with collisions on the
road and skyscraper blazes filling my anxiety quota, I must leave
it to the higher powers doing the driving up there and out there to
do further worrying for me. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NOVA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Escape! Because Accidents Happen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday night and Wednesday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 8) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paula S. Apsell, executive producer; David Dugan, series
producer. ``Fire'' and ``Car Crash'' written, produced and directed
by Nancy Linde. ``Plane Crash'' and ``Abandon Ship'' produced and
directed by Alison Trinkl and written by David Dugan. A Nova
production by Windfall Films for WGBH, Boston, in association with
the BBC and Suddeutscher Rundfunk. Nova is produced for PBS by the
WGBH Science Unit, directed by Ms. Apsell. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
