<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARDIGRAS-BANDS-COX     02-15 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARDIGRAS-BANDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mardi Gras a perfect opportunity for Purple Knights, others to
shine
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Orleans _ In the city where music is second only to food in
the hearts of locals, playing in the band is so cool, kids grow up
dreaming of which instrument they will play. The coolest time to be
in a band is during the Mardi Gras parade season, which winds up
today, and no band gets more cheers of recognition and admiration
than the St. Augustine Purple Knights, better known as the ``St.
Aug Marching 100.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys from this private, mostly-black Catholic school don't
just walk the parade routes; they strut, their knees practically
knocking into their purple and gold lame chests. They swing their
elbows so high you'd think their arms were going to go clear behind
their heads like whirligigs. And they play so loud and so well,
even the tourists take notice and clap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the best in the land,'' said Keith Anthony Linyear as
he stood on St. Charles Avenue Friday night, watching his son stomp
by in his purple-plumed gladiator's helmet, blowing on a trumpet in
the Krewe D'Etat parade. ``They've got a lot of tradition, and the
others just don't match up.''
</P>
<P>
   Linyear's younger son, Lawrence, 11, looked very serious as St.
Aug went by. ``I want to be in St. Aug because they always get to
march first,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Augustine will be the first band to march when Rex, the king
of Carnival, rolls down St. Charles Avenue this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first black band to march with Rex, in 1967,''
said Edwin Hampton, who has been St. Augustine's band director for
46 of the school's 47 years. ``That was a complete break for us,
and we made history.''
</P>
<P>
   When they finish marching in Rex today, the Marching 100 will
have been in eight parades in the last two weeks, logging between
50 and 80 miles of high-stepping, horn-blowing, cymbal-tossing hard
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get huge blisters on your feet,'' said Ollie Stewart, a
ninth grader at St. Aug. The students, in grades 8 through 12,
train for weeks just to build up enough stamina to make it through
the season, Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the riders in the floats, who are high above the crowd
and tethered to posts to keep from falling, band members march,
sometimes for five or six hours, straight through millions of
drunken, lunging, grabbing people. The kids say they've had beer
and beads thrown down their tubas. The drum majors say women, some
bare-chested, hurl themselves at them as they lead the band.
Meanwhile, a central element of St. Augustine is discipline. The
boys are not allowed to talk or even look at revelers along the
parade route. They make guarding Buckingham Palace look easy.
</P>
<P>
   And they march rain or shine. This year, the weather has been
almost perfect, but last year they marched through deluges and in
high winds. On the longest parade, they did that for 12 miles.
</P>
<P>
   But Brett Harrington, a 10th grader and tuba player, says it's
worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in it for the music, and the girls,'' he said while
getting ready for an afternoon practice last week.
</P>
<P>
   Tenth grader Christopher Gaines added: ``Watch, at 4 p.m., the
girls will show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, at 3:48 p.m., five girls from a nearby school
appeared at the edge of the parking lot where the Purple Knights
were marching back and forth and making so much noise that car
alarms in the neighborhood were going off. The girls smiled and
waved; one twirled batons to get attention. The St. Aug band has
been in three movies; they've played for six presidents and have
been in three Super Bowls, Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   Percy Marchand, a senior and one of two St. Aug drum majors,
said kids here dream of being in the St. Aug band like kids
elsewhere dream of being quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you look forward to when you are a little
child,'' he said. ``You see them marching on Mardi Gras and you
say, `That's what I want someday.' ``
</P>
<P>
   See the Marching 100 practice and hear an interview with
director Edwin Hampton: 
http://www.insideneworleans.com/entertainment/mardigras/funfiles/mar
chingband.html
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
