<HEADER>
A6055 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLTEL-UNION-COX     02-15 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLTEL-UNION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alltel workers vote to nix union involvement
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Workers have voted to cast off union representation
for employees at Alltel in Georgia, the second-largest phone
company in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, although not effective until confirmed by federal
officials, would sever the relationship between about 470 Alltel
employees and the Communications Workers of America.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which includes a range of workers from customer
service representatives to technicians, voted 248 to 146 to end its
representation by the union, said John Comparin, Alltel vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Those workers have been working without a contract while CWA
negotiated with the Little Rock-based company. Once the union is
decertified, the company can break off those talks, said John
Comparin, Alltel vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The vote may serve as a caution for the unions that still
represent thousands of employees at Alltel, a $5 billion-a-year
company offering phone and wireless service in more than 14 states.
However, Camparin said the company had mounted no campaign to rid
itself of the union in Georgia. ``This was the employees' decision
and Alltel appreciates the confidence that employees have shown in
the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials were unavailable for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Alltel has about 2,000 Georgia employees, including 1,200 in
metro Atlanta. Of the company's 14,000 employees, about 1,560 are
represented by either the Communications Workers of America or the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, according to
Alltel.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
