<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6057 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBERT-TNT-COX     02-15 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBERT-TNT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Albert returning to national stage
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since returning to broadcasting last fall, Marv Albert
has been embraced warmly by his longtime following in New York. In
April, Albert will discover whether the rest of the country will
greet his return to the booth with open arms, after he pleaded
guilty last year to a misdemeanor assault charge.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Sports signed Albert to a multiyear contract Monday,
starting on April 2 with the first of six regular-season NBA
telecasts on TNT or TBS. Albert also will call games for Turner
during the playoffs, though that number will depend on his
obligations to Madison Square Garden Network and local Knicks
radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to be back doing television on the NBA on a
national basis,'' Albert said. ``I've been saying all along I have
to take it step by step, and this is a big step.''
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer Mike Pearl said Turner had been monitoring
Albert's progress closely, both legally and personally, for six
months. But serious talks about a contract did not begin until the
past month.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the NBA, Pearl confirmed that Albert also will
work on boxing, the Goodwill Games and ``other new programming,''
the latter a veiled reference to the new pro football league being
formed by Turner and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Marv is among the top play-by-play announcers in the
business,'' Pearl said. ``His name has been cleared by the court,
and he has been taking care of his personal life. Any time
something happens, whether it's good or bad, you can't put a time
frame on when something runs its course.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on the production side, where it is a shortened season,
this is the right time for us. We only do two nights a week in
March, because of the NCAA Tournament, so we'll get Marv on in
April, which will give him the opportunity to get used to our
system in time for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The exposure in April will also give viewers time to get used to
the idea of seeing Albert in time for the playoffs. Given the
negative publicity about Albert's court case, there are concerns
about the reception he will receive nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I didn't think there will be some negative
reaction somewhere about it,'' Pearl said. ``But it is our belief
most of the reaction will be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Albert might have some apprehension about the feedback
he'll get from fans outside of New York, for the moment, he's just
glad to be a national announcer again.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the darkest hours, I had no idea what would unfold in my
life,'' Albert said. ``I hope to reclaim my (broadcasting)
reputation. But that's beyond my control, and that's not for me to
make a judgment on. I hope the work will speak for itself. I've had
a great relationship with the fans, and I hope it stays that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Prentis Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
