<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-BUZZ16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall fashion notes from New York
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In her program notes, Donna Karan said the
fall/winter DKNY styles for men and women were, ``designed for the
person who breaks the mold and creates their own.'' That's one way
of describing them. Another way might be: they're clothes for
people who can't quit cocooning; still another description might
be: styles for people who'd rather wear their blankies to work.
</P>
<P>
   In her runway show on Monday, Karan applied names like, ``cotton
slip cover over white duvet coat,'' and ``blanket,'' to outerwear
pieces that were either puffy and quilted or slouchy and knitted.
Cotton t-shirts paired with fluffed-up denim pants were said to be
made of ``cotton sheeting''.
</P>
<P>
   With their zippered, Velcro and magnetic closures, the
cream-colored cold-weather looks from DKNY are undeniably
futuristic. In one sense, they looked like clothes for
intergalactic Beddouins. In another, they smacked of a future spent
in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Rowley: Out of all the liquor company tie-ins saturating
Fashion Week, the one Cynthia Rowley forged with a new booze maker
in order to stage her show at Grand Central Station seemed the most
fitting. But design several decisions by Rowley _ like her choice
of colors, materials and models _ simply served to befuddle
audience members.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the new spud juice (MOR vodka), Rowley's slouchy pants,
ill-fitting sweaters and poof-shouldered dresses hinted at lapses
in taste. Rowley's models appeared wearing the stupidest shoes
shown on any runway, so far. And, once again, Rowley _ who took a
bow in a maternity smock _ also took a step further from the
``pretty'' clothes that earned her her rising-star status.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Girbaud: The song-and-dance spectacle Francois Girbaud
staged was themed, ``Learning to Fly.'' And the statement Girbaud
made on the cover of his program notes, translated from French was,
``I have no interest in he who walks.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewed from a pedestrian perspective on style, Girbaud's
cold-weather clothes would look oddly futuristic. . .jiggy-wear for
the Jetsons. But Girbaud insists that retractable leggings,
convertible coveralls, rubber suits and wearable desks are what
interesting people need now. Too cutting-edge for the masses? Most
definitely. But consider Girbaud's double-side bag designs, which
drape the shoulders like vests and extend to arm's length for easy
access. They can put a 77-year-old man into space, so why didn't
anyone think of making bags that practical before?
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
