<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-VENDING-2TAKES-N     02-15 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-VENDING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVERSION TO EURO POSES CHALLENGE TO COIN-MACHINE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Germany, France, Ireland)  (mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICENZA, Italy _ Luca Adriani is of two minds about the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Adriani, 32, is chief executive of Coges SRL, which manufactures
vending machines. Now that the euro _ the common currency for 11
European nations _ has made its debut in electronic transactions,
orders for his machines are swelling, he says, in preparation for
January 2002, when euro coins and bills will be introduced.
</P>
<P>
   But his company, based outside this city in northern Italy, also
operates vending machines, supplying them to businesses that offer
snacks and coffee to employees. So he expects the cost of replacing
the coin boxes, as well as the loss of revenue while the machines
are being converted, to put a sizable dent in that business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm laughing on one side of my face, and crying on the
other,'' Adriani said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, mixed emotions are found throughout the European vending
industry, which makes and operates coin-operated machines
dispensing everything from soda to cigarettes, candy to condoms. In
the next three years, companies that operate vending machines will
have to spend heavily to rejigger them to accept euro coins. The
swelling demand will be a boon for equipment manufacturers at
first.
</P>
<P>
   But the rush to convert also means that many machines will be
out of commission for long periods, in limbo between currencies.
And come 2002, there are sure to be frustrated customers with
marks, lire, francs and the like still jingling in their pockets
who are unable to use the new euro machines. (The 11 national
currencies are legal tender until July 2002.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The question for us is: When do you convert your machines?''
said Norbert Monssen, spokesman for the organization that
represents the German vending machine industry. ``If you do it too
early, your customers don't have the coins and go elsewhere. It's a
problem unique to vending.'' Stores, he noted, can and must accept
two currencies during the six-month transition period; vending
machines and other coin-operated devices are exempt but still must
be retrofitted to accept the new coins at some point.
</P>
<P>
   And as the investment budgets of vending machine operators are
stretched thin, some equipment manufacturers are apprehensive about
a sharp falloff in sales once the new coins arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll peak in the next two years, and investments will be
considerable,'' said Rainer Puchalski, sales manager at NRI
National Rejectors Inc. near Hamburg, Germany, a leading maker of
coin processing equipment and a unit of Crane Co. of Stamford,
Conn. ``But once that's done, we expect some holding back.''
</P>
<P>
   The euro (worth about $1.13) came into use on Jan. 4 in Italy,
Germany, France, Ireland, the Netherlands, Belgium, Luxembourg,
Austria, Finland, Spain and Portugal. For now, however, it is a
cashless currency, used by banks and financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of euro notes and coins was delayed for three
years to afford Europe's new Central Bank and mints the time to
produce the money needed. Europeans now carry roughly 70 billion
coins in their pockets that can be used for 3.8 million vending
machines and several million more coin-operated devices like
telephones and subway ticket machines. In Germany, home to 2.5
million vending machines, more than $6 billion worth of coins,
weighing more than 86,000 tons, circulate.
</P>
<P>
   The task of changing all that money into euros is ``both a
threat and an opportunity,'' said Catherine Piana, secretary
general of the European Vending Association in Brussels, which
represents the industry.
</P>
<P>
   For one, few euro coins are available to vending machine
manufacturers. Industry officials say they must have samples of the
coins because the microchips in older model coin-recognition
devices, like those often used in vending machines, must learn the
characteristics of new coins by having them repeatedly inserted
into their slots; newer models are programmed by transferring the
information from a laptop. The recognition devices typically judge
the genuineness of coins by examining magnetic fields to determine
alloys and optical sensors to check looks.
</P>
<P>
   National Rejectors has already sent specialists to mints in
France, Germany and Belgium to test equipment on the new euro
coins. Puchalski said he hoped to have samples in the company's own
laboratories by the summer, ``though no one's given it to us in
writing yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar complaints about the availability of samples greeted the
introduction of a redesigned $20 bill in the United States in
September. Vending machine manufacturers say that they have had to
scramble to refit their machines.
</P>
<P>
   European industry officials also worry whether there will be
sufficient coins available in 2002 and whether the amounts will be
properly apportioned in terms of what denominations are most in
demand by vending machine customers.
</P>
<P>
   Some skeptical companies are promoting cashless systems that use
smart cards or programmable keys to activate vending machines,
convinced that coin shortages will occur, and thus present
opportunities for introducing new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Adriani of Coges, for example, can plug a plastic key into a
coffee machine and a digital display tells him how much credit
remains on its programmable microchip before he orders two
espressos. His company, which has big markets in Germany, France
and Spain in addition to Italy, is pushing such cashless payment
systems because he is convinced that Europe will never have
sufficient coins ready on time. In Germany and Italy, Europe's
largest markets, cashless systems are additionally attractive, he
said, because about 95 percent of food and beverage vending
machines are on private premises, like company cafeterias, where
smart cards or other electronic purses are easily distributable,
compared with only about 26 percent in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Italy alone has to mint 7.6 billion coins by 2002, or 10
million coins a day,'' said Adriani, whose company has annual sales
of $60 million, as he sipped his espresso. ``But our mint has a
capacity of 2 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have already adopted cashless systems. Alois
Dallmayr, the Munich-based coffee distributor, says it expects 70
percent of its vending machines to be cashless after the euro
comes.
</P>
<P>
   Adriani and others are also concerned about the uniform quality
required of coins for vending machines. Euro coins are planned in
eight denominations: 0.01, 0.02, 0.05, 0.10, 0.20 and 0.50 euros,
and 1 and 2 euro coins. While European leaders have set the size,
color, weight and metal alloys to be used for each, the coins will
be minted at 15 locations in the 11 euro countries. ``The main
concern is constancy and uniformity in the materials and the
alloys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, that may not be a problem, since national mints will
supply the coins for national territories. But there may be trouble
after summer 2002, when Europeans return home from summer holidays
with pockets full of euros from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, simply getting the coins into circulation and
disposing of the old national coins poses immense logistical and
security problems. In some countries, like Italy, officials are
considering using the army to transport and guard the money. ``It's
an epochal event,'' Adriani said. ``There's no precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   Europe's retailing association, Eurocommerce, predicts that
under the best of circumstances the switch to euro cash in 2002
will cost European retailers 1.3 percent of their annual revenues,
or about $17 billion, said Ceu Pereira, an association spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many European retailers are urging a shortening of
the period of dual currency use from the six months now planned.
Some even argue for a ``big bang'' _ an overnight switch from 11
currencies to the euro. A drawn-out conversion, they argue, means
duplicate cash registers and price tags in stores.
</P>
<P>
   But the vending industry rejects the proposal. Shortages of
technical personnel will mean idling machines for long periods, and
hence lost revenue, they say. As it is, armies of mechanics will
have to fan out to coffee shops, train stations and restrooms. On
older model vending machines, coin boxes will have to be taken to
workshops, a task that will require months. ``At our meetings,
there's panic,'' acknowledged Lucio Pinetti, director general of
the Italian Vending Association in Milan.
</P>
<P>
   His group predicts that conversion of Italy's 517,000 food and
beverage machines will cost almost $150 million, or 10 percent of
annual revenues. In Germany, food and drink vendors, whose revenues
total $2 billion, fear losses of up to $8 million a day.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the vending industry consists of mom-and-pop operations
with an average of five employees, according to the European
Vending Association. But huge multinationals like Coca-Cola Co.,
which has thousands of vending machines throughout Europe, are also
affected. ``It works if you have sufficient lead time,'' said
Shelagh Kerr, a spokeswoman in Brussels for Coca-Cola in Europe.
``It's not cheap, but it's doable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
