<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-ATLANTA-COX     02-15 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    USOC requests more time for Atlanta report; other cities claim
no breach of rules
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (s) Sports and (i) International categories.)By
Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's response to an International Olympic
Committee investigation into improprieties by IOC members in
dealings with candidate host cities has been delayed despite the
local bid team's assurances that it has ``nothing to report.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other bid groups asked to supply information to the IOC
about any improper actions by members during visits also say they
have little or nothing to report, according to an Associated Press
survey of cities.
</P>
<P>
   That answer raises questions about the ultimate effectiveness of
the IOC's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   David D'Alessandro, president of John Hancock insurance, an IOC
sponsor, observed in a published column over the weekend: ``This is
like sending a letter to the proverbial fox in the hen house,
asking, `Would you mind telling us how many chickens you have
eaten?' Then, if the fox sends back a polite note, `None, thank
you,' you issue a public statement exonerating the fox.
Incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the deadline for bid groups to deliver their reports
to the IOC headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland. Atlanta's report
has been stalled by the U.S. Olympic Committee's preoccupation with
the Salt Lake City scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Since many bid groups have dissolved, the IOC sent inquiries to
the national Olympic committees representing all Olympic bidders
from 1996 through 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Payne, president of Atlanta's bid team, has faxed a brief
response to USOC president Bill Hybl indicating that he has no
evidence of corruption by any IOC member.
</P>
<P>
   ``ACOG has advised us they have nothing to report,'' USOC
spokesman Mike Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the USOC has asked the IOC for an extension until March
1 to provide a formal response on behalf of Atlanta. Moran said the
USOC was obligated to provide an official response to the IOC and
could not just forward Atlanta's comments on to Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a few comments we provided that really don't
amount to a whole lot,'' Atlanta bid spokesman Lee Echols
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said the USOC, based in Colorado Springs, Colo., is
``exhausting all our resources'' gathering information for its own
investigation, led by former Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, into bribery allegations in Salt Lake. The USOC's report
is due to be released March 1. The USOC is further bogged down with
subpoenas from the U.S. Justice Department, which also is looking
into the Salt Lake City bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been able to respond to (the IOC's request on
Atlanta),'' Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake ethics board released a report last week detailing
how IOC members received more than $1 million in cash, scholarships
for their families, medical treatment and other favors during the
city's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake report implicated 24 IOC members _ about one-fifth
of the total roster _ for receiving improper or questionable
benefits. The report cited 10 names that were not included in the
list of 14 implicated earlier during the IOC's internal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities will paint a contrasting picture to the IOC's,
according to the Associated Press survey.
</P>
<P>
   _ Berlin (2000 Games): ``It's been investigated and it's all on
the table. We didn't see any rules being broken,'' said Heiner
Henze, general secretary of the Germany Olympic committee.
</P>
<P>
   _ St. Petersburg, Russia (2004): Neither the Russian Olympic
committee nor the St. Petersburg bidding committee will submit a
report. ``We have sent no letter, since there was nothing to
report,'' said Alexander Ratner, Russian Olympic committee
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rome (2004): Italian IOC member Mario Pescante said there
would be no submission. ``I don't think we have sent a letter, nor
are we sending one,'' Pescante said. ``We don't have anything to
report.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Athens (1996 and 2004): Lambis Nikolaou, president of the
Greek Olympic committee, said there was no ``problem with any
member of the IOC for Athens 1996 or 2004. We have no evidence of
wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   In England, an official with Manchester (1996 and 2000) and
Birmingham (1992) said its report was confidential.
</P>
<P>
   As for Cape Town (2004), ``We were not involved in offering any
inducement for votes,'' said Chris Ball, who led the South African
city's bid. He declined to give details of his report to the IOC.
``I have to be discreet,'' he said. ``It's an IOC matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Nagano (1998 Winter Games) have said that nine IOC
members exceeded the limits, while Toronto (1996) previously cited
improper activities by some members.
</P>
<P>
   Like Atlanta, Ostersund, Sweden (2002 Winter Games) has
requested more time to respond.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 1841EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0237 </DOCNO>
