<HEADER>
A6087 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-CHEN-COX     02-15 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CHEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bruce Chen: The fifth dimension
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The newest soon-to-be member of the Atlanta Braves
starting rotation was flying high when his opportunity knocked.
About 30,000 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chen was on his way back to Atlanta from his home in
Panama on Nov. 10 when a flight attendant handed him a Panamanian
newspaper. He opened to the sports section to find a picture of
himself beside one of Denny Neagle accompanying a report that
Neagle had been traded to the Reds in a five-player deal. The
caption under Chen's photo said the 21-year-old left-handed pitcher
had a great opportunity to break in as the Braves' fifth starter.
</P>
<P>
   So did he let out a yelp? A scream? Did he high-five the nearest
person?
</P>
<P>
   No, the reaction was more like a little grin, then serious
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think, `You're going to be the fifth starter,' ''
Chen said. ``I was like, `Oh, there's an opportunity. I'll have to
earn it. I'll have to work hard in the offseason to have the chance
to do it. I'm not going to take anything for granted. If I'm not
going to be the fifth starter, it's not because I'm out of shape.'
''
</P>
<P>
   That type of thought process is one of the reasons the Braves
feel comfortable inserting Chen into a rotation that includes Greg
Maddux, Tom Glavine, John Smoltz and Kevin Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it doesn't hurt that Chen has good pitches _
fastball, curveball, change-up _ good control and had a successful
debut in the major leagues last season. After getting called up in
September, Chen went 2-0 with a 3.98 ERA in four starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to see Chen continue what he did last year,''
manager Bobby Cox said. ``He doesn't have to do anything different.
. . . He's a very young kid, but he's very polished for his years
of experience. He's a very bright kid. He's a fast learner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves signed Chen in 1993 when he was 16 years old. The
following summer he left his parents, older sister and younger
brother to start his professional baseball career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they told me you have six months until you have to
report, so be by yourself, start to be independent,'' Chen said.
``That was kind of scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen pitched for the rookie league Gulf Coast Braves on
Wednesdays and weekends and went to high school the other days. He
roomed with Andruw Jones, another teenage prospect. Chen said the
two struggled with being away from family on days when baseball
wasn't going well. They didn't have many of those days.
</P>
<P>
   Chen moved straight to Class AA Greenville, then moved to
Triple-A Greenville in August. The Braves brought him to Atlanta
three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Phillips was Chen's first opposing hitter during his debut
against the Mets on Sept. 7. Chen threw three consecutive fastballs
on the outside corner, and Phillips never took the bat off his
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, 'If I can do that, my fastball is the same as
anybody's,''' Chen said. ``It doesn't matter how hard you throw
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen gave up four runs in three innings, but he gained
confidence. Pitching coach Leo Mazzone got on him afterward about
not giving in to the strike zone. He responded by allowing two runs
in the next 16 innings while winning two games, against the Florida
Marlins and Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   And now this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be different (than September), but it's also
going to be fun,'' Chen said. ``It's a time for you to get the
first taste of baseball. I want to pitch. I want to grab a ball and
face a hitter. It's hard to describe. You miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   During his first full minor-league season in 1997, Chen was a
member of the highly-regarded young pitching rotation in Class A
Macon (Ga.), which included Rob Bell, Jason Marquis and Jason
Shiell, but Chen was the one lagging. He started 6-4 with a 5.00
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided not to worry about numbers, to get better every
day,'' Chen said. ``At the end of the season, I'll be a better
pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   He had just turned 20 years old at the time. And he was right.
By the end of that season, he was 12-7 and his ERA was 3.51. He led
the South Atlantic League in strikeouts with 182 in only 146 1/3
innings. Baseball America chose him as the Braves top minor-league
prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, who is studying civil engineering at Georgia Tech, blended
in as just another student last year. That will change before long.
``Baseball is my first priority, but getting a diploma would mean a
lot to me,'' Chen said. ``At the beginning, it was more my parents
that were big on it. After the quarter at Tech, I realized I can do
it. It's not that hard. It'd be a great accomplishment if I can
finish my college career. It's going to take a while for me, but it
shows perseverance and hard work, which are the basics for playing
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   If he's as successful this baseball season as he was this
academic quarter at Tech, he'll be in the Braves' rotation for a
while: Chen was named to the dean's list.
</P>
<P>
   BRAVES' FIFTH STARTERS IN THE 1990S
</P>
<P>
   Year Name W-L ERA
</P>
<P>
   1990 Pete Smith 5-6 4.79
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lilliquist 2-8 6.28
</P>
<P>
   1991 Pete Smith 1-3 5.06
</P>
<P>
   1992 Mike Bielecki 2-4 2.57
</P>
<P>
   Pete Smith 7-0 2.05
</P>
<P>
   1993 Pete Smith 4-8 4.37
</P>
<P>
   1994 Kent Mercker 9-4 3.45
</P>
<P>
   1995 Kent Mercker 7-8 4.15
</P>
<P>
   1996 Jason Schmidt 5-6 5.70
</P>
<P>
   1997 Terrell Wade 2-3 5.36
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood 5-3 4.03
</P>
<P>
   1998 Kevin Millwood 17-8 4.08
</P>
