<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOLDEN-GIRLS-ART-2     02-15 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOLDEN-GIRLS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIRST LADIES OF OFF-OFF-OFF-BROADWAY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After the farfalle with porcini mushrooms, ricotta
cheese pastiera and decaffeinated cappuccino at Roberto's two
blocks away on Crescent Avenue, it was almost curtain time at the
Belmont Italian American Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But first, attention had to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``In case you missed them, the Arthur Avenue Golden Girls are
here,'' announced Dante Albertie, artistic director of the
Playhouse, a matchbook-size theater in the Bronx. ``If midway
through the show they start talking, just give one of them a shot,
and they'll all get quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Girls tittered. The lights went down. And since
there's no curtain to go up, the show began, with the Golden Girls
in their customary places, in the first of the seven rows on the
right side of the 75-seat theater overlooking Arthur Avenue, the
Bronx's answer to Little Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction this time was ``Rockaway Boulevard,'' a
no-nonsense three-actor drama written by Richard Vetere in what
could be termed Outer Borough Neo-Realism. But the stars of the
evening were clearly the four Golden Girls, three of them in their
70's and Marie Antoinette Diorio, the baby at 57, who make it to
every Belmont production and hark back to a long gone, probably
irretrievable era in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont area was farmland until late in the 19th century.
Its first residents were mostly Italian workers who settled there
and found jobs in landscaping or construction at the Bronx Zoo and
the New York Botanical Garden. It soon became known as the Little
Italy of the Bronx, and though its ethnic mix has become far more
diverse in recent decades, its heart remains the Italian shops,
bakeries and restaurants, most of them handed down generation to
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont playhouse opened in 1991 with the fiercely
anachronistic mission of being a truly local theater, with a core
clientele in the aging Italian populace and a goal of presenting
new works by Italian-American playwrights and new productions of
classic Italian plays. In addition to contemporary plays, work
presented over the years in Italian and English has included
Machiavelli's ``Mandragola,'' Goldoni's ``Coffee Shop,'' one-act
plays by Luigi Pirandello and Eduardo de Filippo's ``Non ti Pago.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, no part of the core clientele has been as solid as the
Golden Girls, though their configuration can change a bit from
month to month. This evening brought out Anne Mariano, Marge
Cristiano, V Cauttero and Ms. Diorio, all in vintage sweaters and
knits and impeccably coiffed. Loretta Borrello, a founding member,
moved to Florida two years ago. Lena Simioni is a regular now, but
she was out sick this time out. And local chroniclers will no doubt
recount the contributions of Chris Solanto, Marie Panniti and Helen
Caputo, who have been card-carrying members at various times
</P>
<P>
   While members may come and go, in some form the group has made
it to every production the theater has presented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really enjoy the performances; they're excellent,'' said
Mrs. Mariano, who lives two doors down from the theater. ``We sit
in the first row, and you can almost touch the actors. And it gives
us a chance to get together, go out to dinner and go to a play. How
many neighborhoods can you do that in?''
</P>
<P>
   There are some. The South Bronx has the Pregones Theater, which
caters to the Puerto Rican community. Groups like the Thalia
Spanish Theater in Queens and Vaso de Leche Productions on the
Lower East Side offer ethnic fare to audiences made up largely of
local residents. Still, recreating the glory days of ethnic
theater, for example, the Yiddish Theater's following on the Lower
East Side, is no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are behind us,'' said Albertie, one of three full-time
employees at the theater, which occupies what used to be a pool
hall. ``It's different than coming to a neighborhood and opening up
a deli. A deli's not about hope. A theater is. But it's very hard
work, and I'm not sure there's enough of an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to think you would work this hard and there's a
guarantee that you'll be rewarded in the end, but I don't know
that's true,'' he said. ``Which is one reason we're so appreciative
of the support we do get.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Girls meet at 6 p.m. before heading to Roberto's,
Dominick's, Mario's, Ann &AMP; Tony's or Rigoletto's for dinner. This
evening's repast, at Roberto's, with its pictures of Salerno on the
walls, began with a lesson in neighborhood demographics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a neighborhood like it always has been,'' said Mrs.
Mariano, who owns the building next door to the theater where Mrs.
Simioni and Mrs. Cristiano used to run a gift shop. ``It takes me
two hours to walk down the street because there's always someone
with something to say. But it's changing some. It's Italian, but
not Italian Italian, the way it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got Albanians. You've got Yugoslavs,'' said Mrs.
Cauterro, whose Bronx accent seems the most authoritative of the
four.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Mexicans,'' Mrs. Mariano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Asians,'' Mrs. Cauterro said.
</P>
<P>
   The old-timers are mostly staying put, and are so loyal that
Mrs. Cauterro's newly inaugurated e-mail address includes
arthurave. But attrition is a fact of life. Of the six Golden
Girls, only one, Mrs. Cristiano, whose husband, Nick, comes along
as a Golden Boy for a day, has a surviving spouse. And their
children have all left the neighborhood, most of them, like Mrs.
Cristiano's, for the suburbs (Great Neck) or points south or west
(Houston).
</P>
<P>
   So unlike some of the Hispanic or Asian theaters, catering to a
growing population base, the Belmont theater is fighting the
demographic tide.
</P>
<P>
   The theater is a godsend to the Golden Girls. Mrs. Mariano used
to go to Manhattan to see a movie or show or, years ago, to hear
Frank Sinatra sing at a hotel. Mrs. Cauterro used to belong to a
group of women who attended shows in the city and dinner theater
out in Westchester County. But Broadway is expensive and the trip
can be taxing, so a night at the Belmont is a special event for a
group whose tastes run from Italian opera (Mrs. Mariano) to Sinatra
(Mrs. Cauttero) to Barbra Streisand, Sinatra and Tony Bennett (Mrs.
Cristiano), to Paul Anka (Mrs. Diorio).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very good, and I like that it usually has a message,''
Mrs. Diorio said of the plays presented at the theater. ``Maybe you
don't know what it is at the time, but it makes you think.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinner rolled along. Mrs. Diorio and Cristiano discussed their
different experiences with Bell's palsy. There were discussions of
the generosity of the landlord, Lou Izzo, in supporting the
theater, and a request for a plug for a clothing store
(``specialists in cadets and portlys,'' reads one ad) that is owned
by Mrs. Cristiano's cousin, Vincent Borgese. They spoke in a
rapid-fire melange of Bronxese, sounding as much like men at a
poker game as women at leisure. But it was a particularly good
meal, and when Cristiano, a onetime prisoner of war in Japan,
chimed in about his recovery from a heart attack, he got a special
Golden Girl salute.
</P>
<P>
   ``To your heart,'' announced Mrs. Cauttero. ``May it beat
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   After dinner they walked back to the theater for the 8:30
performance. They milled around the lobby until Albertie ushered
the crowd of about 20 people into the theater with a firm,
``Subscribers and Golden Girls first.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear how things will ultimately turn out. The
audience, mostly people from the Bronx but including one man from
Staten Island, probably was not bad for a cold, rainy Thursday. But
it takes more than two dozen people a night to keep a theater
going.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception eight years ago, the theater has been a
critical success and has staged more than 60 classical and
contemporary plays. But this year it hit a financial wall and had
to cut back its five-show subscription program to two open-ended
productions in the Bronx and another in Manhattan. Nor did it help
that the latest production, ``Rockaway Boulevard,'' the story of a
luckless couple and a heartless hustler, received lackluster
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the Belmont needs all the Golden Girls it can find, on
this night, as usual, it managed to please the ones it had. They
managed to stifle the urge to declaim or opine too loudly during
the performance but came away impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``True to life!'' said Ms. Diorio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it all!'' raved Mrs. Cristiano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excellent!'' reported Mrs. Mariano.
</P>
<P>
   They bade Albertie farewell, walked carefully down the steep
wooden staircase, popped open their umbrellas and headed down
Arthur Avenue toward home.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
