<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-750&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA TO PLAY KEY ROLE IN PEACE AGREEMENT FOR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
 (fe) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMBOUILLET, France _ The broad shape of the peace deal that the
two sides in the Kosovo conflict are being compelled to accept
emerged on Monday, with Russia playing a key role in working to
persuade the Serbs to allow NATO-led peacekeepers on their
territory.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac said on Monday that the
Russians, traditionally an ally of the Serbs, had agreed that a
ground force in Kosovo was the best solution to stopping the
bloodshed in the separatist province and that Russian soldiers were
likely to be part of the deployment. ``The Russians accept it, and
I'm convinced they'd participate in it,'' Chirac said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov visited the
castle here where the Serbian and ethnic Albanian delegations have
been sequestered for nine days and said afterward that military
intervention would be ``discussed with Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Slobodan Milosevic, the authoritarian
president of Yugoslavia. Serbia is the dominant republic of
Yugoslavia, and Kosovo is a province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, who have never before been so helpful to the West
on the long-running problem of dealing with Milosevic, pledged
their help on resolving the Kosovo issue last month when Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright visited Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few days, as the Saturday deadline for the
conclusion of the talks approaches, the Russians have promised to
sell to Milosevic the necessity of accepting the troops, a senior
European diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians are working on the Yugoslavs and were asking for
a little more time,'' the diplomat said. ``The Belgrade leadership
needs to put some spin on this, but seems more or less resigned.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquiescence to the presence of troops on Yugoslav soil is part
of a basic tradeoff for the two sides that goes as follows, two
European diplomats close to the talks said: The ethnic Albanians
must drop their demand for a referendum on the status of Kosovo at
the end of the three-year interim period established by the peace
plan. At the same time, the Serbs must agree to a NATO-led
peacekeeping force, a proposition that they have vehemently opposed
on the grounds that it interferes with Serbia's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's yes to NATO for the Serbs and no to a referendum for the
Albanians,'' one of the diplomats said. ``All the rest is
conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspense for the next few days will be seeing how Milosevic
decides to maneuver and whether the ethnic Albanian delegation,
which has shown surprising unity, will accept the disappointment of
not being promised a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   In a visit to the two delegations here on Sunday, Albright said
she believed that the ethnic Albanians saw the peace plan as a
``good deal'' and were prepared to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's room for maneuvering was narrowed further on Sunday
from a quarter where he has sometimes found some comfort, the
European Union, according to the senior European diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   After a Paris meeting of European Union foreign ministers,
German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said that all members of
the union had supported military enforcement of a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   This is a signal to Milosevic that he cannot expect any
financial relief, which he needs for his desperate economy and has
sometimes received, from European Union countries, the diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the ethnic Albanians, the insistence on a referendum after a
three-year period of autonomy was based on the understanding that a
referendum would result in a vote for independence, the long-held
goal of their resistance movement.
</P>
<P>
   European countries and the United States have opposed
independence for Kosovo _ where the people, 90 percent of whom are
ethnic Albanian, have been living under repressive Serbian rule.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who has written of his empathy
with the cause of the ethnic Albanians, visited the delegation here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell called the lack of a referendum in the peace agreement
a poor deal for the ethnic Albanians. He was also upset, he said,
that the peace plan required the ethnic Albanian rebel force, the
Kosovo Liberation Army, to dismantle, but allowed limited numbers
of Serbian police and the Yugoslav army to stay.
</P>
<P>
   During Albright's visit on Sunday, the Contact Group of six
nations _ the United States, four European countries, and Russia _
that is running the talks announced a deadline of midday Saturday
for completion.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the remaining time appears to be a chance for Milosevic
to develop his ``spin,'' one of the diplomats said. By this he
meant the Yugoslav president needed to formulate some way to
explain to his people why he was accepting something he had opposed
so strongly and so long.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic, who manages the most relentless state-run
propaganda machines in Europe, has remained in power for the last
10 years as the Serbs have lost one war after another and the
promise of a greater Serbia has vanished in the reality of an ever
smaller Serbia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A provision in the peace agreement that calls for the
demilitarization of the ethnic Albanian guerrilla force will give
Milosevic a ready-made way to explain why foreign troops are
necessary, one of the European diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can sell the international force by saying it would get rid
of the KLA,'' as the Kosovo Liberation Army is known, the diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's army and security police have been fighting the
insurgents for a year and watched them grow from a handful of
poorly armed men to thousands of volunteers with increasingly
sophisticated weaponry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
