u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-RUSHDIE-500&AMP;ADD-     02-15 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-RUSHDIE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH DISCOUNT RENEWED THREATS AGAINST RUSHDIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Despite calls from Iran over the weekend for the
10-year-old death sentence against Salman Rushdie to be carried
out, the British Foreign Office said Monday that it was confident
that the Iranian government was firmly committed to its repudiation
of the religious edict, or fatwa.
</P>
<P>
   Western experts in Iranian politics tended to discount the
renewed calls for the writer's death, saying they were a product of
conservative factions that are at odds with the Iranian government
and do not have the means to carry out their threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the British government or the European Union had the
slightest doubt that Iran's intentions were anything but honorable,
they would be making an official protest right now,'' said Carmel
Bedford, a spokeswoman for Article 19, an anticensorship group.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to President Mohammad Khatami of Iran, widely
considered a reformer and a moderate, Ms. Bedford said, ``The fact
is that President Khatami has made it very clear that he wants the
rule of law to apply in Iran, and he's bringing about a huge change
in the way they conduct business there.'' Over the weekend, two
hardline Iranian groups used the 10th anniversary of the fatwa to
register their support of the campaign against Rushdie. The edict
was originally issued by the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini. On Feb.
14, 1989, the ayatollah denounced Rushdie's ``Satanic Verses'' as a
blasphemous insult to Islam and appealed to ``all Muslims of the
world'' to collaborate in killing him.
</P>
<P>
   The Khordad Foundation, a semiofficial charity that has put a
$2.8-million bounty on Rushdie's head, said on Sunday that it was
still committed to his death. ``Surely, this verdict will be
implemented one day,'' the group said in a statement published in a
hard-line newspaper, Jomhuri Islami.
</P>
<P>
   A statement by the Revolutionary Guards, which has been divided
in supporting Khatami, accused the West of conducting a
``disinformation campaign to make world people and Muslims believe
that Iran has backed down from its stances toward the apostate
author Salman Rushdie.'' Rushdie, the group added, ``will
eventually be burnt in the fire of Muslims' wrath.''
</P>
<P>
   Such remarks fly in the face of official Iranian policy. In
September, Foreign Minister Kamal Kharazzi said in New York that
Iran was formally repudiating the fatwa. Britain responded by
agreeing to restore full diplomatic relations with Iran. The two
countries also said they would exchange ambassadors, although that
has not been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the continued clamor for Rushdie, there is no reason to
suspect that anything has changed since the agreement in September,
said an official at the British Foreign Office who insisted on
anonymity. ``We're confident that they remain committed to the
assurances they gave us,'' the official said. ``We work on the
basis of government-to-government relations, and we're convinced
that the Iranian government means what it says. You can't hold the
Iranian government responsible for every person who wants to make a
comment on Rushdie.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An expert in Middle East politics, who also insisted on
anonymity because he travels often to Iran and does not want to
jeopardize his access to information there, said the statements on
Sunday were an indication of conflict between moderate and
conservative factions in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iran is a very complex political society, in which there are
all sorts of points of view vying for influence,'' the expert said.
``In a sense, the Rushdie issue is passe. The issues now are who's
been attacking intellectuals in Iran, and how that's going to be
dealt with. What you're seeing is a constant encroachment on the
power of conservative groups by the Khatami agenda. He's
consolidating power.''
</P>
<P>
   The expert called it ``a very hopeful sign'' that the government
recently announced that it had made a number of arrests in the
cases of several dissidents and writers who were slain or found
dead in mysterious circumstances. The government also said its
intelligence minister had been forced to resign, a sign that it was
cracking down on past repression.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how serious are the threats to Rushdie, experts say
that the Iranian government's threat had been the most serious and
that when it officially withdrew its support for the edict last
year, the author's burden was considerably lessened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal made at the United Nations in September between the
ministers of the U.K. and Iran was made at the highest level, with
complete backing from the highest echelons of government in Iran
and with the backing of the European Union,'' Ms. Bedford said.
</P>
<P>
   But threats do remain, friends of Rushdie said. Among other
aspects, he is still under the protection of bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't mean there's been a 100 percent solution,'' said
a friend who knows about Rushdie's situation. ``It was a very big
step. But we were led to believe that all parts of the Iranian
state had signed up for the agreement. Until it's been demonstrated
that that's true, the deal has some holes in it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
