<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEXICO     02-15 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEXICO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SAYS MEXICO SHOULD NOT BE ``PENALIZED'' FOR DRUG EFFORTS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDA, Mexico Endorsing Mexico as a courageous if imperfect
ally in the high-stakes drug war, President Clinton said Monday
this country ''should not be penalized'' for its shortcomings, but
rather encouraged for its progress.
</P>
<P>
   The comments, coming just two weeks before Clinton must decide
whether to certify to Congress that Mexico is doing its best to
thwart the flow of narcotics into the U.S. border, signalled that
he intends to give its counter-drug efforts a passing grade despite
serious deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mexico should not be penalized for having the courage to
confront its problems,'' Clinton said during a daylong summit with
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo in this semi-tropical center of
commerce and tourism on Mexico's Yucatan peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ten years ago, our relationship was marred by distrust,'' said
Clinton, speaking in a 91-year-old theater decorated with the flags
of both nations. ''We have increased our cooperation,'' in the drug
war, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, for his part, pledged that Mexico would ''make every
effort. . .to keep up the fight against drugs until we win.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting for their tenth time, the two leaders signed a series of
low-octane agreements meant to underscore cross-border cooperation
and paper over areas of contention between the neighbors, which
share a 2,000-mile-long border and will do nearly $200 billion in
two-way trade this year.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. drug authorities remain largely dissatisfied, for instance,
with the corruption and inefficiency plaguing anti-drug efforts in
Mexico through which passes more than half of the estimated $50
billion worth of illicit drugs that pour into the United States
each year.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, however, the two leaders could agree only on a new
regime for monitoring advances and setbacks in the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Bi-National Performance Measures of Effectiveness
announced Monday is a largely symbolic agreement on a set of goals
the two countries adopted nearly two years ago, when Clinton went
to Mexico City to declare that the two countries had entered into a
formal alliance in the drug war.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Zedillo also signed agreements meant to widen
cooperation and competition among U.S. and Mexican airlines, which
last year ferried some 14 million passengers across the two
countries' borders.
</P>
<P>
   Other agreements Clinton and Zedillo signed Monday are designed
to:
</P>
<P>
   Enhance cooperation between U.S. and Mexican law enforcement
officials to combat lawlessness along the border and to prevent
criminals on one side from seeking safe harbor on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Provide Mexico with a $4 billion line of credit with the U.S.
Import-Export bank to help fund the construction of infrastructure
projects like roads, water systems and bridges and large-scale
U.S.-Mexican commercial ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Advance U.S.-Mexican cooperation in preventing the spread of
tuberculosis, a major health problem in Mexico, which reports some
11,000 new cases per year.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements constituted modest measures, though, in a summit
whose main purpose was to lessen friction between the two countries
over the most contentious issue between them: drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted that he had not decided whether to certify that
Mexico was cooperating fully with U.S. anti-drug efforts. His
comments, however, suggested that he would support Mexico. American
presidents have done so for each of the past dozen years, despite
congressional criticism that Mexico should be doing more..
</P>
<P>
   ''The question is how can we do better to deal with the drug
problem,'' Clinton told reporters just before meeting with Zedillo
at the 17th Century ''Hacienda Temozon'' _ translated, ``whirlwind
plantation'' _ now a hotel 22 miles south of town. ''Neither
country has won the drug war.''
</P>
<P>
   Hailing what he called ''a new season of friendship,'' between
the giant if disparate neighbors, Clinton laid out the case that
cross-border cooperation in combating drugs has been steadily
improving for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Unspoken but clearly implied was the corollary message: failing
to certify Mexico as a fully cooperative partner in the drug war, a
move that would trigger economic sanctions, would risk shattering
the foundations of the bilateral relationship that has produced
wanted gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not long ago, we could not have had a conversation about drugs
without falling into an unwinnable argument about who is to
blame,'' Clinton said, speaking to some 1,400 government officials,
executives and human rights workers from this city of ancient oaks,
stuccoed villas, narrow streets and 800,000 people. ''We can talk
candidly about this now, because we have started to speak the same
language.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the controversial congressionally-mandated certification
process, the administration must annually evaluate the
</P>
<P>
   anti-drug programs of several dozen countries that are major
producers or distributors of cocaine, heroin, marijuana or other
illicit drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The process is an attempt by Congress to force other countries
to work to help curb trafficking into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Countries that are not certified are subject to immediate loss
of most U.S. economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has long resented the process. Privately, Mexican
diplomats view it as one in which a wealthy country whose drug use
is driving the scourge of narco-crime and corruption is sitting in
judgment of the anti-drug efforts of a far poorer country.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo stressed again on Monday that combatting drugs is not a
job that can be done by any single country, nor can a lone
scapegoat be singled out for blame.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a struggle to be fought by all nations,'' said
Zedillo. ''We will only win if we work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has tried in recent years to reduce the friction the
annual certification process injects into a relationship already
complicated by enormous trade, economic, historic and cultural
ties.
</P>
<P>
   He made the case Monday that those ties can bring the two
countries closer together, if differences are resolved through a
dialogue based on respect.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are more than neighbors,'' said Clinton, as hundreds of
Merida's residents, young and old, lined the narrow streets outside
the Peon Contreras Theater, waiting beneath sunny skies to catch a
glimpse of the presidential motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   ''More and more, we belong to the same American family,'' he
said. ''What binds us together is far, far more important than what
divides us.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
