<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-POLITICS-550&AMP;     02-15 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-POLITICS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MILITARY RULER WINS NIGERIAN PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ Pledging to make Nigeria ``great again,''
Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, who earned international esteem by becoming
Nigeria's first military leader to give up power voluntarily, won
the nomination of the country's leading political party Monday as
its presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo's selection by the People's Democratic Party set the
stage for his return to the position he held 20 years ago, this
time as a democratically elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``My joy knows no bounds,'' the retired general said in an
acceptance speech at the end of a contentious convention in Jos, a
city in central Nigeria. ``I will devote all my energy and all the
powers available to me to the service of Nigeria and humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   His chief rival, Alex Ekwueme, a former vice president during a
brief period of civilian rule in the early 1980s, stood behind the
general, offering his congratulations and support in the Feb. 27
elections.
</P>
<P>
   From 1976 to 1979, Obasanjo, 61, served as Nigeria's military
president and became the only general to leave office voluntarily
since Nigeria's independence from Britain in 1960. Over the years,
he has become an elder statesman in Nigeria, respected in Africa
and in the West, and was even considered for the position of U.N.
secretary general a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he was arrested and jailed with several others on
charges of plotting a coup against Gen. Sani Abacha, whose ruinous
rule ended only with his sudden death last June. After Abacha's
successor, Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar, released Obasanjo and pledged
an end to military rule, many inside and outside Nigeria pressed
him to run for the presidency, viewing him as the only man capable
of keeping the military in check and of navigating the treacherous
ethnic and religious waters in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   So when he declared his candidacy under a scorching sun in early
November on his farm not far from Lagos, Obasanjo immediately
became the front-runner in the race for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Nigerian has a stake in the survival and prosperity of
the country,'' Obasanjo said during a news conference that day.
``This stake should be recognized. No section or group should be
made to feel disenfranchised or alienated.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as quickly, though, criticisms began to be leveled at him.
Even as he delivered that speech, Wasiuogunseye Kunle, a
20-year-old supporter, held a billboard that was a reminder that
Obasanjo, though trusted by the northern military elite, is
disliked by his own people, the Yoruba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the past be forgiven; the future is ours to conquer,''
read Kunle's sign, a reference to the fact that many Yoruba believe
that he betrayed them in 1979 by deciding a close presidential
election in favor of a northerner.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, Obasanjo's party lost the local and statewide
elections in the last two months in his districts; his party even
lost the election in the general's own ward in Otta, about 25 miles
north of Lagos. The general also suffered from the widespread
anti-military mood in the country and the perception that he was
backed by powerful generals.
</P>
<P>
   Given those negatives, Ekwueme emerged as a credible
alternative, a civilian with a clean image, a member of the
southeastern Ibo ethnic group, which has strongly supported the
People's Democratic Party.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Because of bitter disagreements, the party's leaders postponed
the primaries twice and began the weekend convention, scheduled to
start on Saturday, on Sunday evening. But by then, Obasanjo had
locked up enough votes _ more than two-thirds of the 2,500
delegates _ to win easily over Ekwueme and several other
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The All People's Party, which is strongest in the north, and the
Alliance for Democracy, which is essentially a Yoruba party of the
southwest, have also chosen southerners as their flagbearers. They
are expected to present a common presidential candidate in an
effort to challenge the People's Democratic Party, and it is likely
they will intensely court the Ibo, who had strongly backed Ekwueme.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
