<SLUG> BC-SUISSE-WARBURG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT SUISSE TO BUY WARBURG PINCUS ASSET MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Credit Suisse Group announced Monday that it would acquire
Warburg Pincus Asset Management Inc. for $650 million, a move that
allows the asset management arm of Credit Suisse to expand its
sales of mutual funds and retirement investment products in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is expected to close this summer following
regulatory approvals, allows Warburg, Pincus &AMP; Co. to focus on its
venture capital and private equity business by shedding the $22
billion asset management arm that has grown explosively during the
last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   It also continues a trend of banks and larger institutional
firms buying smaller asset managers and boutique fund companies
with strong retail distribution networks and brand recognition
among individual investors, while also giving Warburg Pincus Asset
Management more resources to compete worldwide against larger
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition basically fills in almost any missing piece
we might have had,'' said William Priest, chief executive of Credit
Suisse Asset Management in North America and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will not cause changes for shareholders in Warburg
Pincus funds, and it is not expected to lead to any layoffs because
there is little overlap between the two firms, Priest said.
</P>
<P>
   With close to $40 billion under management in the United States,
Credit Suisse Asset Management has only $12 billion in mutual
funds. In comparison, Warburg Pincus manages about $10 billion in
mutual funds. Worldwide, Credit Suisse Group manages about $680
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The two firms established a joint venture last summer with each
company using the other to help sell its products in the United
States and abroad. After several months, executives of the two
firms decided that they were a good fit and began to think about a
merger, Priest said. No other firms bid for Warburg Pincus Asset
Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all seen the powerful impact of global trends in the
financial services business,'' said Lionel Pincus, chief executive
of Warburg Pincus &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Burton Greenwald, a mutual fund industry consultant in
Philadelphia, predicts that the deal could lead Credit Suisse to
make another purchase in the United States. ``With the acquisition
of Warburg Pincus, they finally have a brand name and a
high-profile player in the marketplace. It's not big enough to make
Credit Suisse a major player in the mutual funds arena, but it
certainly gives them a respectable presence,'' Greenwald said.
``For Warburg, it takes them out of the category of being a
relatively small swimmer in a big pool up against the Putnams and
Fidelitys and Citigroups of the world. To be a global player, you
need pretty deep pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Warburg Pincus acquisition follows a string of deals that
have seen larger institutional firms acquire smaller asset managers
with well-known brand names and strong retail distribution
channels, including Mellon Bank Corp.'s acquisition of Founders
Asset Management Inc., and J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.'s purchase of a 45
percent stake in American Century Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Credit Suisse will pay $450 million
at closing and up to another $200 million over three years if
Warburg Pincus meets certain financial targets. Analysts said that
at roughly 3 percent of assets under management, the price is in
line with what similar firms have sold for recently.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Credit Suisse will also acquire a 19.9
percent stake in Warburg, Pincus &AMP; Co. for undisclosed terms. The
New York-based firm, which has more than $7 billion in private
equity investments and an additional $5 billion in uncommitted
capital, has investments in more than 100 companies, including BEA
Systems Inc. and Covad Communications Group Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
