in a series of ``town hall meetings'' aimed at reshaping the
Republican agenda and drumming up support for broad tax cuts. Trent
Lott and Michigan's top Republican politicians repeatedly call for
a 10 percent reduction in all Americans' income tax rates, while
accusing Democrats of wanting to spend more of taxpayers' money and
to enact more limited tax cuts with narrowly targeted benefits. By
Keith Bradsher. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.) 1,300 words.
