<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SOME UNFINISHED BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The system worked, we are told. Yes, our stable country
and its constitutional institutions handled a year of political
stress as few societies could.
</P>
<P>
   But before we smother in self-congratulation, we should face a
reality. The Clinton saga has left the system wounded. The
presidency, the office on which we stake so much, is newly
vulnerable. Bill Clinton's successors will be at risk unless the
wounds are healed.
</P>
<P>
   The first necessity is to protect future presidents from private
civil lawsuits while they are in office. That is, we must correct
the folly of the Supreme Court's 1997 decision in the Paula Jones
case.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones' damage claim, the unanimous court said, would be
``highly unlikely to occupy any substantial amount'' of Clinton's
time. Only judges with no experience of modern litigation, with its
consuming discovery process, could have said that. The Jones
lawsuit led to events that dominated the president's life, and
ours, for a year.
</P>
<P>
   It does not matter whether one believes Ms. Jones' story that
Clinton as governor of Arkansas propositioned her. She adduced no
evidence of damage, the trial judge found, except that she got no
flowers on Secretary's Day. But her lawsuit had large resources
behind it, provided by conservative organizations.
</P>
<P>
   What an inviting way to harass any future president: Find a
plaintiff, pour money into the case, demand that the president be
deposed. Hardly any politician, or any human being, is so perfect
that some long-ago excuse for suing him or her cannot be found.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is unlikely to admit its mistake. But Congress
could pass a statute providing that any private civil action
against the president be suspended until he or she leaves office.
That may be impossible to pass while Bill Clinton is there,
feelings being what they are. But I think Congress may well act to
protect the next president.
</P>
<P>
   The other great injury of the last year has been to a
president's confidential relationships. All of us expect to be able
to talk with friends and colleagues in confidence. It is hard to
imagine living with the sense that anything you said might be found
out by a relentless prosecutor. But that is where Kenneth Starr's
pursuit of Clinton has left the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Starr succeeded in piercing the lawyer-client privilege,
recognized by courts for centuries as a way of assuring people that
they can talk freely in confidence to their lawyers. He argued
successfully that White House counsel, because they are government
employees, could not resist his demand for testimony about what the
president had said to them.
</P>
<P>
   If that precedent sticks, any future president would be well
advised to retain a private lawyer from the day he takes office.
Who knows when he will need to talk, with the bark off, about some
political lawsuit or other trouble?
</P>
<P>
   Presidents have to talk in confidence not only to lawyers in the
White House but to other staff members. Some of them were
questioned by Starr's prosecutors, too. Courts rejected their
claims of executive privilege _ rightly, but the precedent
introduces a new strain in the work of the White House staff.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Secret Service. Starr demanded that members of
the detail that protects the president testify about what they saw
and heard while on duty. He won in the courts, but at what cost to
the stress on a president? Former President Bush, among others,
said it was a bad idea to force the agents to testify.
</P>
<P>
   All the intrusions on the privacy of discussion in the White
House were justified by Starr as essential to obtain vital evidence
of serious crimes. Did the forced testimony of White House aides
and Secret Service agents actually produce anything of
significance? Not that I know of.
</P>
<P>
   In Shakespeare's ``Henry V,'' the king muses before the battle
of Agincourt about how his people look to him for everything.
``Upon the king!'' he says, ``Let us our lives, our souls, our
debts, our careful wives, our children and our sins lay on the
king!''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes we seem to treat the modern presidency that way,
expecting the president to solve everything. It is a job to daunt
the best of human beings, and it should not have to bear extra
burdens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
