<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HO-CHI-MINH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAMESE IMMIGRANTS PROTEST HANGING OF HO CHI MINH POSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTMINSTER, Calif. _ In an increasingly tense standoff here
between the First Amendment and memories of war, hundreds of
Vietnamese immigrants on Monday blocked the entrance of a video
store where the owner wanted to re-hang a poster of Ho Chi Minh.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of police officers, wearing riot helmets and carrying
batons and plastic shields, stood in a long line of silence as the
protesters, saying they would rather die than allow the poster to
go up, shouted ``Democracy'' and ``Freedom.'' Fearing that the
demonstration might turn violent, the police persuaded the shop
owner, Troung Van Tran, 37, who is also a Vietnamese immigrant,
into staying away from the store Monday. But Tran's wife, Kim, said
in a brief telephone interview, ``we're going to do it another
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Tran's First Amendment right to hang the poster of
the former North Vietnamese president and a Vietnamese flag was
affirmed by an Orange County Superior Court judge, who last month
ordered the items taken down, pending a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Tran, who came to the United States from his native Vietnam in
1980, put up the poster and the flag on Jan. 18, to, he says,
generate dialogue and healing within the Vietnamese immigrant
community. But as word quickly spread that he had put the poster up
in his tiny video shop in a strip mall here, hundreds of his former
countrymen and their families rallied in front of his store,
Hi-Tek, demanding that the picture be taken down.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, as many as 600 demonstrators, many waving tiny orange
and yellow flags of South Vietnam, began gathering at the store
well before 9 a.m. Tran had said he would reopen his shop at 10
a.m., but he never showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Donny Tran, who is not related to the shop owner, arrived the
night before and slept in a homemade replica of a cage used to hold
prisoners of war in Vietnam. ``We forgot about the communist,''
Tran said, ``then he put up his flag and I remember my nightmare, I
remember how my father die.''
</P>
<P>
   At Hi-Tek's entrance, a group of about 20 women and small
children sat on the ground, waving flags and vowing not to move.
``These ladies,'' one of them said, ``say they will die here if
they have to. They risked their lives to be here in this country,
so this is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Lt. Bill Lewis said the authorities were negotiating with
the protesters and with Tran about how to proceed in the coming
days since both sides say they will not give up. ``The bottom line
is,'' Lewis said, ``that we have to maintain the peace and Mr.
Tran's First Amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Several protesters said they cherished freedom of speech, but
that Tran was abusing it. ``He doesn't know how to use his rights
wisely,'' a speaker bellowed through a public address system, ``so
he doesn't deserve to have any rights at all.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-AGENDA-850&AMP;ADD     02-15 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-AGENDA-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERATE REPUBLICANS VOW TO BE HEARD IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Conn., Wis., Minn., N.J., Ind. ) (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Since Republicans won control of Congress in 1994,
the party's conservative leaders have treated Republican moderates
like poor cousins _ patiently tolerated but frequently ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Now these moderates, concerned that impeachment has tarnished
their party, and them, are vowing to play a more forceful role in
Congress this year, demanding that the party take pragmatic stands
on issues like abortion, education, taxes and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People perceived as the most dogmatic, I mean conservative,
are opening their minds to us out of necessity,'' said Rep. Brian
P. Bilbray, a moderate Republican from San Diego. ``They realize
their agenda is not going to move without us.''
</P>
<P>
   Moderates have made pronouncements like that in the past, only
to buckle under pressure from conservatives. But they contend their
hand is stronger this year for several reasons. One is the election
of Rep. Dennis J. Hastert, R-Ill., widely viewed as a pragmatist,
as House speaker. Another is the Republicans' slim five-vote
majority in the House, which will require the leadership to woo
moderate Republicans, or conservative Democrats, to pass
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather we had a larger majority, but for the short term,
it helps us,'' said Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y., who often votes with
the moderates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Republicans of all stripes are saying that the
party must prove it is about more than impeachment. That will
require moving toward the center and passing substantive
legislation on health care, education and taxes, the moderates
contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, Republicans aren't terribly popular in many
parts of the country,'' said Rep. Jim Ramstad, R-Minn., who
represents the moderates in House leadership meetings.
``Impeachment has exacerbated that problem. The pressure is on the
Republican Congress to produce, no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David M. McIntosh, a leading Republican conservative from
Indiana, agreed that conservatives see a need to talk more with
moderates. ``On the social issues, there are big differences of
opinions,'' he said. ``But people understand that when you have a
narrow margin, you can't have everything you want, so let's work
through those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But the limits of the moderates' influence were made clear last
week when the House leadership won passage of a bill that would
make it easier to kill legislation that is considered expensive to
business, typically environmental or health and safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   Republican moderates, who mustered 34 votes against the measure,
were angry that the leadership had chosen that bill to be one of
the first passed by the House this year. ``It sets the wrong
tone,'' said a top aide to one moderate Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the first weeks of the 106th Congress, the moderates
in both houses have asserted themselves on several major issues.
Most prominently, all five Republican senators who voted against
both articles of impeachment last week were moderates from the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact of the moderates is more likely to be felt in the
House, which has been the more polarized and partisan chamber in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of House Republicans two weeks ago, for instance,
moderates insisted that there be fewer floor fights over abortion.
Such battles blocked passage of budget bills last year and,
moderates say, made the Republicans look like ideologues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody agrees there are legitimate differences in the
conference over abortion,'' said Rep. Nancy L. Johnson, a moderate
Republican from Connecticut. ``But you don't have to have them come
to the floor 45 times. There was agreement on that.''
</P>
<P>
   House conservatives said they have agreed to limit votes on
anti-abortion bills this year, though they plan to push for
legislation banning a procedure they call partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   House moderates, led by Ms. Johnson, are also pushing an
alternative to a 10 percent across-the-board tax cut proposed by
House conservatives. The moderates argue that the 10 percent plan
will favor the wealthy and reduce revenues that could be used to
shore up the Social Security and Medicare programs.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates are calling for smaller, more specific cuts, and
many Republicans say they may have won enough support to block the
10 percent plan.
</P>
<P>
   Moderates say they have also won assurances from the leadership
that the party's education agenda will include initiatives for
public schools, and not just for private education. One moderate
proposal calls for increasing federal aid to programs for disabled
students.
</P>
<P>
   And moderates say they expect the leadership to allow fewer
votes on bills intended to roll back environmental protections, an
issue that perennially divides moderate and conservative
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Ideology is part of what is motivating the moderates to assert
themselves. But so is self-preservation. ``You can't look at the
current numbers and be calm,'' said Rep. Amo Houghton, a Republican
moderate from Corning, N.Y., referring to the Republicans' low
approval ratings in many polls. ``Fear rather than love is the
greatest motivator there is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many moderates contend that the Republicans who are most likely
to suffer political damage from the impeachment ordeal are not
those from conservative districts but rather those from moderate
swing districts _ like Bilbray in California, Michael P. Forbes
from Long Island and Bob Franks from Union, N.J. Several moderate
Republican senators from the Northeast are also considered
vulnerable by strategists in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing about impeachment is that the true
believers on impeachment come from districts where they will not
pay any price for their strong feelings,'' said Steve Gunderson, a
former congressman from Wisconsin who is now executive director of
the Main Street Partnership, a policy group for moderate
Republicans. ``The people who will pay the price are those in
moderate districts, no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews last week, conservatives and moderates said there
was general agreement between both wings of the party to find
common ground on major issues so that Republicans would have a list
of achievements to show voters in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share many of the conservatives' views on having smaller
government and more individual freedom,'' said Rep. Christopher
Shays, a moderate Republican from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats, and some Republicans, questioned whether the
moderates would be willing to buck their leadership on major
issues. Last year, many moderate House Republicans were clearly
uncomfortable with impeachment, but in the end, only five voted
against it.
</P>
<P>
   One of those five, King, asserted that pro-impeachment
conservatives tried, unsuccessfully, to prevent him from getting
the chairmanship of a subcommittee this year. King said that if the
party did not put the impeachment wars behind it, Republicans would
lose in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to show we are a national governing party,'' he said,
``not a regional party, not a party of hit men.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
