A6130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN16-COX     02-15 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Washington may be in denial
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The very same prophets who this time last year pronounced Bill
Clinton a goner have spent the last few days analyzing what will
come in the aftermath of his acquittal. They see a future
comforting to their own bruised sense of worth.
</P>
<P>
   Moral decline in the country at large is forecast to accelerate
due to the bad example set by the president _ suitable punishment
for a nation that ignored the prophets last year. Washington,
meanwhile, is seen as returning to the same smug neighborhood it
was before that troublesome Clinton couple moved in.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that public disgust with the impeachment year might
generate a big turnover in the next congressional elections is
being discounted both by Republican strategists, who have reason to
hope it won't be so, and Democrats, who want to hedge their bets.
</P>
<P>
   All these predictions have the classic earmarks of capital
self-denial. Within the Beltway it is hard to see this or admit it,
but the most obvious impact of the impeachment year is the profound
toll it has taken on the prestige of Washington itself.
</P>
<P>
   The nation flatly refused to follow the lead of the capital at
the onset of the Monica Lewinsky scandal and stampede Clinton out
of office, and most Americans appear to feel no worse now for
having done so. They will be that much less likely to take their
cue from Washington when the next big question comes up.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the president's self-absorbed dalliance, and the
obsessive effort to run him out of office over it, have testified
more eloquently than the collected works of Newt Gingrich to how
superfluous Washington has become. If it can take a year off for
this, Washington really isn't as big a deal as it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   What the Georgia General Assembly does about health care,
transportation and taxes will have a more immediate impact on the
lives of most Georgians than what Congress will accomplish this
year, hands down. Washington still doles out a lot of money, but
you don't need 24-hour cable to cover that.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Washington the question is always whether an outcome
hurts one party or the other. This one hurts both.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome in the next election, Democrats and
Republicans come away from the impeachment year more vulnerable to
decline in their ranks and to competition from newer, more vigorous
movements.
</P>
<P>
   One unforeseen outcome of the impeachment year may be to sharpen
regional rivalries. This wasn't seen as a sectional battle in the
South or Midwest. But many in the Northeast saw it as an attempt by
Southern Bible-thumpers to take over the government. Underneath
that simplistic attitude lies considerable resentment toward the
Sun Belt's increasing political power, and it may point toward more
friction in the future.
</P>
<P>
   It's an easy bet to predict moral decline, but at the end of
this impeachment saga, some words should be said in defense of the
oft-maligned American public.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to many representations, many Americans held passionate
opinions over the past year, which they expressed in an avalanche
of e-mail, letters and calls to Capitol Hill and their local
newspapers. In the vast majority of cases, they have spoken calmly
and acted civilly toward those they disagreed with. There was no
national ``Jerry Springer Show'' over this.
</P>
<P>
   The overall concern for most Americans was the good of the
country at large and the integrity of its institutions, whatever
their partisan leanings.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the citizens of this country have acted with more
caution, judgment and maturity than their leaders in Washington.
Maybe they're not declining so fast after all.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
