<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERSHOW-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fundraising for Salt Lake Olympics takes off at Super Show
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A year ago, Gary Johnson sat in a booth at the Super
Show in Atlanta and quickly settled into the routine of spitting
out the same answer to a common trivia question. The Nagano
Olympics were going on, and most of the 100,000 people attending
the world's largest sporting-goods trade show didn't have a clue
where the next Winter Games was.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me see _ how can I say this?'' asked Johnson, the manager
of advertising and promotions for the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee. ``On the one hand, you couldn't have bought that kind of
publicity, but it's with negative overtones, so that's not been
good. But I no longer have to approach people and tell them the
Games are in Salt Lake. They already know.''
</P>
<P>
   He and the other smiling staff members at the spiffy wood-frame
display in the middle of the Georgia Dome on Monday handed out
press releases about their new leader Mitt Romney, recruited after
a scandal that found that SLOC officials had made secret payments
and lavished gifts on International Olympic Committee members.
</P>
<P>
   Romney was hired Thursday, the day before the marketing staff
began lobbying sporting-goods makers to put the bright
blue-orange-and-yellow snowflake motif on apparel and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who's stopped by our booth, the licensees included,
really seem to understand the situation,'' Johnson said. ``And
they're sincere in their discussions that we have taken care of the
problem and taken the high road, and we're moving this along. They
understand there are bumps in the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake aims to raise about 4 percent of its $1.45 billion
budget _ roughly $51 million dollars _ from the sales of licensed
products. In Atlanta, that meant T-shirts and baseball hats. In
Utah, it means limited-edition skis and snowboards, fleece vests
and $1,500 leather jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technical outerwear'' is the industry jargon for the
heavy-duty apparel, but it's done with a twist. Native American
imagery is a recurring theme. Heavy knitted sweaters are fables in
wool, with symbols of seagulls, sego lillies and mountains that
hearken to local legends.
</P>
<P>
   This marketing effort employs a good bit more subtlety, a word
not often used to describe most of the flashy merchandise that
still can be found on Atlanta sales racks. Anderson pointed out a
silk tie with pictograms similar to the ancient paintings found in
caves in southern Utah. The 2002 logo can't be detected unless you
look closely.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the biggest difference from 1996 will be the Salt Lake
mascot, unveiled later this spring. It won't be another Whatizit,
Anderson promised. The mascot ``will be very unique, driven by the
contrast between our mountains and deserts,'' he said. ``The story
around it will be inherent to our part of the country, so it
completely makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Hiskey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
