<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6138 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEMETERY-ROBBERIES-2T     02-15 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEMETERY-ROBBERIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW ORLEANS `CITIES OF THE DEAD,' ANTIQUE CEMETERY ART IS
DISAPPEARING
</HEADLINE>
  (fe) 
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ On an atmospherically moody day, with rain
dripping off the muscadine vines and a concerto by Respighi wafting
through the living room, Peter Patout, an antiques dealer, was
cosseted in the splendor of his Bourbon Street home. There amid
Paris porcelain and ancestral oils in gilt frames, he gave his
version of the insidious crime that has made him one of the most
talked-about men in the city: conspiring to steal cemetery
ornaments from hallowed tombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thieves are in jail,'' said Patout, a descendant of sugar
planters, who is currently out on bail. ``I've been arrested four
times. Would you like some Patout sugar in your coffee?''
</P>
<P>
   Around New Orleans, there is the smell of a rat amid the scent
of sweet olive. It was in Patout's secluded courtyard, lush with
banana trees of deep Louisiana lineage, that detectives seized two
funerary statues, including a $50,000 marble Madonna. The New
Orleans police say they were part of a cache of more than 200 _ and
counting _ romantically patinated urns, angels and Blessed Mothers
plundered by thieves last year from the above-ground marble tombs
and granite sarcophagi that populate New Orlean's legendary
``cities of the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, which started small, with four arrests in
April, has implicated respected antiques dealers who police say
were operating a ring that stole cemetery artifacts to sell to
passionate collectors who pay thousands of dollars for moss-covered
garden ornaments and benches with evocative rust. The police have
recovered statuary valued at more than $1 million, and they say
that is only one-tenth of the booty. The Federal Bureau of
Investigation has entered the case, which has moved on to Los
Angeles and may soon include New York.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this Gothic-appreciative city, where gossip unfolds like
drapery and Anne Rice is a tourist industry, the dark specter of
grave robbers cruising the city's historic cemeteries with hammers
and chisels has sent a shudder through the town.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans, that liveliest of cities, holds its 31 historic
graveyards dear. It is a place where a literary journal is named
Exquisite Corpse, where tombs have their own audio tours and a bus
stop is named Cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   The thefts tap into two New Orleans obsessions: antiquities and
ancestor-worship. ``The dead are not forgotten in New Orleans,''
said Randolph Delehanty, director of the University of New Orleans
Ogden Museum of Art and a co-author of ``New Orleans: Elegance and
Decadence'' (Chronicle Books, 1993). ``Other places in America have
made death an antiseptic phenomenon. But among New Orleans families
tombs have primitive power.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the prominent victims were the restaurateur Ted Brennan,
who lost a Mother Cabrini statue commissioned by his mother for his
father's tomb, and Lucille Prima, a relative of the jazz legend
Louis Prima. But the sense of outrage is widely felt. Cherished
French and Italian marble sculptures were pried off tombs that
resemble elegant funerary mansions, expressions of the unique New
Orleans way of death. For more than 200 years the dearly departed
have been interred above ground to keep them from floating away
with the waterlogged soil, successive generations pushing old bones
to the back of the tomb to make way for new ones.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   From humble brick tombs sprouting ferns to extravagant Victorian
shrines set in formal landscapes, death wears a beautiful face
here. The novelist Walker Percy wrote lovingly of St. Louis No. 1,
the city's oldest cemetery, its ``tiny lanes as crooked as old
Jerusalem, meandering aimlessly between the cottages of the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   On a mild February morning, Rosemary Garcia Sanders, 46, was
replenishing the artificial flowers on her family's tomb at nearby
St. Louis No. 2. ``It's just unbelievable that someone would rob
from the dead,'' she said. On every All Saints Day, Nov. 1, like
many New Orleanians, her family gathers to sweep and whitewash the
tomb, which is topped by a sculpture of the Blessed Mother. She
hollers hello to it every time she drives by on the Interstate.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Along Royal Street and Magazine Street, the fabled antiques
thoroughfares where many stolen ornaments were seized in police
raids, Mardi Gras beads cannot disguise a paranoid mood. Dealers
say that kneeling crying angels are out, cavorting Bacchuses are
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it would have been, `Isn't this pretty?''' said
Stephen A. Moses, president of Neal Auction Co., referring to the
large urns, in exquisite decay, that occasionally cross his
threshold. ``Now it's, `I wonder if it's been stolen.'''
</P>
<P>
   The theft ring, whose moves have been chronicled in detail by
the local news media, began to unravel a year ago when a
groundskeeper at Lake Lawn Metairie Cemetery spotted a van moving
slowly from tomb to tomb. He took down the license plate number.
The van sped away, leaving a tall marble angel awry on its
pedestal. The van's owner was eventually arrested and later gave up
three accomplices.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, Tom Bate, a New Orleans-born contractor
living in Los Angeles, noticed what appeared to be gates, urns and
iron crosses from New Orleans cemeteries popping up with exorbitant
price tags in chic West Hollywood shops. It outraged Bate, who grew
up taking walks with his grandfather in Lafayette cemetery. ``It
kind of killed me,'' he said. ``This was our history being sold at
a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   His New Orleans friend Patty Lee St. Martin alerted the police
and together they started the National Cemetery Conservation
Foundation, the city's third preservation group dedicated to the
funerary cause. The pair lobbies dealers and their high-end
clientele to prevent ``cemetery chic.''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Frederick Morton said the four original ``baseline
thieves'' started snatching urns for heroin money but eventually
graduated to more lucrative loot. They led Morton and his partner,
Detective Lawrence Green, to four antiques dealers, including
Patout, who were subsequently arrested on charges that included
obstruction of justice and possession of stolen property. Formal
charges, if any, are on hold for all suspects pending the outcome
of the investigation, according to Zully Jimenez, a spokeswoman for
the Orleans Parish district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL GRAF)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think antiquity led to infatuation,'' said Green, who
usually analyzes blood splatters but whose office is now strewn
with copies of Garden Design magazine and The Newtown Bee, an
antiques weekly. ``These sculptures were forbidden treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL GRAF)
</P>
<P>
   Detectives say the dealers gave the thieves art-history
tutorials. The more detailed the artistry, the more the statues
were worth, Morton said. ``They told them to look for the
through-and-throughs'' _ the chiseled spaces between fingers _
``and eyes with pupils.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Prima's family tomb at Lake Lawn Metairie was stripped
of two angels, one carrying a cascade of roses. Of the
upper-echelon dealers who were arrested, she said, ``They are the
very ones I was admiring for preserving the heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roy P. Boucvalt, an anesthesiologist, was arrested after
police seized more than $43,000 in stolen cemetery artifacts at
Boucvalt House, his 150-year-old Greek Revival landmark home. His
lawyer, Kendall P. Green, said the delay in filing formal charges
``is unusual and I suspect it's because they can't find any
evidence to support the conspiracy theory.''
</P>
<P>
   The police also arrested Aaron Jarabica, co-owner of Top Drawer
Antiques and Auction on Magazine Street, who said he had no idea
the artifacts in his shop were stolen. Thieves told him they ``were
from their grandmother's estate.'' Lieut. Jeff Winn, who is leading
the investigation, said such an estate ``didn't exist to our
knowledge, but if it did, the place would look like a Roman
coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   Also arrested was Andrew P. Antippas, owner of the Barristers
Gallery on Royal Street. In 1979, Antippas spent a year in jail
after pleading guilty to stealing five rare maps from Yale
University. Since then his pursuits have included the sale of
Haitian and outsider art _ including the work of serial killers. He
acknowledged being ``guilty of being stupid'' for not having known
the origin of two wire cemetery benches found in his home. Police
were shocked to find a self-portrait by John Wayne Gacy hanging
there too. ``It was an investment, not a sign of my depravity,''
Antippas said.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Patout, whose shop and home have been featured in
the magazines House Beautiful and Vogue, publicly proclaimed his
innocence at the tomb of his ancestors at St. Louis No. 3. One of
Patout's arrests came after police got a call from a citizen who
recognized Ms. Prima's angel as one he had bought at Patout's shop.
``Basically, I bought some things that turned out to be stolen,''
Patout said recently, sitting in a mahogany lyre-backed chair. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thieving for profit is hardly unique to New Orleans.
``Cemeteries are a treasure-trove for those larcenous of mind, ''
said John W. Keefe, the decorative arts curator at the New Orleans
Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, seven iron gates were stolen from the historic Mount
Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge, Mass., but were recovered, largely
because they were well-documented with telltale iconography,
including weeping willows, said Meg Winslow, the cemetery's
curator.
</P>
<P>
   At the Forest Hills cemetery in Roxbury, Mass., where E.E.
Cummings and Eugene O'Neill are buried, the theft of a bronze
bas-relief inspired cemetery owners to organize an art-theft
committee for New England, a part of the country where owners have
avoided reporting theft for fear of copycat crimes and the
perception of negligence.
</P>
<P>
   In the rural South, a booming collectors' market for folk
pottery has made remote African-American burial grounds
particularly vulnerable. Decorative pottery, used as grave markers,
now fetches thousands of dollars. Dr. John Burrison, a curator at
the Atlanta History Center, said, ``I'm cautious about giving
specific locations when I lecture on cemetery traditions, because I
know a few people in the audience will capitalize on the
information.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, the City Council recently set up a task force on
cemetery theft. But that may not stop the national compulsion to
transform one's house and backyard into Hadrian's villa.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Charbonnet, a New York decorator and native New Orleanian
whose clients include Michael J. Fox and his wife, Tracy Pollan,
has seen cemetery art at the 26th Street Flea Market in Manhattan.
Its presence in Los Angeles does not surprise him, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have one city seeped in the miasma of its own culture, and
another city with none,'' he said. ``You pull up a pot and a cross
and place it in an L.A. loft with some overstuffed Edwardian
furniture, and someone decides to call it neo-Gothic. But in New
Orleans, the Gothic is real.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 1948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
