<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-BAIL-DENY-COX     02-15 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-BAIL-DENY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio bill would deny bail to certain crimes; House to hear
victim testimony
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When appeals court judges reduced the bond for
the man who had attacked her, Michelle Freeze feared the assailant
would get out of jail and come after her again.
</P>
<P>
   When he posted bond and shot another woman before killing
himself a year ago in Clayton, Freeze thought her troubles were
over.
</P>
<P>
   She is going to relive them today, however, in testimony before
the Ohio House criminal justice committee in support of a bill that
would enable judges to deny a criminal defendant bail when the
victim might be at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The change was approved by a statewide vote in 1997, but Ohio
lawmakers have yet to set the guidelines for the bail denial and
have kept it from taking effect.
</P>
<P>
   A bill setting those guidelines has passed the Ohio Senate this
year and is expected to pass quickly through the House.
</P>
<P>
   Freeze said it is overdue because the rights of victims have
been left out of court proceedings for too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are going to have a violent past, they pretty much
are going to have a violent present and a violent future,'' Freeze
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Her former boyfriend, Jeffrey Scott Blair, attacked her in June
1997 in what his attorney later said was a steroid-induced rage.
She needed 200 stitches to repair the knife wounds to her face and
neck.
</P>
<P>
   Blair posted his bond of $500,000 and was released. Police
arrested Blair again in July 1997 after he ate lunch in a
restaurant in a downtown Dayton building where Freeze worked.
Prosecutors charged him with stalking, and Common Pleas Judge
Barbara Gorman increased Blair's bond to $1 million. The Ohio 2nd
District Court of Appeals reduced it, ruling it was
unconstitutionally high.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio law at the time required judges to set bail based only on
whether a defendant was likely to return for court dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had the bond been to protect the victim, one person wouldn't
have been shot and he probably wouldn't be dead,'' Freeze said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Jeff Jacobson (R-Phillipsburg) introduced the bill
and expects it to pass the House quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am comfortable with the bill as it is,'' Jacobson said. ``It
is constitutional and it's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow bail to be denied to defendants charged
with aggravated murder, murder, a felony of the first or second
degree, aggravated vehicular homicide or a fourth-degree felony of
driving under the influence of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Some Senate Democrats, including Sen. Rhine McLin (D-Dayton)
voted against the bill because they said it was unnecessary since
judges still could set high bonds for dangerous offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
