<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hairless tradition shaved for Reds
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Just when the Cincinnati Reds should be
stepping into the 21st century, they instead have decided to join
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The hairy issue involving the team's new slugger, goatee-waering
Greg Vaughn, was resolved on Monday. For the first time since 1966,
facial hair is permitted _ beards, mustaches, long sideburns. .
.any hirsute adornments.
</P>
<P>
   One day before the official opening of spring training, the club
announced the elimination of its no-facial hair policy, instituted
in 1967 by former general manager/club president Bob Howsam.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, one certain way to get traded was to challenge the
no-facial hair policy, which outfielder Bobby Tolan did in 1973 and
pitcher Jim Kern did in 1982. Both were traded.
</P>
<P>
   Players were not required to report Monday, but some who did
showed up wearing beards, mustaches or both, expecting a required
visit with a razor to the shower room.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Dmitri Young and infielder Pokey Reese walked into
the clubhouse with short goatees and mustaches and were ecstatic
with the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some ugly people without facial hair,'' Young said,
rubbing his goatee. ``And I'm one of them. But this is going to be
fun, fun, fun. The new-look Reds. . .nice new uniforms, facial
hair, new players. I like the attention we're getting. Last year,
we were written off because a few pieces were missing. Now we have
them in guys like Denny Neagle, Steve Avery and Greg Vaughn. Vaughn
will take the pressure off us guys under 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``My facial hair? Yeah, I'm going to keep it,'' Young added.
``It's a doggone shame some guys had to come through Cincinnati,
guys known for their beards and mustaches _ like pitcher Jeff
Reardon _ and shave it all off.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Reese, who gets a try at winning the second base job left
vacant when Bret Boone was traded, ``See what one man can do? A lot
of things might change.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese referred to Vaughn, who put the issue on the front burner
after the Reds obtained him via trade with San Diego by pleading
with the media to get the policy changed, ``Because I have two kids
who have never seen their daddy without a goatee. . .they wouldn't
recognize me.''
</P>
<P>
   As he talked, Reese fingered a pair of diamond ear rings in his
lobes. Those are still a no-no, but Reese said, ``I guess we can't
go that far, but who knows, if Greg wants to wear 'em. . .''
</P>
<P>
   The lifting of the ban doesn't faze fuzzy-cheeked pitcher Danny
Graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take me 10 years to grow one, and then you wouldn't
notice anything but a few stray hairs. Maybe when I reach
puberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jason Bere says to grow or not to grow depends on how he
is pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superstition, y'know?'' he said. ``I'll start without one, but
if I'm not going good I might grow a beard to change my luck.''
</P>
<P>
   New catcher Brian Johnson walked into camp with a bald head,
something he started doing as a rookie five years ago. But he had a
small goatee and a pencil-thin mustache.
</P>
<P>
   When he heard the news, he said, ``Oh, good. I was wondering if
I should try to keep this or not. Now it is no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no issue for pitcher Steve Parris, who said, ``I'm not
into beards or hair on the face. It feels bad on my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jack McKeon wore a bushy mustache when he managed in
Oakland and San Diego, but plans to keep a clean upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me grow a mustache? No, no,'' he said. ``This just makes it a
little easier, one less thing to worry about. Now the players can
do what they want to do, do their thing. I'm only interested in how
they play. We all have our different views and you change with the
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the times changed 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While CEO Marge Schott is taking bows for changing policy, the
truth is that any player could have taken the club's stance to
arbitration and/or litigation and won a verdict. The Reds were
fortunate that no player challenged the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
