<SLUG> BC-VOLVO-NAVISTAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLVO GOES SHOPPING STATESIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ill.)  (jw) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Volvo AB, the Swedish automaker that agreed last month to sell
its car division to Ford Motor Co. for $6.45 billion, has again
turned its attention to the United States. But this time, the
company is interested in being the buyer, and the property it is
looking for is a truck manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Junior-level executives from Volvo have held discussions with
counterparts at the Navistar International Corp., the Chicago-based
maker of heavy trucks, school buses, diesel engines and service
parts, people close to the talks said. But those talks, which were
first reported in The Financial Times of London, are still
preliminary and, according to one person, have not included any
high-level negotiating between the chief executives of the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Navistar, the person said, is not yet sold on being taken over
or even selling part of its operations to Volvo. Volvo, the world's
second-largest maker of heavy trucks, is interested in other
American properties, as well, and also continues to explore
opportunities in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Volvo bought a 13 percent stake in Scania AB, a
Swedish rival in the truck industry, and it has said it was
interested in buying the rest of the company as well. If Volvo did
acquire all of Scania, the newly combined company would become the
largest manufacturer of heavy trucks in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Any acquisition by Volvo in the truck sector would give it a
market in which to compete more powerfully against major
competitors, including DaimlerChrysler. That was something Volvo
was not able to do in the car sector despite its well-respected
brand name. And Volvo can afford to buy market share now that the
sale to Ford is expected to leave it with a full pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   Navistar, with a market value of $2.3 billion, was formerly
known as International Harvester and was a maker of agriculture
machinery. The company set up its first overseas factory in 1905 in
Sweden. But it fell on hard times in 1980 when a recession and a
six-month strike by the United Auto Workers hurt earnings and
nearly forced it into bankruptcy. In 1985, the company sold its
name and its agricultural equipment business to Tenneco Inc. A year
later, it was renamed Navistar International, specializing in heavy
truck and engine manufacturing. Shares in Navistar shot up $2 on
Friday, to close at $35.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
