<SLUG> BC-MEAD-MCLACHLAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Fisher-Price VP picked to head Mead division
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Mead Corp. on Monday named a former toy executive
to run its school and office products division, company officials
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Neil A. McLachlan, who was senior vice president-international
for Fisher-Price, a subsidiary of toy maker Mattel Inc., will take
over the Mead job March 1. He replaces Patricia B. Robinson, who
left Mead Sept. 30 after 21 years with the paper maker to pursue
personal interests, Mead officials said.
</P>
<P>
   McLachlan will be taking over a division that suffered a 25
percent decline in earnings for 1998. The division earned $42.8
million last year versus $57.3 million for 1997. Sales for the
division fell 7 percent in 1998 to $482.4 million from $516.2
million in 1997. Retailers have been buying products from foreign
suppliers and paper sales overall have been slumping, said Mead
spokesman Doug Draper.
</P>
<P>
   Mead's school and office products division operates eight
manufacturing plans in North America that make spiral and wireless
notebooks and other items. The division recently branched out to
selling day planners, backpacks, laptop bags, folders, stationary
and other material.
</P>
<P>
   McLachlan, 42, spent the last 17 years with Fisher Price in
various marketing positions. In his most recent job, McLachlan was
responsible for the development of Mattel's infant and preschool
business around the world. He also was senior vice president for
toys and children's products for Fisher Price and general manager
of Fisher-Price Canada.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to be interviewed. McLachlan holds a bachelor's
degree in marketing from Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton-based Mead is a $3.8 billion paper company that makes
clay coated paper for catalogs, paper for beverage containers,
colored paper for flooring, and office paper.
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
