<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: THE INSIDE EDGE IN INTERNET STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic on Active Apparel Group stock is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Christmas, shares of Active Apparel Group, a clothing
wholesaler, were swept up in the market enthusiasm for retailers
doing business on the Internet. Active Apparel promoted its
Internet debut in a news release and on CNBC, and though the
company had not yet sold any goods in cyberspace _ indeed, its Web
site was not up and running when the first release went out _
investors bid up the stock as high as $25, from $1.25 on Christmas
Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several officers and directors took advantage of the
stock's surge to sell close to $1 million of their shares.
</P>
<P>
   After those sales, the price of Active Apparel shares quickly
fell back into the single digits. On Friday, they closed at
$4.6875, meaning investors who still own shares bought during the
frenzied days of late December have big losses.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Active Apparel nor the insiders who sold have been
accused of any wrongdoing. But for the buyers of those shares, it
was a painful lesson, and not an isolated one. Outside investors do
not always fare as well as insiders when companies advance on
Internet euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   The tide that has lifted Internet stocks the last few months has
brought with it plenty of flotsam _ companies with only the most
tenuous connections to the Internet but whose shares were bid up as
if they were the next Yahoo or Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Now as the tide recedes and even the biggest Internet stocks
fall sharply from their highs, some investors find themselves with
the equivalent of driftwood _ stocks in companies whose insiders
have bailed out at higher prices and in companies whose promoters
issued ``research reports'' because they were paid to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, insiders of companies that issue new stock to the
public agree not to sell for a ``lock-up'' period of up to six
months. But companies that are already publicly traded and that
suddenly announce an Internet plan are not under the same
restrictions. That makes investors particularly vulnerable to a
downdraft caused by insider selling.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has taken action against
some companies and promoters that have not fully disclosed their
practices, and regulators are warning investors to proceed with
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``More companies, legitimate and illegitimate, seem to be
getting onto the Internet every day,'' said Chris Ullman, an SEC
spokesman. ``Technological developments have made it so that it
doesn't take much to set up a Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the newly christened Internet companies, of course, may
bounce back from recent stock declines. Active Apparel, for
example, now has a fully operating Web site. Its stock, which had
been threatened with delisting from Nasdaq's biggest market when
its market value fell below Nasdaq's requirements, is trading on
Nasdaq's smaller, less prestigious small-cap market.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Marbach, an outside spokesman for the company, said that
the recent stock sales by insiders are no reflection on the
company's prospects. In most cases, the sales represented only a
small portion of their total holdings, Marbach said, and some
insiders have bought stock the last year in addition to exercising
options and selling stock.
</P>
<P>
   Those explanations are not likely to comfort individuals who
bought Active Apparel stock at high prices when insiders were
selling, however. ``Give me hope!'' wrote one such investor, a
California woman who goes by the screen name ``Portofoy,'' on the
Yahoo message board for Active Apparel stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, folks, I bought AAGP at 22, repeat 22,'' she added,
referring to Active Apparel's stock symbol. ``Too much caffeine
that morning, I guess. Is there hope? Should I hold on? I'm hurtin'
for certain.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, timing is everything in the fast-moving, volatile
world of Internet stocks. And insiders have key advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Connect Inc., a Mountain View, Calif., company that
distributes software allowing companies to sell goods over the
Internet. On Nov. 30, as investors heard reports of the crowds
flocking to Internet shopping sites over the Thanksgiving weekend,
shares of Connect, which has since changed its name to
Connectinc.com, soared to more than $15, up from less than $2 the
previous day.
</P>
<P>
   Only weeks later, after the shares fell back into the single
digits, was it revealed that on the very day that its stock price
soared, insiders sold nearly 1.5 million shares, at prices ranging
from $5.63 to $12.44.
</P>
<P>
   Greigory Park, the company's chief financial officer, said the
sales were timed ``to take advantage of a run in the stock that was
pretty much speculation-based.'' He said the company had issued no
news to account for the sixfold increase in its stock price. ``The
run in the stock was a complete surprise to everybody here,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the company was under notice from Nasdaq that its
stock might be delisted because the company had only $1.1 million
in net tangible assets, versus the $4 million minimum Nasdaq
requires.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's efforts to raise money to put it in compliance
with the listing requirement came at a much more lumbering pace
than that insiders displayed when they were selling their own
shares in November.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Connectinc.com raised $4 million from new
institutional investors in a private sale on Jan. 20, the price was
a mere $2.60 a share. That was far less than the $6 the stock was
fetching in the open market at the time and less than half what
insiders had reaped weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Park said the company opted to sell the shares at such a
discount because it wanted to satisfy the Nasdaq listing
requirements as soon as possible. ``Yes, the institutional
investors got a better price than the average investor could have
gotten in the market, but individuals weren't being asked to come
up with one and a half million dollars each,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Park said, the company's sale of shares was
unrelated to the sale of personal holdings by insiders several
weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Because the company's stock had been publicly traded for more
than two years, its insiders were not under the same restrictions
that often govern newly public companies, like the many
Internet-related companies that have gone public in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-MARKETPLACE-     02-15 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MARKETPLACE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: recent months. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Insiders at newly public companies usually agree with their
underwriters to refrain from selling additional shares for up to
six months. That ``lock up'' period gives buyers confidence that
millions of additional shares will not flood the market, depressing
the stock's price, and that managements are in it for the long
haul.
</P>
<P>
   But once the lock-up period expires, the psychological drain can
deflate a stock, whether or not actual selling follows. Take, for
example, Broadcast.com, which feeds audio and video broadcasts over
the Internet and which went public last July, selling 2.5 million
shares. The owners of its other 14.5 million shares agreed not to
sell any of their holdings for 180 days. (The shares have since
split two-for-one.)
</P>
<P>
   Beginning late last month, two big holders and early backers of
the company, Intel and Motorola, filed to sell shares. On the days
those filings became public, Broadcast's share price fell sharply,
although it has since rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   At $68.87, it remains far above the initial offering price of
$9, after accounting for the split, but is well below the high of
$144.75 reached on Jan. 12, before the insiders registered their
shares.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing inherently wrong with insiders turning their
hard-earned shares into cash, of course. But unlike with recent
IPOs, selling by insiders at companies that have long been public
is much less transparent to the investing public.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Internet has speeded up the rhythms and cycles of
corporate life and investment, the quick rise of Internet stocks
has brought a flurry of regulatory actions against companies
promoting their alleged Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the SEC filed 23 enforcement actions against 44
individuals and companies across the country, charging that they
used the Internet to fraudulently promote the companies or their
investments.
</P>
<P>
   A particular concern of regulators has been over promoters who
are paid a fee to publicize a company's Internet connections, but
which do not disclose that fact to investors. And even when a
service discloses that it might have been paid such a fee, the
disclaimer is sometimes so far away from the stock tips that an
investor could be confused about the fee or could miss it
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   One example of that trend is the Internet Stock Review, a web
site that provides information about companies involved in
electronic commerce and other Internet-realted businesses. In
January, the Internet Stock Review published a list of ``20
companies to watch during 1999.'' The aim of the list, according to
a press release, ``is to bring attention to the names and or to the
existence of these companies (many of which have no coverage on
Wall Street),'' and then to have investors decide on their own
whether to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Several names on the list are well-known companies like Borders
Group, the bookstore chain; Fingerhut, the catalog retailer that
last week agreed to be acquired by Federated Department Stores; and
Federal Express, which delivers many of the goods bought over the
Internet. None of these companies went to any lengths to show up on
the list. But sprinkled on the list are upstarts like Aim-Smart,
which provides access to Internet shopping sites, and other small
companies like AllNetServices, Dynamic Media.com and MediaX _ all
of which have paid the owner of the Internet Stock Review to
publicize them.
</P>
<P>
   The press release notes that certain companies listed are
``client companies,'' and invites readers to read the disclaimer on
the web site. That disclaimer states that the list is not a buy
list, and notes that for services to certain companies, ``payment
at the time of engagement in each instance was valued at less than
$250,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors are not told, however, that since the report on
``companies to watch'' was issued, 1.5 million shares of Aim-Smart
restricted stock have been registered for sale by its owners,
legally the only hint public shareholders may get that a sale of
stock might be afoot.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Perry, who operates Perry &AMP; Co., the public relations
company that publishes the Internet Stock Review, says he believes
the service's disclosures about its compensation are adequate.
Perry &AMP; Co. has not been accused by the SEC of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys try to hide it,'' Perry said. ``We're proud of
what we do. We're not a buy-sell service,'' but simply one that
points investors to places to begin their own research.
</P>
<P>
   But even the SEC admits that it is becoming much harder for
investors to distinguish between the real and the unreal when it
comes to investments in Internet-related companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the messages that came out of the October sweep is that
just because something is on the Internet doesn't mean it is
legitimate,'' said Ullman of the SEC. ``Something can be the
equivalent of a boiler room but on the Internet it can look as
impressive as a Fortune 500 company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
