<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-BANKS-570&AMP;ADD-     02-15 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-BANKS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FRANCE, SECOND THOUGHTS ABOUT A BIG BANK MERGER
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Investors cheered only halfheartedly earlier this month
when Societe Generale SA announced it was paying $18 billion for
Paribas SA.
</P>
<P>
   What French banking needed above all, they argued, was to bring
down costs by thinning out an overly dense network of branches, but
these two banks had few that overlapped. And while the acquisition
brought together Societe Generale's investment banking arm with
Paribas, which has focused on that business in recent years, it
failed to create a player in the top tier of investment banks. With
little overlapping business of any kind between the two banks, they
complained, little room for cost-cutting presented itself in their
combination.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst, David Grinsztajn of Merrill Lynch in Paris, said
his valuation of Societe Generale, France's second-largest
commercial bank, alone was equal to the value he placed on the
combination of the two. ``It's above all a tactical move; it has no
strong industrial logic,'' he said of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Smith, an analyst of European banking for MFS Investment
Management in London, agreed that the deal had not created new
value. ``It is a question where one and one equals three,'' he
said, ``and it's hard to see that it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors appeared to buy that logic. At the close of trading
Monday, shares of Paribas, France's fifth-largest bank, stagnated
at 85 euros, or $96, roughly their level before the deal was
announced; Societe Generale has fared worse, closing Monday at
137.8 euros, down from 153 at the time of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   But Jean-Claude Branchereau thinks the investors may have missed
the point.
</P>
<P>
   Branchereau is a trade union leader at Societe Generale, and his
attitude typifies the unease of employees who feel the merger
speeds up a movement among French banks, glacial until now, that
could lead to greater job losses and increased insecurity _ even as
he grudgingly admits the changes may assure the banks' survival in
an increasingly competitive world. Pointing to a shuffling that
began in 1996, when Credit Agricole paid $2.3 billion to acquire
Banque Indosuez, Branchereau said, ``That was the first step; this
is an acceleration.'' And he believes the pace will not let up.
</P>
<P>
   The Socialist government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin plans
to sell its stake in Credit Lyonnais later this year, and suitors
are lining up. This week, Lucien Douroux, the chairman of Credit
Agricole, said he would be among those bidding for a stake. ``Very
informal contacts have already taken place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors may not yet agree with Branchereau's assessment, but
some analysts and experts say he is onto something. True, Daniel
Bouton, the chairman of Societe Generale, and Andre Levy-Lang, his
counterpart at Paribas, may have been in part avoiding the
distasteful task of closing bank branches, and hence cutting jobs,
when they chose each other over other potential partners. But their
banks, by combining, gain economies of scale in a European market
that is fast unifying under the impulse of the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Dermine, a professor of banking at the Insead business
school, said European banks needed two kinds of mergers,
consolidations that enable them to close branches and cut costs,
and alliances that create the larger capital bases they will need
to finance customers in the big new euro market. ``Very clearly
this merger was of the second type,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jean-Luc Lepreux, chief banking analyst at Moody's Investors
Service in Paris, agreed, adding that the greater size will have
more than one advantage. ``It is both defensive and offensive,'' he
said of the alliance between the two banks. The volatility of the
prices of stock in French banks, he said, was a sign of their
potential as takeover targets. The deal also affords each of the
banks a chance to increase outlets for retail financial services.
And by bringing together Societe Generale's specialization in
equities and Paribas' in fixed-income securities, the merger
increases their clout on the increasingly liquid euro-denominated
securities markets.
</P>
<P>
   The logic behind the merger, these experts say, is largely
dictated by the peculiarities of French banking. Societe Generale,
which was nationalized after World War II, was one of the first
French banks to be returned to the private sector when it made the
transition in 1986, and it has had to struggle to assert itself in
a market distorted by state-owned and mutual banks that typically
gained market share while paying scant attention to returns. These
banks, said Dermine, ``focused on size and not profitability.'' He
added, ``That is disadvantageous for banks that have to compete on
international capital markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was distaste for French retail banking among private
French banks and foreign banks alike. Last year, when the Paris
government auctioned off the nationalized bank Compagnie Financiere
de CIC, British banks, traditionally focused on profitability, were
singularly absent among the bidders; Barclays Bank, one of
Britain's largest, closed its unprofitable French retailing arm in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast with Credit Agricole, one of the largest banks by
assets, is revealing. Credit Agricole is effectively owned by its
regional units, which are in turn owned by bank customers, who
receive fixed returns on their investments. Its 8,000 branches,
with 21 percent of the retail market, compared with Societe
Generale's 2,700 branches, or 7 percent, give Agricole a vast
reach.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, government-assured monopolies on certain savings
products assure captive markets, and fixed returns to shareholders
erase concerns for return on equity. And Credit Agricole is not
alone. Its two biggest rivals in the retail sector are also mutual
banks, Credit Mutuel and Banques Populaires, which together control
5,300 branches.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure for change is increasing. Low profitability and mutual
ownership have traditionally blocked the access of the mutual banks
to capital markets. This will put them at an increasing
disadvantage, experts say, as profit-rich banks in other European
countries, like Britain, Spain and the Netherlands, seek expansion
outside domestic markets.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin's government, urged on by strong bank unions, has been
slow to touch the mutual ownership arrangements. Yet the walls of
mutualization have begun to crumble nonetheless. Banques Populaires
has been partially demutualized while others, including Credit
Agricole, have gained access to capital markets by offering shares
in some of their regional banks on stock markets. The banks are
competing for international capital, and that will keep the
pressure on for greater returns. If Agricole enters the circle of
Credit Lyonnais shareholders, the pressure to move away from the
mutual style of ownership can only increase, and Societe Generale's
move on Paribas has created competition that is likely to force the
process. In 1997, Agricole's return on equity was 8.8 percent, and
Credit Mutuel's was 7.5 percent. Societe Generale, by contrast,
reported a return of 10.2 percent, and the combined banks say they
are targeting 15 percent by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it puts pressure on the pedal,'' said John Bennett,
investment director in London for Global Asset Management.
Describing himself as ``fairly ambivalent'' about Societe
Generale's acquisition of Paribas, he said he was ``less ambivalent
about what it means for the sector'' of French banking, which he
thinks will be pushed further toward change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never as fast as you like, and French banking certainly
needs costs taken out,'' he said. But the combination will keep
pressure on bankers and policy makers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the government wants and the French banks need is
mutually exclusive,'' he said, ``but it's getting closer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
