<HEADER>
A6190 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-GUGLIOTTA-HNS &LR;      02-15 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GUGLIOTTA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
If you had told Tom Gugliotta 10 years ago he would one day be the
subject of a multimillion-dollar tug of war between two NBA teams,
he probably would have laughed in your face.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Come to think of it, if you had tried to tell anybody that, they
would have laughed in your face.
</P>
<P>
   But Gugliotta was the subject of just such a tussle, eventually
signing a six-year, $58.5 million deal with the Phoenix Suns _ and
turning down an offer from the Minnesota Timberwolves that would
have paid him almost $30 million more.
</P>
<P>
   Professional athletes don't typically do something like that,
but this isn't your typical professional athlete. Gugliotta, whose
Suns visit Compaq Center tonight to play the Rockets, is a guy who
not only wasn't heavily recruited coming out of Walt Whitman High
in New York but one who actually wound up at a major college
because his father called in a favor.
</P>
<P>
   The serendipitous journey to the NBA began with a simple phone
call. Gugliotta's father, Frank, called family friend Jim Valvano,
then coaching at North Carolina State, and asked if he would at
least come and watch his son, Tommy, play.
</P>
<P>
   Valvano twice came to see Gugliotta but quickly realized it
would be a reach to offer him a scholarship. At 6-7 and 190 pounds,
Gugliotta was a painfully undersized power forward, and in the
rugged Atlantic Coast Conference, size matters.
</P>
<P>
   Offering the kid a scholarship just didn't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   But then, neither did Valvano's thought processes at times.
Never one bound by convention, Valvano had a coaching philosophy
that was shaped by his outlook on life _ 70 percent emotion, 20
percent instinct and 10 percent logic. Using that same formula,
Valvano offered Gugliotta a full ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father told him he thought I could play at a high level _
maybe not right away, but he thought I could be good,'' Gugliotta
said. ``Coach Valvano saw me play a couple times, and he was honest
with me. He said, `I haven't seen you enough to know if you can be
good at this level. But if you're willing to work hard, be a good
student, work on your game and graduate, you have a scholarship.'
Before he could even think about what he said, I signed my name.''
</P>
<P>
   And then went about making a name for himself. Valvano advised
hard work, both on the court and in the weight room, and Gugliotta
responded to the prodding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said I could be a great player,'' Gugliotta said. ``And I
believed him. Everybody knows he was a great coach and a great
motivator, but anybody who knew him knows he also was just an
unbelievable person. He always had so much excitement about
everything he was doing. He was enthusiastic about everything he
did in life. That's why I believed him. It was great to hear him
say something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta, now 6-10 and 240 pounds, became not only an All-ACC
pick at N.C. State but an NBA All-Star as well, even though that
road was a bit different _ and lengthy. Drafted by the Washington
Bullets, Gugliotta was traded to Golden State for Chris Webber
before winding up in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Gugliotta became one of the best all-around
players in the game, able to pound inside for rebounds like a power
forward or use his deft touch and passing skills to play outside
like a small forward. In Minnesota, he teamed with Kevin Garnett
and Stephon Marbury to lead the Timberwolves into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But when his contract came up at the end of last season,
Gugliotta found himself one of the most high-profile free agents on
the market. And Phoenix was definitely interested.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns had been left high and dry by Antonio McDyess, who
bolted Phoenix for a return trip to Denver, where he had started
his career in 1995. The Suns, who were rebuffed by Scottie Pippen
as well, set their sights on Gugliotta, who was coming off a season
in which he averaged 20.1 points, 8.7 rebounds and 4.1 assists with
the Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns had one big ace in the hole _ winning.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 seasons, only once have the Suns endured a losing
season. That, more than anything else _ and in this case ``anything
else'' includes an extra $28 million from the Timberwolves that he
left on the table _ was the lure. His Washington teams won just 46
games in two seasons. The Warriors were on the way to 56 losses in
Gugliotta's brief stint there before he was traded to Minnesota.
And his teams there finished above .500 just once, going 45-37 last
season before being eliminated by Seattle in the first round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta wanted to win, and he placed that desire above money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk to some of the older players in the league who
have made a good amount of money and saved a good amount of money,
when you're younger, contracts are very important,'' he said.
``They are at any stage, but I was fortunate enough to put myself
in a (financial) situation where I didn't have to make the contract
the most important thing. That left other options open for me for
what I really wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Suns couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Gugliotta, we would have taken a big step backward,''
said Phoenix coach Danny Ainge. ``This was risky business. This was
anything but a guarantee. We let a lot of free agents go by, but we
waited and got the guy we're all very excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta debuted with 24 points and 17 rebounds in a 101-92
victory over the Los Angeles Clippers and followed with 29 points
and 13 rebounds in a 115-108 victory over Denver. Big things were
expected, and Gugliotta obviously wasted no time in delivering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to come out here and try to continue my career in
the direction it's been going the last couple of years,'' Gugliotta
said. ``That's playing at an All-Star level and trying to help make
this team very successful, to be able to compete against the other
elite teams in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Others around the league think the Suns came out just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they lost anything,'' said Utah's Karl Malone.
``What Googs brings to the table is a well-rounded forward who can
do a lot of things. He can do it all. Antonio is a talented player,
but I don't think they lost one step by getting Googs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
