<HEADER>
A6191 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-NEWYORK-90     02-15 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-NEWYORK-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON WOULD BE `TERRIFIC' SENATOR, PRESIDENT
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also MEXICO-CLINTON, moved in `i' category) 
(fe) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDA, Mexico _ President Clinton said on Monday that Hillary
Rodham Clinton would be a ``terrific'' senator from New York,
adding his praise to a growing Democratic clamor for Mrs. Clinton
to run for the Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a decision she'll have to make,'' the president said,
after a reporter asked if he would encourage her to run. ``She'd be
great if she did it.''
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned that that the idea had not occurred to Mrs. Clinton
before ``a lot of people started calling'' and urging her to seek
the seat of Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``For reasons I'm sure you'll understand,'' Clinton said in an
apparent reference to his impeachment trial, ``she hasn't had
anything like adequate time to talk to the people who think she
should do this, much less people who think perhaps she shouldn't. I
mean, she just hasn't had time to deal with this.''
</P>
<P>
   With the trial behind him, Clinton, publicly cheerful and at
ease during a 24-hour working visit to this colonial city in the
Yucatan, seemed happy to fan speculation about the futures of him
and his wife after he leaves the office he has been fighting so
fiercely to keep. ``She and I both would like to continue to be
useful in public affairs when we leave office,'' Clinton said. Mrs.
Clinton did not comment on her plans.
</P>
<P>
   From a wispy notion planted by a few New York Democrats, the
prospect that Mrs. Clinton might run for the Senate has sprouted
into full speculative bloom. On Sunday, Moynihan spoke glowingly
about Mrs. Clinton's ``magnificent, young, bright, able,
Illinois-Arkansas enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday, Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., who is dean of the
state's congressional delegation, said he was ``very excited'' by
Clinton's remarks. ``Politically, we have pulled together an offer
that the first lady can't refuse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Mrs. Clinton had been assured that she would have
no opposition in the primary and that she would have the support of
the Democratic Party and organized labor. Further, he said, major
New York donors have called Mrs. Clinton to say that they would
back her bid for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, it's a question of will,'' said Rangel, who is
a member of the official delegation here. ``She's been through so
much that if she decided it would be too much, nobody should lean
on her just because it would be good for our state and our
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel did not elaborate on the nature of the assurances that no
other Democrat would enter the race. But Judith Hope, the state
party chairwoman, described Rangel's remarks as ``a figure of
speech'' and said he was not describing ``any kind of official or
formal process.'' But Mrs. Hope, who has repeatedly encouraged Mrs.
Clinton to enter the race, said Monday night night that ``it is
more clear to me now than it has been that she is in fact giving
this quite serious consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joe Biden of Delaware, who is also part of the delegation,
said he discussed the possibility of a Senate race with Mrs.
Clinton on Sunday night. ``She seemed very serious,'' he said.
``She said everybody tells her, `You could win this thing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton also met on Friday with Harold Ickes, a White House
adviser who has long been active in New York politics, in part to
discuss the Senate race, Ickes said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who returned to Washington Monday evening with her
husband, has never held elective office, and as first lady, she has
spoken longingly of her wish for a ``zone of privacy'' around her
family. Instead, her hairstyles have been critiqued, her billing
records as an Arkansas lawyer scrutinized, and her steadfast
loyalty to her husband lampooned. Reporters monitor her every move
_ did she take her husband's hand? did she move out from under his
encircling arm? _ for signs of marital peace or discord. She does
not like that at all, friends say.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons do not own a home. To register to vote, they have
used the Little Rock address of Dorothy Rodham, Mrs. Clinton's
mother.
</P>
<P>
   For a Senate race in New York, Mrs. Clinton would have to
establish residency there and determine how to balance campaigning
with her extensive duties as first lady. She would almost certainly
face a full-time and well-financed Republican opponent, possibly
Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani. She plans to decide whether to run soon,
officials say, to avoid unnecessarily interfering with other
potential Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior White House aides seem baffled by the Clintons'
interest in a possible race for Senate and express surprise that
they have not dismissed the idea. They predict that Mrs. Clinton
will ultimately decide not to run.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the president, White House officials dodged comment
on the subject on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But as the speculative bubble grows, few senior public
officials, in or out of the administration, can avoid being asked
for their opinion of Mrs. Clinton's plans _ whatever they may be.
It was the first question put on Monday to Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright, when she tried to brief reporters on the
multitude of incremental agreements on fighting drugs, controlling
illegal immigration and snuffing forest fires that Clinton reached
here with President Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton is a fantastic human being, and anyone who knows
her knows that she would be a great public servant,'' Ms. Albright
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite her qualms about the spotlight, Mrs. Clinton, who has
become resoundingly popular nationally, clearly relishes her
influence on policy.
</P>
<P>
   After her public approval ratings collapsed over the failure of
her plan to remake the health care system, Mrs. Clinton retreated
from the aggressive role she had played at the start of the
administration. She still wielded great influence on a wide variety
of issues behind the scenes, but in public she kept a lower profile
as she pushed for better education and child care and a more
innovative approach to foreign development.
</P>
<P>
   The public overwhelmingly approved of Mrs. Clinton's decision to
stand by her husband after he was accused of an affair with Monica
S. Lewinsky and after he admitted that the accusations were true.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip to Mexico _ where the Clintons' honeymooned (in the
company of Mrs. Rodham) 24 years ago, as the president recalled
today _ they have been all smiles and clasped hands. On Sunday,
they even made an extremely rare appearance in the rear cabin of
Air Force One. Mrs. Clinton wore a gold heart-shaped pin that she
said the president had given her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a better kind of heart of darkness,'' the president
said as he dispensed Valentine's Day chocolate from a giant
heart-shaped box in his hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
