u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-THREAT-440&AMP;ADD-N     02-15 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-THREAT-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ-TURKEY)
</HEADLINE>
  
 IRAQ THREATENS TO ATTACK AIR BASE IN TURKEY  (See also IRAQ-FRANCE,(sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Iraq threatened on Monday to attack an air base in
southeastern Turkey if American and British jets based there
continue to patrol northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The threat, delivered by Iraq's vice president, Taha Yassin
Ramadan, came after weeks of strikes by American and British
warplanes against military targets in the northern and southern
no-flight zones of Iraq, including new attacks on Monday. His
remarks about the base at Incirlik, Turkey, also followed sharply
worded Iraqi threats against Kuwait and Saudi Arabia on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The comments appeared to reflect mounting Iraqi frustration with
the air strikes, which have steadily eroded Iraq's defenses in the
weeks since the United States and Britain pounded Iraq for four
nights in December.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those air raids and continuing attacks that have clearly
weakened Iraq, military experts say it could still pose a
significant military threat to its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan warned Monday on the Monte Carlo radio, ``I say if
America and Britain do not retreat, they'll soon pay dearly in
relation to the properties and elements they use to launch
aggression on the people of Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   In remarks on Iraq's official television, Ramadan mentioned the
countries that have supported the United States and Britain by
allowing use of their air fields for the patrols of the restricted
zones. ``We can reach the dens of evil in Turkey, just as we can
those in Kuwait and Saudi Arabia,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has issued ominous threats in the past, but just as often
failed to carry them out.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said on Monday in Mexico,
where she was traveling with President Clinton, that the American
response to any attack by the Iraqis would be ``swift and sure.''
</P>
<P>
   While officials at the Pentagon on Monday viewed the newest
Iraqi threat with skepticism, they did not dismiss it. The
vehemence of Iraq's warnings seem certain to heighten tensions
among its neighbors, already made uneasy by the low-level warfare
that the United States and Britain have been conducting against
Iraq nearly every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an empty threat,'' the Pentagon's spokesman,
Kenneth H. Bacon, said on Monday, adding that if Iraq attacked
Turkey, Kuwait or Saudi Arabia, the consequences would be
devastating. But he said the Pentagon would take the threat
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the threat to Turkey seemed unusual given that
Iraq's deputy prime minister, Tariq Aziz, visited the Turkish
capital Monday on a diplomatic mission intended, at least
symbolically, to ease Iraq's isolation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Iraq could have missiles able to reach bases in Turkey and
Kuwait. President Saddam Hussein's government was supposed to
dismantle its long-range missiles as a condition of ending the
Persian Gulf war in 1991, but U.N. weapons inspectors never
accounted for all of the Scud missiles Iraq had before the war.
Also, Iraq was allowed to keep building missiles with ranges
shorter than 100 miles _ long enough, conceivably, to be used
across its borders with Kuwait and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Monday's warnings, Turkey considered the threat from
Iraq serious enough that it asked the United States to send a
battery of Patriot air-defense missiles to Incirlik, which the
Pentagon agreed to do in January. The United States also has
Patriots defending bases in Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq considers the no-flight zones to be violations of its
sovereignty, but it has never challenged them in such a sustained
way. The United States and its allies created the zones to protect
Iraqi ethnic groups facing repression by Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   After the raids in December, Iraqi forces began to confront the
American and British jets patrolling them in a series of one-sided
exchanges that have resulted in the destruction of several Iraqi
anti-aircraft missile sites and other targets with no loss of
allied aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Those exchanges continued on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In northern Iraq, two American F-15E's attacked an anti-aircraft
artillery battery north of the city of Mosul after Iraqi forces
opened fire, according to the Pentagon's account.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, an EA-6B electronic warfare jet fired a high-speed
radar-seeking missile at an Iraqi radar installation that was
tracking the jet, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Iraq, American and British jets attacked four
separate targets in response to an incursion by two Iraqi warplanes
into the no-flight zone below the 33rd parallel.
</P>
<P>
   All of the American and British jets returned safely to their
bases. Iraq's news agency announced that five civilians had been
killed in Monday's attack; officials at the Pentagon said there was
no way to verify the Iraqi claims of casualties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
