<HEADLINE>
NO. 2 IRAQI TELLS TURKS HIS COUNTRY WANTS DIALOGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IRAQ-THREAT, IRAQ-FRANCE)  
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz of Iraq told
Turkish officials Monday that his country had complied at least
partly with U.N. disarmament resolutions and was ready for dialogue
with the outside world, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The visit to Ankara by Aziz, Iraq's second-ranking leader, is
something of a landmark because it comes as the United States is
trying to isolate and depose the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
   But any progress that Aziz made in soothing Turkish concerns may
have been wiped away soon after his talks ended. Another senior
Iraqi official, Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan, warned in
Baghdad that his country was preparing to attack the Turkish base
from which American planes launch bombing raids over northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said they were pleased that Aziz had
apparently not achieved anything substantial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to think that he could be going home happy,''
said an American diplomat, who, like others who discussed the
talks, spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``If he was trying to
redefine the terms of debate, quite clearly he failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats who took part in the Ankara meetings said Aziz was
soft-spoken and not confrontational. They said he had asked Turkey
to help persuade foreign powers that Iraq was not bent on unending
confrontation with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the point that he wants dialogue, even with the United
States,'' a diplomat said. ``He wants the world to acknowledge that
there has been at least some compliance with the U.N.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
