<HEADER>
A6194 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-EHRLICHMAN-1STLD     02-15 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EHRLICHMAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(1,100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EHRLICHMAN, NIXON AIDE WHO WENT TO PRISON OVER WATERGATE, DEAD AT
73 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS last graf with 2 grafs, Ehrlichman was born ..., to add bio
info and expand on survivors; ADDS optional 2nd take with more
background on Watergate, quote from colleague.) (nk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John D. Ehrlichman, who served as President Nixon's
pugnacious defender and domestic policy chief and went to prison
for his role in the Watergate scandals, died Sunday at his home in
Atlanta. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman had been suffering from diabetes for about a year,
his son Tom said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After serving time in prison for conspiracy and other counts,
Ehrlichman made a new life for himself in 1978, first as a writer
living in Santa Fe, N.M., and for the past several years as a
senior vice president of Law Environmental, an Atlanta-based
engineering company engaged in hazardous-waste handling, his son
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ehrlichman, of Seattle, said that, in his later years, his
father continued to feel ``remorse for the impact on his family''
that his wrongdoing had caused, along with the hope that history
would recall the accomplishments of the Nixon administration, not
just its crimes.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the Nixon presidency in 1969, John Daniel
Ehrlichman was a central figure, first as domestic-policy chieftain
in the White House, and later as a participant in the Watergate
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   When five men were caught during a burglary at the headquarters
of the Democratic National Committee in Washington's Watergate
complex on June 17, 1972, the incident at first was airily
dismissed by Nixon aides as a ``third-rate burglary,'' with no
connection to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But as investigations unfolded, it was revealed that the
burglars had links either to the White House or to the Nixon
campaign's Committee to Re-Elect the President and were trying to
fix a faulty listening device installed during an earlier break-in.
</P>
<P>
   The investigations (and the president's own tape-recordings)
would also disclose that Nixon and some of his top aides had begun
an effort to cover up White House involvement in the break-in
almost from the start. Nixon resigned on Aug. 9, 1974, rather than
face all but certain impeachment and removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Nixon aides were implicated in Watergate and related
crimes, some for relatively peripheral roles. The most important
case involved Ehrlichman and three other high-ranking officials:
former Attorney General John N. Mitchell, who died in 1988; Nixon's
chief of staff, H.R. Haldeman, and Robert C. Mardian, a former
assistant attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   After a trial lasting two and a half months, all were convicted
on Jan. 1, 1975, of conspiracy, obstruction of justice and perjury.
They were sentenced to two and a half to eight years in prison,
though Mardian's conviction was overturned on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman's sentence was made concurrent with a term of 20
months to five years imposed on him for his role in the September
1971 break-in at the office of Dr. Lewis Fielding in Beverly Hills,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding was a psychiatrist who had been treating Dr. Daniel
Ellsberg, who had said publicly that he had given journalists a
copy of a secret government study of U.S. involvement in the
Vietnam War. A covert White House unit, known as ``the plumbers''
and answerable to Ehrlichman, was assigned to find and plug such
``leaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The plumbers' break-in at the psychiatrist's office, apparently
in quest of material damaging to Ellsberg, did not become public
until some two and a half years after it was committed, and it
added to the White House embarrassment over the burgeoning
Watergate scandal. Indeed, Ehrlichman later referred to the
Fielding break-in as ``the seminal Watergate episode,'' one that
set the tone for all the cover-ups to follow.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ehrlichman entered prison in Stafford, Ariz., in the
fall of 1976, deciding not to wait until his appeals were
exhausted, Nixon had been pardoned by President Gerald R. Ford and
was trying to rehabilitate his reputation for history.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman had already undergone a major life change after his
conviction. He had left his first wife, Jeanne, and their Seattle
home and moved to Santa Fe, where he began to write.
</P>
<P>
   After his release from prison, Ehrlichman returned to New Mexico
to resume his writing career and to give occasional lectures. He
wrote four novels and a memoir, 1982's ``Witness to Power'' (Simon
and Schuster), in which he reflected on his relationship with the
former president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't miss Richard Nixon very much,'' he wrote. ``Richard
Nixon probably doesn't much miss me either.''
</P>
<P>
   His association with Nixon began because he had known Haldeman
while both were attending the University of California at Los
Angeles. After graduating from Stanford University Law School, he
joined a Los Angeles firm before starting his own law firm in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman specialized in zoning and land-use law and made many
acquaintances in politics. Haldeman recruited him to help out in
Nixon's 1960 campaign for the presidency and again for Nixon's
unsuccessful run for governor of California in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman went back to practicing law in Seattle, then became a
strategist in Nixon's 1968 campaign for president. In his role as
White House counsel and later as chief domestic-policy adviser,
Ehrlichman became known as the ``White House fireman,''
extinguishing political and bureaucratic brush fires before they
became public.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors referred to Ehrlichman and Haldeman together as ``the
Berlin wall,'' because they were said to shield the reclusive,
occasionally paranoid president from unpleasant news and
unpalatable choices.
</P>
<P>
   But another perspective was offered by Theodore H. White in
``The Making of the President 1972.'' Writing before the Watergate
scandal began, White said of Ehrlichman: ``His shop was one of the
few at the White House where ideas were seriously entertained _
good ideas, too, on energy, on land-use policy, on urbanization, on
preservation of the American environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman was born in Tacoma, Wash., on March 20, 1925. He was
an Eagle Scout and after his freshman year at UCLA, he enlisted in
the Army Air Corps in 1943. He flew 26 missions over Germany as a
navigator in a B-24 bomber and was awarded a Distinguished Flying
Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman's first two marriages, to Jeanne Fisher and Christine
McLaurine, ended in divorce. He is survived by his mother, Lillian
Ehrlichman, who is 97; his third wife, Karen; three sons and two
daughters from his first marriage: Peter and Tom of Seattle and Rob
of San Francisco; Jan Ehrlichman of Sante Fe and Jody Pineda of
Santa Fe; a son from his second marriage, Michael, of Princeton,
N.J., and 13 grandchildren.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dismayed by the excesses of the plumbers, Ehrlichman eventually
ordered it disbanded. But by then, the Watergate scandal had taken
on a life of its own. Though later accounts suggested that
Ehrlichman favored an admission of wrongdoing before it was too
late, he became caught up in the all-out cover-up attempt.
</P>
<P>
   When L. Patrick Gray III, the acting FBI director, was
peripherally linked to the Watergate defendants, Ehrlichman
famously advised Nixon to leave Gray ``twisting slowly, slowly in
the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon eventually sacrificed Ehrlichman and Haldeman to the
cover-up campaign; they resigned at the president's request on
April 30, 1973, weeks before the Senate hearings in which John
Dean, the president's former counsel, would begin to reveal the
depth of Nixon's complicity.
</P>
<P>
   After going to prison, Ehrlichman said he had brought his
troubles on himself. ``I abdicated my moral judgments and turned
them over to somebody else,'' he said in 1977. ``And if I had any
advice for my kids, it would be to never, ever defer your moral
judgments to anybody _ your parents, your wife, anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Egil (Bud) Krogh, who headed the plumbers unit for a time and
served four months in prison, said Monday that he regretted his own
role in the Watergate-related scandals and that he should have
served Ehrlichman better. He said they had remained close over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``John felt really saddened by the whole thing,'' said Krogh,
who practices law in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman called the characters in his 1976 novel ``The
Company'' (Simon and Schuster) ``wholly fictional,'' but the
disclaimer was unconvincing to anyone at all familiar with
Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   In the novel, a White House operative is caught burglarizing the
office of a Democratic candidate in San Francisco. Hearing of this,
a high government official (not the president) worries to his wife:
``I have a feeling someone has just lit a very long fuse that leads
right to me, sweetheart. Just pray to God I'm wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 2053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORONTO-HOCKEY-ART-70     02-15 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-HOCKEY-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM ON, BOOMER, AND DON'T TRIP OVER THE PUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
(Eds., also filed in `s' category) 
(fb) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ At any other time, Lewis R. Mitz would have been an
easy touch for the young man who came to his front door collecting
money for the Salvation Army. But he politely brushed off the
fund-raiser because this was a Thursday night in winter, and, as it
has been for the last quarter century of Mitz's life, Thursday
night is hockey night.
</P>
<P>
   A successful lawyer and real estate investor, Mitz, 54, had
already changed from his suit and tie into an old pair of nylon
pants so worn and torn they were held together with safety pins. He
pulled on a 30-year-old red windbreaker, and carried a pair of
thick hockey gloves, worn at the palms, that were almost as old as
his son Ryan, 21, who was back from college and free to play in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The game. For nearly three decades, every Thursday night, it has
been the game. Same place, the Phil White Arena, tucked into a
hard-to-find Toronto ravine. Same time, 8:30 p.m., an absolutely
luxuriant hour compared with the midnight or 1 a.m. that some adult
hockey teams get ice time in this hockey-crazed city. And largely
the same group of people, who come together week after week, year
after year, in a ritual as Canadian as saying ``excuse me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a moment that is sacred to me,'' Mitz said, excited as
any peewee player about to take the ice. He was prepared to spend
most of the next two hours in a clammy, and cold, bare-bones arena
where he had learned to ice skate before the place even had a roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing about this place is beautiful,'' he said. ``In fact,
it's pretty rugged. But this is the way Canada lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Any Canadian will tell you it can be tough living under the same
North American big top with the United States always filling the
center ring. Sometimes you just want to cling to what sets you
apart, they say, what reminds you who you are.
</P>
<P>
   Some people say hockey is Canada, and that has never been more
true than now, while Toronto is braving a major bout of
hockey-induced nostalgia. The Toronto Maple Leafs, after 68 years
playing at what to many Canadians is the Vatican of hockey, Maple
Leaf Gardens, will be moving to a new arena a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   During the final game last Saturday, one of the 15,726 fans who
paid up to $2,000 for a ticket held up a sign that said ``Hockey is
my religion and I'm in church.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Canadians begin playing hockey just about as soon as they
start to walk. Then some keep playing until they need to walk with
a cane. Dick Cordick, director of registration and insurance for
the Canadian Adult Recreational Hockey Association in Ottawa,
figures there must be at least 600,000 Canadian men and a growing
number of women who play hockey while they are in their 30s, 40s,
50s and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   With so many baby boomers trying to hang on to the vestiges of
youth, the competition for ice time has become fierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is less ice available than what is needed in this
city,'' said Rita Shahani, a Toronto recreation department employee
who keeps track of rink time at the Phil White Arena and other
rinks in Toronto's west end. ``It's become a commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   It is only by sheer stamina that Mitz's group manages to keep
its privileged time slot at a publicly owned rink. It was Robert
Masters, the father of two of the current Thursday Night Hockey
players, who originally reserved the time, but an injury sidelined
him years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Masters, a lawyer, cannot remember how long the 8:30-to-10 slot
has been in his name, but he knows it dates back to before the Phil
White Arena was covered with a Quonset hut-style roof.
</P>
<P>
   That was 27 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is a homely thing, just a few smelly locker rooms, a few
soda dispensers, a whirring Zamboni machine that lays down a fresh
flood of shimmering ice before each game, and the stirring
possibilities of the ice itself, which all 20 men will tell you has
the ability to make dreams real.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about business and this is not about networking,''
said Stephen Kauffman, 50, the director of real estate for Home
Depot in Canada, who has been a Thursday night regular for more
than 20 years. ``This is not about anything except being a boy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Part of the mystique, the players say, is that for an hour or
so, each player gets to set up the dimensions of his own world.
Some imagine being center ice at the Gardens. Some imagine they are
18 again. Some just skate and imagine what it would be like if life
really were hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Although every player can afford the newest and best hockey
equipment, they take the ice in some pretty ratty outfits. Robert
M. Davidson, 48, has as many holes in his hockey socks as he does
houses in the real estate listings he handles as a successful
agent. Throughout the locker room, ancient shoulder pads sit on
shoulders that were once squarer than now, and gloves are old
enough to genuinely be called wizened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that those guys can't afford better clothes,''
Kauffman said. ``But we live in a world where you get your car
washed once a week. This game is like the rebellion against
structure. When you're out there on the ice there's no referee.
It's all self-regulating.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows the rules because they made them: no checking,
no rough blocking, no slap shots unless you have a clear path to
the goal.
</P>
<P>
   But there should be no mistaking _ this is no Sunday afternoon
softball game. The younger players, in their early 30's, skate hard
enough to make the old-timers sweat. To keep things competitive,
they use itinerant goalies provided by an agency called
Rent-a-Goalie, and they play hard.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of missed shots, erratic pucks and dropped
sticks. There isn't too much in the way of organized play making,
or fancy skating. As the night wears on, Kauffman switches to a
special hockey stick that is longer than normal by about six
inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 50 years old, I need every inch I can get,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the night, nobody really knows the score but they
all know that the light jerseys have two more goals than dark.
</P>
<P>
   Fridays after the game are often filled with creakiness and sore
spots, but not on the heart. ``I may get bruised, and I get cut
sometimes,'' Mitz said, ``but the people I deal with on Friday
can't get me upset.''
</P>
<P>
   These have been difficult times for Canadian hockey. Americans
dominate the National Hockey League, the Canadian women's hockey
team did not win the Olympic gold medal it was expected to win last
year, and junior hockey has been hit by several sexual abuse
scandals, including the discovery of a group of adults who preyed
on young boys at Maple Leaf Gardens itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs will play their first game in the brand-new Air
Canada Center next Saturday. Hockey memories have been revived
nonstop in offices and around restaurant tables throughout Toronto
for the last few weeks, and some fans even cried when the last game
ended.
</P>
<P>
   But no memory, no matter how strong, no matter how evocative,
substitutes for the game itself. Sammy Davis, president of the Late
Night Adult Hockey Association of Toronto, said that on the night
of the last game at Maple Leaf Gardens, all of his scheduled adult
hockey games went on as scheduled, and every player showed up. He
expects the same this Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tradition is important,'' Davis said, ``but the game is more
important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
