<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORONTO-HOCKEY-ART-70     02-15 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-HOCKEY-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM ON, BOOMER, AND DON'T TRIP OVER THE PUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
(Eds., also filed in `i' category) 
(fb) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ At any other time, Lewis R. Mitz would have been an
easy touch for the young man who came to his front door collecting
money for the Salvation Army. But he politely brushed off the
fund-raiser because this was a Thursday night in winter, and, as it
has been for the last quarter century of Mitz's life, Thursday
night is hockey night.
</P>
<P>
   A successful lawyer and real estate investor, Mitz, 54, had
already changed from his suit and tie into an old pair of nylon
pants so worn and torn they were held together with safety pins. He
pulled on a 30-year-old red windbreaker, and carried a pair of
thick hockey gloves, worn at the palms, that were almost as old as
his son Ryan, 21, who was back from college and free to play in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The game. For nearly three decades, every Thursday night, it has
been the game. Same place, the Phil White Arena, tucked into a
hard-to-find Toronto ravine. Same time, 8:30 p.m., an absolutely
luxuriant hour compared with the midnight or 1 a.m. that some adult
hockey teams get ice time in this hockey-crazed city. And largely
the same group of people, who come together week after week, year
after year, in a ritual as Canadian as saying ``excuse me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a moment that is sacred to me,'' Mitz said, excited as
any peewee player about to take the ice. He was prepared to spend
most of the next two hours in a clammy, and cold, bare-bones arena
where he had learned to ice skate before the place even had a roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing about this place is beautiful,'' he said. ``In fact,
it's pretty rugged. But this is the way Canada lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Any Canadian will tell you it can be tough living under the same
North American big top with the United States always filling the
center ring. Sometimes you just want to cling to what sets you
apart, they say, what reminds you who you are.
</P>
<P>
   Some people say hockey is Canada, and that has never been more
true than now, while Toronto is braving a major bout of
hockey-induced nostalgia. The Toronto Maple Leafs, after 68 years
playing at what to many Canadians is the Vatican of hockey, Maple
Leaf Gardens, will be moving to a new arena a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   During the final game last Saturday, one of the 15,726 fans who
paid up to $2,000 for a ticket held up a sign that said ``Hockey is
my religion and I'm in church.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Canadians begin playing hockey just about as soon as they
start to walk. Then some keep playing until they need to walk with
a cane. Dick Cordick, director of registration and insurance for
the Canadian Adult Recreational Hockey Association in Ottawa,
figures there must be at least 600,000 Canadian men and a growing
number of women who play hockey while they are in their 30s, 40s,
50s and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   With so many baby boomers trying to hang on to the vestiges of
youth, the competition for ice time has become fierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is less ice available than what is needed in this
city,'' said Rita Shahani, a Toronto recreation department employee
who keeps track of rink time at the Phil White Arena and other
rinks in Toronto's west end. ``It's become a commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   It is only by sheer stamina that Mitz's group manages to keep
its privileged time slot at a publicly owned rink. It was Robert
Masters, the father of two of the current Thursday Night Hockey
players, who originally reserved the time, but an injury sidelined
him years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Masters, a lawyer, cannot remember how long the 8:30-to-10 slot
has been in his name, but he knows it dates back to before the Phil
White Arena was covered with a Quonset hut-style roof.
</P>
<P>
   That was 27 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is a homely thing, just a few smelly locker rooms, a few
soda dispensers, a whirring Zamboni machine that lays down a fresh
flood of shimmering ice before each game, and the stirring
possibilities of the ice itself, which all 20 men will tell you has
the ability to make dreams real.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about business and this is not about networking,''
said Stephen Kauffman, 50, the director of real estate for Home
Depot in Canada, who has been a Thursday night regular for more
than 20 years. ``This is not about anything except being a boy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Part of the mystique, the players say, is that for an hour or
so, each player gets to set up the dimensions of his own world.
Some imagine being center ice at the Gardens. Some imagine they are
18 again. Some just skate and imagine what it would be like if life
really were hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Although every player can afford the newest and best hockey
equipment, they take the ice in some pretty ratty outfits. Robert
M. Davidson, 48, has as many holes in his hockey socks as he does
houses in the real estate listings he handles as a successful
agent. Throughout the locker room, ancient shoulder pads sit on
shoulders that were once squarer than now, and gloves are old
enough to genuinely be called wizened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that those guys can't afford better clothes,''
Kauffman said. ``But we live in a world where you get your car
washed once a week. This game is like the rebellion against
structure. When you're out there on the ice there's no referee.
It's all self-regulating.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows the rules because they made them: no checking,
no rough blocking, no slap shots unless you have a clear path to
the goal.
</P>
<P>
   But there should be no mistaking _ this is no Sunday afternoon
softball game. The younger players, in their early 30's, skate hard
enough to make the old-timers sweat. To keep things competitive,
they use itinerant goalies provided by an agency called
Rent-a-Goalie, and they play hard.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of missed shots, erratic pucks and dropped
sticks. There isn't too much in the way of organized play making,
or fancy skating. As the night wears on, Kauffman switches to a
special hockey stick that is longer than normal by about six
inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 50 years old, I need every inch I can get,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the night, nobody really knows the score but they
all know that the light jerseys have two more goals than dark.
</P>
<P>
   Fridays after the game are often filled with creakiness and sore
spots, but not on the heart. ``I may get bruised, and I get cut
sometimes,'' Mitz said, ``but the people I deal with on Friday
can't get me upset.''
</P>
<P>
   These have been difficult times for Canadian hockey. Americans
dominate the National Hockey League, the Canadian women's hockey
team did not win the Olympic gold medal it was expected to win last
year, and junior hockey has been hit by several sexual abuse
scandals, including the discovery of a group of adults who preyed
on young boys at Maple Leaf Gardens itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs will play their first game in the brand-new Air
Canada Center next Saturday. Hockey memories have been revived
nonstop in offices and around restaurant tables throughout Toronto
for the last few weeks, and some fans even cried when the last game
ended.
</P>
<P>
   But no memory, no matter how strong, no matter how evocative,
substitutes for the game itself. Sammy Davis, president of the Late
Night Adult Hockey Association of Toronto, said that on the night
of the last game at Maple Leaf Gardens, all of his scheduled adult
hockey games went on as scheduled, and every player showed up. He
expects the same this Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tradition is important,'' Davis said, ``but the game is more
important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
