<HEADER>
A6202 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-SKOLVOUCHER     02-15 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-SKOLVOUCHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shifting support will make voucher fight different this time
around
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ask Samantha Smoot about the chances of a school
voucher pilot program getting through the Legislature this session,
and the staunch voucher opponent breaks into a broad grin.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Texas Freedom Network, which Smoot now heads,
and other voucher opponents had little to smile about. They were up
against a savvy and well-heeled voucher lobby, favorable public
opinion polls and a lackluster public school system. Though the
vote fell short for vouchers, it was close.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers again are wrestling with the question of whether
public tax dollars should be used to send students to private
schools. But this time, Smoot and others sense they have the upper
hand _ if not the money _ in the ongoing battle.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a major rally today in support of vouchers that is
expected to draw Gov. George W. Bush and as many as 1,500 Texas
parents, several observers say the political momentum for vouchers
has slowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things are going on in education that undermine the
voucher lobby's momentum,'' Smoot said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas public schools have registered marked improvement _ even
gaining national acclaim in some areas. Dozens of state-financed
charter schools are up and running, providing parents more choice
in the public school setting. Furthermore, public opinion polls
have shifted, with Texans now less supportive of diverting public
tax dollars to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   With battle lines increasingly blurred and public opinion
shifting, a voucher program _ even a small pilot as proponents now
are pushing _ faces high hurdles in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will not be easy,'' said Lt. Gov. Rick Perry's spokesman,
Ray Sullivan, when asked about the chances of a voucher pilot
passing this session.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the voucher proposals before lawmakers this session
would give thousands of students in low-performing schools the
right to transfer to any public, private or religious school at
state expense.
</P>
<P>
   Private schools that participate in the voucher pilot, however,
would have to test voucher students by using the state achievement
test, agree to take students on a first-come, first-served basis,
and follow other state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Those strings, tied to money, are necessary for accountability,
said Democratic House Speaker Pete Laney, a voucher opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are using taxpayer dollars, you just can't give
taxpayer dollars away without accountability,'' Laney said. ``Many
of these schools very much would like to have free money, but there
must be accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment worries some private school operators and social
conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any private school that whole hog buys into a voucher funding
system will inevitably lose the ability to provide education that
is uniquely built around the values of their faith group,'' said
Phil Strickland, director of the Christian Life Commission, the
public policy arm of the Baptist General Convention of Texas.
``Ultimately, private schools will get entangled in the spider web
of government control.''
</P>
<P>
   Government regulations, which surely would accompany a voucher
pilot, have raised the red flag among social conservative
organizations and some Catholic school operators, long considered
loyal to the voucher movement.
</P>
<P>
   Cathie Adams, president of the socially conservative Eagle
Forum, warned in December: ``We see it as a back-door approach to
control every private school in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Talley, a spokesman for Putting Children First, one of the
leading pro-voucher groups, concedes that defections by these
groups have slowed momentum. But he says he believes a pilot
project still has support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't going to be for every private school, and if they
don't want them, they don't have to take them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But as some private school operators and conservative groups
have shifted away from vouchers, some Democrats and minority
parents have started leaning toward them.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Wilson, D-Houston long was the sole African American
lawmaker supporting vouchers. In recent years, he has been joined
by Rep. Glenn Lewis, D-Fort Worth. Lewis and Wilson support a
voucher pilot because they say it would allow minority students
trapped in low-performing, inner-city schools to flee to better
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   That's also why Angie Garcia and her group of Hispanic parents,
San Antonio Parents for School Choice, are supporting vouchers and
targeting South Texas lawmakers to win support.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts run counter to shifting public opinion. In 1995,
more than half _ 55 percent _ of Texans favored a voucher program
using tax dollars to send public school students to private
schools, according to the Texas Poll. Thirty-five percent were
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   That has flip-flopped: Now, nearly half _ 49 percent _ of Texans
surveyed are opposed to vouchers, while 41 percent favor them. The
recent poll of 1,001 adult Texans was conducted between Jan. 21 and
Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Support appears to be fading, even for a limited voucher project
as proposed by Rep. Mike Krusee, R-Round Rock, or Sen. Teel Bivins,
R-Amarillo, chairman of the Senate Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Texans split almost evenly when asked if they supported the
Legislature creating a pilot voucher program to allow
low-performing students in poor-performing schools to use tax
dollars for private schools _ with 45 percent favoring a voucher
pilot and 46 percent opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, however, more than half _ 56 percent _ of Texans
favored such a program, according to the Texas Poll, while 36
percent opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   At least one lawmaker says he owes his November election to a
shift on voucher sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any doubt I was elected because of the
swing vote _ Republicans who voted for me,'' said David Lengefeld,
D-Hamilton, who opposes vouchers and whose district includes parts
of Copperas Cove, Gatesville and Stephenville.
</P>
<P>
   The freshman lawmaker, who replaced Allen Place, added: ``I
believe a big part of that was the voucher issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in rural areas, vouchers are losing ground,
Lengefeld and Laney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In rural areas your whole community is centered around the
church and school,'' Laney said. ``The school is the biggest
employer in a lot of communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, vouchers, even in a small pilot, will be
tough-going in Laney's House. Currently, seven Democrats _ most of
whom are opposed to vouchers _ sit on the nine-member House Public
Education Committee, which would consider any voucher legislation.
</P>
<P>
   It still could pass the House via an amendment, but likely would
be felled in the Senate, where it takes only 11 of the 31 votes to
block consideration of a bill on the floor _ which happened in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   All of those factors have voucher opponents smiling and voucher
proponents scurrying for additional support.
</P>
<P>
   A. Phillips Brooks writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
