<HEADER>
A6205 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-JUDICIALELE     02-15 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-JUDICIALELECTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Change in judicial elections proposed
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In what may be the Legislature's boldest stroke
to change how Texas judges are selected, state Rep. Pete Gallego
has drafted legislation to get rid of party politics and big money
in top judicial elections.
</P>
<P>
   Gallego's draft bill, incorporating Chief Justice Tom Phillips'
proposals, would finance Supreme Court and Court of Criminal
Appeals races with taxes collected from most of the state's 65,000
lawyers. Gallego, D-Alpine, sits on the Texas Judicial Council and
Phillips leads the policy-planning group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sounds like the most creative idea on campaign financing
yet,'' said Anthony Champagne, a University of Texas at Dallas
professor and national authority on judicial selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very different, very creative effort in that
regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Partisan election of Texas judges was villainized on the eve of
last fall's Supreme Court election by ``60 Minutes'' correspondent
Mike Wallace. Wallace updated a 1987 investigation of campaign
contributions influencing the state Supreme Court, concluding that
Texas judicial elections remained open to abuse despite limits on
judicial contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Gallego said the idea was born at a breakfast he had last fall
with Phillips as they talked about the ``60 Minutes'' television
report. Phillips, stung by criticism that the court's decisions
generally favor the defense lawyers who have been its biggest
recent contributors, has lobbied for limiting campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Phillips was saying he hated raising campaign money,
that everyone on the court hated it,'' Gallego said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gallego proposal may meet opposition even among the
judges on the Supreme Court. ``It's horrible,'' said Justice Greg
Abbott, who favors a merit-selection method by which judges would
be appointed first and later stand for a retention election in
which voters approve or disapprove of their job. ``I'm against
taxing people for the purpose of using it for campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Center for State Courts, only
Wisconsin now finances judicial campaigns (and other statewide
races) with public money. Texas would be unique in paying just for
judicial elections and unique in financing it through a levy on
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Gallego's proposal is similar to a proposed constitutional
rewrite and other bills that allow the governor to appoint judges
and have retention elections, while getting rid of party labels.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is one of eight states with partisan judicial elections.
But critics say the current state system is tainted because
expensive partisan campaigns are necessary for statewide election
in judicial races.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush remains opposed to changing the current
system, however, said his spokeswoman, Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallego bill would finance campaigns with proceeds from the
$200 lawyer occupation tax assessed on private attorneys in Texas.
That tax raises about $9 million a year, said Laureen Chernow,
Texas State Bar spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Under a draft of Gallego's proposal, judicial candidates would
qualify for public campaign financing by raising at least $30,000
from contributors who would give when they signed the candidate's
petition. Contributor-- would give no more than $100 apiece. That
$30,000 or more would then be supplemented by a share of a campaign
fund split among qualified candidates running for the Supreme Court
or Court of Criminal Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   But Champagne said the problem of indirect contributions
supporting a candidate _ law firms, for example, buying TV ads _
could undermine the Gallego proposal. ``The result is that you get
Baker &AMP; Botts, Vinson &AMP; Elkins and Fulbright &AMP; Jaworski still
spending hundreds of thousands of dollars in the campaigns,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can stop those independent expenditures.''
</P>
<P>
   Osler McCarthy writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
