<SLUG> BC-JASPERDEATH-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Testimony begins in Texas dragging deathBy Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ It is perhaps the most watched jury in the
country and it will gather at an undisclosed location this morning
to be escorted to work by armed guards.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 jurors and two alternates will be driven in a small bus
to a special driveway cordoned off by yellow rope at the
Victorian-style Jasper County courthouse. They will wear badges
that identify them as jurors and news photographers are forbidden
from taking their pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The government is taking no chances as testimony begins today in
the trial of the first of three white men accused of dragging James
Byrd Jr. behind a pickup until he was beheaded last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more brutal and it's more racial than you guys
anticipate,'' Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray told
reporters on Monday. ``It's a bad case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The proof is going to be more than just Saturday night drunks
in a fight,'' he said. ``I expect the community and the jury to be
astonished as the evidence unfolds.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury of seven men and five women is not all-white. Court
officials have released no other details about the panelists who
will decide the fate of John William ``Bill'' King, 23, an
unemployed labor.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities allege King, an ex-convict, was the ringleader in
plotting Byrd's death on June 7. Byrd, who was unemployed and
disabled, was beaten, stripped and chained to a pickup that dragged
him nearly three miles on a backwoods road outside Jasper,
prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   King, who claims he is innocent, could receive the death penalty
if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say they found a spot of blood on King's shoes and
confiscated white supremacy literature and photographs from his
apartment the morning after Byrd's murder. King was a member of a
white supremacy group called the Confederate Knights of America and
was working to form his own white supremacy group in the Jasper
area, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   King is heavily tattooed with white supremacy symbols. One
tattoo shows a black man hanging from a tree branch.
</P>
<P>
   King's court-appointed defense attorney, C. Haden ``Sonny''
Cribbs, Jr., said the government has compiled about 4,500 pages of
documents, photographs, charts, and records, as well as several
video tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence appears overwhelming'' against King, Cribbs said,
but ``some of it may or may not be admissible.'' Still, ``you've
got to prove that the person did it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cribbs tried to have the murder trial moved away from Jasper
County because of intense news coverage of Byrd's death, but was
overruled by State District Judge Joe Bob Golden. Cribbs plans to
seek a change of venue again this morning before testimony begins,
he said, but doubts it will be granted.
</P>
<P>
   The judge has been asked by the New Black Panthers of Dallas to
rescind his order prohibiting any groups from gathering within a
two-block radius of the courthouse during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the New Black Panthers, many carrying shotguns,
came to Jasper to counter protest at a courthouse rally held by the
Ku Klux Klan. The two groups exchanged heated words, but law
officers prevented any fights.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County authorities support the judge's order prohibiting
courthouse gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can guarantee you that the judge is not going to permit any
activity that would intimidate this jury,'' said Gray, the district
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gamino writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
