<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-FASHION-ART-NY     02-15 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-VALENTINES FROM KARAN AND ROWLEY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
(fb) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Never mind those cozy Valentine's Day sentiments.
Donna Karan's DKNY show on Sunday caught the weird chill blowing
between the sexes, and it wasn't just because her guys and gals
were bundled in polar-white rubber coats, padded pullovers or
trousers with a slick, icy feel. Halfway through the show, which
Karan staged on a metallic-blue runway, one fashion editor looked
up, as if snow-blinded, and said, ``Have we seen any men yet?''
</P>
<P>
   There were men, all right, but Karan had unwittingly blotted
them out.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful that Karan, who has trains of products to keep
running, was thinking of the cold sexual climate in recent films
and plays like ``In the Company of Men'' by Neil Labute and
``Closer'' by the British playwright Patrick Marber, which opens
next month on Broadway. In those dramas, the men and women come out
of their smug, well-insulated cocoons only to mate _ and then with
hostile indifference. They're too cynical, too smart, to bother
coming together on any other level when all they really want from
each other is sex.
</P>
<P>
   Though no first-rate designer has come forward to deal with this
theme, it's intriguing that Karan and Cynthia Rowley, who also
showed men's and women's clothes on Sunday, presented collections
that completely hazed the gender lines _ to the point where all the
models, male or female, seemed isolated in their own
anonymous-looking drag.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the first time, Karan relied on high-tech fabrics, like
leather bonded with polar fleece lining and cotton laminated with
resins, to create a look that was resolutely urban, informed, yet
also strangely lacking in flesh-and-blood romance.
</P>
<P>
   Piece by piece, the clothes were certainly novel: a
fleece-bonded coat in icicle-blue calf hair; felted wool jackets
and jersey tops made without shoulder seams; down coats with
pop-on, pop-off duvet covers, and a pair of molded, white leather
motorcycle pants. But as a collection, the many bonded and molded
clothes seemed stiff and Gumby-like, lacking in that offhand
attitude that modern clothes need to avoid being high-tech
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Rowley missed the boat entirely with her collection. She had the
actor Alan Cumming from ``Cabaret,'' dressed as a kind of satyr in
laced-up breeches, mincing down her runway.
</P>
<P>
   But there, in the front row, was his erstwhile co-star Natasha
Richardson, who will be seen next in ``Closer.'' That made Cumming,
however charming, seem like yesterday's news.
</P>
<P>
   Rowley has no obvious feeling for the postmodern mix of colors
and textures, and many of her creations, like a black taffeta shift
striped with leather and a shredded gauze dress, looked hastily
thrown together. In any case, they've been done better by other
designers.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable if Rowley wants to go in a new direction _
apparently toward a tougher urban look _ but it seems foolish to
abandon the sweet prints and lighthearted touch for which she has
been known.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's collections were indeed something of a mixed bag, as
retailers and fashion editors shifted from tent to tent at Bryant
Park, where many of the big-name shows will be held this week, and
then raced downtown to catch Bruce, a new label designed by Nicole
Noselli and Daphne Guttierrez, or maybe to see Jade Jagger's
jewelry at a party at Lot 61.
</P>
<P>
   Moet &AMP; Chandon, the Champagne maker, organized a show for four
young design teams: David Rodriguez, who showed dandified tweeds
and wide flannel trousers; P.A.K., a line that seemed to
overintellectualize the plainest wrap dress; Robert Danes, who
noted the inspiration of Richard Serra's sculpture and Frank
Gehry's architecture, when a more common touch would have served
for his generic slips, and William Calvert, the most accomplished
of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Calvert, who worked at Balenciaga and Balmain before setting up
his own evening-wear business on West 57th Street, used a lot of
luxe satins in ivory and red, which he mixed with humbler mohair.
</P>
<P>
   Among the British designers showing in New York is Tomasz
Starzewski, who recently got a lot of attention for dressing both
Camilla Parker-Bowles, who is Prince Charles' companion, and Sophie
Rhys-Jones, the fiancee of Prince Edward.
</P>
<P>
   Starzewski, who makes society clothes, was apparently so keen on
making a big impression in New York that he flew over 10 models, as
well as the London florist Stephen Woodhams, who decorated the
designer's runway with pussy willows. Before his show, Starzewski,
who has prominent New Yorkers buying his so-called ``demi-couture''
(made-to-measure clothes at significantly less than haute couture
prices), said that he hoped to expand his $5 million business.
``Our lives are changing, and it's because of New York,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Starzewski's clothes are certainly very glamorous. He uses a lot
of beautiful tweeds, mohair and glossy silk, in shades of brown,
charcoal, pistachio and violet and then jazzes them up with beading
and dyed-to-match feathers and fur.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something passe about gathered-up satin skirts,
little felt crash helmets and a model whipping open her
important-looking fur to reveal _ shock! _ another satin slip
dress.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Brown, the famously dapper Mayor of San Francisco,
happened to be in the front row at Starzewski's show and afterward
said he was intrigued by the designer's new men's-wear line but not
altogether sold on its dandified colors and velvets. ``I don't know
yet,'' said a politic Brown. ``I've got to get closer to the
fabrics. I'm not a velvet person, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce is not a name that many people know; it may not even be a
name that means anything except to the two women who design it.
</P>
<P>
   In a smoke-filled ballroom on the Lower East Side, Noselli and
Guttierrez showed only a couple of dozen outfits _ gray gaucho
pants, slinky gray sweaters with puckering up the front or strands
of yarn exploding from the shoulders like dreadlocks, a slim dress
inset with a mink bodice _ but they were all charming.
</P>
<P>
   The designers didn't come out at the end, and the audience sat
there for two or three minutes before it realized the show was
over.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Herrera, showing Monday, left little doubt that she has
an uncomplicated sense of what American women want: good-looking,
wearable clothes with a low-key spin of luxury. Herrera cut caramel
leather outfits close to the body and, in lieu of jewelry, added
fur collars or stoles, some of which were tied around the back of
suits or a cashmere sweater.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of self-conscious attempts to be hip or arty, it's
hard not to be seduced by a gray mohair coat in windowpane plaid
with pinstriped trousers and the palest blue shell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
