<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AEROSPATIALE-MATRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE SELLS A THIRD OF AEROSPATIALE TO GROUPE LAGARDERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The French government announced agreement Monday on the
terms of a long-expected combination of the state-owned
Aerospatiale group and the privately owned Matra High Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Groupe Lagardere, Matra's owner, will pay
the government as much as $345 million for a third of the shares in
the new company, Aerospatiale-Matra.
</P>
<P>
   It would become the world's fifth-largest military and aerospace
contractor _manufacturing satellites, rocket launchers,
helicopters, weapons systems, fighter-bombers and fighters, as well
as civilian aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities here also hope that the restructured French
military giant could eventually attract DaimlerChrysler Aerospace,
a unit of DaimlerChrysler of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Such a combination would produce a huge armaments contractor
that could compete effectively with British Aerospace, which has
just acquired the Marconi armaments unit from General Electric of
Britain, and with Boeing, Lockheed Martin and Raytheon in the
United States, fulfilling President Jacques Chirac's hope of
keeping Europe on the map as a global arms power, with technology
to match.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospatiale also owns a 37.9 percent share in Airbus Industrie,
the four-nation European consortium that is Boeing's biggest
competitor as a builder of civilian airliners.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring will essentially complete a vast
reorganization of French defenses originally announced three years
ago by Chirac, a conservative who abolished the draft and began
privatization of much of the vast French military-industrial
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin's Socialist Cabinet, which came to
office in June 1997, essentially carried on with most of the plan,
but prefers to call the partial privatizations of state-owned
companies an ``opening of capital.''
</P>
<P>
   British Aerospace's deal for Marconi last month came as a shock
to the French, who had flirted with the hope that British Aerospace
might choose to join forces with a French company instead. After
that did not happen, French officials renewed efforts to attract
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace, which had reportedly hoped for a deal
with the British as well.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this month, Germany's chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder,
referring to the possibility of building a French-German company on
the scale of the American and British competition, warned, ``It
will only succeed if the French are willing to make greater
progress in privatizing and reducing the state's share in the
enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   That got the green light with publication of a decree by Jospin
over the weekend announcing the decision to reduce state ownership
in Aerospatiale below 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The government's announcement Monday said the state would remain
the largest single owner, even after the partial privatization. A
stock issue is expected to be floated before the second half of the
year ``if market conditions permit,'' the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospatiale and Matra kept silent Monday, but a statement
released by Economics Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn, Defense
Minister Alain Richard and Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot
said the merger would not mean the loss of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Groupe Lagardere, the announcement said, would initially pay
$147 million for its interest in the company and as much as $198
million more in the future, depending on the market value of
Aerospatiale-Matra shares.
</P>
<P>
   Outside bank appraisals had valued the shares' potential above
$800 million, according to French press reports, prompting some
criticism from the Socialist Cabinet's labor union supporters that
it had sold out to private enterprise for too little.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Lagardere's 71-year-old chairman, Jean-Luc
Lagardere, will become head of Aerospatiale-Matra's supervisory
board, while Yves Michot, Aerospatiale's chairman and chief
executive, will be president of its executive directorate.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospatiale acquired the state's 45.76 percent share in
Dassault Aviation, the privately held maker of the Mirage 2000 and
Rafale fighter planes and Falcon executive jets, late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The French government will retain a stake of 45 to 49 percent in
the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospatiale had revenue of 58 billion francs _ roughly $10
billion _ last year and profit in the first half of the year of
1.216 billion francs, or $210 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
