<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHTING-SOLO-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENOWNED SOLO SAILOR SENDS MESSAGE THAT SHE CAPSIZED AT SEA 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: S.C., Wash., France, Australia)  (fb) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another tale of potential disaster in the high-risk world of
yacht racing was developing on Monday as word came from the South
Pacific Ocean that Isabelle Autissier, the renowned French solo
sailor, was in serious trouble in a single-handed race around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   An emergency beacon belonging to Autissier, a veteran of three
global sailing competitions who was the overall leader in the race,
sent a satellite signal indicating that her 60-foot yacht had
capsized. She was sailing in intermittent squalls of about 30
knots.
</P>
<P>
   Her mayday was transmitted from a reach of cold and wind-driven
ocean 1,900 miles west of South America's tip at Cape Horn. She was
sailing her boat alone, as are the 10 sailors competing against the
42-year-old Autissier, perhaps the most popular female sporting
figure in France.
</P>
<P>
   The fleet of sailboats ranging in length from 40 to 60 feet is
racing in the Around Alone, a 27,000-mile single-handed competition
that began in Charleston, S.C., last Aug. 26. The eight-month race,
which includes three stopovers _ the next one is in Uruguay _ is
scheduled to conclude in Charleston this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Autissier once had to be rescued in a forerunner of this race.
And the news of another sailor fighting to survive comes on the
heels of the Sydney to Hobart Race, in which six yachtsmen died and
seven yachts were abandoned on Dec. 27. A severe storm with
80-mile-an-hour winds and 30-foot seas produced that ocean tragedy,
which started out as a friendly but competitive race for fully
crewed sailboats from Sydney to Hobart, a small Australian port on
Tasmania.
</P>
<P>
   With Autissier now in jeopardy, the issue of safety in
long-distance yacht racing comes under scrutiny again. Dan
McConnell, a race spokesman, said from Seattle on Monday that no
one knew for certain whether Autissier was in a life raft or still
on her boat.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schrader, the Around Alone race director, instructed
Giovanni Soldini of Italy, a competitor who was about 200 miles
north of Autissier's position, to go find her. Her mayday signal
came a few hours after a telephone call from Autissier to a friend
in Paris. Her message was relayed to a French shore crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking over a line that was crackling with interference,
Autissier reportedly said she'd been `capsized,' before activating
the beacon,'' race officials said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling at about 17 knots, Soldini might have been able to
reach the area as early as midnight last night.
</P>
<P>
   Soldini was instructed by satellite e-mail to divert from his
position. He too is on a 60-foot racing boat, Fila, designed by
Groupe Finot, the same French naval architecture firm that created
Autissier's racing machine.
</P>
<P>
   She was into the outer reaches of open ocean at a latitude of 55
degrees south when her beacon went off. The weather there is nasty
and inhospitable almost all the time. John Rousmaniere, author of
the ``Annapolis Book of Seamanship,'' questioned why any sailor was
racing there.
</P>
<P>
   ``These boats are probably beyond the ability of one person to
handle,'' Rousmaniere said. ``They are extremely unstable and would
be a handful even if they had a full crew. But to put them out in
the lower latitudes of the Screaming Fifties, each with only one
exhausted crew member on board, is like going into harm's way
intentionally.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell took issue with that analysis, citing the safety
record of the races since the first quadrennial competition of
1982-83. In the previous four competitions, two of the 87
competitors died at sea; 56 finished the global races.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has been done in the design of these boats to make them
more stable and self-righting,'' McConnell said. ``We have worked
closely with their designers. But there are conditions that are
extreme where no boats can stand up to the weather. Our safety
record indicates that we've been able to solve most of our problems
ourselves.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On several occasions, most notably in the 1994-95 BOC Challenge
_ the forerunner of the Around Alone race _ a competitor was picked
up by another racer and taken to the next port-of-call. In that
race, Josh Hall of England hit a submerged object in the
mid-Atlantic. Alan Nebauer, a BOC competitor from Australia,
rescued Hall from his yacht just before it sank.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Hall suffered a major mishap last week in the
Around Alone race. His 60-foot sailboat was dismasted, and he is
now limping along under a jury-rig sail to Chatham Island in the
South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Mike Plant, a former BOC Challenge competitor, died at
sea en route to a French single-handed yacht race. His
disappearance led to a multimillion-dollar rescue effort that
failed to find him or his boat.
</P>
<P>
   And in the last BOC race, in 1994-95, Autissier also was
responsible for a large rescue effort. Her 60-foot sailboat was
dismasted in the Indian Ocean, and two weeks later, smashed by
giant seas 1,000 miles off the coast of Australia. Autissier was
rescued by an Australian military helicopter, which plucked her
from her sinking boat, at a cost of $6 million to Australian
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Autissier rests her reputation on being a survivor. No one could
have suspected from her last e-mail sent to race headquarters in
Charleston on Monday that she was concerned about anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``A beautiful morning,'' she wrote, ``with snowy squalls
alternating with sunshine, which melted the snow. But this morning,
it turned very gray, and the wind picked up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
