<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S SCHEDULE HURTS LONDON'S 
MILLENNIUMS OF CHINESE FASHION  
 DIBBEN'S PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)  (fb) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The move by American designers to pre-empt the
European fashion calendar by showing fall collections this week is
wreaking havoc across the Atlantic. The latest fallout is in
England, where top designers are bailing out of London's fashion
week, or considering such a move.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Berardi has decided to present his collection in Milan,
Italy, on March 1. Jaspir Uppal, a spokesman for Berardi, said
Monday that the designer was concerned about low attendance in
London, where the collections run from Saturday through Feb. 25.
</P>
<P>
   With Americans moving to the front of the women's ready-to-wear
schedule, fashion retailers and journalists face a calendar running
from Feb. 11 through March 15, when the Paris shows end. Several
American retailers are skipping London because they must remain in
New York to write orders after the American shows wind up on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports in British newspapers, Alexander McQueen
plans to show his spring collection in New York next fall. McQueen
did not return telephone calls seeking comment. Hussein Chalayan is
said to want to move his signature collection from London to Paris.
Chalayan declined to discuss the topic.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, none of this pleases the British Fashion
Council. ``The only one who's actually made the decision is Tony
Berardi _ he's absolutely right for the development of his
business,'' said John Wilson, chief executive of the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of Lee,'' Wilson added, referring to McQueen by
his nickname, ``he feels he's putting on the best or one of the
best shows in the world, and he would like, when he does his show,
to see members of the major media, especially from America,
present.''
</P>
<P>
   As a countermove, the council is working on stronger promotion
of its designers and seeking to keep its schedule short. The group
has no plans to squeeze the London shows into a two- or three-day
window between Paris and Milan, as was sometimes done in the past.
This year it would be impossible: Paris begins March 7, the same
day Milan ends.
</P>
<P>
   From China's Attic
</P>
<P>
   China Millennium is a fashion show that presents a living
history of textiles and clothing in China dating to 221 B.C.
Sponsored by the Chinese government, the exhibition was seen in
Paris last October and is to be shown again at the New York Public
Library on Friday, the last day of fashion week.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation-only show includes originals and reproductions of
spectacular handmade clothing worn by Chinese peasants and those
who ruled them. Familiar signposts of Chinese style _ the
cheongsam, the kimono, platform shoes _ are presented throughout,
but often with unexpected sumptuousness. Some of China's top models
wear robes threaded with thousands of gold filaments, or beautiful
silk gowns.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Han, foreign affairs director of China's official textile
and fashion exhibitions, said China Millennium was intended to
educate not just international audiences, but those at home as
well. ``Chinese don't treasure their own fashion,'' she said.
``They copy Western. If Ralph Lauren recognizes something in
Chinese fashion, then they'll say, `Oh, so we do have some
treasures.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dibben's Offstage Moves
</P>
<P>
   Absent from the men's and women's shows this week are the
designs of Andrew Dibben, whose collections have been a bright spot
on New York's runways for the last two years. But instead of
staging a show, Dibben is preparing to open his first store, in Los
Angeles on April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Time was, it was much harder to open one's own store than to
sell to a big department store. But for small-scale designers like
Dibben, that is no longer so. ``It's the best way to gain control
of your business and have freedom,'' he said. ``I don't believe in
categories like shirts and suits. People in department stores say
they can only buy your clothing if you're doing suiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Dibben, who worked as an assistant designer for Helmet Lang and
Marc Eisen before striking out on his own, creates clothes that
embody a sort of glamorous slacker stance. His store and design
studio will be at 1618 Silver Lake Boulevard, near Sunset
Boulevard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
