<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6234 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-LOTT-1STLD-WRI     02-15 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-LOTT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `TOWN HALL MEETING,' LOTT AND OTHER REPUBLICANS PUSH BROAD TAX
CUTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs 3rd graf to note that the tax cuts would come out of the
projected budget surpluses in coming years. In 2nd take, inserts
new 5th, 6th and 7th grafs with comments from citizens in
attendance. Subs 8th graf to correct the description of the
Republicans' differences over tax cuts.)  (fe) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN, Mich. _ Republican leaders came to this blue-collar
Detroit suburb on Monday to hold the first in a series of ``town
hall meetings'' aimed at reshaping the party's image and agenda in
the wake of the unpopular impeachment trial and at drumming up
support for broad tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of about 500 people, mostly Republicans, responded
fairly warmly, but the enthusiasm was tempered by worries that tax
cuts are not compatible with reducing the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, and Michigan's top
Republican politicians repeatedly called for a 10 percent reduction
in federal income tax rates to make use of part of the projected
$4.35 trillion budget surplus over the next 15 years. They accuse
Democrats of both wanting to spend more of taxpayers' money and
wanting to enact more limited tax cuts with narrowly targeted
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should it be spent on a myriad of federal programs, or should
it be returned to the people?'' Lott asked, drawing considerable,
but not unanimous, applause.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, dozens of people in the audience did not raise their
hands when Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., asked who would like to
pay less in taxes. A repeated theme in the questions at the
Presidents Day event and in subsequent interviews with members of
the audience was a desire to repay some of the national debt before
taxes are reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and his fellow Republicans, including Gov. John Engler,
answered questions from 15 members of the audience chosen by the
moderator, a local television anchorman. Nobody asked about the
impeachment trial, although one person briefly complimented Lott on
his handling of the issue, as the questions focused mainly on
economic issues like Social Security, taxes and the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   George Gomez, a 43-year-old middle manager for an electric
utility who identified himself as a former supporter of Ross Perot,
asked during the meeting whether his 17-year-old son, Sean, would
be shouldered someday with a large national debt. ``I'm not so sure
I got a really solid answer about how we're going to repay the
debt,'' he said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been heavily criticized this winter for staying
in Washington and focusing on the impeachment of President Clinton.
Their new strategy, laid out here on Monday by Lott and Patricia
Harrison, the co-chairwoman of the Republican National Committee,
is to hold town hall meetings _ a political art form perfected by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said that Republican members of Congress would hold 150
such meetings across the nation this year and that he would try to
attend a dozen of them. Ms. Harrison said that the next two would
probably be held in Virginia and Pennsylvania but that the schedule
would depend on the availability of state governors.
</P>
<P>
   Having been bloodied at the polls for their emphasis on
impeachment, Republicans were eager to listen for new ideas on
Monday, even as they stressed tax cuts, and were loath to discuss
the impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans here spoke about the trial only when asked after
the meeting by reporters, and with evident relief that the
proceedings were over. ``This meeting here today is to show we're
through with it, and we're ready to move on,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Having lashed out at the president after last Friday's
acquittal, Lott struck a more conciliatory tone with reporters
Monday afternoon. He said that the president had called him at home
last Saturday at 9 a.m. and that they had spoken on subjects
ranging from Kosovo and health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still the president, and every bill that we pass he has
to sign or veto,'' Lott added.
</P>
<P>
   Lott predicted that moderate Republicans, conservative
Republicans and Democrats would also be able to work together
closely in the Senate despite their recent differences during the
impeachment process. ``We've been in a foxhole together and
survived a crucible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first town hall meeting was held at the Ukrainian Cultural
Center here, partly because the Republican National Committee had
used the community center before and partly because Warren is still
known as a center of ``Reagan Democrats,'' Ms. Harrison said.
``Reagan Democrats'' are politically conservative, outspokenly
patriotic industrial workers who defied their union leaders in the
1980s by supporting Presidents Reagan and Bush in large numbers,
allowing them to carry Michigan, always a fiercely contested state.
</P>
<P>
   But these workers tended to back President Clinton in the 1992
and 1996 elections. Warren, which has 138,000 residents, is the
heart of Macomb County, which lies on Detroit's northeast border.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are eager to woo back swing voters in this
politically important state.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both of Macomb County's congressmen are perennially vulnerable
Democrats. Rep. Sander Levin, who represents the part of Warren
where the meeting was held, has been near the top of Republicans'
lists of targets ever since his district was redrawn after the 1990
elections and has been re-elected each time with only 53 percent to
57 percent of the vote despite strong efforts by unions on his
behalf. Rep. David Bonior, the minority whip, represents the rest
of Macomb County and won only 53 percent of the vote last November.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harrison said Republicans wanted to tell conservative
workers that they were welcome in the party. ``Reagan Democrats,
y'all come in; we've got a seat at the table for you,'' she said in
an interview after the town hall meeting ended.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and the other Republicans spoke in front of a huge canvas
painted with a scene of a pine-fringed lake and emblazoned with the
words, ``Listening to America ... Tax Cuts for Everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Senor, a spokesman for Abraham, said that half the tickets
for the event were distributed by local Republican officials and
the other half were given to people who called after hearing about
the meeting on local television. Those who called were given
tickets regardless of their political affiliations, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Alphonse Singer, a 75-year-old retired unionized auto worker and
former Democrat, said before the meeting that the first economic
priority should be paying down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald W. Pruss, 60, a precinct delegate of the Michigan
Republican Party and a Chevrolet retiree, agreed in a separate
interview after the meeting, although he also liked tax cuts.
``They didn't really address getting rid of the debt, and that's
important,'' Pruss said.
</P>
<P>
   But Betty Norlin, another precinct delegate and a retired
68-year-old manager of a health food company, said tax cuts were
needed now.
</P>
<P>
   While Lott and his fellow Republicans tried to present an image
of united support for reducing income tax rates, Republicans are
deeply divided on tax policy. They differ over whether to pursue an
immediate 10 percent reduction in tax rates or to implement tax
cuts gradually as the projected budget surplus grows.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Fred Upton, the senior Republican in Michigan's
congressional delegation, was not here on Monday and said in a
telephone interview from his district in western Michigan that he
believed that there were not enough votes in Congress to approve
lower income tax rates. Upton said he would push for targeted tax
cuts instead, notably reducing the marriage penalty _ a popular
theme among many social conservatives in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Lott spoke strongly in favor of a 10 percent tax cut during the
town hall meeting. ``The great thing is, it doesn't pick winners
and losers _ it's good for everyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in a brief interview afterward, he voiced a willingness to
compromise on the amount of any reduction, saying that a cut
slightly smaller than 10 percent could be paired with a few
targeted tax cuts, notably an elimination of estate taxes. ``I'm
not dug in or locked into this number or that number _ maybe it
should be 8.7 percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed that 62 percent of the projected $4.35
trillion in federal surpluses over the next 15 years should be
devoted to putting Social Security on a more firm financial
footing, while the rest should be spent on a variety of federal
programs and targeted tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Lott repeated his general support for devoting 62 percent to
Social Security, which would reduce the need for future federal
borrowing and thereby reduce the national debt. But Lott said that
he strongly disagreed with the president on how to use the
remaining 38 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
