<HEADER>
A6237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DAYTONA-NYT &LR;      02-15 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LACK OF PIT STOP, BIG RACE WAS LOST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The yellow flag waved on Lap 175, and for
those lucky enough to avoid the messy 12-car wreck on the previous
lap, there was a tough decision to be made: Stay out or come in?
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Rusty Wallace was leading Sunday's Daytona 500. He
radioed his crew chief, Robin Pemberton, to discuss strategy. Stay
out on worn Goodyears, or come in for some new ones? Since the car
was handling OK, Wallace and Pemberton chose to stay out and take
their chances. Wallace's teammate, Jeremy Mayfield, stayed out,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Their gamble didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon and Dale Earnhardt, who both passed Wallace some 15
laps later and finished 1-2, had come in under the caution on Lap
175 for new rubber. Gordon and Earnhardt, both driving Chevy Monte
Carlos, came to the decision after watching the Ford Taurus' of
Wallace and Mayfield stay out on the track.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was shuffled out of the lead pack with 10 laps left and
finished eighth; Mayfield met the same fate and wound up 20th.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, there was much debate over that final pit stop,
whether the extra grip provided by the new tires affected the
outcome of the race. Some say the fresh rubber made the difference.
Others aren't so sure. In recent years, pit stops have often
decided Nascar races in the late stages.
</P>
<P>
   But Wallace had the day's strongest car. Gordon and Earnhardt
had struggled at times on Sunday to maintain contact with the top
group of cars. But after taking on the new tires, the cars of
Gordon and Earnhardt appeared to outhandle Wallace's. ``Well, I
thought the decision was OK,'' Wallace said on Sunday. ``Looking
back on it right now, maybe if I would have had a little bit more
grip in the tires I would have been able to hold that bottom line a
little bit better, but the car still handled good. I wasn't having
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace added: ``People keep talking about the tires, but the
only thing that lost me the race was that he got a fender
underneath me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, referring to his crew chief, Ray Evernham, said: ``I was
glad that Ray made the call to come in for four tires. A lot of
other guys came in, too, so that helped my decision. My car was
handling great, and with those four tires I was able to make some
pretty, I don't want to say wild, but I was able to make some moves
out there I wouldn't have if I'd only had on the older tires.''
</P>
<P>
   The moves Gordon referred to came on Lap 190, and they were
wild. Wallace was leading when Gordon pulled low on the track and
went to pass on the inside. The problem was, Ricky Rudd's
slow-moving mangled machine was blocking Gordon's path. With a
last-second jerk of the steering wheel, Gordon avoided Rudd, who
saw what was happening and dived onto the infield grass.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's daring move _ made at nearly 200 miles an hour _ surely
will be talked about for years. Gordon's wife, Brooke, told
reporters that she screamed as she watched her husband make the
pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brooke and I talked about it a lot last night,'' Gordon said
Monday morning before his Daytona 500 winning Monte Carlo was
handed over to Nascar for display at the trackside museum at
Daytona USA. ``I would have done it time and time again if I had to
just because it's the Daytona 500. Probably in some races you might
not do something like that. It's such a big event.''
</P>
<P>
   The guts it took to make that move, combined with the smarts it
took to stay out on the track several laps before, are the
ingredients of champions.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's victory was worth a record purse of $2,172,446,
including a $1 million bonus from Winston. And it has him rolling
at full speed toward a third straight _ and fourth overall _
Winston Cup championship. The circuit moves to Rockingham, N.C.,
next week for the second of the season's 34 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think winning on Sunday works a couple of different ways,''
Gordon said. ``It shows these guys that we are back at it again.
They're ready to go and we're going to have to fight them all year
long for it. At the same time, it makes those guys even hungrier to
put us away. They're thinking we're tired of that No. 24 team
pulling into the victory lane. That makes it even more difficult
for us. We already had a bull's-eye on us. Now it's even bigger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
