<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUSPECT-DIAZ-NYT &LR;      02-15 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-DIAZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER'S KINSHIP WITH SLAIN IMMIGRANT FUELS CRITICISM OF POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related NY-SUSPECT-SHOT, NY-SUSPECT-COPS) 
(nk) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was early on the morning after the shooting of a
West African immigrant that Assemblyman Ruben Diaz Jr. received a
call from the commander of a police precinct in his district in the
South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I asked was whether a police officer had been
hit,'' said Diaz, whose sister is an officer assigned to the
precinct. ``But then they told me what had happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Since first hearing the news that the immigrant, Amadou Diallo,
had been killed in a barrage of 41 bullets fired by four police
officers, a number of elected officials have been vehement in their
reaction to the shooting. But few have been more outspoken and
visible than Diaz, a two-term assemblyman who represents the
Soundview and Hunts Point sections of the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz has appeared with the parents of Diallo, speaking
passionately about his contention that young black and Hispanic men
are disproportionately targeted for abuse by police officers. He
has met with the Bronx district attorney and has asked U.S.
Attorney Mary Jo White for federal assistance in conducting the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   And he has introduced legislation in the Assembly that would bar
what is known as the 48-hour rule from being a provision in future
contracts with the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association. The rule,
which gives police officers two business days to consult with union
lawyers before they speak to investigators, was not invoked in the
Diallo case because it applies only when the Police Department
pursues possible administrative charges.
</P>
<P>
   What has fueled his own passions about the Diallo case, Diaz
said, is that the shooting took place in his Assembly district, a
half-mile from his home and three blocks from his Assembly office.
But also, Diaz, who is 25, said he has come to feel something of a
kinship with a man he had never met, the 22-year-old immigrant from
Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I spoke with the commander, I went to the scene of the
shooting,'' Diaz said. ``It was sickening to see all the bullet
holes.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that since those first few hours after the shooting, he
has spoken at great length with Diallo's relatives and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have felt that I have come to know this young man and to
love him,'' Diaz said of Diallo. ``And I have come to realize that
although I am a Puerto Rican man and he is from Africa, the only
difference between us was the half-mile distance between his home
and mine. We're in the same generation, and if it happened to him,
it could happen to me or anyone in my community.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz developed an interest in politics as a child through
viewing the campaigns of his father, Ruben Diaz, a Pentacostal
minister who ran unsuccessfully for the City Council, the Assembly
and the state Senate. The younger Diaz was elected to the Assembly
three years ago at age 22.
</P>
<P>
   He easily won re-election last year. Diaz, who is married and
has two young sons, is also a student at Lehman College, pursuing a
bachelor's degree in political science.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians have accused Diaz of using rhetoric bordering
on the inflammatory in his criticism of the police in the Diallo
case. But Diaz said that he has been measured in his remarks and
that he gives high marks to the overwhelming majority of police
officers in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as a 25-year-old Hispanic resident of the South
Bronx, Diaz said that he was qualified to discuss the interaction
of the police with young black and Hispanic New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most police officers are doing a good job,'' he said. ``But
what I've been saying is that I see a pattern where the victims of
aggressive police conduct have been black and Latino young men. It
has even happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The assemblyman is gaining admirers in some quarters. ``I have
been impressed with him in this situation,'' said the Rev. Al
Sharpton, who has been advising the Diallo family. ``He has not
been afraid to advocate for the people he represents both in the
streets and in the legislative chambers.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to his critics, Diaz said, ``I'm not calling for
people to retaliate. We just want justice in this case. I feel that
if I don't come out strongly in a situation like this, then my
community would deserve another representative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
