<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-EHRLICHMAN-COX     02-15 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EHRLICHMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    John Ehrlichman: Nixon aide key to president's rise and fall
 &HT;    By Tom Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Ehrlichman spent his last years in Atlanta
enjoying his freedom and working to show the public how he had
changed from the hard-bitten Richard Nixon loyalist who went to
prison for taking part in the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman, 73, of (Atlanta suburb) Sandy Springs, died Sunday
of complications from diabetes at Grace Communities private care
facility. A private family service is planned. Atlanta's H.M.
Patterson &AMP; Son, Spring Hill, is in charge of arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   A decorated World War II veteran, lawyer, novelist, lecturer and
amateur sketch artist, Ehrlichman was the presidential adviser for
domestic affairs in the Nixon White House from November 1969 to
April 1973. He was, Nixon said, the ``conscience'' of the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   In the hierarchy of Nixon's first term, Ehrlichman was second
only to the chief of staff, his best friend and former UCLA
classmate Bob Haldeman, who died in 1993. As the palace guard, they
controlled access to Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman and Haldeman fell from their lofty roles and resigned
April 30, 1973. Critics say they took the fall for Nixon, who
escaped impeachment and possible prosecution when he resigned and
was pardoned by President Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman and Haldeman went to prison for their roles in
Watergate, including covering up the June 1972 break-in by White
House ``plumbers'' at Democratic National Committee headquarters in
the Watergate complex in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Once fiercely loyal to the president, Ehrlichman turned on Nixon
after he refused to testify or give a deposition during
Ehrlichman's two federal trials in 1974-75.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman blamed the former president for starting and covering
up Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman was one of the contradictory figures in American
political history. He seemed to bear the persona of a political
ogre and flagrant abuser of executive power when he testified
before the Senate Watergate Committee for five riveting days in
July 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he also was a man who was ``predisposed to be gentle,''
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger wrote.
</P>
<P>
   To be seen as a new person _ markedly different from the
sarcastic, ruthless Machiavelli during the hearings _ seemed most
important to him. ``I would hate to think that the way I was in
those five days is the way I really am. But that image is out
there, embedded in the memory of people. I frequently hear people
say, `You aren't the way I remember you.' I never was, in that
sense,'' Ehrlichman told Don O'Briant of the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution in 1992. The ex-presidential adviser still was
working to tell his side of Watergate almost three decades after it
happened. In 1997, he worked with novelist Tom Clancy and Cobb
County, Ga. film producers Thomas J. and Mark Barnette to produce
the Watergate documentary, ``John Ehrlichman: In the Eye of the
Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman was married three times, first in 1949 to his UCLA
classmate, Jeanne Fisher. With the breakup of his second marriage
in 1991, Ehrlichman left his longtime post-prison hideaway in Santa
Fe, N.M., and moved to Atlanta. Here he became senior vice
president for Law Companies Group, an architectural and
environmental engineering firm. In January 1995, Ehrlichman and
Atlanta restaurateur Karen Hilliard married. They traveled and
seemed to enjoy visiting his children, meeting his speaking
engagements and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman was a self-described Christian Scientist teetotaler
and former Seattle Sunday school teacher who, before the Senate
Watergate Committee, criticized members of Congress for drinking
too much. However, to keep him writing a cookbook, Hilliard said,
``We just keep his wine glass full.'' A native of Tacoma, Wash.,
Ehrlichman enlisted in the Army in 1943. He flew 26 bombing
missions over Germany and received the Distinguished Flying Cross.
</P>
<P>
   After his discharge, he enrolled at UCLA on the G.I. Bill
andbecame friends with Haldeman. He received his law degree from
Stanford University in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   As a founding partner in the Seattle law firm of Hullin,
Ehrlichman, Roberts and Hodge from 1952 to 1968, Ehrlichman was an
expert on real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Bored with the law, he accepted Haldeman's invitation to join in
running the 1959-60 Nixon political campaigns for the GOP
nomination for president against Nelson Rockefeller, and for
president against John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman also helped guide Nixon's disastrous run for
California governor in 1962. The Nixon team returned from oblivion
to defeat Hubert Humphrey for the presidency in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman was counsel to the president for the first 11 months
of the Nixon administration, from January to November 1969. He then
moved up to presidential assistant for domestic affairs, a role
paralleling Kissinger's in national security. Ehrlichman argued for
a national energy policy, welfare reform, anti-poverty programs and
liberalized abortion laws.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlichman's protege and former Seattle law associate, Egil
``Bud'' Krogh, headed the White House's special investigations
unit, nicknamed the ``plumbers.'' Ehrlichman was its ``chairman of
the board,'' wrote Frank Mankiewicz, a longtime Democratic insider.
The June 1972 break-in at Democratic National Committee
headquarters by five ``plumbers,'' and their subsequent arrest, was
dismissed by the White House as a ``third-rate burglary.'' It
eventually brought down the Nixon administration. Ehrlichman went
to trial twice. He was found guilty of conspiring to violate the
civil rights of Dr. Lewis Fielding (Dr. Daniel Ellsberg's
psychiatrist), and of three counts of perjury for lying to the FBI
and a grand jury, in July 1973. He was found guilty of conspiring
to hinder the Watergate investigation in January 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Karen Hilliard of Atlanta; two
daughters, Jan Ehrlichman of Santa Fe, N.M., and Jody Pineda of
Seattle; four sons, Tom Ehrlichman of Everett, Wash., Peter
Ehrlichman of Seattle, Bob Ehrlichman of San Francisco and Michael
Ehrlichman of Princeton, N.J.; his mother, Lillian Ehrlichman of
Seattle; and 10 grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of flowers, the family requested that contributions be
made to Adventure Unlimited, Camper Scholarship Fund, 5201 S.
Quebec St., Englewood, CO 80111.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
