<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6245 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     02-15 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
89-YEAR-OLD REBEL WITH A CAUSE HITS ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGUILA, Ariz. - In front of her stretches a straight strip of
miles and miles of U.S. 60 and not much else. Somewhere in the
distance is Wickenburg. It seems a long way off when you're
walking, but it's nothing, really. Not when you've got thousands of
miles to go.
</P>
<P>
   And Dorris Haddock does. The New Hampshire resident is walking
across the country, from Pasadena, Calif., to Washington D.C.,
gathering petitions and drawing attention to the need for
campaign-finance reform. She calculates the trip at 3,055 miles.
She started after the Rose Parade on New Year's Day; walking 10
miles a day, she hopes to get to D.C. by November.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, one more thing _ she's 89 years old. Is she nuts?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my dear friends have said that,'' she said last week,
laughing. ``My family said that. I said, `Look, I've got 10
great-grandchildren in this world. I want them to come into a
democracy that is of the people, by the people and for the people
instead of, of the corporation, by the corporation and for the
corporation.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If one person can do that, I can.'' &QL; 
Longtime activist &QL; 
 &QL; 
She's probably right. Whether protesting with her husband to stop
nuclear testing in Alaska in the '60s _ they lived, for a time, in
skin-covered huts near the Bering Strait _ or working to stop a
major highway from going through Dublin, N.H., where she lives,
Haddock has long been an activist. Not a professional one, mind
you. Although she's plenty savvy about politics, she doesn't spend
her time poring over ``Mother Jones'' magazine, looking for issues.
She just waits for the right one. And then she runs _ or in this
case, walks _ with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see something that's not right and I say, `Can one woman do
something about this? Let's try.' Sometimes, it works and
sometimes, it doesn't. But I keep trying.''
</P>
<P>
   The walk is her biggest effort at activism. She thought the feat
would draw the most attention to her cause. But there's another
reason she chose such an arduous method.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother has always been an adventurer,'' said Betty Lawrenz,
her daughter, from her home in Chevy Chase, Md. ``She just is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrenz, 64, remembered with a chuckle her mother starting
church dances for teenagers, which stirred up trouble for a time
with other churches _ until they followed suit and started their
own dances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a cause she wanted to be a part of, she'll do it,''
Lawrenz said. ``(But) she wasn't doing it all her life. She was
making a living.''
</P>
<P>
   She did that at a shoe company where she worked; her husband,
James, who died in 1994, worked for a utility company. When the
right issue struck, he was just as committed as his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my dad was living, they both did such things,'' Lawrenz
said.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing inflames Haddock like the need for reforming
campaign finances. She'd much rather talk about that, for instance,
than her walk. She's been interviewed on CNN and by National Public
Radio, events that left her a little frustrated _ she felt like the
reporters were more interested in the saga of an 89-year-old woman
walking across the country than the cause itself. But the cause is
what drives her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, to me, is the biggie,'' she said. ``I feel the
corporations have taken over the elections. I feel a poor man has
to sell his soul to run for office because the costs are so
prohibitively high. I find as I go along that people are not
voting. They say, `Oh, politicians are crooks. I don't vote
anymore.' They just feel that they've been isolated from the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Haddock says all this in a crisp New England accent, the words
coming faster and faster as she warms to her subject. That's the
way she walks, too. I walked two miles with her and Doug Vance, a
35-year-old California man who is accompanying her partway; forget
89 _ her pace was brisk for any age.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll cut it down a bit if you like,'' Haddock said, in all
seriousness. No need. Her enthusiasm and energy inspire you to keep
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has an incredible grasp of politics,'' said Dennis Burke,
executive director of Arizona Common Cause. (The group is assisting
Haddock's walk; members and friends have offered meals and
lodging.) ``I think what she hopes is to take an issue that is
fairly complex and ho-hum in the minds of most people and put a
personal face to it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Indomitable spirit' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That face is wrinkled and creased, and topped most of the time
by a disintegrating straw hat. She wears a sign around her neck
that says, ``Granny D _ pilgrim for campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona swing of her trip will take her through Buckeye,
Phoenix, Tempe, Guadalupe, Chandler, Sacaton, Coolidge, Picacho,
Marana, Rillito, Tucson, Benson, Willcox and San Simon (to follow
her progress on the Internet, visit www.arizonatimes.com). She's
never met Sen. John McCain, himself a proponent of campaign-finance
reform, but hopes to. She also hopes to meet Sen. Jon Kyl, and
twist his arm to support her cause.
</P>
<P>
   Can she make it to D.C.? Even Haddock doesn't know. She began
walking 10 miles a day last year to train, said Jim Haddock, her
son. Told she might have to sleep outdoors, she pulled a sleeping
bag into her front yard and slept there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always been a rebel,'' Jim said from the donated van he
was driving, a sort of mobile rest stop for his mother (he'll be
with her a month before returning home to New Hampshire). ``She's
an indomitable spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, at times her age has shown. Haddock developed a mild case
of pneumonia walking through the California desert and had to take
a few days off. Her son worries about her, of course. But she
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it matter to me if something happens to me on the
way?'' she asked. ``That's all right. But if I can just nudge those
senators . . . .'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
