   (NYT7) MIDDLE ISLAND, N.Y. -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- WAL-MART, 2-15 --
The Wal-Mart store in Middle Island. The company, the nation's
largest retailer, has lately been mounting an aggressive expansion
drive with little of the uproar that accompanied its rocky start
earlier in the decade. (Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TORONTO -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- TORONTO-HOCKEY, 2-15 -- Lewis
Mitz, 54, in the dressing room of the Phil White Arena in Toronto,
is one of the ageless baby boomers who play hockey every Thursday.
``Nothing about this place is beautiful,'' he says. ``In fact, it's
pretty rugged. But this is the way Canada lives.'' As a teammate
says, ``This is not about anything except being a boy.'' (Brian
Willer/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- VITAL-SIGNS, 2-15 --
Three-dimensional motion analysis of 20 recreational athletes found
that women run and perform some other athletic movements in a much
less crouched position than men, causing the quadricep muscles in
the fronts of the thighs to generate a great deal of power. In an
awkward movement, like landing on uneven ground, the highly
activated quadriceps have enough force to pull the tibia, or shin
bone, forward and tear the ACL, making women more prone to knee
injuries than men. (Richard Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- NY-GOLDEN-GIRLS-2, 2-15 --
In their customary places in the front row at the Belmont Italian
American Playhouse: from left, Anne Mariano, Marge Cristiano, V
Cauttero and Marie Antoinette Diorio. While members may come and
go, in some form the group has made it to every production this
matchbook-size Bronx theater has presented. (Nicole Bengiveno/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- NY-GOLDEN-GIRLS-1, 2-15 --
Showtime: from left, Golden Girls Anne Mariano, Marge Cristiano, V
Cauttero and Marie Antoinette Diorio. Members may come and go, but
in some form the group has made it to every production the Belmont
Italian American Playhouse - a matchbook-size theater in the Bronx
- has presented. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ARLINGTON, Va. -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- SCI-NSF-COLWELL, 2-15
-- Dr. Rita Colwell is the first woman to head the National Science
Foundation, whose $3.6 billion budget finances basic research. ``I
agree with Harold Varmus, the head of the National Institutes of
Health, who said that human stem cell research is very important,''
she says. ``I think the value to humanity, plus the wonderful
information it can bring about life and development is so very,
very important.'' (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) VERO BEACH, Fla. -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- SCI-MIDLIFE, 2-15 --
Dr. Orville Gilbert Brim, director of the MacArthur Foundation
research network, says of his study, ``On balance, the sense we all
have is that midlife is the best place to be.'' The years between
35 and 65, and in particular the decades between 40 and 60, are a
time when people report increased feelings of well-being and a
greater sense of control over many parts of their lives. (Susan
Greenwood/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
