<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/15/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) CHEVY CHASE, Md. -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- CHINA-HUMMEL, 2-15
-- Arthur W. Hummel Jr. began his career as a China specialist in
the era of McCarthyism. ``There was very little paranoia among
those you worked with because everyone felt like it was us against
them,'' says Hummel, 79. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) FOSTER CITY, Calif. -- Feb. 15, 1999 --
MICROSOFT-PROTEST, 2-15 -- Tim O'Mahoney of the Linux Users Group
and others favoring a free operating system marching Monday near a
Microsoft office in Foster City. Many carried unopened Windows
systems and asked for refunds. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-PISTONS, 2-15 --
Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse, who was 1 for 11 from the field,
looking to shoot between Patrick Ewing, left, and Larry Johnson.
For the first time since the inception of the 24-second clock, the
Knicks held a team to fewer than 70 points for the second straight
game during their 78-69 victory Monday over the Pistons at Madison
Sqaure Garden. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- REVIEW-FASHION-2, 2-15 --
From left, DKNY hand-knit chunky sweater and skirt by Donna Karan;
satin evening dress by William Calvert at the Moet &AMP; Chandon show;
man's jigsaw puzzle shearling coat by Cynthia Rowley. (Corina
Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- REVIEW-FASHION-1, 2-15 --
From left, carmel leather ensemble with a fitted top and fur collar
by Caroline Herrera (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo); man's
classic wool overcoat with a fur and feather stole by London
designer Tomasz Starzewski; his sculptured silk gown with a
bouffant coat of fur and feathers. (Corina Lecca/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- DC-MEMORIAL-FLOATER, 2-15
-- Tourists exploring the columns of the Lincoln Memorial on Monday
in Washington during an unseasonably warm winter day. In the
background are the Washington Monument, which is being renovated,
and the Capitol. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WESTMINSTER, Calif. -- Feb. 15, 1999 --
CALIF-HO-CHI-MINH, 2-15 -- Women protesting Monday at a store in
Westminster, where a Vietnamese immigrant wants to hang a poster of
Ho Chi Minh. Fearing that the demonstration might turn violent, the
police persuaded the shop owner, Troung Van Tran, 37, into staying
away from the store Monday. But Tran's wife, Kim, says ``we're
going to do it another day.'' (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) HONG KONG -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- GLOBAL-ECON-II, 2-15 --
Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin, right, and his deputy, Lawrence
H. Summers, left, the dynamic duo of freer capital flow, at a 1997
Hong Kong meeting of the World Bank. In Asia, a Thai official
recalled, the two men were pushing on an open door. (Robert
grossman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- GORE-POLITICS, 2-15 --
President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore at a recent Social
Security forum in Washington. Gore, 50, has emerged from the
impeachment ordeal in a more commanding position to capture the
Democratic nomination than he would have had the world never heard
of Monica S. Lewinsky. (Carol T. Powers/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MIDDLE ISLAND, N.Y. -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- WAL-MART, 2-15 --
The Wal-Mart store in Middle Island. The company, the nation's
largest retailer, has lately been mounting an aggressive expansion
drive with little of the uproar that accompanied its rocky start
earlier in the decade. (Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TORONTO -- Feb. 15, 1999 -- TORONTO-HOCKEY, 2-15 -- Lewis
Mitz, 54, in the dressing room of the Phil White Arena in Toronto,
is one of the ageless baby boomers who play hockey every Thursday.
``Nothing about this place is beautiful,'' he says. ``In fact, it's
pretty rugged. But this is the way Canada lives.'' As a teammate
