<HEADER>
A6261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COL-DANCERS-NYT &LR;      02-15 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-DANCERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: LOVERS AND DANCERS KNOW MEANING OF `UNREQUITED'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.Y., N.C.)  (jw) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Valentine's Day, thoughts turned to matters both
heartwarming and heartbreaking. They led to the brightly lighted
studios of the Joffrey Ballet School, up two flights from Avenue of
the Americas in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   It was audition day for 200 young people _ just about all girls
in, or approaching, their teens _ who hoped to be accepted into the
school's summer program, a rigorous exercise geared to those truly
serious about dance. No dilettantes need apply, which may also be
said of similar training offered by other New York dance companies.
</P>
<P>
   If they are lucky, to say nothing of talented, a few dozen of
those who showed up on Sunday will hear good news when Joffrey
sends out letters of acceptance or rejection in a few weeks.
Auditions are also held in 16 other cities in the United States and
Canada, with roughly 1,500 children altogether competing for fewer
than 200 places.
</P>
<P>
   In short, as with so many things in New York, this was not a
scene for anyone short of pluck or skill. The girls knew they had
to be _ forgive us _ on their toes.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes ran high as they limbered up in black leotards and pink
tights. That was the heartwarming part. But nervousness poked
through. A foot jiggled incessantly here, a nail was bitten
furtively there. Heartbreak, everyone knew, could be a step away.
``It's very competitive,'' said Edith D'Addario, the school's
director since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   While the girls went through their paces in groups of 45 or so,
Ms. D'Addario and other judges could see almost right away who had
what it took and who did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know in the first five minutes what training the girls
have,'' said Angela Corosanite, who came by bus with 20 young
hopefuls from Philadelphia, where they study at the Children's
Ballet Theater, which she runs. ``They can tell immediately what
technique they were trained in, sometimes even what school.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one will get the final word until the letters go out.
``I don't believe in telling them on the spot, because it's so
emotionally shattering for them,'' Ms. D'Addario said.
</P>
<P>
   The parents did not have it much easier. ``I should have brought
worry beads,'' Lorraine Peate said to Loretta Woods as they waited
in a hallway for the auditions to begin. She was kidding. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peate's daughter, Lauren, studies with Ms. Woods' daughter,
Lisa, at the Seiskaya Ballet School in St. James, N.Y. Yes, said
Lisa, who is 13, she thought she was ready. But when asked how she
felt, she offered a nervous laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're worried about their feelings,'' Ms. Peate said. ``If
they get hurt, you get hurt.'' But there is just so much sheltering
that a parent can or should give, she added, a point that had Ms.
Woods nodding agreement. ``They have to learn to accept
rejection,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There must have been a few stage moms around, the ``Sing out,
Louise!'' types who give involved parenting a bad name. If so, they
did not announce themselves. Mostly, the mothers and fathers lent
their daughters low-key support while trying to keep their own
fidgeting under control.
</P>
<P>
   They were people like Amy Carrasco, who flew up for the day from
Chapel Hill, N.C. Her daughter, Tammy, 13, made it into the Joffrey
summer program last year, but now had to earn her stripes all over
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that the rejection can come, and you have to handle
it yourself,'' Ms. Carrasco said. ``She only reacts as well as I
do. My attitude has to be: OK, we'll keep trying. You have to throw
as many darts at a target as you can and hope one of them hits.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Jessica Concannon's feelings as well. Jessica, 14, was
part of Ms. Corosanite's Philadelphia contingent, which, win or
lose, was determined to have a perfect Sunday in New York,
following the auditions with lunch and then the New York City
Ballet at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty confident I'll get in,'' Jessica said before she
stepped up to the barre. And if she turns out to be wrong? ``I'll
try again next year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So will many of the others, who already put in hours and hours
of work each week, convinced that a dancing career is not beyond
their grasp. In an age when the rallying cry of many young people
is ``whatever,'' their commitment was all anyone needed to
guarantee that the day's heartwarming side triumphed over
heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Carrasco put it, ``to have a passion is a wonderful
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
