<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Last Supper' Site To Close for 3 Months &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The refectory of Santa Maria delle Grazie housing Leonardo da
Vinci's ``Last Supper'' in Milan will close from March 1 to May 27
for completion of a restoration that began two decades ago. The
painting can be seen by visitors during Holy Week from March 30 to
April 4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The delicate operation on the fresco was necessary because the
masterpiece began disintegrating soon after it was completed in
1498, mostly as a result of the artist's unfortunate choice of
medium: not conventional fresco, in which the paint is applied to
wet plaster, but tempera applied to dry plaster.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from as early as 1517 spoke of its deterioration. The
fresco underwent a number of restoration attempts and touch-ups
throughout the centuries, and the refectory that houses it was
badly damaged in 1943 when a bomb demolished the roof of the
building. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This most recent restoration began in the late 1970s and has
involved dozens of specialists and technicians. This is the first
scientific restoration of the masterpiece, following a careful
scientific analysis, where the restorers are removing rather than
adding to the fresco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is that it will be longer lasting than earlier
attempts,'' said Pietro Cesare Marani, a fine-arts expert who has
been closely involved in the project, ``but we aren't presumptuous
enough to believe that it will last forever. Nothing lasts
forever.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Bedtime for Bonzo' In a Presidential Suite &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For his eight years as president, Ronald Reagan almost never
stayed anyplace else in Los Angeles but the Westin Century Plaza
Hotel and Tower. Reagan's 88th birthday was Feb. 6, and the hotel
took the occasion to formally rename its renovated presidential
suite in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, the 8,000-square-foot suite, which occupies the
entire 30th floor of the tower building, will be known as the
Ronald Reagan Suite, and it comes equipped with floor-to-ceiling
windows, a wraparound balcony, two whirlpool baths and its own
butler _ all for just $5,400 a night. The tower was built in 1984
with security in mind _ the suite has reinforced concrete walls,
bulletproof glass, access to a rooftop helipad and its own
elevator.
</P>
<P>
   The most personal touch is the Reagan memorabilia, with more
than 40 gilt-framed photographs chronicling his life, including one
of him happily tossing a paper airplane from the suite's balcony.
Guests will also have a private videotape library of Reagan's
films, including ``Kings Row,'' ``Brother Rat'' and, for late-night
viewing, ``Bedtime for Bonzo.''
</P>
<P>
   The Westin Century Plaza is at 2025 Avenue of the Stars in
Century City, next to Beverly Hills; (800) 228-3000, fax (310)
551-3355.
</P>
<P>
   Todd S. Purdum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Midtown Manhattan Gets 2d Visitor Center &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The theater district of Manhattan will soon be home to another
visitor center, joining the Times Square Visitors Center, which
opened last fall on Broadway between 46th and 47th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The new center will open March 3 on Seventh Avenue between 52nd
and 53rd Street, across from the Sheraton New York Hotel and Towers
and a block away from the Broadway Theater, currently the home of
``Miss Saigon,'' and the Ed Sullivan Theater, where ``Late Night
With David Letterman'' is taped.
</P>
<P>
   Free publications _ including maps, guides and brochures _ will
be offered at the center, which will also provide help from a
multilingual staff.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive electronic kiosks will feature updated information
on attractions and events throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   Admission tickets for some museums and attractions such as the
Brooklyn Museum of Art will be sold at the kiosks. An ATM will
accept major bank and credit cards, and souvenirs sold at the
center will not be available anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The Visitor Information Center, 810 Seventh Avenue, (212)
484-1222, will be open weekdays from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m., and weekends
from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 European Tours Strike Classical Music Themes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a year that commemorates Johann Strauss, Chopin, Schoenberg
and Smetana, among other composers, Vienna will be a major stop on
many tours. In the Footsteps of the Great Composers, a 12-night
program that visits Vienna, as well as Prague and Budapest, departs
May 6, Sept. 23 and Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   A seven-night Storybook Musical Adventure cruise on the Danube
aboard the river cruiser Mozart calls at Durnstein, Vienna,
Esztergom, Budapest, Bratislava and Melk and Grein. Departures are
May 26, following three nights at the Vier Jahreszeiten Hotel in
Munich, and Sept. 22, with three nights at the Bayerischer Hof
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Both programs offer tickets to concerts and operas, backstage
visits and a classical-music expert as guide. The Storybook cruises
will also be accompanied by George Shangrow, musical director of
Orchestra Seattle, and Joseph Fratianni, an American classical
guitarist who lives in Salzburg.
</P>
<P>
   The Footsteps tour is $6,615 a person, double occupancy,
including round-trip air fare from New York. Storybook fares range
from $5,770 to $7,965, depending on cabin, and also include
round-trip air fare from New York. Information: I.S.T. Cultural
Tours; (800) 833-2111, fax (212) 594-6953. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Museum Celebrates New Space &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Heard Museum in Phoenix, known for its extensive collection
of Native American, African and Oceanic tribal art, is growing. In
a series of events beginning next Sunday, the museum will celebrate
a 50,000-square-foot expansion that creates room for three new
galleries, a studio for artists in residence, an auditorium, an
education pavilion, a cafe and a bigger shop. With a total of
130,000 square feet, the museum hopes to better accommodate annual
attendance of over 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The grand opening on Sunday, with free admission, will feature
artist demonstrations, crafts activities, music and dance
performances and offerings of traditional Native American foods.
</P>
<P>
   The Heard's annual two-day Indian fair and market begins March
6, with close to 500 Native American artists selling their pottery,
jewelry, basketry, weavings, carvings, paintings and sculptures.
Musicians and dancers will also perform.
</P>
<P>
   On March 20 and 21, the museum will hold the World Championship
Hoop Dance Contest, with dancers from the United States and Canada
moving in and out of hoops in creative displays of athleticism and
grace.
</P>
<P>
   During all these events, visitors will be able to view several
exhibitions in the new and old galleries, including ``More Than
Art,'' an introduction to native cultures; two exhibits of
contemporary Indian art; ``Horse,'' which uses saddles, tack,
blankets and other artifacts to explore the meaning horses hold for
Native Americans in the West and Southwest, and ``Cradles, Corn and
Lizards,'' a hands-on exhibit about the relationships among
Arizona's tribes, plants and animals. Zuni artifacts from the 20th
century are featured in ``Blue Gem, White Metal: Carvings and
Jewelry from the C.G. Wallace Collection.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heard Museum, 2301 North Central Avenue, is open daily.
Admission is $7, $6 for seniors and $3 for ages 4 to 12.
Information: (602) 252-8848; www.heard.org.
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
