<HEADLINE>
SPAIN'S CASALS MUSEUM  
 NEW LONDON FESTIVAL  
 KONA FISHING CHARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics) Do you have information on the Pablo Casals museum
in Barcelona? _ Maria Hernandez, New York, N.Y.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. The museum, which is also the home where the cellist Pablo
Casals was born in 1876 and lived for 11 years, is actually in El
Vendrell, 50 miles south of Barcelona. The house was opened as a
museum last year.
</P>
<P>
   El Vendrell, which already honors Casals with a copper statue
and a summer music festival in an auditorium which also bears his
name, has lately been sprucing up other Casals-related landmarks,
starting with the birthplace museum, at 2 Calle Santa Anna.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibits there include photographs of the young cellist
wearing a sailor's suit, a piano on which his musician father gave
lessons, and furniture recreating a late-19th-century ambiance in
the narrow, four-story home that his family rented.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the museum is free, and it is open daily from 11
a.m. to 1 p.m. and, except for Sunday, from 5 to 7 p.m. as well.
</P>
<P>
   El Vendrell's City Hall also is directing the $2.5 million
restoration of the spacious Mediterranean beachfront home that
Casals bought in town early in this century. He rarely visited it
after going into exile during the Franco regime. Casals died in
1973, in Puerto Rico, and the beachfront home in El Vendrell, about
two miles from the birthplace home, later became a museum. It
closed in late 1997 for repairs and is expected to reopen next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Another link to Casals is the 18th-century Baroque organ in the
Sant Salvador Church, a five-minute walk from his birthplace.
Casals began playing this organ when he was about 9 years old and
paid for its restoration in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can reach El Vendrell by driving an hour southwest of
Barcelona on the A-16 toll road, which was recently named after
Casals. For more information: (34) 977-665-684. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I've heard rumors of a new literary festival in
London. Can you tell me anything about it? Also, when are the Hay
and Cheltenham festivals this year? _ Anne-Marie Stand, Bangor,
Maine.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. ``The Word,'' a new literature festival, is scheduled to take
place across London from March 19 to 23. Sixty-six writers, 22 from
London, 12 from elsewhere in Britain and 32 from other countries
will participate in a celebration of the written and spoken word.
The director of the event is Peter Florence, who also founded the
annual literature festival in the Welsh border town of Hay-on-Wye.
</P>
<P>
   Some 350 events _ including readings, lectures and workshops _
will take place throughout the 33 boroughs that make up London.
Writers taking part include Antonia Fraser, Doris Lessing, Richard
Dawkins, Orlando Figes, Margaret Atwood, Armistead Maupin, Seamus
Heaney, Ariel Dorfman and Toni Morrison. Among the events are
these:
</P>
<P>
   At 5:30 p.m. on March 21 at the Barbican Center on Silk Street,
Richard Holmes, a biographer of the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge,
will talk about the current boom in biographical writing, followed
by a reading by Joseph Heller at 7:30 (information, (44-171) 638
8891. On March 22, Nadine Gordimer, David Said and David Grossman
will discuss the role and engagement of the writer in society and
political life, and on March 23, Germaine Greer will talk about her
new book ``The Whole Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Both events are at 7:30 p.m., at Westminster Central Hall,
Storey's Gate, telephone (44-171) 494 5371. On March 26 at 7 p.m.
there will be an evening of readings and discussion with Peter
Carey, Ms. Lessing, Chinua Achebe, Derek Walcott and Emily Perkins
at the Commonwealth Institute on Kensington High Street, (44-171)
494 5371.
</P>
<P>
   For information about ``The Word,'' call (44-171) 837) 2555; fax
(44-171) 278 0480. There is no central number so reservations
should be made at each place. Some events are free; others range in
cost to $60.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Sunday Times Hay Festival, runs from May 28 to June
6. Among the writers and personalities provisionally signed up to
appear are the former president of South Africa, F.W. de Klerk, and
the writers Hilary Spurling, John Mortimer, Jan Morris and Paul
Auster. Details will be available in April. Information: (44-1497)
821299, fax (44-1497) 821066.
</P>
<P>
   The Cheltenham Festival of Literature is to take place 120 miles
west of London in the Regency spa town of Cheltenham from Oct. 8 to
24. To celebrate its 50th anniversary, the festival will run twice
as long this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Details will be available in April, with a brochure to be
published in August. For a brochure, call (44-1242) 237377; the
number for reservations is (44-1242) 227979. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I'd like to find out about chartering fishing boats
on the Kona coast in Hawaii. Do you know the names of some
operators? William Keenan, Miami Beach(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Chartering a fishing boat along the Big Island of Hawaii's
Kona coast should not be a problem given the number of outfitters
that offer excursions. Dozens of boats are available for full- and
half-day trips from Honokauau Harbor, just outside the town of
Kailua Kona, off Route 19.
</P>
<P>
   The water offshore is celebrated for its bounty of marlin,
yellowfin tuna and mahi-mahi. While all three fish may be caught
throughout the year, the best season for marlin (the most
sought-after fish, which can weigh well over 1,000 pounds) is
January to March, and July to September; yellowfin tuna abound in
the summer; and mahi-mahi are most frequently caught after winter
storms. Because the climate is so temperate, rough seas are
relatively uncommon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The price of hiring a boat usually includes a captain and crew,
fishing bait and the use of fishing tackle. However, passengers are
usually asked to bring their own food and drinks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boats are generally 30 to 35 feet in length and limited to four
to six passengers. Most excursions stay within about 10 miles of
shore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charter boat operators from Honokauau Harbor include: Notorious
Sports Fishing, $475 per eight-hour day on a 35-foot boat, and $350
for a four-hour half day, (808) 325-7558; Why Knot, $375 a day,
$250 for half day, on a 31-foot boat, (808) 937-4144; and Kona
Marina Sports Activities, $600 (for a 35-foot boat) to $1,000 a day
for a 50-foot boat (half-days are discouraged), (800) 347-2271.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact the Hawaii Visitors Bureau, Big
Island at (808) 329-7787.
</P>
</TEXT>
