<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN SCHEDULE HEADING BACK TOWARD NORMAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DAN REED 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ American Airlines operated nearly 90 percent of its
scheduled flights on Monday, for the first time since Feb. 7, as
the number of pilots still out sick dwindled to fewer than 800.
</P>
<P>
   American cancelled about 250 flights on Monday, and it expects
to operate 99 percent of its 2,250 scheduled flights on Tuesday,
said Robert Baker, executive vice president of operations. The
airline plans to cancel only 18 flights, mostly on long-range
international routes, because cockpit crews aren't yet in position
to fly the return legs, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, negotiations between the Fort Worth-based carrier's
management and the Allied Pilots Association, the union that
represents American's pilots, resumed for the first time since
Thursday. The talks continued into the evening, and were expected
to continue on Tuesday, but neither side would say whether they
made progress toward a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   American has cancelled more than 6,000 flights since Feb. 5,
disrupting the travel of an estimated 600,000 people, after large
numbers of pilots called in sick to protest the specifics of
American's plan for combining the recently purchased Reno Air with
American.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Joe Kendall in Dallas came down hard on the
union last week, ordering it to deposit $10 million with the court
by Tuesday, as a down payment on contempt of court fines, and
damages incurred by American. Union President Rich LaVoy and Vice
President Brian Mayhew were told to deposit $10,000 and $5,000,
respectively. Kendall is expected to assess fines and damages at
hearing scheduled for Wednesday in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall ruled that Allied Pilots leaders were in contempt of
court when they didn't do enough to encourage their members
participating in the sickout to return to work, as he had ordered
them to do last Wednesday. The number of pilots on the sicklist
grew by several hundred after Kendall issued his back-to-work
order.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, on Friday, the number of pilots on the sick list
hit 2,473. American has 9,300 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials declined to answer questions on Monday. They
were working on two items of business: urging pilots who remained
on the sick list to call in and declare themselves fit to fly; and
responding to Kendall's contempt ruling and his ruling in favor of
American on underlying issue of the case, that the sickout was
illegal under the federal Railway Labor Act.
</P>
<P>
   While union officials are considering an appeal, they have no
choice but to comply with the judge's order to deliver a check to
his office by noon Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The union has an estimated net worth of about $38 million. But
much of that money is invested in securities and property,
including a new office building that opened late last year in far
east Fort Worth. LaVoy said Sunday the union does not have $10
million in cash and will have to convert some of its invested
capital into cash to comply with Kendall's order.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's revenues are expected to continue to suffer, both
because of consumers' hesitancy to book the airline in the wake of
last week's disruptions, and because it plans to reduce its
schedule as a defensive move against future cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   The airline plans to cut back its daily flight schedule by about
2 percent in the months of March, April and May, or about 45 to 50
flights a day, because management does not believe enough pilots
will volunteer to fly additional hours each month to cover all
2,250 flights now on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Although the pilots' sick roll is only a third as long as its
was at the peak of the sickout on Thursday and Friday, there
continued to be nearly twice as many American pilots out sick than
400 who normally would be out ill at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, American officials spoke optimistically about getting
their carrier's operation back up to full speed by Wednesday. And
they said they are determined to restore both consumers' confidence
in American and the morale of those employees who bore the biggest
part of the burden created by the sickout that began Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not necessarily talking about a big fare sale,'' a common
response by airlines whose operations have been disrupted by labor
strife, Baker said. ``We've got a number of heavy promotional
efforts we're going to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker also said the airline has ``a lot of work to do within our
own company to get this thing put back together right.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker _ to whom the pilots report _ and Cecil Ewell, American's
vice president of flight and chief pilot, later this week will
launch a whirlwind tour of the airline's various pilot bases, where
they plan to listen to pilots' concerns about the integration of
Reno Air and the more deeply-rooted problems that both sides agree
were the underlying causes of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Baker, American Chairman Donald Carty, and other
senior executives are urging American's nearly 80,000 non-pilot
employees to not be upset at the American pilots, 75 percent of
whom did not participate in the sickout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need everybody working together to rebuild the traveling
public's trust in our company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
