<HEADER>
A6280 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PISTONS-NY     02-15 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PISTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHT-FISTED KNICKS BEAT PISTONS, 78-69 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (Eds: See also BKN-ARATON-COLUMN) 
(mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Wingate stepped onto the floor with hair as
gray as a cloudy day, lug nuts for knees and an aging thin frame. A
player fit for a cardigan and a game of bingo. But the 35-year-old
reserve, who was sitting next to Siberia on the Knicks' bench, did
not spend Monday afternoon in search of a catnap.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a lively Wingate sneaked into the game for 30 pivotal
seconds. For half a minute, Wingate leaned on his 12 years of
experience and the mental notes he had been taking on Detroit's
Grant Hill through nearly three quarters of a sleep-inducing game.
For half a minute, Wingate gave up 3 inches, 40 pounds and,
ultimately, his body to guard Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Wingate was flat on his back after taking a charge
with 5.4 seconds left in the third quarter. Suddenly, the groggy
Madison Square Garden crowd lifted its voice in approval as yet
another Hill-led comeback attempt was snuffed out. In one microcosm
of the game, Wingate displayed the kind of smart, physical and
energetic defense that led the Knicks to an esthetically
displeasing, but perfectly satisfying, 78-69 victory against the
Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach just asked me to go out and play good defense for 30
seconds,'' said Wingate, who has played just four total minutes in
five games for the Knicks(3-2). ``I was in the game and paying
attention. We go over everyone's tendencies and weaknesses. I knew
what Grant liked to do and didn't like. I knew to keep the ball in
his left hand, and shade more to his right. I stuck to the details
and played aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   A little brains and a little brawn. This is how a Knicks team
that went 12 minutes without a field goal and shot zero for 13
during one unbearable stretch of the second half managed to win
anyway. This is how they contained Hill (31 points) and shut down
the satellites that whirl around him. No other Piston _ not Jerry
Stackhouse (one for 11) nor Joe Dumars (0 points) _ scored in
double figures on a team that shot 33.3 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   And this is how you make team history. For the first time since
the inception of the 24-second clock, the Knicks held a team to
fewer than 70 points for the second straight game. Three days
earlier, the Bulls managed to squeeze just 68 points out of the
tight-fisted Knicks. Part of their opponents' paltry sums can be
attributed to the hangover effect of the National Basketball
Association's lockout. But the Knicks can take credit as well.
</P>
<P>
   They made the Pistons sweat every shot. It was in the way Chris
Childs (four steals) attacked Hill (four turnovers) when his shift
to guard the superstar came, and how Patrick Ewing (14 points, 10
rebounds) popped up out of the paint like a cork and blocked six
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel if we continue to play the kind of defense we're
capable of,'' said Ewing, who was six for 12 from the field, ``when
our offense catches up to us, we'll be unstoppable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' offense was as lost as a set of keys in the second
half. They looked everywhere, under seat cushions and in their
pockets, but could not unearth a field goal for 12 minutes
beginning midway through the third quarter and ending mercifully
with six minutes left in the game. During that time, the Knicks'
14-point lead began to evaporate as Hill put the Pistons on his
shoulders. With seven minutes left, the Knicks were up by a fragile
four points.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, this would have been Allan Houston's cue to fade
into the background against his former team. Before the game, he
had averaged seven points and shot 28 percent against the Pistons
in the three years since his departure.
</P>
<P>
   But Houston, who scored a team-high 19 points, pressed onward.
It was Houston, struggling to hit six of 18 for the game, who ended
a string of 13 missed field-goal attempts by plopping in a 13-foot
jumper over Hill with 5 minutes 27 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The shot fell like a domino. As the Pistons got as close as two
points with three minutes left, Ewing put down a 14-foot jumper,
followed by another score from Houston. Fighting through a slump _
not succumbing to it _ shows why Houston has the potential to
develop into a dominant star, much like Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of myself that way,'' Houston said. ``The key is to
know that no matter what happens, you have to believe in
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks believed in defense Monday. Wingate revealed just how
deep down the bench that belief reaches. He could have nodded off
in his remote spot on the bench. He could have stepped on the floor
and showed his age. Instead, he showed his experience and acute
attention to detail. It's that kind of effort that allowed the
Knicks to limit the Pistons to fewer than 70 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a terrific accomplishment for us,'' coach Jeff
Van Gundy said. ``Our guys do an extraordinary amount of studying,
comparatively to other teams, concerning film. It's not only as a
team, but on their own, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
