<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6281 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-15 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S SOMETHING MISSING FROM THE LIST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I will be eligible to participate in my company's 401(k) plan
soon, and I would appreciate some guidance as to what percentages
of my investment should go into the following fund choices: Invesco
Select Income, SoGen International, Fidelity Equity-Income II,
Templeton Foreign, Invesco Small Company Value, and Invesco
Dynamics funds. My husband and I are both 35, and we have a
2-year-old child. Retirement is 35 years away. L.C., Cape
Elizabeth, Maine
</P>
<P>
   A. It almost seems that there's something missing from the list.
Usually at the head of such a list is a fund focusing on large-cap
growth stocks, or at least a fund that seeks to duplicate the
results of the Standard and Poors Index. The closest to that you
have here is Fidelity Equity-Income II, a fund which focuses on
large-cap stocks, but usually ends up at the value end of the
investment style spectrum as a result of its search for stocks with
substantial dividend payouts.
</P>
<P>
   The reason I start out there is that you want to begin with what
most people call their core holding, which is a fund that largely
seeks to reflect the results of US economy as a whole, or of the
dominant growth-oriented segments of the economy. If there is
indeed no other large-cap fund available, the best you can do here
is Fidelity Equity-Income II _ a fine fund in its way, but not
precisely the ticket I'd prescribe. But if that's your only
large-cap play, I'd assign half of my investments there. (If there
were an index fund or a large-cap growth fund, I'd change the
prescription to 30 percent in one of them and 20 percent in
Equity-Income II.)
</P>
<P>
   That leaves you with the other half of your investment to
diversify the portfolio. Given your very long investment time
frame, I'd give Invesco Select Income fund a skip altogether _ this
is a fund that invests in long-term bonds, and while it's the
safest fund on the menu, it's also the fund that's liable to
deliver the lowest long-term results. This is the kind of thing
you'll want to look to during the last ten years before retirement,
when you want to moderate risk and preserve the retirement savings
you've built up. But for now, the right percentage for the bond
fund is zero.
</P>
<P>
   Invesco Dynamics fund puts the lion's share of its assets in
midcap growth stocks, and has built a strong record there. If your
401(k) allows you to use any percentage you chose for investments,
I'd suggest 16 2/3 percent; if your plan requires, as many do, that
allocations be made in multiples of 5 percent, I'd bump the figure
up to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Invesco Small-Cap Value fund will complete your diversification
within the US securities market. Although the fund doesn't have a
particularly stellar record _ it's rated below-average by
Morningstar Mutual Funds _ to a large extent that reflects the
general doldrums that have affected small-cap stocks in recent
years, rather than the results of the fund itself. Over the long
haul it should be a winner, and I'd put 16 2/3 percent there, or 15
percent if you have to choose round numbers.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves us with the final 15 or 16 2/3 percent to go into
international stocks. The two choices here _ Templeton Foreign and
SoGen International _ are pretty different, and I'd give the nod to
the Templeton offering. This is a fund that invests nearly all its
assets in non-US stocks, and is one of the oldest and largest funds
in this arena. It's fairly cautious, weighting its investments
heavily in utilities and industrials, but the caution has paid nice
dividends over the years, propelling it to a 10.59 percent record
of 10-year average annual total returns, a figure which compares
nicely to the 8.54 percent reported for the same period for the
average foreign stock fund tracked by Morningstar Mutual Funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am trying to plan an investment strategy for my financial
security in later years. I'm 25 years old and single. I have
$10,000 in cash and $30,000 equity in a new home with a $96,000
30-year mortgage. I have no other debt. My full-time employer will
match with company stock 80 percent of my $35 weekly payroll
deduction for a tax-deferred savings plan. That $35 is the maximum
I am allowed to save at this point. My choices for this money are a
bond fund, a stock index fund, an interest income fund, which I
think is pretty much a money market, an asset allocation fund, a
global fund, and company stock, which I am already getting in the
match funds. How should I divide this up?
</P>
<P>
   N.B., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A. This is a more typical menu than that offered to L.C. in the
letter above, but it's still unsatisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly you'll want to treat the stock index fund as your core
holding, and put 70 percent of the money there _ not because that's
the right number, but because your opportunities to diversify are
so limited.
</P>
<P>
   I'd put the other 30 percent in the global fund, which will
doubtless take your domestic large-cap commitment well beyond that
70 percent. (This is because a global fund means just that _
investing in stocks of all nations, and usually with a very
substantial position in US equities; a foreign fund such as
Templeton Foreign mentioned in the letter above, invests entirely
outside the United States.)
</P>
<P>
   One thing I think too many people, and especially newer and
lower-level employees, are shy about doing is lobbying management
for a broader menu in 401(k) plans and other tax-deferred
retirement savings plans. But if you and a number of your coworkers
politely suggested that you'd like to see some small- and midcap
funds, a pure overseas fund, and perhaps even a fund investing in
the health care sector, perhaps management would listen.
</P>
<P>
   What can you lose? Such options would allow you much better
diversification, and probably would lead you to better returns over
the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker will answer selected investors' questions in the
Sunday Mutual funds and Monday Money sections. Send letters,
including your name, address and telephone number, to: Kenneth
Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
