<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MAYFAIR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYFAIR HOPING TO RECAPTURE MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What can an early-season win on the PGA Tour do
for you? There are the benefits of the winner's check, but for
Billy Mayfair, a win at last year's Nissan Open (in nearby
Valencia) had a lot more effect than just financial.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair capitalized on his playoff win over Tiger Woods at the
1998 Nissan to have one of his best seasons. Now he's looking to
defend his championship beginning Thursday at the Riviera Country
Club, which will host the tournament for the 35th time in its
73-year history of what used to be called the Los Angeles Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different course, so I don't think Billy has much of an
advantage,'' said Scott McCarron, who challenged eventual champion
Nick Faldo into the final round the last time the Nissan was played
at Riviera, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he is defending champion and that makes you walk a little
bit lighter on your toes that week.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair would agree to that. He floated confidently through the
rest of the season after his '98 Nissan victory _ one made more
memorable by the fact he held off long-hitting Woods in a playoff
on a par-5 hole.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair rode that confidence to his best year since 1995, adding
a win at the Buick Open and posting five top-10 finishes while
earning $1,281,685 for his second-highest season total in 10 full
years on tour. He had earned nearly $1 million less the year before
his win at Valencia and had not won in 27 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a thrill when you win, but when you don't win for
a couple of years, it's a much nicer win,'' he said. ``Coming the
way that I won (getting into a playoff with a birdie on his final
hole of regulation) helped Billy Mayfair a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of got my game form back and I beat Tiger in a playoff,
then just went on and played pretty solid the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from last year and in '95, when he won the Tour
Championship and ranked No. 2 on the final money list, the former
Arizona State star was more famous for what he accomplished before
his pro career or before a PGA Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair gave indications of his pro potential in 1986 when he
won the U.S. Public Links championship. The next year he added a
U.S. Amateur title and was named college Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Mayfair and Tammy McIntire were married on the 18th
green at TPC at Las Colinas, prior to the Byron Nelson Classic in
Irving, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be spending most of our lives on golf
courses,'' he explained at the time. ``We thought we might as well
be married on one.''
</P>
<P>
   Turned out, it wouldn't be the final Mayfair family get-together
on an 18th green. Last year at Valencia, Tammy brought along
Rottweiler pups Dallas and Tulsa _ ``our kids,'' said Mayfair _ for
the celebration after Billy held off Tiger in the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Tammy went home at the turn and got them and we kept
them in one of the tents, just in case,'' Mayfair said. ``They
seemed to have a good time out there on the green. Daddy was out of
breath _ he didn't know what to do _ but they were having a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair won't enter this week breathless, except maybe for the
anticipation. He sat out the last two tournaments resting up for
the Nissan and next week's World Match Play Championship at La
Costa.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at Riviera still carrying the confidence he won last
year at Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing was I knew I could win again,'' he said.
``Right now, I'm swinging at it so well, I'm putting so good that
if I hit a bad shot or bad drive, I'm not letting it bother me. I'm
not trying to change anything. . . . I'm not worried about it, I
just go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of the difference from when you're struggling a
little bit. If you hit one bad shot, you want to change
something.''
</P>
<P>
   After the way in played in last year's Nissan, Mayfair hopes
nothing changes this week besides the venue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
