<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-COPS-1,140&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREARMS TRAINING QUESTIONED AFTER POLICE SLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Pa., Calif., N.H.)  (See related NY-SUSPECT-SHOT, NY-SUSPECT-DIAZ) 
 (nk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time was, firearms training for police officers was
all about how to shoot. Now, it increasingly focuses on when to
shoot _ and when not to.
</P>
<P>
   But even as police academies in New York and across the nation
spend more hours and energy on tactics, using interactive videos as
well as role-playing exercises, officers are still formally judged
only on their marksmanship. They win qualification to carry weapons
based on their scores in target practice, not their performance
under pressure in training exercises designed to test
decision-making skills.
</P>
<P>
   The fatal Feb. 4 shooting of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed West
African immigrant, by four police officers has renewed calls among
police critics and black and Latino leaders to improve the training
in firearms use, with a particular emphasis on how the city's
cultural diversity should fit into officers' split-second choices
on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not the shooting, the problem is who they're
shooting,'' said Officer Charles Billups, an 18-year veteran of the
Police Department who heads a statewide group of black officers,
the Grand Council of Guardians. ``Proper firearms training is
knowing when to draw the gun or to keep it holstered, and they
don't get enough of that.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the goal of video simulators like that used by Firearms
Training Systems, a company that provides training programs to 450
law enforcement agencies, including the New York department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absolute worst thing you can have in a no-shoot situation
is an accurate shooter,'' noted Steve Higgins, a former director of
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, who now works at the
firearms training company, which is based in Suwanee, Ga. ``This
has taken training to whether or not you should be shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   When law enforcement experts here and around the nation were
asked in interviews last week to isolate the tenets of arms
training, they struggled to get beyond the generalizations of their
manuals. The policies are written in strong, simple language _ in
New York, for example, officers are told to shoot only as a ``last
resort'' and only enough to stop a threat. But that leaves a lot of
room for interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   What does it take to stop a threat? Can a suspect be stopped
without being killed? As the number of bullets fired at Diallo _ 41
_ is repeated across the city in incredulous conversations, police
experts cannot even agree on whether it is realistic to expect
officers to pause after a few rounds rather than empty their
16-bullet clips.
</P>
<P>
   Firearms training, in New York and elsewhere, starts at the
police academy and continues throughout officers' careers.
</P>
<P>
   New York rookies get 10 days of training in firearms and tactics
during their seven months at the academy. That is less than the 90
hours provided for the state police but about average nationally,
several experts said. Officers then get informal training in their
precincts, and a day of seminars twice yearly when they are tested
again in the use of their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Some departments test officers every month (Los Angeles does so
quarterly) but others require requalification just once a year,
experts said. And by and large, requalification tests only measure
the accuracy of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the scores do is test your mechanical ability to hit the
target,'' said James Fyfe, a criminologist at Temple University.
``The more ephemeral stuff is encouraging officers to approach
situations in a more careful way. I don't know how you can test for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the New York Police Department, when officers are transferred
to undercover assignments like the Street Crimes Unit that was
involved in the Diallo shooting, they attend a special three-day
workshop that includes some firearms and tactics review. An
additional two-day firearms training unit for street crime officers
is being designed and, in the days since the shooting, the unit has
had extra training sessions before each shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our training is very dynamic,'' said Marilyn Mode, the
department's chief spokeswoman. ``We're always looking at different
things to see how we can improve.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 10-day course in weapons use at a firing range,
police academy recruits spend half the time on shooting
fundamentals and reviewing the law and policy on deadly force, and
in firing exercises using 600 rounds of live ammunition. The other
five days are devoted to tactics. Two of those days are given to
the Firearms Training Systems simulator, which uses a
laser-equipped gun and an interactive video to imitate dangerous
situations. In addition, they fire 350 more rounds and take a trip
through what officers call the ``fun house,'' a mock tenement
building filled with surprises that present rookies with common
``shoot/don't shoot'' choices.
</P>
<P>
   At the ``fun house,'' in a large, hangar-like building just off
the main shooting range, yellowed newspaper clippings taped to the
walls tell of police officers killed in the line of duty;
instructors tell students they are trying to keep the collection of
clippings from growing.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the building, trainers act out harrowing scenes by
playing innocent citizens and vicious thugs, harmless junkies and
murderous kingpins. The scenes are crafted to make the students
anxious, and they are often more ambiguous than the situations
described in the department's Patrol Guide.
</P>
<P>
   The fundamental message is simple: Shoot only when life is
threatened, and then only enough to stop the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should shoot when they think their life is in danger, but
that may differ: I may shoot before you shoot,'' said Ron McCarthy,
a firearms consultant based in California who is familiar with New
York's training program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things that are boilerplate, like a deadly force
policy, like the law, and all of those are mitigated by
circumstances,'' McCarthy said. ``And then there's an intangible.
You can be right by the law, and right by the policy, but deep down
inside know that you could resolve this without firing a shot.
That's the ethics thing, that's the personal character, what you
only see when nobody else is looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, New York officers were taught to shoot to kill;
later, the instructions were changed to aim at ``central mass,''
the torso. Now it is ``shoot to stop,'' which is intended to be
more restrained, but is also more vague.
</P>
<P>
   William J. Bratton, the first police commissioner in the
Giuliani administration, said in an interview that officers should
fire several bullets and then reassess the threat. But others say
that is unrealistic in the rapid-fire world of semiautomatic
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not Picasso,'' said Aaron Rosenthal, a retired New York
officer who now teaches at John Jay College of Criminal Justice.
``You don't paint and then step back to admire your work.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 2203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
