u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUSPECT-COPS-2NDTA     02-15 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-COPS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: your work.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If officers are mistaken in their perception of threat, not
pausing can result in a barrage of bullets like the 41 fired at
Diallo; if the threat is real, pausing can be deadly to the
officers.
</P>
<P>
   New York's policy on the use of force goes beyond state law and
is more restrictive than that of the FBI, forbidding officers to
fire from or at moving vehicles, to sound warning shots, or to
shoot at a fleeing felon. National experts praised both New York's
policies and its training regimen as a model for the nation,
although several noted that it is difficult for the department to
find the time and money to keep its huge force of about 40,000
officers in top form.
</P>
<P>
   The department's live firing range accommodates only 150
officers at a time, and the department has only a half-dozen
Firearms Training Systems machines, which cost about $80,000 each.
With large academy classes of 2,000 recruits, ``the logistics of
training them is a nightmare,'' Fyfe said.
</P>
<P>
   Expanded training in other areas, such as the diversity of an
urban population, has eaten into the budget and time available for
training in traditional areas, such as firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have suggested that cultural issues be included
more directly in the firearms training. If a person does not
respond to commands like ``Show me your hands,'' for example, they
suggest that the person may not be able to understand English.
</P>
<P>
   Others have criticized the videos for presenting negative
stereotypes of members of minority groups, and for not including
situations common in New York, such as high-rise apartment
buildings, subways and crowded streets. (The department and the
training company are at work on a video that is specific to New
York.)
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement experts say the best training is just running
officers through as many situations as possible, so right and wrong
decisions can be internalized and recalled instinctively when
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more about software than hardware,'' said Massad F.
Ayoob, a police officer in New Hampshire who heads the firearms and
deadly force committee of the American Society of Law Enforcement
Trainers. ``We educate the brain before the trigger finger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
