<SLUG> BC-ROMAN-RESIGNS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMATOR LEAVING HOME OF `SIMPSONS,' OTHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Phil Roman, founder and chairman of Film Roman,
has resigned from his struggling animation studio after 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 67-year-old Roman and his company, best known as home to
Bart, Homer and the rest of ``The Simpsons'' family for the past
eight years, gave no reason for the departure when it was announced
Friday evening. The company was closed Monday for Presidents Day.
</P>
<P>
   Roman's departure ends a four-decade-plus career that included
25 Emmy nominations, six Emmys and the creation of a company that
employs more than 200 people. Film Roman currently supplies the
animation for a quartet of TV shows _ ``The Simpsons,'' ``King of
the Hill,'' ``Family Guy'' and ``The Downtowners'' _ and is
developing ``Johnny Tsunami,'' a two-hour movie for the Disney
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   But the North Hollywood-based company has never been able to
turn a profit since it went public in late 1996. Film Roman sold
$33 million of stock at $10 a share but investors quickly became
skeptical of its goal to convert from a fee-for-service specialist
to a studio owning its cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   The company began bleeding red ink because its properties were
unable to draw high enough prices to make up for production costs.
Additionally, TV networks were squeezed financially as their
audiences became increasingly fragmented.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which has traded between $1.50 and $3.50 this year,
closed Friday at $2.25, down 18.75cents.
</P>
<P>
   Roman grew up near Fresno in a family that picked crops for a
living. Inspired by The Walt Disney Co.'s ``Bambi,'' he came to Los
Angeles in 1949 with $60 in his pocket and began taking classes in
animation, then broke into the business in 1955 by working on
Disney's ``Sleeping Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   After working on a wide variety of animation jobs, Roman opened
his own company in 1984 with two employees in Toluca Lake and saw
his first production, ``Garfield in the Rough,'' win an Emmy. The
company gained national prominence in 1991 when it took over
production of ``The Simpsons'' and also produced ``The Critic,''
``C-Bear and Jamal,'' ``Bruno the Kid,'' ``The Mask,'' ``The
Twisted Tales of Felix the Cat,'' ``CRO,'' ``Richie Rich'' and
``Bobby's World.''
</P>
<P>
   Roman was replaced in August 1997 as chief executive officer by
industry veteran David Pritchard in an attempt to regain investor
confidence, but the stock has never reached $4 since then. In the
last nine months of 1998, the company lost $3.95 million on
revenues of $22.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Pritchard said, ``Phil is a unique talent and
the impact he has made on the world of animated entertainment
speaks for itself. We have every intention to continue with the
creative passion he instilled in everyone who worked with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
