<SLUG> BC-BKN-TURNER-ALBERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNER RETURNING ALBERT TO TV FOR NBA GAMES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marv Albert's comeback from a season in exile received its
latest boost Monday when Turner Sports hired him to announce
National Basketball Association games for TNT and TBS beginning in
April. He is scheduled to call six regular-season games starting in
April and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Albert was unemployed last season after being fired by NBC and
resigning from MSG Network after he pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor
assault charge for biting a woman during a sexual encounter in a
Virginia hotel room. He returned to work last September, when MSG
hired him to be host of its ``SportsDesk'' program and to call New
York Knicks games on WFAN radio.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, it was believed that Turner was interested in
hiring Albert. But the first meeting with him did not come until
last month. His MSG work will take precedence over his Turner
schedule, and the number of playoff games he calls will hinge on
how far the Knicks advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've followed his progress in his personal and professional
life,'' said Mike Pearl, the executive producer of Turner Sports.
``His name was cleared by the courts and he's taken care of his
personal situation. We did some research, checked with MSG and
everything was positive.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I'd be lying if I said there wouldn't be some
negative reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert, NBC's lead NBA voice for seven seasons, said: ``It's
thrilling to do the game on a national level. I'd hoped that
something like this would take place, but it's just wonderful that
it took place at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert will be in Turner's NBA play-by-play rotation with Kevin
Harlan, Dick Stockton and Bob Neal; Neal's games will be reduced to
accommodate Albert. In addition to NBA games, Albert will call
boxing, 2001 Goodwill Games events and pro football if a league
planned by Turner and NBC comes to life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
