<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN: UNSIGNED, UNSEALED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Dennis Rodman might one day be a Laker _
maybe even today _ but the past few days have proven that when it
comes to the Worm, nothing is certain, or predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Various reports had the seven-time rebounding champion due to
sign over the weekend, but it never happened. Sunday night, unnamed
sources told the Associated Press that Rodman could sign Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen either. A source close to the situation told
the Daily News that Rodman is expected to sign a deal with the
Lakers today. The source added that everyone associated with the
matter is taking Rodman's apparent intentions with a few thousand
grains of salt because, simply, ``Dennis will do whatever Dennis
wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, team officials again denied that Rodman has agreed to
anything and insisted nothing was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   No Rodman sightings, no Rodman signing, no nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, what he wants to do is drag out the process and
maximize his publicity, since there are no negotiations to conduct.
The Lakers can only offer a prorated version of the $1 million
veterans minimum, or about $12,195 per game _ that's $536,585 if he
signs now, and of course less with every game he isn't in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Even players are treating Rodman's supposed interest with
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard he's coming,'' Shaquille O'Neal said. ``But I don't
like to get my hopes up high until it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, I know as much as you guys know,'' he said.
``I wake up every morning and go though the same ritual. I read the
articles that you write. The other day it said, `Rodman chooses
Lakers.' I thought he was coming. I'm not sure now.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, coach Del Harris, already coping with endless roster
uncertainties caused by injury and illness, wants the matter
resolved this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping,'' he said. ``Hopefully we can settle and be who
we're supposed to be and commit to one another and say, `Hey this
is our team and we're going to make things happen in a very
positive manner for ourselves.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's arrival would probably knock Robert Horry out of the
starting power-forward slot and potentially knock a player off the
roster entirely. Add that to the persistent rumor that Elden
Campbell and Eddie Jones will be traded to Charlotte for Glen Rice
once Rice is healthy, and it's clear the Lakers (3-3) are swimming
in uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it does weigh on our players a little bit,'' Harris
said. ``It's not the best situation, where you feel like you have a
good team and yet so many of the players think that maybe they're
going to be (traded) or replaced in some way. I want our guys to
know the likelihood of changing is minimal and that it's just the
nature of the beast. And that we can't use that for any kind of
excuse for not playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to us, no matter what is being said, to perform to our
utmost. Our guys are good enough players, they should have
confidence in their own abilities and not worry about what people
might be saying.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are mostly tuning out the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really haven't talked about it that much,'' guard Derek
Fisher said. ``Nobody in the front office has come to us and said
these rumors are true, so as far as we're concerned, he's not part
of the team. It's not our position to assume (anything).''
</P>
<P>
   But is it a distraction?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Fisher said, ``our distraction is losing games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
