<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-HUMMEL-NYT     02-15 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HUMMEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WITNESS TO A SMEAR: `WHO LOST CHINA?'
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Md., W.Va.)  (Eds., also filed in `i' category) 
(fb) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arthur W. Hummel Jr. is far from China these days, but it is
never far from his mind. The living room walls of his modest
red-brick house in Chevy Chase, Md., are covered with the delicate
screens and placid clay figurines he collected in China first as a
child, then as a teacher, then as an unlikely soldier and finally
as U.S. ambassador from 1981 to 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The hum of nearby traffic is muffled by a thick stand of bamboo
he planted alongside his driveway, and he is hard at work
translating into English the memoirs of a Nationalist Chinese
guerrilla leader.
</P>
<P>
   With the death this month of John S. Service _ the first of the
so-called ``China hands'' falsely accused of being Communist
sympathizers and driven from the State Department in the 1950s _
Hummel, 79, took an afternoon last week to recall an era when his
long career as a China specialist was just beginning and he watched
paranoia and demagoguery prematurely end the careers of so many
others.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fate that struck closer to home for Hummel than for
many of his young colleagues. His life before coming to the State
Department closely mirrored that of Service and a handful of other
China experts whose careers were destroyed. Though about a decade
younger, he too was born in China, the child of missionary parents,
with a knowledge of the language and culture much deeper than that
of his superiors in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Hummel joined the State Department in 1950, the year that North
Korea invaded South Korea. It was also the year that Sen. Joseph
McCarthy stood up in Wheeling, W.Va., and first announced that he
had a list of 205 people ``known to the secretary of state as being
members of the Communist Party and still working and shaping the
policy of the State Department.''
</P>
<P>
   The climate at Foggy Bottom then was one of circled wagons, but
a growing sense of bewilderment and anger, he recalled. ``There was
very little paranoia among those you worked with because everyone
felt like it was us against them,'' he said. In fact, one of
Hummel's first jobs was helping Oliver Edmund Clubb, another of the
accused China hands, compile documents for his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we all discussed it a lot,'' Hummel said. ``Where is it
going to go next? What kind of idiocy can right-wingers be
perpetrating next _ maybe domestically, and not just foreign
affairs?''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, Hummel had little to worry about. He had an
anti-Communist credential that even McCarthy would have had trouble
tarnishing: during World War II, for 15 months, he had actually
fought against both the Chinese Communists and the Japanese with a
column of Nationalist Chinese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   In his low, gravelly voice, Hummel does his best to play down
any heroic Hemingway plot lines. At that point in his life, during
his early 20s, he said, he was simply trying to find anything to
occupy his time and ``get my parents off my back.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been born in Shanxi province, west of Beijing, where his
father _ a noted Sinologist and later head of the Oriental book
division of the Library of Congress _ was then a Congregationalist
minister. The family returned to the United States when Hummel was
8, and he struggled for a sense of belonging. He said he was kicked
out of two prep schools and dropped out (``well, actually, flunked
out'') of Antioch College. He then lived as a self-described
``early hippy,'' working a series of odd jobs _ including factory
worker and detective _ before agreeing to go back to China in 1940
to help his father on a book-buying trip.
</P>
<P>
   But his father ended up not going, and on the day the Japanese
invaded Pearl Harbor, Hummel was rounded up and locked in an
internment camp along with about 2,000 other foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way,'' he explained, ``to ask the Japanese
kindly, `Would you let me go home?''' So he and a British friend
engineered an escape with the help of Nationalist guerrillas
concealed nearby. He crawled over barbed-wire and walked most of
the night and the next day.
</P>
<P>
   He was 20 and had no military training. But he was handed a
small Belgian pistol, and he had little choice but to stay and
help, harassing Japanese patrols by night and trying to defend a
small patch of land against a communist takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why, but I really cannot remember being scared,''
he said. ``It all seemed like great fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after McCarthy's fall, Hummel said he liked to joke that
he ``was too small a fish for him to be interested in, but if he
had ever hauled me up for a hearing, I would have said, `I was
fighting Chinese communist troops in 1944. Where were you,
senator?''' Through his experience, though, he learned of the
corruption of the Nationalist leadership, which later became the
refrain of Service and his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back now, Hummel said perhaps the only shortcoming of
many of those drummed out of the State Department was a lack of
political sophistication. Clubb, for example, read from his diary
during a hearing. McCarthy then subpoenaed the whole diary and
``went through it with a red paintbrush'' to make it appear that
Clubb was disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   As senators only a few miles away wrapped up the impeachment
trial of a president, Hummel recalled those earlier years as a
crisis in government still unlike any he has known. ``We worried
not merely about these people,'' he said, ``but about the whole
apparatus of government. It was a feeling of, `What the hell is
happening?' and `Thank God,' when it was over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 2212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
