<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6307 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-95     02-15 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BATTLE OF BAGS, CONFUSION RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Iowa, N.Y., Mo., Kan., Fla., Wash.)  (For release Sunday, Feb. 21.) 
(jw) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The airlines are all driven by the same need: to get passengers
aboard smoothly, latch the luggage bins and take off on schedule,
without alienating the customers who are dragging their belongings
aboard. In addition to the unarguable safety problems created by
overloaded luggage bins and obstructed aisles, late flights cost
airlines profits.
</P>
<P>
   But in the domestic-flight carry-on luggage wars, the airlines
are setting varied rules. The results are confusing, and
particularly maddening for the passenger in a rush whose bag is
deemed one too many for the cabin and has to yield it.
</P>
<P>
   The evolving tug-of-war at the boarding gate is partly caused by
passengers' fear of losing checked luggage, a possibility that
increases with the number of connections. Pilfering from luggage is
also a worry. And even if nothing evil happens, there is the
irritating wait for bags at the carousel.
</P>
<P>
   And some people truly cannot check everything: Families with
toddlers must have diapers and bottles on hand, and for speed in
debarking, usually take the opportunity offered by early boarding
to get strollers aboard. Flight attendants may initially let them
pass, but may have to reverse themselves in the crunch. And parents
are not the only ones: Researchers need to keep original materials
in sight; antiques and fragile acquisitions are not always packable
for checking.
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight major airlines, four _ Northwest, American, TWA and
Southwest _ fall into a semitough category of enforcing their
carry-on rules but not going out of their way to do so. Continental
and US Airways appear to be the most carry-on-friendly. United and
Delta, both enforcing size rules with templates outside their
security barriers, are the toughest.
</P>
<P>
   The differences are so pronounced that late last year,
Continental _ which is enlarging the luggage bins on 184 MD-80s,
737s and 757s _ sued Delta for what it considered overzealous
enforcement. As it happened, last fall, Gordon Bethune, the chief
executive of Continental, was at the San Diego airport, where his
airline and Delta share a concourse, where Delta had installed its
metal template. Carry-on bags had to fit through the hole _ 9
inches high and 14 inches wide _ and if not, they were taken away
for checking.
</P>
<P>
   Bethune watched as some Continental passengers, unable to get
their bags through, according to David Messing, a Continental
spokesman, ``experienced great frustration.'' Continental, which
has no measurement requirements for carry-ons, then told Delta to
remove the template. When Delta did not, Continental sued on Nov.
24. Two months later, Messing said, Delta took the template down
and Continental dropped its suit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment, Kay Horner, a Delta spokeswoman, said her line
had a policy of saying nothing about the suit, even if it had been
settled. At the end of January, Ms. Horner said that Delta had
templates in place at about 10 airports nationally.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines is using templates with those same dimensions on
its security machines. According to Joseph Hopkins, a United
spokesman, the first installation was in Chicago in November, after
a test in Los Angeles. They are now in 27 domestic airports, mostly
big ones.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, suitcases with the proper dimensions will not fit
because overpacking makes the soft sides protrude. Hopkins said
passengers had been seen taking out clothes and putting them on, or
stuffing sweatshirts into pockets. Garment bags, the staple of the
business traveler, sometimes go through, he said, but they have to
wrap up pretty snugly to meet the nine-inch requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said that where there were common concourses and
airlines shared the security costs, United got its neighbors to
support the use of templates as a way of speeding planes on their
way.
</P>
<P>
   United also conducted a well-publicized experiment on its
flights out of Des Moines 15 months ago. Passengers who bought the
cheapest coach tickets were limited to one carry-on.
</P>
<P>
   Although first-class and business-class passengers always have
more latitude for stowing luggage, United's test was an opener to a
further refining of the idea that ticket dollars buy better bin
space as well as more leg space. United's effort, not a success,
was quickly ``declared over,'' according to Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its Procrustean bed, United is joining luggage-friendly
Continental in increasing the depth of bins on its 737s by 2.5
inches. This measurement means that four of the wheeled suitcases,
called ``wheelies,'' will go into a bin side by side if the wheels
face outward. Shallower bins will hold only two of these bags end
to end.
</P>
<P>
   The retrofitting will not change United's rule limiting each
passenger to two bags, but it may mean that fewer passengers
boarding at the end of the process will have to check their bags
willy-nilly because the bins are full. The 59 737s used by United
on its West Coast Shuttle will have deeper bins by the end of May,
as will all 182 of its 737s by the end of October, Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   When the templates first went up, Hopkins said, there was
considerable tension. ``But as we have settled in, those who fly
frequently have adapted what they carry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other airlines, middle-of-the-road TWA is testing
templates at La Guardia in New York and Kansas City, where,
according to Jim Brown, a spokesman, TWA need not get any other
line's agreement on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Many airline officials concurred with the view that the earlier
in the departure process luggage is measured or counted, the easier
the boarding goes. For that reason, smaller airlines frequently
accede to the big lines' wishes for templates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines limits its passengers to one carry-on,
although a briefcase, purse or umbrella is permitted in addition.
The seven other lines allow two carry-ons within their specified
dimensions. What else is permitted often depends on size: A purse
of briefcase dimensions may not qualify. Except at Continental and
US Airways, most garment bags are not making the cut in coach.
</P>
<P>
   But these rules are not absolute. On a lightly booked flight,
passengers are welcomed aboard with additional dunnage. On a full
flight _ increasingly common _ airlines with two-bag limits simply
take the second bag away from people waiting to board, especially
toward the end of boarding. On a United flight to Denver last
winter, two agents stood observing the flow into the plane. Behind
their backs, they held batches of luggage tags to pop onto second
carry-ons that they would not allow into the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   All the airlines say boarding by row, from the rear forward, is
essential for on-time departure, because it means people are not
squeezing past one another. But they all let their higher-level
frequent-flier members board when they like; TWA calls for them
first. This means that people with 20,000 or 25,000 miles in their
accounts, and the gold or platinum plastic card to prove it, get to
shove their two bags into the bins before the limit is lowered.
</P>
<P>
   American, which described its position on luggage as in the
middle, is not modifying its existing bins, but rather, getting
bigger ones on its new Boeings. Tim Smith, an American spokesman,
was asked about letting its premium frequent-flier members aboard
early. In the summer of 1997, he said, American began to ask its
Aadvantage members to show their cards, which have magnetic
stripes. ``We thought there might be some resentment,'' Smith said,
``but it turned out that the members liked that recognition and it
works well.''
</P>
<P>
   The carry-on issue is causing problems all the way back to the
luggage store. Most purchasers are not going to buy a bag 10 inches
thick when it may have to be pushed through a 9-inch template.
</P>
<P>
   Anne DeCicco, executive vice president of the Luggage and
Leather Good Manufacturers of America, said that all association
members and retailers were now being told that nothing should be
described or sold as a carry-on bag if it exceeded the dimensions
of 22 by 14 by 9 inches, which is known in the trade as a ``45-inch
bag'' because that is what the dimensions add up to.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeCicco's association petitioned the Federal Aviation
Administration in December for a standard carry-on rule to be
applied to all domestic airlines, as did the Association of Flight
Attendants. Both want to take the issue out of competition among
airlines. There has been no response to either, but Margaret
Gilligan, deputy associate administrator of the FAA, said she
believed the carry-on situation was improving anyway because
passengers were being educated by airlines and the media about
limited cabin space.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeCicco and Ms. Gilligan scheduled a joint news conference
for Saturday in Orlando, Fla., to press a new campaign: ``Think
small, think smart, think safety.'' Ticket-sized leaflets are to be
distributed by airlines, travel agents, luggage makers and others.
Basically, the message is: Be prepared to give up your luggage on a
crowded flight; be sure prescriptions are in bags that will
absolutely stay with you; don't put heavy bags in the overhead
bins.
</P>
<P>
   An unscientific poll about carry-ons was made by CNN Interactive
on Jan. 11. Fifty-one percent of the 31,469 voters said ``strict
carry-on limits'' would be the best solution to ``the carry-on
crunch.'' A better baggage-check system was favored by 26 percent.
Bigger bins and the same limits got 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (According to Kerrin Roberts, a spokesman, visitors to the Web
site were allowed to vote only once, but otherwise the poll
``cannot be presumed to represent the opinions on Internet users in
general nor the public as a whole.'')
</P>
<P>
   Department of Transportation statistics show that the rate of
``mishandled baggage'' for domestic flights rose in 1998 to 5.16
reports of ``lost, damaged, delayed or pilfered'' bags for each
1,000 passengers, compared with 4.96 for each 1,000 in 1997. Almost
all of the 2.49 million mishandled bags covered by the 1998 reports
_ most estimates say 95 percent _ reach their owners within 36
hours. Most did not make their connections or were sent to the
wrong airport through mislabeling.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague owns a bag that will create two blips in the January
1999 ``delayed'' report. Bound for Berlin on Lufthansa, he was
required to change in Frankfurt. He always checks his bags because
he takes books, magazines and work, heavy items he says he has no
wish to carry through an airport. The plane was too late to make
his Frankfurt connection. He got on a flight to Berlin a few hours
later, but his bags, with the bags of hundreds of others, did not.
</P>
<P>
   His luggage, with the requisite dinner jacket, was delivered to
his hotel the next afternoon, in time for dinner. On the way back,
his flight was late, and although he barely made his connecting
flight, the bag did not. It was delivered to his office a day
later. He said that although he traveled a lot, he had never lost a
bag, and seldom suffered delays.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Reich, a lawyer in the law office of Gerald Lefcourt in
New York, lost a suitcase for good on the way to Seattle last
August, although three others made it safely when all were checked
with United by Ms. Reich, her husband and their infant.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reich had a long, fierce correspondence with United, and in
December it paid $1,250 for the lost bag, adding a travel voucher.
``In Seattle for a visit with friends,'' she said, ``and I had to
go shopping for a nursing bra!''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of this sort of inconvenience is what makes
travelers cling to their carry-ons, but if the airlines keep the
squeeze on, travelers will have to learn to pick and choose better
when they pack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 2219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
