<HEADLINE>
DRUGS ARE AT TOP OF THE AGENDA AS CLINTON, MEXICO'S ZEDILLO MEET
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDA, Mexico _ Standing at center stage of an 18th-century
theater in the heart of this tropical city Monday, Presidents
Clinton and Ernesto Zedillo formally agreed to intensify antidrug
efforts by implementing new ways to measure their progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not long ago, we could not have had a conversation about drugs
without falling into an unwinnable argument about who is to
blame,'' Clinton told an audience of 1,500 people, which included
business leaders, Cabinet members, and legislators from both
countries. ``That has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hinted that he would renew Mexico's ``certification'' as
an ally in the war against drugs by March 1. Failure to win
certification could mean loss of most-favored-nation trading status
and economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The visit marked Clinton's first trip out of the country since
he was acquitted on two impeachment articles on Friday by the
Senate. Asked if he felt vindicated by his acquittal, the president
responded, ``This is the time for reconciliation and renewal. What
we have to do is serve the American people. If we do that, we'll be
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidents, who met for two hours  &UR; yesterday &LR;   &UR; morning  &LR; at a
17th century hacienda in the middle of Mayan ruins outside Merida,
also signed modest agreements related to environmental and health
issues and to increase airline business between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they announced $4 billion in loan guarantees for
Mexican businesses looking to purchase equipment from US firms.
National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said the agreement was
important for increasing US exports, which last year increased by
11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the new drug-fighting agreement, Clinton and Zedillo
committed their administrations to following 82 new benchmarks for
determining whether joint efforts along the 1,900-mile US-Mexico
border are successful.
</P>
<P>
   US officials estimate that two-thirds of Colombian cocaine on US
streets crosses Mexican territory. Mexico is also a major producer
of marijuana, opium and amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has come under fire recently from US law enforcement
authorities and Republican lawmakers for failing to extradite more
drug suspects and making fewer drug seizures over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico considers the certification process insulting and blames
much of its drug problems on heavy demand in the United States, but
it has been certified for the last 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although top administration offcials declined  &UR; yesterday &LR;  to say
whether Mexico's certification this year was guaranteed, they
repeatedly praised the country's work. In his address at the
theater, Clinton said the country's efforts have vastly improved
under Zedillo, who recently announced a $500 million drug-fighting
package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico should not be penalized for the courage to confront its
problems,'' Clinton said to applause from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Zedillo called Clinton ``a sincere friend'' of
Mexico and said his people are ``convinced and determined to keep
up the fight against drugs until we win.''
</P>
<P>
   The new drug-fighting benchmarks are meant to help guide
officials in both governments on their work, but are not meant to
be binding, US officials said. Some of the benchmarks for Mexico
include extraditions and drug seizures, while the US must show how
it is succeeding in reducing demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago we developed this strategy and now we have the
concrete steps on practical ways of cooperating,'' the US drug
policy coordinator, Barry McCaffrey, told reporters in a briefing
after the presidents' speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Both governments also agreed to train Mexico's new federal
police force, which officials said will be modeled after the FBI
and represents a break from traditional, corruption-ridden
departments.
</P>
<P>
   Both presidents repeated their praise of the five-year-old North
American Free Trade Agreement, which they say has created jobs and
economic growth in the United States, Mexico and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo credited the pact with generating $185 billion in
economic activity. A Clinton administration official said
 &UR; yesterday &LR;  that 1 million US jobs now depend on trade with Mexico,
which has overtaken Japan as America's second-largest trading
partner. Canada ranks first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we still have work to do on labor, environmental
and other issues,'' Clinton said. ``But NAFTA has taught us that we
have far more to gain by working together.''
</P>
<P>
   Other bilateral measures that were signed include increased
border safety for immigrants, strategies to reduce border pollution
and tuberculosis infections and an order allowing for increased
commercial air traffic, including joint marketing between airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Following the speech at the Peon Contreras Theater, which was
the only public event for the two presidents, Clinton met with US
diplomats stationed in Mexico before he and Hillary Rodham Clinton
returned to Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
