<HEADLINE>
BIG SNOWS BRING SPORTSMEN, BUT ALSO DEADLY AVALANCHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The global weather pattern known as La Nina has been
credited with helping to bring heavy snowfall to many parts of the
West this winter. But while all the snow has meant excellent
conditions for thousands of skiers, it has brought danger as well,
a fact underscored this weekend by a massive avalanche in the North
Cascade Mountains of Washington state that killed a snowboarder and
swallowed a skier who is missing and presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, avalanches also killed five people in
California, Colorado and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cascades on Sunday, the two men had both ventured into a
wilderness area adjacent to the Mount Baker Ski Area, when a wall
of snow at least 200 yards wide and 15 feet high broke loose above
them, roaring down at speeds of 200 miles per hour, said Gwyn
Howat, a spokeswoman for the operators of the ski area. It is about
90 miles northeast of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche killed 19-year-old Justin M. Parker, of Parkland,
Wash., almost instantly. Sean Riches, 25, of London, Ontario, who
was skiing several hundred yards downhill, was buried. A search
Sunday with helicopters and trained dogs flown in from British
Columbia failed to turn up his body, and the fear of another
avalanche on Monday hampered further search efforts.
</P>
<P>
   An avalanche last month in the same area, known as Rumble Gully,
apparently killed Jason Fuller, 25, a snowboarder from Bellingham,
Wash. He disappeared in the tons of snow that rolled down the
mountain and has not been seen since.
</P>
<P>
   In straying off marked ski trails, which are designed to avoid
areas most at risk of avalanche, the men were breaking no law, but
they were flouting widespread warnings of dangerous off-trail
conditions. They would have passed safety ropes and signs alerting
them of a $500 minimum fine for any rescue efforts, and advising
them that such rescues might not even be possible.
</P>
<P>
   Some safety advocates want stricter guidelines to prevent
adventure-seekers from risking their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Venturing outside of the ski area, where about 20 feet of snow
had fallen in the last two weeks, was like ``playing Russian
roulette,'' Ron Peterson, a sheriff's deputy in Whatcom County,
Wash., said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While officials were not sure what triggered the avalanche, the
slightly warmer weather in recent days was a possible factor.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the snow slid three-quarters of a mile down the slope,
creating a draft so strong that it knocked down several skiers on
the trails nearby. Howat said the authorities had put off the
search for Riches in part because they believed the wilderness area
was still ripe for similar avalanches.
</P>
<P>
   All told, nearly 60 feet of snow has fallen on Mount Baker this
season, which, while not a record, is more than in many recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   One major factor is believed to be La Nina, an unusually cold
pool of Pacific Ocean water near the equator that spurs widespread
atmospheric changes. The same weather pattern has been linked to
record snowfalls in Chicago and Buffalo, snaps of arctic weather in
parts of the Midwest and Northeast, and a high number of tornadoes
in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, no stranger to rain, has received 27.44 inches of
precipitation in November, December and January, one of the highest
amounts on record for that period. While most of the region has
absorbed the rain with few major problems, more downpours will
increase the danger of mudslides, which racked the region two
winters ago.
</P>
<P>
   At higher elevations, the huge amounts of snow have posed a
danger as well. A snowboarder and a telemark skier died in separate
incidents at Crystal Mountain, Wash. And near Leavenworth, Wash., a
couple on a snowmobile were engulfed by snow and stranded for 12
days. The woman died, while the man, dazed and racked by hunger and
frostbite, was discovered earlier this month by other snowmobilers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
