<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-VALLEY-HOMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME SALES DIP, PRICES RISE IN L.A.'S SAN FERNANDO VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After maintaining a blistering pace during 1998,
the San Fernando Valley's residential real estate market cooled
considerably during January as single-family home sales fell 12.6
percent from year-ago levels, a trade group said.
</P>
<P>
   Prices, though, continued their steady climb with the median
rising to $190,000, or a gain of 8.9 percent from January 1998,
said the monthly report from the Southland Regional Association of
Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the steep decline in sales, the market remains strong;
last month's 721 closed escrows is the second-highest total for a
January this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's downturn was expected and is in line with an
earlier forecast predicting fewer sales this year than last. It
comes on the heels of a 12 percent decline in December 1998 from
the previous year's volume level.
</P>
<P>
   This two-month drop in annual sales was the first since
March-April 1997, when sales fell 4.6 percent and 3.6 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But in the nearby Santa Clarita Valley, sales kept up a torrid
pace, rising 19.8 percent from a year ago on the sale of 145
single-family homes. Condominium sales rose 39.5 percent on the
sale of 60 units.
</P>
<P>
   The median price _ the point at which half the units sold for
more and half for less _ was $222,800 for a single-family home in
Santa Clarita, a gain of 17.9 percent. The median price for a
condominium was $122,000, up nearly 9 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   Single-family home sales have been torrid for nearly two years
in the San Fernando Valley, a period in which they topped the 1,000
mark for 17 months. That is by far the best run of the decade. And
last year's total of 13,242 single family sales was the most since
1988.
</P>
<P>
   So a slowdown is not causing much concern at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feverish pace started to tail off in November and December
and it continued in January. I still think this is a very strong
market; it's just not going at the pace it was during the spring
and summer of last year,'' said Jim Link, executive vice president
of the Realtors group.
</P>
<P>
   Link expects sales this year to be flat or decline slightly from
the 1998 level. Beth Sommer, the group's president, likewise is not
alarmed. She believes the market is simply catching its collective
breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not see a single negative on the horizon,'' Sommer said.
</P>
<P>
   The market does exhibit signs that the sales drop could be
short-lived. Pending escrows, an indicator of future sales, rose
11.1 percent from December's level, the first such increase in
three months.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the slowing sales is a tight inventory. There are
about 5,170 properties for sale throughout the Valley, with active
listings up 6.2 percent from this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   But that is still about 2,000 units shy of what Realtors believe
is needed to keep pace with demand.
</P>
<P>
   This will keep exerting upward pressure on prices, which should
appreciate between 5 percent and 9 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Los Angeles County Economic
Development Corp., said that low unemployment and interest rates
coupled with strong consumer confidence should keep driving the
market.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks demand is still strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets your attention but you have to look at what is out
there,'' he said of January's sales drop. ``The unsold inventory is
getting kind of thin so people may not be able to find what they
want and price appreciation has been such that it may be another
limiter on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the condominium market gained ground last month.
</P>
<P>
   Escrow closed on 191 units, up 6.1 percent from January 1998.
The median price, the point at which half the units sold for more
and half for less, soared to $123,000, or a gain of 19.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
