A6325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIWI-AIRLINES-600&AMP;ADD     02-15 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIWI-AIRLINES-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DISCOUNT AIRLINE IS IN PERIL AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla., Mich., Minn., Ill., Mass. )  (fb) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe Kiwi International Air Lines is not a phoenix, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the airline, based in Newark, N.J., seemed to be
rising out of the ashes of bankruptcy, rehiring workers and
resuming its low-cost flights to Florida and Puerto Rico, which
have been popular with thousands of New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the airline is in financial peril again. Unpaid bills
are piling up, passengers are complaining about poor service,
once-loyal employees are becoming increasingly disgruntled, and the
airline is in danger of having two of its five working jets
repossessed.
</P>
<P>
   And some days, the airline just seems jinxed. Late Saturday
night, passengers on a Cancun charter flight, which had already
been delayed for 12 hours because of mechanical problems on one
plane, boarded another _ whose right wheel promptly fell into a
sinkhole that opened in the tarmac at Newark International Airport.
A third plane was called in, bouncing passengers bound for Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The company says its troubles are temporary, just one more
chapter in its strange and colorful history. That history began in
1992, when its founders _ former pilots from several bankrupt
airlines _ named it after the flightless bird of New Zealand. Once
owned by its employees, Kiwi now is owned and run by a Baltimore
surgeon who took control with the help of some denizens of Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, customers raved about Kiwi's inexpensive
flights _ $99 to Orlando, a fraction of what the big airlines
charged _ and its service. With the Northeastern economy then weak
and other lines going broke, workers jumped at the chance to get a
job at Kiwi, and New Jersey officials were glad to guarantee its
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the situation is far different. Newark is one of the
busiest airports in the world, and Kiwi's 550 employees there
account for just a fraction of the airport's 18,000 jobs. Strong,
low-cost carriers like Southwest Airlines are bringing competition
and lower air fares to the region. Many airlines have just reported
one of their best years and are vying to hire people.
</P>
<P>
   Kiwi, meanwhile, is struggling.
</P>
<P>
   The company insists that things are not as bad as they may
appear. The number of passengers rose more than 20 percent last
month compared with the previous year. Financially, ``things are
tight, but distressed, no,'' said Robert B. Kulat, a Kiwi
spokesman. ``What for a lot of companies would be a cash crunch,
for us is a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles C. Edwards, the doctor who owns the airline and is
running it while continuing to do spinal surgery in Baltimore,
declined to be interviewed; Kulat said the doctor planned to raise
several million dollars from private investors in the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But outsiders, including former employees, suppliers and lawyers
who worked on its bankruptcy case, are not so sure that it can
recover this time. Its previous efforts to raise cash from sources
other than Edwards have failed, and some of its most experienced
senior managers have left.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the employees, I truly hope Dr. Edwards can find a
long-term partner with $5 or $10 million,'' said Jerry Murphy, who
resigned as president in November after a series of disagreements
with the doctor. ``The company clearly needs an infusion of cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are even gloomier. ``I am personally skeptical about
Kiwi's abilities and prospects _ this is a critical month for
them,'' said Jeff J. Friedman, a lawyer who represents Fly Finance,
which is considering repossessing the two planes it leased to Kiwi.
After a court battle over rental payments, Kiwi agreed to buy the
planes by Jan. 31, but did not. Kulat said the company had received
an extension on its plane leases; Friedman said his client had not
decided what to do about them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At Newark, where most of Kiwi's flights originate and where most
of its 600 employees work, the company is current on its payments.
But the Transport Workers Union and Kiwi are now in mediation over
the flight attendants' contract, said Richard Boehm, president of
Local 504 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest complaint among the flight attendants is the
airline's erratic schedule. In the last year, Kiwi has added and
dropped flights to Detroit, Minneapolis, Flint, Mich., and Niagara
Falls, N.Y. It has pulled out of Chicago and, now, Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Kiwi passengers' complaints to the U.S. Department of
Transportation more than doubled last year, to 209. These
scheduling problems have drawn the attention of the agency's
regulators, who in December met with Edwards to discuss the
airline's financial fitness, a meeting first reported in The Newark
Star-Ledger. Safety was not an issue in these discussions, and the
Federal Aviation Administration has not increased its safety
inspections. ``We are aware of their economic status and we will
monitor that,'' said Arlene Salac, an FAA spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Kiwi has never had a serious accident, but some of its early
problems stemmed from run-ins with the FAA In 1994, the agency
grounded the airline, complaining that it did not have adequate
records of its pilots' training. In June 1996, the airline stopped
flying four of its 15 jets because the FAA said it did not have
enough properly trained pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, the airline filed for bankruptcy protection.
Two weeks after that, it ran out of money and stopped flying.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's executives frantically searched for cash. Soon, a
savior seemed to appear in the form of Joe Logan Jr., president of
a Florida company, Wasatch International. But he could not come up
with the $5 million he had promised. A month later, Logan showed up
with Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards did have money _ the ability to borrow up to $20
million, based on his large real estate holdings. What he did not
have was any experience at all in running an airline _ or much
information, apparently, about his new business partners.
</P>
<P>
   According to a court deposition of Edwards, he did not realize
when he went into business with Wasatch that it was controlled by a
South African with a history of clashes with securities regulators,
who was deported from the United States after pleading guilty to
criminal securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Logan did not return repeated phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
