</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-LOTT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT SAYS HE'LL ENFORCE GOP UNITY WHEN IT COMES TO TAX CUT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN, Mich. _ The moderate Republicans who voted to acquit
President Clinton, including four senators from New England, may
have escaped the full wrath of party leadership during impeachment,
but they had better not even think about breaking away on tax cuts,
Senate majority leader Trent Lott said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be different from impeachment,'' the Mississippian
told a group of mostly Republicans following a town hall meeting in
this working-class Detroit suburb. ``We won't let them off the
hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's remarks came in response to a question from a 60-year-old
retiree about whether the Republican Party planned to rein in
members who voted against the party on impeachment. It fit neatly
into the subtext of the day: redefining the GOP in the wake of the
impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The event, called ``Listening to America: Tax Cuts for
Everyone,'' was the first of 150 such Republican forums planned in
cities nationwide. But it was Lott who ended up doing most of the
talking _ along with Senator Spencer Abraham, Michigan Governor
John Engler, and Representative Joe Knollenberg _ in promoting
across-the-board tax cuts as the best gift the majority party can
deliver this legislative year.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-picked crowd was overwhelmingly friendly to the
participants and their ideas, giving a standing ovation to each
speaker and cheering promises to return money to the taxpayers.
Despite a few critical questions _ about Social Security and
military pay _ the crowd of 400 made it mostly a pep rally for
Lott, giving him an easy backdrop against which to ``move on to the
issues,'' as Republicans, flagging in polls, have said they are
eager to do.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, reiterating remarks he has made several times in recent
weeks, said he was in favor of an across-the-board tax cut.
Although he had previously said he would like to see a 10 percent
cut, he said Monday he could be flexible as long as the cut was
significant and broad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not locked in to only this number and that number. Maybe
it should be 8.7 percent, and take the other part and do something
else with it,'' Lott said. But, he added, ``I think the concept of
an across-the-board tax rate cut is fairer and better for the
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of cut, which is at the center of the Republicans'
post-impeachment message, is already facing serious opposition on
all sides. Clinton has begun a campaign to use the budget surplus
to strengthen Social Security before slashing taxes, and would
prefer that any tax cuts be aimed at targeted groups. Many
Democrats view an across-the-board tax cut as elitist, helping
wealthy taxpayers more than it does the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Most perilous for Republicans, however, may be opposition from
their own moderates, who could help kill the measure, particularly
in the House, where the GOP majority shrank after the November
elections. And from the standpoint of morale, an internal dispute
could also destroy efforts to reunite the party around a popular
cause, a much-desired goal after the impeachment ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a group of Republican House moderates has backed away
from broad tax cuts. Led by Representative Nancy L. Johnson of
Connecticut, the group of 11 moderates has devised its own tax
plan, complete with targeted cuts, closer to what Clinton supports.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, moderate Republicans have long been wary of
sweeping tax cuts. John H. Chafee of Rhode Island and James M.
Jeffords of Vermont have advocated targeted cuts in the past;
Olympia Snowe of Maine has preferred balancing the budget and
examining Social Security before cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Maine Senator Susan M. Collins expressed
reservations about broad tax cuts as well, saying she would rather
pay down the national debt and concentrate on eliminating certain
targets, including a far more popular tax cut, the marriage penalty
tax.
</P>
<P>
   But because those four Republicans _ known as the ``mod squad''
for their consistent departures from the more conservative core of
the party _ were at the center of the Republican opposition to the
articles of impeachment, they may enjoy less leeway on the tax
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, in fact, said he would ``get real aggressive with any
senator who says, `I'm not going to vote for that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different, an impeachment vote from a tax vote,'' Lott
said, speaking to a small group of reporters after the town hall
meeting. ``I did not lobby anybody (on impeachment). When it comes
to tax cuts, you're talking about a tax cut or not for my
daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   The four Republican senators from New England were not available
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lott insisted his remarks did not indicate lingering resentment
over impeachment. And he tempered his comments on Clinton; although
he said immediately after the impeachment trial he was unsure
whether he could trust the president in their working relationship,
Lott said Monday that Clinton called him the next day, Saturday, at
9 a.m. to talk about ``Kosovo, the Medicare Commission, issues we
were going to have to be dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to be cautious, but he is still the president,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also said he ``bent over backwards'' not to pressure the
New England moderates before the Senate vote on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they would be the first to tell you, I was very
aggressive in trying to keep them involved in the process,'' Lott
said. ``I called Olympia Snowe. I called Susan Collins. I realized
that New England is a tougher area than the Midwest or the
Southeast, for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he said, ``I was disappointed that they had to vote
that way.'' But, he added, ``I think I have a better relationship
with them now than we've ever had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
