<SLUG> BC-NY-BABY-NAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD STANDARDS ARE MAKING A COMEBACK IN CHILDREN'S NAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First, Renee Bell named her wire-haired dachshund
Ashley, a name Ms. Bell had liked since childhood. It seemed
appropriate because it sounded vaguely British, and her dog had
come from England. Then she gave the same name to her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had Ashley dog, and then I got married and I had Ashley dog
and Ashley baby,'' Ms. Bell, a legal assistant here, said Monday.
``I have no idea why.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Ashley, the girl, is 9, and in 1997, her name was the most
popular name for girls born in New York City for the sixth year in
a row, after rocketing to the top seemingly out of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to names, the experts say, the most popular ones
are uncannily consistent across the country, from the biggest
cities to the smallest rural towns. But if any place is likely to
produce surprises, it is New York City, as demonstrated by the
top-10 chart for 1997, just released by the New York City Health
Department. (The breakdown of names by city lags a year behind the
national statistics, said Sandra Mullin, the associate health
commissioner.)
</P>
<P>
   Because of the large number of immigrants and ethnic groups
stirring the pot, New Yorkers tend to be a bit behind, and a bit
rebellious when it comes to what the experts call onomastic trends.
So in New York, the top name for Asian boys is Kevin, while in the
rest of the country, Kevin is more likely to be the name of the
fathers than of the sons. And David, Daniel, Rebecca and Rachel
still make the top 10 in New York, helped, perhaps, by a large
concentration of Jews, while those names are fading elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But like parents in the rest of the country, some experts say,
New Yorkers are coming out of a cycle of highly individualistic
names and moving into a cycle of more traditional ones. Parents
still want their children to stand out, if only through their
names, but they are returning, perhaps, to the Bible and family
roots for inspiration, rather than television and the mass media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking back to history to give a kind of stability to
the kids and society,'' said Edward Callary, a linguist at Northern
Illinois University and editor of Names magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be the millennium approaching? ``That would be an
interesting speculation,'' said Cleveland Kent Evans, an associate
professor of psychology at Bellevue University, outside Omaha, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, parents favored more conventional names for boys than
for girls, perhaps because they are still viewed as heirs to a
family tradition. ``That's why we name boys Junior,'' Callary said.
``And businesses are so and so and son, but it's very rare to see
one that says so and so and daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   So Michael and Christopher were the first and second choices for
boys in New York City, continuing a trend since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   For girls, Ashley has been in first place since 1992. It first
appeared on the list in 1990, when it ranked third. It is, the
experts say, part of a waning trend toward giving girls names once
reserved for boys. Ashley Wilkes, for instance, was a male
character in ``Gone with the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Brianna made the list for the first time this year, ranking 10th
among all girls. But among black girls, Brianna ranked second,
after Ashley. And spelled slightly different, as Briana, it also
ranked eighth among black girls.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said it was not surprising that Brianna was so popular
among black parents, because it sounded like many African names,
which are three syllables long with the accent on the second
syllable.
</P>
<P>
   Destiny was the fifth most popular name for black girls and
ranked 10th among Hispanic girls. Evans said it has spread across
the country, especially among black and Hispanic families. But he
said he believes it is connected more to the working-class
background of parents who use it than to their racial background.
It is favored, he suggested, among people who feel ``buffeted by
destiny.'' Another name more popular in the rest of the country,
which he believes is related, is Desiree.
</P>
<P>
   Although the experts could not be sure it was a factor, the
album ``Destiny'' by Gloria Estefan ranked high on the music charts
in 1996, the year before the crop of babies being studied was born.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle, No. 1 among Asian girls, might have been influenced by
Michelle Kwan, the champion figure skater, as well as the desire to
assimilate, experts said. Kevin, now No. 1 among Asian boys, was
the first-ranked name in many European countries _ including
Austria, Germany, France and the Netherlands _ in the early 90s,
when Kevin Costner, Kevin Kline and Kevin Spacey were exported via
American movies, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Callary has a ``saturation'' theory of naming. When too many
children in a kindergarten class have the same name, he suggests,
parents start to move on. That may account, he said, for the rising
popularity of old-fashioned names like Sarah (No. 6) and Emily (No.
9), which were last popular decades ago. Indeed, Sarah ranked No. 8
in New York City in 1898.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
