<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-LIGHTNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE 3-3 TIE WITH LIGHTNING, STEWART SEES SOME POSITIVES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ With two months left in the regular season and
their chances of a playoff berth approaching the vanishing point,
the Islanders have but one choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every guy has to ask himself, `What's going on?' '' said
Zigmund Palffy, who scored two goals as the Islanders skated to a
3-3 tie with the Tampa Bay Lightning on Monday afternoon. ``You can
see on the ice what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, not enough.
</P>
<P>
   While Coach Bill Stewart said he saw ``a semblance of
consistency'' in the Islanders' past three games, he intimated that
some players are not pulling their weight and that changes are
going to be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll re-evaluate the lines,'' he said. ``We'll look at all
different avenues. We will look at the overall game and assess
things player by player.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a dollar factor there, too. Are we getting fair market
value from our players?''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart spoke well of Palffy, who scored his 10th and 11th goals
of the season, and of Mariusz Czerkawski, who opened the scoring
for the Islanders at 15 minutes 55 seconds of the first period on
assists from Trevor Linden and Kenny Jonsson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing with a lot of heart,'' Stewart said of
Czerkawski, who scored the game-tying goal against Buffalo on
Saturday night. ``I'm a positive guy and I see a lot of positive
things in our last three games.''
</P>
<P>
   But Palffy, who scored his first goal of the season Dec. 26
after a contract holdout, appeared frustrated by the Islanders'
failure to beat the worst team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working hard in practice,'' Palffy said. ``We have to
work the same way on the ice each game. It's been 3-3, 2-2. We have
to be better in our zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play one good game is not enough,'' he said of the tie with
the Sabres. ``We have to play four or five games that way. We can't
give it up. There are too many games left.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy's first goal, at 1:18 of the second period, gave the
Islanders a 2-1 lead, with Darcy Tucker having scored for the
Lightning at 2:04 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   After Michael Nylander tied it 2-2 at 6:08 of the third period,
Palffy found himself alone with the puck past the face-off circles
a minute later and laced it through a tangle of players at 7:10 for
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the victory slipped away when Vincent Lecavalier took a
cross-ice pass from Pavel Kubia and sent it past Tommy Salo at
10:29 for the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, I didn't feel we played as well,'' said Stewart,
3-4-4 since taking over from Mike Milbury. ``I have respect for
Tampa, but we will be back to work tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said that if his team plays the same way against
Pittsburgh on Wednesday, it will be a long night. ``But we are
starting to get some consistency in our game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Rich Pilon agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, we had some lapses, but we're playing pretty
well,'' he said. ``As a group of 20 guys, we have to find a way to
make it work. Obviously, he is not going to play the same 20 guys
all the time. And he's made it clear to us that if you play well,
your reward will be ice time, which is what we all want. We have a
choice: We can either make it a fun two months, or a miserable two
months. I'd rather have fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
