<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-JOYNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL JOYNER FACES LIFE'S LESSONS WITH HIS THIRD-GRADER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a sports day for third-graders, and all of
them, girls and boys alike, wanted to run against a certain
8-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone kept challenging her,'' her father said, ``so she ran
race after race and beat them all.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not surprising, considering that her mother, father and
Aunt Jackie had won seven Olympic gold medals among them. Her
mother was the late Florence Griffith Joyner, the celebrated Flo
Jo, who in 1988 set world sprint records that still stand. Her
father is Al Joyner, a triple-jumper of the past and, he hopes, the
near future. Aunt Jackie is Jackie Joyner-Kersee, perhaps the
greatest female athlete ever.
</P>
<P>
   The young star is Mary Ruth Joyner, who, her father says, is 8
going on 28. At Monday's New York Track Writers Association
luncheon and in conversations during the past week, Al Joyner said
his daughter was handling the loss of her mother better than he
was.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner died Sept. 21 at home in Mission Viejo, Calif.
She was 38. A coroner's report found that while she was sleeping,
she suffered a seizure caused by a congenital abnormality of blood
vessels in the brain and suffocated.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Mary had been an aspiring gymnast. Her last day in
the gym was the day her mother died. A few days later came this
conversation with her father:
</P>
<P>
   ``How come you're not going to gymnastics?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to start a track team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to run?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   So now she is running. She wants to be a hurdler, and her father
says that as young as she is, she can clear the 33-inch hurdles
used by women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw her do it,'' he said, ``it scared me. In
the house, she set up hurdles _ a coffee table, chairs, a balance
beam. She made me a hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the human hurdle is in New York as part of a book tour. When
his wife died, she had almost completed ``Running for Dummies''
(IDG Books, $19.99 paperback). Joyner finished the book, a
compendium of advice for veteran and new runners.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner said that until her death, his wife had been training for
the marathon. He said that every Wednesday she had been running 22
miles in 2 hours 40 minutes to 2:50. That translated into a 3:10
marathon, good but almost 50 minutes slower than the world best.
</P>
<P>
   Why a race of 26 miles 385 yards for someone who usually ran 100
or 200 meters?
</P>
<P>
   ``She just wanted to do it,'' Joyner said. ``She never missed a
workout, even if she had to get on a treadmill at 2 in the morning.
She just loved to run. I don't love to run. Anyone who can get on a
treadmill and run through two movies, that's someone who loves to
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner insists that at 39, he is planning a serious comeback to
make next year's Olympic team. When he won the triple jump in 1984
by jumping 56 feet 7{ inches, he was 6 foot 3 and 170 pounds. His
weight soared to 210, but he is down to 193 and, he said, is headed
to 180.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can jump 55 feet,'' he said. ``I've done 52 and 53 in
practice with six steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he does not say so, one reason for his comeback seems
to be his desire to keep his daughter happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florence was my friend, my training partner, my inspiration,
my coach, the mother of my daughter,'' he said. ``I miss her
dearly. This is the hardest thing I've had to deal with in my life.
Mary helps me. The reason I'm still alive is because of my
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, you forget which one is the parent and which one
the child. When I'm going somewhere, she'll say: `Daddy, I don't
want anything to happen to you. Where are you going? When are you
coming back?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary is dealing with things. She keeps my spirits up. That
comes from Florence, who laid down a foundation. Mary's gotten her
strong personality and beliefs from her mother. Aside from jumping,
I run a bit. I'm not too faithful with it, but Mary says, `Daddy,
Mommy wants you to run.' So I run.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
