<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-INTERNET-FREE-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FREE SPEECH AND THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 16:
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state lawmakers may be eager to shield children and
others from smut on the Internet, but it is very difficult to do so
without trampling on the First Amendment. Two recent cases show the
constitutional harm misguided laws can inflict.
</P>
<P>
   One case involves the 1998 federal Child Online Protection Act.
Federal District Judge Lowell Reed of Philadelphia showed proper
sensitivity to the First Amendment in issuing a preliminary
injunction against enforcement of the statute.
</P>
<P>
   The law would require all commercial sites, including free
sites, that contain material that might be deemed ``harmful to
minors'' to obtain credit card numbers or adult identification
numbers from users. Violators could be subject to heavy fines and
up to six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   This would force Web site operators either to put up age
verification barriers or delete potentially sensitive materials
from Web pages in an effort to avoid possible prosecution. It could
also deter adult Internet users from obtaining access to all kinds
of nonpornographic material because they may not want to lose their
anonymity by entering an identification or credit card number into
the computer.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
unwisely brushed aside First Amendment concerns in upholding a
Virginia law that prohibits state employees from using office
computers to read or download sexually explicit material on the
Internet without getting written approval from a department head.
Six professors at Virginia's public universities argued that the
law violated their free-speech rights by barring access to all
sexually explicit information on line that could be relevant to
research or teaching. The court, however, ruled that the state
could control the work-related speech of the professors as
employees, including their access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, better options exist. Filtering software can
protect children from on-line pornography more effectively than a
law that infringes on the rights of adults. Similarly, Virginia can
prohibit state employees from using office computers for
non-job-related purposes, without resorting to a content-based
distinction that hurts free speech and limits the legitimate use of
computers by educators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
