<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOK ON IMPEACHMENT 
BILLIE JEAN KING GETS ASHE AWARD 
VOCAL AUDIENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH CHARLES STRUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How will William Rehnquist's book about impeachment sell now
that the Senate trial is over?
</P>
<P>
   The monthlong impeachment proceeding provided the chief justice
with something that other authors only dream of: day-to-day
exposure on national television, which might be second only to an
endorsement from Oprah Winfrey in helping to sell a stolid volume
like Rehnquist's book, ``Grand Inquests: The Historic Impeachments
of Justice Samuel Chase and President Andrew Johnson.'' (Published
in 1992, it was reissued by William Morrow in December as a
paperback.)
</P>
<P>
   The end of the trial gave ``Grand Inquests'' a boost. Between
Friday and Sunday, ``Grand Inquests'' climbed to 572nd from 712th
in the sales rankings reported by the online bookseller Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist's book was 53rd on Barnes &AMP; Noble's online sales chart
at the end of January. By last week, it had dropped off the chain's
list of 100 top-selling titles; calls to Barnes &AMP; Noble's corporate
headquarters to see how ``Grand Inquests'' was faring were not
returned.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, sales of other books that appealed to
impeachment-minded readers had already slackened off as the trial
drew to an end.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the impeachment referral by the independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr, slipped noticeably.
</P>
<P>
   Released by three publishers in September, the Starr report is
no longer the hot seller it was in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The 336-page version from Prima Books was 20,023rd in
Amazon.com's rankings on Sunday. The 421-page volume from Public
Affairs Press was 37,918th, and the 523-page paperback edition from
Pocket Books was 56,685th.
</P>
<P>
   Profiles in Courage
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I tried to get my hit on the weekends or maybe for
10 minutes and see if there's anything new,'' Billie Jean King said
the other day. She was talking not about a tennis match but about
the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning I watched a lot more and thought this was not
very productive for my life,'' she said. ``It started to become
very repetitive. I thought, `I get the picture, it's going to take
forever, it's going to be a war between Democrats and Republicans,
and that's not a healthy situation.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. King was in New York to attend Monday night's ESPY Awards at
Radio City Music Hall, where she received the Arthur Ashe Award for
Courage for leading the effort to improve the status of women in
professional tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. King recalled talking with Ashe several years ago when both
were commentators for HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a lot of time talking about how we wanted to make
tennis more hospitable,'' she said. `We were born in the same year,
but I was discriminated against because of my gender and he because
of his color. One time I asked him, `What's the most difficult
thing for you?' He said, ``Most people would think it's HIV, AIDS
or my heart, but it's really being a black man. Every time I walk
out the door, I know my day could be difficult because of
prejudice.'''
</P>
<P>
   A Sing-Along
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The house lights dimmed for the second act of ``Babes
in Arms'' at the City Center over the weekend, the band struck up
``Where or When,'' and _in a first for the six-year-old Encores
series of revivals _ the audience began to sing.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Fisher, the music director, said he wasn't sure what he was
hearing. Only later did he learn that audiences at two of the five
performances were so swept away by the melancholy Rodgers and Hart
tune that humming broke out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at center stage,'' said Fisher, who conducts an onstage
ensemble. ``I hear the band so loudly that it's hard to hear
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where I stood, I heard giggling a few bars into it,'' he
said. ``Apparently, people began to hum, stopped, giggled, and as a
group decided to go for it with everything they had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
