<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUNMAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CLOSING IN ON THE GUNMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 16:
</P>
<P>
   Last week's federal jury verdict against firearms manufacturers
for negligent marketing and distribution practices marks an
important turning point in the fight against gun violence. The
Brooklyn jury found 15 of 25 gun manufacturers named in the lawsuit
negligent and found that nine of them were collectively liable for
three of seven shootings with illegally obtained handguns, even
though it was not proved what brand of gun had been used in a
particular shooting. In effect, the jury said the companies had
allowed the guns to fall into the wrong hands, thereby putting the
industry on notice that it can be held accountable for violence.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmakers are claiming vindication because the jury imposed
no damages for six of the seven shooting victims. But the industry
knows it is in big trouble. There is growing evidence linking
industry practices to illegal trafficking in guns, and five large
cities have already filed suit against the industry to try to
recover their considerable costs of mopping up after gun violence.
These suits are based on the so-called ``negligent-marketing
theory'' used in the Brooklyn case as well as a more conventional
product-liability theory that argues that manufacturers have made
their product ``unreasonably dangerous'' by failing to incorporate
feasible safety devices.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the verdict, the gun lobby was so nervous it had
begun appealing to gun-friendly state legislatures to pass measures
aimed at blocking lawsuits. The industry has lavished millions on
high-pressure lobbying tactics to preserve its unique exemption
from government safety regulations _ all the while trying to
prettify that exemption by calling it a constitutional right. The
gun lobby knows that the political muscle and money it deploys to
control lawmakers will not work in a courtroom. That is why it is
trying so hard to shut courthouse doors.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to say whether anti-gun lawsuits will be able to
replicate the success of the tobacco litigation. But a responsible
industry would not resort to a desperate court-blocking strategy.
It would instead be concentrating on designing products with
effective safety locks, and on fighting illegal trafficking, for
example by requiring dealers to limit gun purchases to one a month
for each individual customer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0376 </DOCNO>
