A6350 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-FOREST-SERVICE-N     02-15 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FOREST-SERVICE-NYT </SLUG>
 
EDITORIAL: THE FOREST SERVICE'S NEW DEAL  (fb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 16:
</P>
<P>
   From the day he assumed control of the U.S. Forest Service two
years ago, Michael Dombeck made clear that his first priority would
be the conservation of natural resources as opposed to their
exploitation. He said he wanted to trim the annual timber harvest,
protect watersheds and restore wildlife habitat _ heretical
thoughts in a federal agency that historically has been far more
interested in harvesting trees than in acting as a responsible
steward of the American landscape. Given the obstinate attitudes of
the logging industry and its obedient friends in Congress,
conservationists gave him little chance of succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, however, Dombeck has begun to make good
on his promises in important ways. First he announced a ban on
mining along the 100-mile Rocky Mountain Front, one of the richest
wilderness areas in the lower 48 states. Then last Thursday he
announced a long-awaited 18-month suspension of the construction of
new logging roads in much of the undeveloped back country of the
national forests. The move would effectively put 33 million acres
of national forest _ one-sixth of the total _ off limits to
logging. The newly protected acres include critical spawning
grounds for fish and habitat for animals that need unbroken
wilderness to survive. At the end of the moratorium, Dombeck will
unveil a permanent national plan governing road-building policy
throughout the 192-million-acre system.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists were generally but not completely happy with
Dombeck's plan. About 15 million roadless acres were not protected
by the ban, including large tracts in the Pacific Northwest and the
Tongass National Forest in Alaska. Dombeck's explanation is that
most of these areas are covered by newly drawn plans that have yet
to prove their worth and, in some cases, are under appeal in the
courts. That is true. It is also true that including the Tongass
would have infuriated Alaska's congressional delegation and other
influential Western senators who underwrite Dombeck's agency and
who are already incensed by his departures from Forest Service
orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   The Tongass in particular deserves better. The latest forest
plan allows for an annual ``cut'' of 267 million board feet a year.
That is more than double the 1996 cut, and could require 1,100
miles of new roads. Meanwhile, Alaska's congressional delegation is
placing heavy pressure on Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman to
make a sweetheart deal with Louisiana Pacific, an aggressive
logging company that is demanding millions of board feet at
subsidized prices. Glickman, who is Dombeck's boss, should tell
Louisiana Pacific to go away.
</P>
<P>
   But the only sure way to sustain what is left of these
magnificent old-growth forests is for Dombeck to put them off
limits to new roads when he unwraps his final plan in 18 months.
That would make a good policy even better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
