<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6354 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-LADN     02-15 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNS POSITIVE THAT NFL WANTS L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the NFL's expansion committee meets today in
Atlanta, neither of the two groups seeking a franchise for Los
Angeles, the Michael Ovitz/Carson team nor the Ed Roski/New
Coliseum squad, will be in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   A skeptic would say that's a bad sign. It's hard to score
touchdowns when you aren't allowed on the field.
</P>
<P>
   But if one is to believe the NFL, this is the clearest sign yet
the league is serious about returning to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   While the committee will receive updates and discuss the Ovitz
and Roski proposals, it will also deliberate its own alternative _
selecting a site somewhere in L.A., assisting in stadium
construction, and then opening up the bidding for a franchise to
all comers.
</P>
<P>
   That is the model the league used to return a franchise in
Cleveland. Working with city officials who contributed $166 million
to a new stadium, the league spent $54 million to help finance
construction and assisted with private seat-license sales. Al
Lerner won the bidding for the Browns franchise at $530 million,
which included paying the NFL back its $54 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the league's criteria were merely a new stadium, oodles of
public money and a well-heeled owner, then the NFL would already
have handed a franchise to Houston and businessman Robert McNair.
The Houston proposal has been complete and in hand for more than
six months.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. is important enough, league sources say, to consider the
Cleveland option and commit to it as early as mid-March, when the
league owners hold their annual meetings in Phoenix. That decision,
they add, wouldn't necessarily preclude Ovitz or Roski as owners or
Carson or the Coliseum as the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance (in L.A.) is to do it right and eliminate the
risks,'' said Roger Goodell, the NFL's vice president of
development. ``There's been a high degree of frustration in the
L.A. market and we've taken a (public relations) hit in the
process. We need to do this one right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we should vote for is a plan with holes,'' said
Jerry Richardson, the Carolina Panthers owner who is on the
expansion committee. ``And at the end of the day, the biggest issue
usually is the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has every right to be as skeptical of the league as
it was of Georgia Frontiere and Al Davis. The NFL did nothing to
stop the Rams from leaving, never wanted the Raiders to come, and
did very little up to this point to fill the void they left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The league says it has the best interests of L.A. in mind, but
the push for the Cleveland option raises several other questions:
</P>
<P>
   __ Is the league actually saying that Ovitz and Roski can't pull
this off?
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz's personal worth has been estimated at $250 million to
$500 million. But much of the $138 million settlement he received
upon leaving Disney _ he was hired as the company's president but
fired a year later _ came in stock options with limits on when and
how they could be cashed.
</P>
<P>
   Precious little information regarding the financial strength of
his ownership group has been available. Carson Mayor Peter Fajardo
expected a position paper detailing all revenue and equity shares
last September, but he's still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   An Ovitz NFL-presentation document obtained from Carson
officials included no equity breakdown, alluded to Ovitz ``or an
affiliate'' as principal owner, and did not include stockbroker Ted
Forstmann. Ovitz spokesman Peter Levin said Forstmann is still of
the group but declined to answer any other specific questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working very closely with the league in shaping our
proposal,'' he said. ``We have made what we consider to be a sound
proposal and it's been the same proposal from the beginning. And
we're not comfortable elaborating (on it publicly).''
</P>
<P>
   The net worth of Roski, the Kings' co-owner who is building The
Staples Center, is estimated at $400 million to $700 million. But
NFL concerns that he is overextended led him to take on billionaire
Eli Broad as a partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want anyone thinking there was an equity
restraint,'' said New Coliseum vice president John Semcken. ``We're
not trying to encourage anyone raising the (franchise fee number),
but we wanted the league to know it can be covered.''
</P>
<P>
   A league source said the committee considers worse-case
scenarios in awarding franchises and the biggest fear is that the
cost of building a stadium and buying a team in L.A. could be too
much at one time for any group.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL builds the stadium, he said, it can remove that
potential problem. It would also be involved in selling name rights
to the facility and PSLs, and balance those figures into stadium
costs. The NFL considers PSL revenue projections of both groups
(Carson $75 million, Coliseum $100 million) to be too optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   __ Is the league stalling because it knows expansion fees are
only increasing?
</P>
<P>
   The Browns' franchise value has been set at $476 million, and
the Redskins and their stadium just sold for $800 million. Both
L.A. groups are speculating that the franchise fee will be $500
million. But if the NFL delays naming an owner for a year, that
price could increase by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Phoenix Cardinals are seeking public money for a new
stadium. Any decision in March tied to a dollar figure could impact
how much state and city officials are willing to spend to keep the
Cardinals happy.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of value inflation, Philips Electronics has
offered $150 million to $180 million for naming rights to a new
arena in Atlanta, dwarfing the $100 million Staples is paying (over
20 years) to name the new Kings and Lakers downtown arena.
</P>
<P>
   __ Is this the NFL's way of getting more public money, its
favorite kind, and creating new competition?
</P>
<P>
   Carson's proposed investment has been capped at $180 million.
The New Coliseum says its proposal includes in excess of $300
million of public money, but the league does not agree with the
Coliseum's math. Much of the public money in the Coliseum proposal
comes in the form of already-completed investment.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is getting much greater public investment in new
stadiums in other cities _ Pittsburgh ($147 million), Cleveland
($166 million), Detroit ($180 million), Nashville ($292 million),
Seattle ($300) and Cincinnati ($404 million). Connecticut will
spend $375 million to build the Patriots a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL plan would encourage Hollywood Park and Inglewood to
renew its bid to build a stadium adjacent to the race track and
casino.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has always liked the idea of a stadium next to Dodger
Stadium. Dodgers President Bob Graziano said the team and Fox
officials will continue to support the New Coliseum as requested by
Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan until it hears otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   League sources say its plan doesn't preclude Ovitz or Roski as
the prospective owner or either Carson or the Coliseum as the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I think they have the leverage to ask for a decision
now, and would prefer we pick them now, they would rather get a
franchise (anyway) than not,'' said a league official. ``And we
would probably continue to develop the sites until we were
convinced there's a better one.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Is it stalling because it wants the pending lawsuit, over who
owns the NFL rights in L.A., involving Al Davis and the Raiders,
settled before moving ahead?
</P>
<P>
   Davis has been and remains the NFL original wild card and the
case isn't scheduled to begin until this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-15-99 2254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
