<DOCNO> NYT19990215.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUSPECT-ATTACKS-25     02-15 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-ATTACKS-255&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPE SUSPECT WHO SPARKED POLICE SHOOTING STRIKES AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (See related NY-SUSPECT-SHOT, NY-SUSPECT-DIAZ, NY-SUSPECT-COPS) 
 (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two women were sexually assaulted over the weekend by
the same rape suspect four police officers were looking for on the
night they shot and killed an unarmed West African immigrant
earlier this month, police said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday morning, two women, ages 22 and 25, were going into
a building in the Washington Heights section of Manhattan when a
man with a gun followed them into the elevator, said Capt. John
Creegan, commander of the major crimes unit of the Bronx
detectives.
</P>
<P>
   The man then used a purse to hold the door open so that the
elevator could not move, sexually assaulted the women and robbed
them, Creegan said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect has now raped or robbed 39 women since 1993, Creegan
said. The police felt the same man is responsible because of the
similarities of the attacks; the suspect typically follows women
into their buildings and is not afraid to attack women who are not
alone, Creegan said.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 4, four officers belonging to the Bronx Street Crimes
Unit were seeking the suspect when they encountered Amadou Diallo
and shot him to death in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment
building.
</P>
<P>
   A Bronx grand jury on Tuesday is expected to begin hearing
evidence against the four officers involved in the shooting _
Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon and Richard Murphy.
Lawyers said the officers probably would not be called until next
week and that the jurors are likely to hear first from medical
examiners, ballistics experts and any possible witnesses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Also Monday, as Diallo's body was returned to Guinea, religious
leaders and outraged citizens in New York and Washington held
another day of rallies and prayers Monday to call once again for an
end to police violence.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1,500 people jammed the Abyssinian Baptist Church in
Harlem to hear the Rev. Calvin O. Butts III offer prayers not just
for victims of police violence but also for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
and the police. In Washington, about 400 civil rights advocates
marched from the White House to the Capitol carrying signs
denouncing the shooting of Diallo and chanting ``enough is
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Butts urged the overflow crowd to work together to ``root out
the evil that permeates our city,'' then read a list of dozens of
people killed by New York City police officers since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Though the audience was mostly black and mostly female, there
were a smattering of yarmulkes and Asian faces in the crowd. The
head of the Central Conference of American Rabbis, Paul Menitoff,
spoke at the three-hour service, as did the general secretary of
the Islamic Leadership Council, Shaykh Abd'Allah Latif Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Mim Warden, who lives on Manhattan's Upper West Side, said she
went to the service after hearing about it at her synagogue because
she felt she needed to take a stand for justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If what I say in synagogue isn't acted out, then my belief is
not made real,'' Ms. Warden, 63, said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
