<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-MAPLELEAFS     02-15 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-MAPLELEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTOREK MAKES STATEMENT AS DEVILS BATTLE TO A TIE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The first period was not even halfway
through Monday when Devils Coach Robbie Ftorek called for a
timeout. Gathering the Devils together, Ftorek calmly addressed the
team and delivered a message that has been slow to get through.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils again seemed on foreign ground in front of the home
fans, stumbling to a quick two-goal deficit, and when the second
goal came, Ftorek had seen enough and stopped play. But before the
period was over, the Devils had erased the Toronto Maple Leafs'
lead, and in the end, they recovered to forge a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had to hang on just to get the one point as they were
outshot by 31-22. They survived a scare in the final minute of
regulation when Aleksandr Karpovtsev fed Sergei Berezin just
outside the left post and Berezin blasted a shot that Martin
Brodeur turned away. With 3:20 left in overtime, Brodeur again came
up big, trapping the puck against the outside of his skate as
Ladislav Kohn hacked away at it.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams went a man down at 9:48 of the third period, a swap
that the Devils were not pleased with. Randy McKay was battling in
front of the net with Dimitri Yushkevich, with both players
tumbling into the crease. As McKay tried to get to his feet with
Tie Domi banging him around, Kris King grabbed McKay's left arm and
held it. Domi, like a professional wrestler in a tag-team match,
grabbed McKay's head with both hands and pinned it backwards over
the crossbar of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   When the officials separated the two, both players were assessed
two minute penalties, Domi for roughing and McKay for goaltender
interference. Scott Stevens and Igor Korolev then followed them to
the penalty box, both for slashing just 31 seconds later. But
neither team was able to mount a credible threat and the penalties
were all killed off.
</P>
<P>
   In its first game since closing down the long-time home ice at
Maple Leaf Gardens, Toronto seemed to be making itself at home at
Continental Arena. The Devils have done little to exert a home-ice
advantage at the Meadowlands, enduring a five-game winless streak
here until besting the Carolina Hurricanes on Saturday. Currently
in a six-game homestand, their longest of the season, the Devils
started it with a 3-2 loss to the Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took their first lead of the night at 1:41 of the
second period on a power-play goal by Jason Arnott. The Maple Leafs
nearly cleared the puck, but Scott Niedermayer was able to keep it
in, lunging and hacking the puck back into the corner, where Patrik
Elias retrieved it and found Arnott floating toward the net. Arnott
was able to trickle it through the pads of Curtis Joseph for a 3-2
lead. But the Maple Leafs, outshooting the Devils by 14-4 in the
second period, tied the score with one minute remaining when Garry
Valk fired from the left circle and beat Brodeur to the far post.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs built a 2-0 lead, scoring a pair of goals 1
minute and 1 second apart. First, the former Devil Steve Thomas
rushed the left side of the ice, leading Bryan Berard with a pass
in front that was just out of reach of Scott Stevens and Sergei
Brylin, and Berard slipped the puck under the pads of Martin
Brodeur. Then, Ladislav Kohn carried the puck in and slipped it to
Derek King, who faked his way past Sheldon Souray and bounced a
short shot from the left circle through Brodeur's pads at 9:04 of
the period.
</P>
<P>
   But 30 seconds after a timeout, the Devils began to assert
themselves as Arnott crunched Dimitri Yushkevich into the boards..
Then, at 15:54, Berard slipped as he retreated into his own zone
and Bombardir whisked past him and charged the net, firing a shot
that was stopped by Joseph. Joseph again denied the Devils on a
rebound attempt by Brian Rolston, but when the puck came free, Jay
Pandolfo reached as he dove forward and banged the puck past
Joseph.
</P>
</TEXT>
