<P>
   Of the injured firefighters, two remained in the burn unit at
Parkland Memorial Hospital in Dallas. They were identified as Joe
Hamilton Jr., 24, and Andrew Ailara, 29. Both were in good
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Two others were treated at area hospitals and released.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials did not explain why firefighters entered the
church to battle the blaze, which was visible to witnesses who
stepped outside about 10:45 a.m. as the first fire trucks arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But Fort Worth Lt. Kent Worley said the wind, with gusts of 30
mph, was likely a major factor in the flames' rapid spread. Fifteen
minutes after the first crews arrived, the roof caved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears from looking at the building that the fire got up
into the attic and the wind pushed it through the attic very
quickly,'' Worley said. ``The roof came down on them very quickly,
probably at the moment they were going to change tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   As two crews of volunteer firefighters arrived, dense smoke
poured from the building and flames were slightly visible,
Cartwright said. A 17-year volunteer, he was among firefighters who
went into the church through a back door, spraying water, while
another crew burst into the front of the church.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``pitch black'' inside, and even over the roar of fire
and water, he said he heard the roof begin to give way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear the beams beginning to let go'' and men
scrambled for the exits, dragging water hoses as they went,
Cartwright said.
</P>
<P>
   When Cartwright emerged, his jacket had begun to curl from the
heat, and all he had left of the fire hose was the nozzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky is all,'' he said, rubbing his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of people from the surrounding neighborhood and two strip
shopping centers watched in horror as the roof began to buckle with
firefighters on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were five or six of them up there cutting holes in the
roof,'' said David Simpson, owner of DFW Electronics, down the
street from the church. ``You could just watch the roof begin to
fold in and guys jumping off.''
</P>
<P>
   Belinda Hart of Massage from the Hart store said the fire was so
immense that heat from the fire hit her like an oven blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flames were billowing and the smoke was covering the sky,''
Hart said. ``The firefighter was on the roof with his hatchet. Next
thing I knew, the ceiling collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awful. I could see the guy hanging on with his hands.
It was just so amazing to think he could have lost his life, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Another witness, Charity Emanuel, 19, said she saw the
firefighter clinging to the roof, flames licking around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His buddy just turned around and pulled him up over the
edge,'' Emanuel said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Lt. J.R. Whiteside, a fire training instructor with the Fort
Worth Fire Department, said ``truss roof'' buildings like the
church are ``the most dangerous structures'' that firefighters
face.
</P>
<P>
   Like many churches, auditoriums and other buildings without
interior load-bearing walls, the church had a roof supported by
lightweight wooden trusses, he said. If one truss or connecting
plate fails, the whole roof comes down, pulling down with it the
exterior walls to which the trusses are bolted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trusses kill firemen more than anything else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two nearby businesses were transformed into makeshift grieving
and counseling areas for families and firefighters. They were
operated by Fort Worth's critical incident caseworkers and American
Red Cross volunteer counselors.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, a lieutenant and 14-year veteran in Fort Worth, and
Dean, who was recently promoted to engineer after six years on the
force, had completed their regular shifts and were off just a
couple of hours when they responded as suburban volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Collins often dressed as a clown as part of the department's
``Learn Not to Burn'' campaign, teaching children at elementary
schools, festivals and other venues about the dangers of fire. He
had been a suburban volunteer for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dean, a Sunday School teacher at Trinity Baptist Church, had
been a volunteer in the suburbs for more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were about to become fathers _ Collins for the third
time, Dean the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Collins and Dean were family guys who loved the fire
department,'' said Fort Worth Capt. Steve Beasley, who had worked
with both for several years at Station 16 in west Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths were the area's first multiple firefighter fatalities
in more than a decade, when Dallas firefighters Ed
Metters.MDBR/.MDNM/ and Charles Rogers.MDBR/.MDNM/ died battling a
blaze at the Hunt oil mansion on Aug. 21, 1981, said Denny Burris,
.MDBR/.MDNM/chaplain for the Dallas department.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Anita Baker, Elizabeth Campbell, Yvette Craig and
Laura Vozzella also contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
