<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHNS-PROVIDENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S FLOORS PROVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The interest in St. John's has risen so high that the
competition for tickets outside Alumni Hall on Monday night was
greater than the competition between the teams inside.
</P>
<P>
   The fans who did grab the few tickets available for sale in the
parking lot saw Reggie Jessie trying no-look, spin-around passes,
Albert Richardson careering through the lane like an out-of-control
taxi and all of it working just fine. This is what total domination
looks like when even the most absurd of St. John's shots are
falling, it is doing all the rebounding and the Providence Friars
are struggling to stay in the building.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm, ranked 10th in the nation, gave a clinic on
tuning up for the post-season, demolishing the Friars, 104-70, and
moving to 21-6 overall and 12-3 in the Big East with three games to
go in the regular season. It was the first time a St. John's team
had hit the 100-point mark against a Big East opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The Friars are 14-11 and 7-8 and seem destined for a berth in
the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a team that has a final-something look _ a Final Four,
or final eight look,'' Providence Coach Tim Welsh said of St.
John's. ``They're hard to play because they've got so many answers.
You help out on one guy, and they move the ball. In a nutshell, it
was a domination.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. John's victory was so complete that even the normally
loquacious players, who always seem to have some constructive
criticism for each other at the foul line, were silent.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's scored 18 straight points in the first half as part
of a 28-2 run that displayed everything it can do so well. That
nine-minute span should be preserved behind glass, to be broken
only if St. John's needs it in an emergency during the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play like this, nobody can beat us,'' said Tyrone Grant,
who was honored in his last game at Alumni Hall as the senior who
contributed the most to the basketball program. ``Somebody was
yelling `Sweet 16' and I looked at him like he was crazy. We are
not settling for the Sweet 16.''
</P>
<P>
   On offense during the game-breaking run, the Red Storm broke
Providence's pressure defense. When the Red Storm was on defense,
Erick Barkley (9 points, 6 assists) stayed so close to Providence's
Corey Wright that he seemed to be peering into Wright's pores. On
one play, Barkley stripped Wright of the ball and tossed an outlet
pass to Bootsy Thornton (15 points) for a layup.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Artest (16 points) showed two head fakes before easing in a
layup and Thornton hit Richardson (14 points) with a pass in the
low post for an easy lay-in.
</P>
<P>
   Grant (12 points, 7 rebounds) hit a bank shot and Barkley had a
pull-up 3-pointer. Lavor Postell didn't score during the run, but
he was the team's high scorer with 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what this team can do when they're making stops on one
end and then running and passing,'' Coach Mike Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's was doing all of that, and then some. St. John's shot
50 percent from the field and held Providence to 41.8 percent, with
Artest's defense limiting the Friars' Jamel Thomas to 7-of-17
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's had 24 assists (on 39 field goals) and just 12
turnovers and, as usual, the Red Storm dominated the boards, 50-32.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis, who believes something can be learned from even a
seemingly flawless victory, will likely try to find something to
improve upon after this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to play a game where you shut out the opponent and
you don't have any turnovers,'' Jarvis said, raising the bar just a
little higher. ``Coaches are never satisfied. That's why we're
coaches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
